N2  - In 43 patients with Stein LeventhaJ syndrome the histological picture of the ovary formed the basis of a study to establish whether there is a connection between the hirsutism or the endocrinal status of the patient and the various morphological changes. The results suggest that hirsutism is connected neither with hyperplasia of the theca interna, nor with luteinization of the theca cells nor with the presence of paralutein cells. The distribution and histochemical peculiarity of the lipoids observed in most polycystic ovaries points rather to sustained estrogen secretion. The presence of so and iuteinization of the cells of the theca interna are not characteristic morphological changes in this disease.
