AN  - 290089218
T1  - Pregnancy outcome and the time required for next conception
A1  - Jain A.K.
Y1  - 1969//
N2  - This is an empirical investigation of how the outcome of a preceding pregnancy affects the length of the time required for the next conception (pregnancy interval). The present study is intended to be a contribution to our knowledge of the factors determining the length of the pregnancy interval in the absence of contraception. The effects of one such factor, age of woman, on the length of pregnancy intervals are ascertained. Finally, the average and variance of post partum amenorrhoea are inferred from the averages and variances of pregnancy intervals. In the preent analysis, the pregnancy interval is defined as the period between the end of one and the beginning of the next pregnancy. Thus, the pregnancy interval excludes the period of gestation, and is assumed to be made up of two additive components: Infecundable period which is made up of post partum amenorrhoea and anovulatory period, and fecundable period. During the infecundable period the probability of conception is probably close to zero, whereas during the fecundable period a woman is exposed to the risk of conception with a defined monthly probability. The length of a pregnancy interval or the time required for conception is expected to vary with the outcome of the preceding pregnancy because of the variations in its components. Four variables which can lengthen the pregnancy interval are considered: Lactation, age of woman, temporary separation between spouses, and the use of contraception for spacing or limiting childbearing.
