T1  - The transition from the normo- To hyperfonadotrophic state of women in the pranenopuue
A1  - Kaiser R.
Y1  - 1969//
N2  - The total gonadotrophic excretion of 12 women in the premenopause with an almost regular cycle of 24 to 35 days was examined in every 48 hr urine sample. Signs of ovulation could still be traced in 7 cycles, although they showed a definite corpus luteum insufficiency. Five cycles were anovulatory. The determinations showed, that in contrast to the normal cycles the basic excretion of gonadotrophins was higher in cases of corpus luteum insufficiency. The excretion rose from an average of 6 mg HMG 20 A/24 hr urine to an average of 15 mg. At the mid cycle peak an increase from 16 to 40 mg could be found. The anovulatory cycles showed an average excretion of 29 mg HMG 20 A/24 hr urine. It can be concluded that a HMG excretion of more than 20 mg indicates hypergonadotropism. In these cases it is improbable, that treatment with gonadotropins can induce ovulation. Between 15 to 20 mg ovulation is still possible, although it is assumed that a high dose of gonadotrophins is necessary to induce it.
