T1  - Ovarian function after hysterectomy with conservation of the ovaries in pre menopausal women
A1  - Beavis E.L.G.
A1  - Brown J.B.
A1  - Smith M.A.
Y1  - 1969//
N2  - Ovarian function has been studied in 69 putitMit.s subjected to hysterectomy between the ages of 25 and 48 yr. Total conservation of the maries was practised in 48 patients and partial conservation in 21, the operations being performed under the routine conditions of a general hospital. Ovarian function was monitored fur periods of 4 to 6 wk at intervals for up to 2.5 yr by weekly urinary oestrogen and pregnanediol measurements. In the group with total conservation of the ovaries, ovarian function continued completely normally up to the expected time of the menopause; the incidence of o\ulatory cycles was 73X of anovulatory cycles 2(U, and of inactive cycles TL Of the 99 uvula toi y cycles studied in this group, 94 had a length of approx. 28 days, 3 were noticeably shorter than this, und 2 were longer. The age incidence of the patients with inactive function was the same as that for a population of normal women of the.same age. In the group with partial conservation, the incidence of anovulatory ovarian function was considerably higher; this was ascribed to the removal of ovarian tissue. The finding that ovaries which are functioning normally before hysterectomy continue to function completely normully after hysterectomy, adds considerable weight to the arguments that whenever possible, such ovaries should be totally conserved during the operation.
