T1  - Discrepancies between colpocytology and urinary steroid hormone excretion in women treated with domiphene citrate or gonadotropins for anovulatory sterility
A1  - Boquoi E.
A1  - Hammerstein J.
Y1  - 1969//
N2  - A comparison of colpocytology and urinary ketosteroids and 17 hydroxysteroids was carried out in seven patients treated with gonadotropins or clomiphene citrate for anovulatory sterility. Altogether eight treatment courses were investigated as continuously as possible over periods of three to five weeks. Ovulation was induced in seven patients, of whom three conceived and five developed more or less severe ovarian ovei stimulation. Only one woman did not respond at all to the administration of ovulation inducers. A good correlation between colpocytology and hormonal excretion was seen in only two out of seven treatment courses resulting in ovulation. With regard to the latter, colpocytology appeared to be a better and more sensitive guide than estrogen excretion in one of the two patients. Four women with clinical features closely related to the Stein Leventhal syndrome failed to show adequate proliferation of the vaginal mucosa in spite of convincing evidence for striking overproduction of estrogens due to ovarian overstimulation. Luteal activity became colpocytologically apparent as early as one to two days after the assumed date of ovulation in all cases but one. During the luteal phase, nothing pointed to hormonal overproduction in these cases with ovarian overstimulation. The one patient who did not respond to gonadotropin treatment, however, displayed proliferated vaginal mucosa in the absence of any appreciable estrogen excretion. The possible causes and practical implications of these findings are briefly discussed.
