T1  - Problems of contraception in Afghanistan
T3  - Probleme der konzeptionsverhutung in afghanistan
A1  - Nevin H.S.R.
Y1  - 1969//
N2  - Afghanistan is an example of an under developed country with problems in birth control. In a 3 year period a total of 860 Afghan women were instructed in the use of contraceptive methods and materials at the University Clinic in Kabul. The acceptability and efficacy of the various methods were evaluated with special reference to the economic and social conditions in the country. Coitus interruptus is the most used method of contraception among the lower social classes and has a failure rate of 10 per 100 use years. Complicated methods, such as basal temperature measurement, have, up to now, failed because of inexperience of the female partner and the frequency of mild, febrile infections. The efficiency and acceptability of oral contraceptives were examined using 301 women who received Anovlar, and 379 women who received Lyndiol. Anovulatory agents have, up till now, been used by only a small number of women from the lower social classes as well as young women. In this series failure rates of 6% and 4% of treated cycles were observed with Anovlar and Lyndiol respectively. In all cases the cause of failure was omission to take the prescribed course of tablets regularly.
