T1  - Binucteate human oocytes from large follicles
A1  - Kennedy J.F.
A1  - Donahue R.P.
Y1  - 1969//
N2  - In examining over 900 oocytes recovered from human ovaries the authors have found 2 ova each containing 2 nuclei in the germinal vesicle stage. The 2 binucleate ova were obtained by puncturing antral follicles in ovaries removed for gynecologic indications. The first ovum is 1 of 14 obtained from a sterile 29 yr old woman who had had a wedge resection of her ovaries 5 yr earlier for polycystic ovarian syndrome. Reexamination of all ovarian tissue from this patient confirmed the earlier diagnosis of polycystic ovary, but no evidence for it was found in the present specimen. The second ovum is 1 of 9 obtained from a 31 yr old woman at the time of therapeutic abortion at 20 wk gestation. No other multinucleate ova were found in sections of either of the woman's ovaries. Interviewing of both women did not reveal any personal or family history of multiple gestation, teratoma, or genetic abnormalities, and neither of the women had received gonadotrophins or oral contraceptives. Since multiovular follicles have been seen in women after gonadotrophic stimulation, such stimulation may increase the frequency of multinucleate ova. Both patients could have been subject to a high level of gonadotrophin either from pregnancy or from polycystic ovarian syndrome.
