T1  - Induction of ovulation with Sexovid (compound F6066) and its mode of action
A1  - Sato T.
A1  - Ibuki Y.
A1  - Hirono M.
Y1  - 1969//
N2  - A total of 122 patients with menstrual disorders were treated by Sexovid, a nonsteroidal synthetic drug, with the intention of inducing ovulation. Of the 122 women. 53 (43%) had fine or more ovulations; and of the 234 cycles during which the drug was administered, 82 (357) were ovulatory. Excepting the group of patients with amenorrhea due to estrogen deficiency, we noted that 47 patients (54%) ovulated (74 cycles, 447%). and 12 conceived. Thus, Sexovid is not effective in the amenorrheal patient with estrogen deficiency. Repeated administration of Sexovid is more effective than treatment of only one cycle. Spontaneous ovulation during the cycle following cessation of treatment was observed in 507 of the responsive patients. Dosage of 400 mg daily for 7 days was the most effective regimen. No untoward effects were observed in 234 cycles of 122 patients, and the development of cystic ovaries were not encountered during treatment. Kvidence was adduced to show that this compound caused release of LH from the pituitary. The sequence of events was probably as follows: Direct action upon the anterior pituitary was demonstrated by the increase of plasma and pituitary LH following the stereotaxic implantation of Sexovid into the rat brain. Subcutaneous injection of this compound for 10 days also increased both LH synthesis and release in rats. Urinary LH levels also were elevated in all patients. These results suggest the mode and, site of action of Sexovid in the induction of human ovulation.
