T3  - Les tachycardies ectopiques supraventriculaires prolongees chez l'enfant (a propos de 16 observations)
A1  - Fidelle J.
A1  - Cloup M.
A1  - Nouaille J.
Y1  - 1969//
N2  - Cases of this kind will be found to be commoner than is usually believed provided they arc always sought in the presence of unusual symptoms, e.g. vomiting, dyspnea. Usually wrongly confused with myocarditis, the rhythm is variable, but is sometimes close to sinus rhythm. The ectopic focus may be cephalic, it is then confused with sinus tachycardia, or caudal when it is often undetermined. Untreated these cases go on to heart failure. With treatment, the prognosis should be good. Treatment should aim at restoring physiological frequency; eradication of the ectopic focus takes much longer; weeks or months. Digoxin seems to be the drug of choice; once the heart failure has been overcome, propranolol may restore sinus rhythm.
