T1  - Treatment of functional disturbances of the first periods at puberty
T3  - Conduite a tenir en presence des perturbations fonctionnei-les des premieres regles'. puberte nubilite
A1  - Sersiron D.
Y1  - 1969//
N2  - Before diagnosing a functional disturbance due to the absence of the corpus luteum in a girl with normal genitalia and secondary sexual characteristics, all organic causes, such as pregnancy, malformations, tumors or imperforate hymen should be excluded. The periods are then probably anovulatory. The temperature curve enables one to determine the presence or absence of a corpus luteum. Hormone assays and culdoscopy may be necessary to complete the diagnosis. Severe hemorrhage may be stopped with large doses of estrogen (at least 0.05 g by injection) followed by progesterone (0.025 g for 5 to 7 days). Progesterone alone is sufficient in the less serious cases. It is also necessary in subsequent months to avoid recurrent anovular cycles. Amenorrhea also requires periodic progesterone therapy in order to develop the endometrium without the risk of blocking ovulation (thus artificial periods are not indicated). Estrogen and progesterone given together in low dosage for 10 days may induce ovulation, which is also useful after metrorrhagia. Other considerations, such as age, morphology or possibility of supervision, may contraindicate treatment, which is best avoided when there is no definite evidence of luteal insufficiency.
