T1  - Thrombosis of the internal carotid after a single cycle of oral contraceptive treatment in the third month post partum in a woman aged 27 yr with familial hyperlipidemia
T3  - THROMROSE de la CAROTIDE INTERNE APRES UN SEUL CYCLE de CONTRACEPTIFS ORAUX au TROISIEME MOIS du 'POST PARTUM CHEZ UNE FEMME de 27 ANS PRESENTANT UNE HYPERLIPIDEMIE FAMILIALE
A1  - De Gennes J.L.
A1  - Maunand B.
A1  - Sacks M.
A1  - Truffert J.
Y1  - 1969//
N2  - A detailed study of lipids in 2 cases suggests that a sufficiently thorough analysis has for the first time provided what might be a positive contribution to this delicate problem. The detection of latent lipid anomalies of hereditarily transmitted type and not due simply to the administration of steroids may constitute one, if nut the only, 'actor predisposing tu the increased risk of thrombotic arterial accidents, particularly the involvement of cerebral arteries, in the course of treatment with anovulatory steroids. As the estimated frequency of latent lipid anomalies in the population is about 3% it is quite plausible that anovulatory steroids could cause a statistically significant increase of thrombotic episodes in this group. As lipid anomalies were demonstrated in the 2 cases reported, it is now obligatory to undertake detailed lipid analysis in all subsequent cases. It would also be advisable to investigate the blood lipids before recommending the use of anovulatory steroids in any patient. The early occurrence of thrombosis in the case reported together with anatomical evidence of thrombosis in the absence of arterial disease suggest that intra arterial thrombosis is more important than atheroma. Treatment with anovulatory steroids should not be viewed with unnecessary alarm but the precautions suggested might reduce the risk of unfortunate thrombotic accidents.
