T1  - Hormonal treatment of anovular sterility
T3  - MENOPAUSEURINGONADOTROPIN BEHANDUNG AF ANOVULATORISKE. STERILE PATIENTER
A1  - Beithelsen H.G.
Y1  - 1969//
N2  - The investigation revealed that by administering the HMG preparation in question in a dosage of 160 international FSH units for 10 days followed by choriongonadotrophin in a dosage of 6,000 international units for 4 days, it was possible to provoke ovulation in 13 out of 18 previously anovulatory patients of whom 7 became pregnant. Treatment with the dosage mentioned had no effect in 5 patients. Apart from the possibility of the dosage having been too low in the treatment of these 5 patients the lack of effect may have been due to a wrong diagnosis. It is therefore recommended at present that the investigations for selecting patients for treatment should include peritoneoscopy and gynecological laparotomy, possibly with biopsy of the ovaries to assess the state of these. The investigation also showed that the complications fall into 2 categories: multiple pregnancy and the risk of overstimulation of the ovaries and a consequent strong peritoneal reaction. These complications have been investigated and discussed by many research workers. In order to avoid these complications it is important to be able to fix the time for optimal follicle stimulation. Study of the acidophilic index by vaginal cytology and the appearance of the cervical secretion has not proved sufficiently helpful. By the introduction of Brown's rapid method of estrogen determination a more reliable assessment of the time will be possible.
