T1  - Modifications of total and fractional estrogenuria induced by clomiphcne in subjects with alterations of the menstrual cycle and with Stein Leventhal syndrome
A1  - Morresi G.
A1  - Ingrassia F.
A1  - Levi D'Ancona V.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - A total of 83 assays was performed on 11 subjects presenting various menstrual disturbances (oligomenorrhea, menometrorrhagia, etc.) and on 5 patients with Stein Leventhal syndrome, in order to evaluate the modifications in total and fractional estrogenuria induced by clomiphene. An ovulatory cycle was ascertained following treatment in all patients. Curves representing the average excretion levels for both the control period and the period immediately following the beginning of treatment were plotted and the standard deviation was calculated. The results show a similar increase of the average estrogenuria in both groups. This is determined above all during the period of treatment by a marked increase in the excretion of estrone. The amount of increase and the pattern of the curve are different however. In the case of an altered menstrual cycle where the average excretion level was rather high during the control period, the drug was able to provoke a notable rise in the curve with a peak between the 9th and the 16th days after the beginning of treatment The wide standard deviation suggests that the reaction to the drug varies according to the sensibility of the subject. The Stein Leventhal patients, who presented a flat curve and values lower than 15 ftg during the control period, presented average estrogen excretion curves with a parabolic pattern after clomiphene treatment and a peak was seen in a successive period. The difference in behavior in the Stein Leventhal cases may be due to a slow and gradual ovarian stimulation which tends to induce a sufficient fbllicular maturation. When this occurs, ovulation takes place, given the high endogenous LH levels preexisting in these cases. In cases with altered menstrual cycles, on the other hand, clomiphene easily acts on follicular maturation, finding a simpler dysmetabolic situation. For this reason the estrogenic pattern resembles that present during a normal menstruel cycle.
