T1  - A new diagnostic test in the Stein Leventhal syndrome
A1  - Zieleniowski T.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - The curves of values of 24 hr urinary excretion of 17 ketosteroids (17 KS) during the 6 days suppression test with dexamethasone were analyzed (1st day: preliminary investigations, 2nd and 3rd days: 2 mg of dexamethasone pro die were given, 4th and 5th days: 8 mg of dexamethasone pro die, 6th day: final investigations). Among different syndromes of hormonal disturbances a characteristic behavior of 17 KS in patients suspected of the Stein Ixventhal syndrome was observed. On the 4th or 5th day, after 8 mg dexamethasone administration, an increase in the 17 KS values in the urine was noticed with a characteristic elevation of the curve. In Il cases with the appearance of an inhibition curve, a wedge resection of the ovaries was performed. The diagnosis in all cases was confirmed histologically. The inhibition curves after dexamethasone showed much lower initial 17 KS values without the characteristic elevation. In order to clarify the problem, a supplementary dexamethasone test was made in 3 patients. These patients were simultaneously treated with Lyndiol 2.5 a tablet twice a day. The appearance of the inhibition curve after dexamethasone administration was then fully normalized and in 2 cases it was even similar to the curve obtained after wedge resection of ovaries. It is concluded that the characteristic elevation of 17 KS excretion during the dexamethasone suppression test is caused by gonadotropins. It is considered that in the conservative therapy of the Stein Leventhal syndrome, in addition to glucocorticoids administration, simultaneous inhibition of conadotropins is of substantial value.
