N2  - In a group of 23 females from 16-37 yr of age, androgenic function was investigated by administration of dexamethasone and chorionic gonadotropins. The study included 4 normal subits, 6 with minimal post puberal adrenogenital syndrome, 4 with associated clinical and pathological finding of Sleiu Leventiiai syndrome, 4 with hirsutism of uncertain etiology, 4 who had had oophorectomy for breast cancer, and 1 with Turners syndrome. The adrenogenital function wus assessed on the basis of the excretion of urinary 17 KS: (1) under basal conditions; and (2) during the daily administration of 3 mg. of dexamethasone during 11 days. Chorionic gonadotropins (10,(MK) units) were injected on the 5th. and 6th. day of corticosteroid intake, bringing about an increase in the excretion of 17 KS in practically all cases. The differences from the basal figures were statistically significant. In the response to gonadotropin stimulation significant differences were registered between patients with minimal post puberal adrenogenital syndrome and those with polycystic ovaries. These differences were apparent in the excretion curve of urinary 17 KS during the 6 days following the administration of gonadotropins, when the rate and persistence of the increase were analyzed.
