N2  - Investigations showed that: (1) For the Stein Leventhal Syndrome cyclic disturbance of menstruation, sterility and bilateral ovarian enlargement are characteristic. (2) The macroscopic change of the ovary is the necessary criterion for the correct diagnosis. (3) The characteristic leatures lor the morphological picture are: (a) A significant diminution of the primordial and the maturing follicles; (b) hyperplasia of the theca interna in a large number of atrestic follicles; (c) characteristic changes of the stroma which become obviousduring the growth of the collagenous fibers of the reticular connective tissue, in the focal hyperplasia of the stroma as well as in the apparent thickening of the tunica albuginea. The latter actually develops on account of the marked fibrosis of the superficial stroma. (d) the presence of vascular lumina with a thickened sclerotic wall in the tunica albuginea and in the stroma. (e) in the case of absence of fresh and regressive corpora Iutea, the fibrous bodies increase considerably. (4) No correlation could be established between the hirsutism of the patients, the luteinization of the theca cells and the presence of the paralutein, stroma Iutein cells. The latter are not characteristic of polycystic ovary which accompanies the Stein Leventhal Syndrome. (5) The histochemical examinations: the structural distribution of RNA, of the mucopolysaccharides and of glycogen indicates that in the polycystic ovary the dystrophic processes, the follicular atresia, the degeneration of the ovum and of the granulosa layer are preponderant At the same time, however, proliferation of the theca internacan be observed. For the stroma of the ovary, the accumulation of acid and neutral mucopolysaccharides is characteristic and becomes evident by the intensive growth of the connective tissue.
