T1  - Comparison of clomiphene and human gonadotrophins in failure of ovulation
A1  - Tsapoulis A.D.
A1  - Crooke A.C.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - 36 women with failure of ovulation were treated at different times with clomiphene and with human gonadotrophins. Patients with early menopause and with primary amenorrhea responded to neither form of treatment. Patients with secondary amenorrhea, no clinical evidence of estrogenic activity, and moderately increased gonadotrophins responded to gonadotrophins but rarely to clomiphene. Patients with anovular menstruation, evidence of positive estrogenic activity, and low excretion of gonadotrophins responded to gonadotrophins and, usually, to clomiphene also. The average dosage of FSH required by patients with secondary amenorrhea was 3 times greater than that required by those with anovular menstruation. The diagnosis of Stein Leventhal syndrome was not helpful in prognosis for treatment.
