Y1  - 1968//
N2  - Cytogenetic studies of cultures of peripheral blood (8 patients) and tissue taken from the polycystic ovaries (8 other patients) revealed a normal female karyotype. There was no evidence for a cryptomosaicism of the gonads. Apparently, a chromosomal anomaly, detectable with present cytogenetic methods, is not involved in the etiology. There is no evidence of a relationship between the Stein Leventhal syndrome and the gonadal dysgenesis associated with the chromosomal abnormalities. The possibility that gene defects may be involved in the Stein Leventhal syndrome is not to be excluded.
