AN  - 288074812
T1  - Anovulatory cycles
A1  - Matsumoto S.
A1  - Igarashi M.
A1  - Nagaoka Y.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - The existence of environmental amenorrhea such as war amenorrhea, emotional amenorrhea detention amenorrhea, and psychogenic amenorrhea is well established theory. However, it appears that the same environmental changes in life or psychic trauma can also induce anovulatory cycles and ovulatory oligomenorrhea (retarded ovulation). This report illustrates environmental anovulatory cycles in 16 cases, and environmental ovulatory oligomenorrhea in 2 cases. The effects of the external stress of environmental change vary with the phase of the menstrual cycle affected. If the environmental change occurs in the follicular or preovulatory phase of the cycle, ovulation is inhibited and an anovulatory cycle or ovulatory oligomenorrhea results. However, if the same environmental change occurs in the postovulatory luteal phase of the cycle, the subsequent menstrual bleeding occurs and the next ovulation is inhibited (anovulatory cycle) or delayed (ovulatory oligomenorrhea). The mechanisms of such environmental anovulatory cycles are discussed. (10,3,21).
