T1  - The treatment of ovarian insufficiency with clomifene
T3  - Die behandlung der ovarialinsuffizienz mit clomiphen
A1  - Bettendorf G.
A1  - Breckwoldt M.
A1  - Bordasch C.
A1  - Neale C.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - The clinical effect of clomifene was tested in 189 women with anovulatory ovarian insufficiency. The hyper- and hypogonadotropic forms of ovarian insufficiency did not respond to the treatment. In 69% of the women with eugonadotropic ovarian insufficiency (primary and secondary amenorrhea, anovulatory cycles), it proved possible to induce ovulation with clomifene. Another 13% responded with hemorrhage only after a monophasic evolution of the basal temperature. Spontaneous biphasic cycles occurred in 25% of the women treated. As regards the individual clinical symptoms, the following rates of success were achieved: primary amenorrhea 50%, secondary amenorrhea of more than 2 years' standing 49%, secondary amenorrhea of less than 2 years' standing 76.5%, anovulatory cycle 83%, oligomenorrhea 84.6% and Stein-Leventhal syndrome 86%. In 44% of the therapy cycles, ovulation occurred between the 11th and 15th day. A better fixation of the ovulation term could be achieved by the additional administration of chorionic gonadotrophin. In 82.5% of the cases, ovulation could be assured in the first treatment cycle. In 37% of the women who showed a positive reaction corpus luteum function was insufficient. Corpus luteum insufficiency also could be favorably affected with clomifene. The incidence of undesirable side-effects was slight: flushes (18.2%), abdominal pain (8.9%), and enlarged ovaries (10.8%). Of the anovulatory women who wanted children, 34% became pregnant, most of them during the first therapeutic cycle. Of the 42 pregnancies, 13 ended in abortion. The incidence of abortion was particularly high in women aged 28 to 41 yr. No multiple pregnancies and no malformations were seen.
