T1  - The anovulatory cycle as a cause of infertility and its treatment with clomifene
T3  - Uber den anovulatorischen zyklus als sterilitatsursache und seine behandlung mit clomiphen
A1  - Doring G.K.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - After discussing the definition and diagnosis of the anovulatory cycle, the author gives its incidence in a personal series of 1205 infertile women, as 6.9%. It ranks second in frequency among the ovarian causes of infertility. Twenty-nine women with anovulatory cycles and desiring children were treated with clomifene. The most favorable dosage was found to be 100 and 150 mg per day from day 6 to 11 of the cycle. Among 167 cycles treated, 208 were ovulatory; this means a success quota of 78%. The rise in the basal temperature curve occurred on an average 14.4 days after the start of treatment. Ten conceptions occurred in the whole series and 6 pregnancies were carried to term, including 2 twin pregnancies. Three pregnancies ended in abortion, one is now in the 5th mth. The problems arising in clomifene therapy are then discussed. An undesirable side-effect is the occurrence of ovarian cysts as an expression of ovarian overstimulation. No such cysts were seen in the author's own cases. According to comprehensive statistics on clomifene the proportion of multiple pregnancy is 10% higher than normal. On the other hand, pregnancies with more than 2 fetuses are more infrequent than after treatment with effective gonadotrophins. The comprehensive statistics showed the incidence of abortion to be higher than normal (22%). This, however, corresponds with the frequency of spontaneous abortion in successfully treated cases of infertility. The malformation-rate of 1.8% in the comprehensive statistics does not differ from the average incidence. Clomifene is contraindicated in cases of liver dysfunction and early pregnancy. Owing to the associated dangers and the need for elaborate safety and control measures, treatment of anovulatory cycles with clomifene should be restricted to clinical gynecologists with experience in endocrinology and the treatment of infertility.
