N2  - The behaviour of the urinary total neutral 17-KS and of the total 17-OHCS excretion in 10 patients with the Stein-Leventhal syndrome revealed that: Dexamethasone did not significantly depress the 17-KS absolute values because of the wide range group variation, but considering the values of the individual percent fall a significant depression was observed. The 17-OHCS were depressed with dexamethasone. H.C.G. did not significantly stimulate the depressed 17-KS when their absolute values were considered because of the wide range variation, but the values of the individual percent increase shows a significant stimulation. In the same conditions. H.C.G. did not stimulate the 17-OHCS. There was a significant linear regression of the values of the 17-KS individual percent fall over their percent increase. Interpretation of this phenomenon showed that the more the depression of the 17-KS values the greater the stimulation, the opposite occurring when there was little depression. The authors advance the hypothesis that there is a probable endogenous overstimulation in some Stein-Leventhal patients, as other investigators have already suggested, and define that phenomenon mathematically. There was no mutual relationship between the decrease or increase of the 17-KS and the 17-OHCS.
