N2  - Details are given of treatment and results in a series of cases of sterility due to ovulatory failure in order to discuss the problem of dosage, the factors involved in the production of multiple pregnancies, and the 'hyperstimulation' syndrome. Thirty-four sterile patients, of whom 16 had prolonged amenorrhea with no detectable gonadotropins in the urine, and 18 with oligomenorrhea (with or without anovulation) were treated with a combination of human menopausal gonadotropin and human chorionic gonadotropin (Humegon-Pregnyl). The total doses of HMG varied between 570 I. U. and 4,030 I. U. The total doses of HCG varied between 5,000 I. U. and 20,000 IU Most often 15,000 I. U. was used. Seventy-three courses of treatment HMG-HCG were given. Of 34 patients treated, 18 became pregnant; one patient became pregnant twice. Five of 19 pregnancies were multiple, i. e., 29%.
