N2  - One cause of involuntary infertility is an ovulation. Instances of thyroid and adrenal dysfunction should be recognized. Anovulation associated with normal endogenous estrogen levels (such as is often the case in polycystic ovary syndrome) may be treated with clomiphene citrate with a 74% incidence of ovulation and a 21% incidence of pregnancy. In cases where the estrogen levels are low or in clomiphene failures, injections of sequential menopausal-chorionic gonadotropin may induce ovulation and result in pregnancy. The major side effects of both types of therapy have been ovarian cysts. multiple pregnancy and abortion.
