T1  - Human gonadotrophins in the treatment of conjugal sterility
T3  - Le gonadotropine umane nel trattamento della sterilita coniugale
A1  - Marchesi F.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - The characteristics of human gonadotrophins obtained from the urine of women in menopause (HMG) are outlined and a personal approach to treatment of anovulation and dyspermias with such gonadotrophins is presented together with results obtained. As regards the treatment of patients with anovular cycles, a careful selection of cases is necessary in order to achieve positive results. Candidates for such therapy are those subjects in whom the gonadotrophic stimulus is deficient with a normally receptive ovary, or cases of altered peripheral receptivity to normal gonadotrophic stimuli. All functional explorations of the hypophyso-ovarian axis should be performed so as to exclude organic causes. Another interesting aspect of the problem is that of dosage. This has to be controlled throughout the treatment period by means of colpbcytology and measurement of ovarian steroids. An average dose program would be to administer an ampoule of HMG per day from the 4th to 13th days of the cycle, followed by an ampoule (2500 U) of HCG for five days. Good results were obtained in this way in 29 subjects among whom 10 pregnancies occurred. No adverse side effects due to overdosing were ever encountered, nor were there any multiple pregnancies. The use of HMG and HCG in males has given good results, almost certainly as a result of correct dosage. The following dosage program was used: daily administration for two months of an ampoule of HMG. followed during the second month by an ampoule of HCG (2500 U) every 5 days; other drugs such as vitamins E and C and arginine were used collaterally. The best results were attained in cases of moderate oligo-asthenospermia whereas there was no effect in azoospermia cases. Numerous pregnancies occurred following the improvement in the sperm situation. Undoubtedly, the introduction into therapy of human gonadotrophins represents a substantial advance in the treatment of sterility.
