T1  - Recent progress in treatment of sterility from anovulation
T3  - Recenti acquisizioni sul trattamento delle sterilita' anovulatoria
A1  - Caviezel F.
A1  - Gavazzi G.
A1  - Carraro A.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - A review is presented of the most recent developments in the treatment of anovulatory sterility. After reporting recent data on the physiology of ovulation, the most important therapeutic methods which are presently in use are dealt with. The most effective methods for the induction of ovulation are: (1) human menopausal gonadotrophins, (2) human pituitary gonadotrophins in association with human chorionic gonadotrophin, and (3) some nonhormonal compounds: clomifene citrate and F 6066. The 2 latter substances are readily available and show considerable therapeutic activity. Clomifene citrate, an antiestrogenic drug, has been shown to be particularly effective in anovulatory patients with some residual follicular function and an adequate endogeneous secretion of estrogens. Patients showing premature menopause, gonadal dysgenesis, panhypopituitarism or Sheehan's syndrome, have not responded favorably to the administration of clomifene. Clinical and experimental data suggest that the most important site of action of clomifene is in the hypothalamus: the drug stimulates the secretion of L.H. It also acts, to a lesser degree, on ovarian steroidogeaesis. The activity of F 6066, whose mechanism of action has not been completely clarified, seems to be similar to that of clomifene citrate. The compound acts, however, at a slower rate.
