T1  - The action of chlormadinone on the endometrium
T3  - La accion de la clormadinona sobre el endometrio
A1  - Airighi L.A.
A1  - Arrighi A.A.
A1  - Vivoli C.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - Experience is presented in the use of isolated Chlormadinone in 3 groups of patients treated with 4 different dosage forms. To induce secretion in estrogenic endometrium Chlormadinone was administered to 2 groups of women: (I) Patients with spontaneous anovulatory cycles: the progestational agent was administered in doses of 14 mg (1 case), 10 mg (1 case), 20 mg (3 cases) and 40 mg (1 case). The proliferative features of the endometrium were not greatly modified in the majority of cases; in 1 case the endometrium was dissociated and in another a 19th day endometrium was found. (2) Patients premeditated with Mestranol: (80 gammes on the 13th to 15th days) to proliferate the endometrium: Chlomadinone was given in dosages of 20 or 40 mg; either one or the other of the endometrial patterns corresponded to a 17th or 18th day of a normal cycle. (3) The last group of women was treated using 2 different plans of administration: (a) in the 1st, 1 mg of Chlormadinone was given from the 1st day of the cycle until the spontaneous period; biopsies were performed at the 22nd or 23rd cycle day. (b) the 2nd plan consisted of administering Chlormadinone in a dosage of 2 mg daily for 20 days, beginning from the 5th day of the cycle. The endometrial characteristics, except in 2 cases, did not agree with the stage of the cycle in which they were taken, showing complex features. In 3 cases it was imperfect and dissociated; 1 case was that of an immature progestational phase, 1 was proliferative and the remaining one was dissociated. In summary, the endometrial patterns obtained by the administration of Chlormadinone are believed to depend basically on: (1) the concomitant estrogenic stimulus and (2) the length of administration which determines the type of response achieved.
