T1  - Urinary testosterone determinations in hirsutism of women
T3  - Uber testosteronbestimmungen im urin beim hirsutismus der frau
A1  - Gobel P.
A1  - Theurer G.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - Testosterone determinations in the urine of women with hirsutism have shown that the decree of virilization depends on the nature of the enzymatic effect in the adrenal and/or ovaries, c.q. on an adrenal hyperplasia followed by a more or less enhanced production of testosterone from precursors. Such precursors are notabily present in C<ovid:inf>21</ovid:inf> hydroxylase deficiency (congenital adrenogenital syndrome), in adrenal tumors and in dehydroepiandrosterone producing adrenocortical hyperplasia. In C<ovid:sup>21</ovid:sup> hydroxylase deficiency, the excretion of testosterone is above the limits of variability of healthy male subjects, in dehydroepiandrosterone producing adrenocortical adenoma it is within the limits of normal variability and in dehydroepiandrosterone producing adrenocortical hyperplasia it is slightly below the limits of normal variability in the male. In adrenal hirsutism, the limits of normal for women were exceeded only slightly in 2 cases, and the same could be said of the Stein Leventhal syndrome. The testosterone levels in constitutional hirsutism are particularly high, a phenomenon that cannot be explained as yet. In Cushing s disease, especially in the mixed forms, the testosterone excretion is also increased, sometimes considerably. In the group with acromegaly and hirsutism, the testosterone excretion was once within the limits of normal for men and once distinctly above the limits of normal for women.
