A1  - Purola E.
A1  - Nerdrum T.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - The purpose of this study was to clarify the resumption of ovulation during the first 2 menstrual periods after abortion. The methods used were endometrial biopsy, measurement of the basal temperature and vaginal smear. The occurrence of ovulation during the first menstrual cycle could be established in only 4 (12%) of the 33 cases studied, while the cycle was anovular in 25 and the finding was uncertain in 1. Anovularity was more frequent among the patients on whom interruption of pregnancy had been performed than among those who had had spontaneous abortions. The occurrence of ovulation could be established in 15 of 27 patients who attended check up examinations on the 19th to 24th day of the second menstrual period. As regards the cycles of the remaining 12 patients, the possibility that delayed ovulation occurred cannot be confidently excluded, no data being available concerning the onset of their next menstruation.
