T1  - Distribution of some oxidative enzymes in the ovaries in Stein Leventhal syndrome
A1  - Bronshtein M.E.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - A histochemical study of the activity and distribution of 4 oxidative enzymes (3beta oxysteroid dehydrogenase, TPN and DPN diaphorases and succinodehydrogenase) was carried out in the ovaries of 17 patients operated on for Stein Leventhal syndrome. There was a distinct topographic association between the enzymes studied and the principal steroid producing structures of polycystic ovaries. A possible cause of the revealed reverse relationship between the activity of the oxidative enzymes studied and the lipid content in the corresponding cells is discussed. No deficiency of 3beta oxysteroid dehydrogenase could be revealed in the polycystic ovaries with the aid of Wattenbergs method. There is a possibility of 5 4 isomerase deficiency in the ovarian tissue of a number of patients suffering from this syndrome, leading to the formation of a surplus amount of dehydroepiandrosterone.
