T1  - The effects of wedge resection of the ovaries in 63 cases of the Stein Leventhal syndrome
A1  - Rhodes P.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - The diagnosis and treatment by wedge resection of the ovaries of the Stein Leventhal syndrome has been considered in 63 cases. The periods were restored to normal for many years in over 627% of those cases. Successful pregnancy was achieved by 67% of those complaining of infertility. Ovulation occurred in 86% of patients. Attention is drawn to the depression which may follow the operation and which may be caused by the inability to conceive. If surgery is to be abandoned in favor of medical therapy, laparoscopy must be undertaken in suspected cases to exclude other gynecological lesions. These results give a basis on which the efficacy of future medical therapy can be judged.
