AN  - 289034340
T1  - Human urinary FSH
T3  - Sull'ormone follicolo stimolante (FSH) urinario umano
A1  - Donini P.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - FSH is important in the regulation of births, either to prevent over population or to make it possible for fertile couples to have children. Insufficiency may be due to changes in the pituitary gland itself or to deficiency of releasing factors in the hypothalamus. This may lead to gonadal changes producing azoospermia or asthenospermia in the male or to amenorrhoea or anovulation in the female. Substitution therapy with gonadotrophins prepared from animal sources has given disappointing results both because of antibody reactions and because of species specificity. Attempts to synthesize human FSH have been largely unsuccessful but gonadotrophins have been extracted both from human pituitary and from the urine of post menopausal women. Other synthetic substances such as Clomid have also been widely used. The human menopausal gonadotrophin (HMG) prepared by the author and his associates in 1949 was so impure and of such low potency as to be ineffectual. The work of Gemzell (1958) with human pituitary FSH stimulated further research on HMG. Radio immunological methods of estimating dosage and the elimination of antibodies and other impurities by gel filtration with Sephadex has made possible the preparation of extracts with an FSH activity up to 800 units/mg which compares with the best of the pituitary extracts. It has also been possible to separate FSH and LH fractions by this means. Injected into prepuberal mice, the preparation of HMG containing 444 units/mg has caused increase in uterine weight. Similar lower dose preparations have apparently caused ovarian stimulation without affecting the weight of the uterus. It is hoped that further development of these substances will make possible observations of the mode of action at the cellular level.
