N2  - Rank shows that variant polycystic ovarian disease cases and carcinoma cases follow similar distributions which are significantly different from typical polycystic ovarian disease cases and controls. In the centromere index, carcinoma cases are significantly different from controls and both polycystic ovarian disease groups, while these 3 are similar. Rank versus centromere index shows no correlation. The occasional high values of the centromere index found in the typical polycystic ovarian disease cases and carcinoma support the earlier findings of truncate drumstick appendages in about the same proportion of cells from the polycystic ovarian disease cases (typical and variant groups).
