T1  - Steroid excretion in the Stein-Leventhal syndrome
A1  - Lawrence D.M.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - A study was made of urinary metabolites of androgens, pregnanediol, pregnanetriol, estrone, 17beta estradiol and estriol in 8 patients with the Stein Leventhal syndrome before and from 1 wk to 7 mth after bilateral wedge resection of the ovaries. Comparison with normal menstruating women and normal men showed that the urinary androsterone and etiocholanolone levels were raised significantly above the normal female mean and were in the male range. The 11 oxygenated 17 ketosteroids were not elevated. After operation levels of androsterone and etiocholanolone which had been significantly elevated decreased to normal, suggesting that the ovaries were the source of these androgens. There was some tendency for the 17 ketosteroids to rise again over periods of several months after the ovarian wedge resection. Urinary pregnanetriol was in the low normal range and fell 1 to 6 wk after operation. Urinary pregnanediol was in the normal female follicular range in the Stein Leventhal syndrome and in the luteal range in 1 case with a corpus luteum. Total urinary estrogen excretion was unremarkable, but from the fractions a deficiency in metabolism of estradiol and estrone to estriol was found. The conversion ratio to estriol was increased significantly 9 to 12 days after operation, although the total estrogen level was unchanged.
