T1  - Hirsutism and the Stein-Leventhal syndrome
A1  - Greenblatt R.B.
A1  - Coniff R.F.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - Hirsutism may be genetic, idiopathic, or endocrine in etiology. The genetic and endocrine aspects of hirsutism have been presented. Simple hirsutism is most often nonendocrine in nature but may be the initial manifestation of a virilizing syndrome or other endocrine disorder. When additional clinical features of virilism are present, major adrenal and gonadal disorders must be suspected. A large number of women are seen with hirsutism, menstrual disorders, and infertility, many of whom are found to have large microcystic ovaries. When this condition is present, the disease is categorized as Stein Leventhal syndrome. This syndrome, however, is clinically quite variable, and considerable confusion surrounds its pathogenesis. However, the fact that typical Stein Leventhal ovaries secrete increased amounts of androgens seems to be established beyond reasonable doubt and would explain the hirsutism. A variant of the syndrome is believed caused by increased adrenal androgens and may explain failure of wedge resection in what appears to be typical cases of the Stein Leventhal syndrome. Much remains to be explained about this interesting syndrome. It is the consensus of the authors that the microcystic disease of enlarged ovaries represents a disturbance in ovarian steroidogenesis. The ovulatory disorder may be modified favorably by improving the ratio of gonadotropins available per unit of ovarian mass. This may be accomplished by ovarian wedge resection, clomiphene treatment, or gonadotropin administration.
