N2  - With reference to 43 cases which were subjected to endocrinological examinations and operated on, the clinical picture associated with polycystic ovarian changes is discussed. The most characteristic clinical symptoms of this disease are the functional bleeding anomaly (whatever its type), sterility (primary and secondary), bilateral ovarian enlargement and the continued absence of ovulation. Hirsutism can only be regarded as a secondary, and not as a characteristic, symptom. In 50% of the cases the disease becomes manifest at the time of the menarche and in the rest it develops many years later after a normal menstrual cycle.
