T1  - The crystallization of the cervical mucus as a routine test in the diagnosis of infertility
A1  - Campos Da Paz A.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - Over a period of 17 yr, 10,409 tests for crystallization of the cervical mucus have been carried out. An analysis of the results shows that the initial findings, confirmed by other authors, are correct. Crystallization of the cervical mucus exclusively depends on the estrogens; progesterones have the specific property that they can partially or completely prevent it. This makes it possible to use the test in the majority of cases where the estrogen function and the effect of progesterone is to be examined. For the diagnosis of ovulation, 2,730 such tests were done, for instance. The results were checked by examination of endometrial biopsies, determination of the basal temperature and cytological smears, and in more than 90% of cases agreement was obtained. The rare occurrence of a corpus luteum cyst does not detract from the diagnostic value of the test, even if results are negative; the presence of pregnancy is then very likely. In threatened abortion the arborization test can indicate a hazard to pregnancy long before any clinical symptoms develop. The test was found to be valuable in the diagnosis of missed abortion and for supervision of patients treated with anovulatory drugs. There is a dose relationship between the receptivity of the cervical mucus for spermatozoa and the degree of crystallization, as shown by the agreement of the results with those of the Sims-Huhner test in 97.7% of 3,408 cases. Therefore, the arborization test is considered to be a suitable method for the diagnosis of cervical receptivity. It is also suitable for determination of the minimal dose of estrogens for treatment of cervical hostility to spermatozoa and for assessment of the results of hormonal therapy.
