AN  - 289033294
T1  - The value of synthetic progestagens in endocrine infertility
A1  - Roland M.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - Synthetic progestagens are preferable to natural progesterones for hormonal therapy, as they are up to 50 times more potent and can be administered orally. In addition they are much cheaper. The actual pharmacological effect is still not clear. Empirically there is a thermogenic effect on the basal temperature and - in combination with small doses of estrogens - inhibition of ovulation. Although side-effects are frequent they are not serious; functional disorders of the liver and kidney have not been demonstrated. Administration of some progestagens during pregnancy occasionally causes masculinization of a female neonate, even if dosage is low. Carcinogenic effects are definitely absent. There is no increased tendency to thrombophlebitis consequent to progestagen treatment. A detailed discussion is presented of progestagen therapy in patients with functional bleeding-disorders, anovulatory cycles, secondary forms of amenorrhoea and insufficient lutein phase, with reference to practice and the possible mode of action. In a small percentage of cases pregnancy can be obtained. This also applies to so-called idiopathic infertility. Detailed data are given on dysmenorrhoea, its various causes (especially endometriosis and mental changes), its relationship to infertility and temporary treatment with synthetic progestagens, which is successful in many cases. At present progestagen therapy of infertility from endocrine causes is purely empirical, although it is successful in some cases. The exact mode of action of the ovarian steroid hormones is not completely clear.
