T1  - Cytology from the urinary sample
A1  - Sturgis S.H.
A1  - Castellanos H.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - The urocytogram can be an effective diagnostic aid in the hormonal evaluation of the patient. In the hands of experienced workers, the proportion of the major types of epithelial cells washed down in a voided specimen is virtually the same as those obtained by a vaginal wall scraping. A series of urinary smears, read 'blind' and independently by 2 individuals in a laboratory, gave a mean difference of only 3.3% in cornified cell counts as evidence of the reliability of the method. The urinary smear showed the same consistency as the vaginal smear in a daily appraisal of a postmenopausal patient through a 3 mth interval. The sensitivity of the urethral mucosa to increasing doses of an estrogen in the same patient was also the same as that of the vaginal smear. The chief advantages of using the urinary sample rather than the vagina result from the method of collection, and the inclusion of a nonnucleated cell fragment as an element in the per cent findings that is only present in the voided specimen. The paurity or profusion of cells smeared on a slide from urinary sediment may give added meaning to an interpretation of the cytogram when the timing and amount of the specimen is controlled, whereas the number of cells on a vaginal smear does not always carry the same significance. The ease of collection of a morning urine makes this method acceptable and repeatable on a daily basis. It provides an appropriate way of measuring dose response to estrogenic hormones, utilizing a castrate or postmenopausal subject. The effectiveness of added progestogens in such a patient can similarly be measured. A progesterone effect with characteristics seen in the luteal phase of a normal menstrual cycle does not necessarily imply that these changes can only result after ovulation from progesterone alone. Other steroids, probably adrenal in origin, may produce the same picture. This is encountered at times in the polycystic ovary syndrome or under corticotropin administration. Adrenal corticoids, however, were found to have no direct effect on the urocytogram. This is an important point in differential diagnosis of the source of cornified cells in some patients. The use of corticoid suppression and corticotropin stimulation can be monitored daily, and even at home if desired, by the collection of morning urine samples while under therapy. The main advantages of the urinary smear are its greater availability and lack of trauma in virginal females from birth to old age, its simplicity - no instrumentation is called for - and its use in the presence of vaginal bleeding. This inclusion of the nonnucleated cell in the urocytogram report is admitted by controversial. This is, in fact, not a cell, but only an epithelial, degenerated fragment with peculiar staining properties probably due to its exposure in a urinary environment Many laboratories disregard these particles entirely as inconsequential debris. It was found helpful to include them in evaluation of the total cytological picture. In conditions of estrogen deficiency they assume a prominent proportion of all cellular elements seen. When there is a buildup of the epithelium under estrogen stimulation, then a wave of superficial and intermediate cells is washed down and the nonnucleated cells diminish proportionately. A few are always encountered in a normal urinary smear; when more then 20% of the cells seen are repeatedly of this variety, it suggests some abnormality affecting ovarian steroid production. In conclusion, the urinary smear as a diagnostic tool is widely applicable and acceptable; it is as sensitive as the vaginal smear and more easily obtained in many situations where a series of tests are indicated in a continuing survey of an endocrine problem in the female.
