A1  - Sturgis S.H.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - The first phase of this study was an attempt to determine the number of treatment days (pill days) required to suppress ovulation. By progressively increasing the number of pill days prior to the estimated day of ovulation in each subsequent treatment cycle, the authors hoped to obtain some indication of the number of pill days required to suppress ovulation. The increase in pregnanediol levels in the postovulatory phase and the presence of an LH midcycle peak were the parameters chosen to monitor ovulation. The LH midcycle peak offers a fair estimate of the date of ovulation. In 1959, Taymor demonstrated a correlation between LH excretion and actual ovulation, as determined by corpus luteum biopsy. In this study of the dating of ovulation by corpus luteum histology, LH excretion was found to precede ovulation by 12-36 hr, and in the majority of cases by 24 hr. The mechanism by which estrogen-progesterone combinations prevent ovulation has been shown to be associated with a suppression of the LH midcycle peak. The authors found that at least 3 days of pills were necessary subsequently to suppress ovulation. It is evident that such a limited number of cycles precludes the possibility of a definite conclusion. In the second phase of this study, the effect of ethynodiol diacetate 1 mg and mestranol 0.1 mg, given daily from Days 15 to 25, on ovulation and irregular cycle lengths was analyzed. A satisfactory control of irregular cycles was achieved by this regimen. A majority of cycles were limited to 27-28 days. Suppression of ovulation was achieved in two-thirds of all treatment cycles as compared to the control cycles, which were found to be anovulatory in only a third of the cases. The discrepancy in the ovulatory rates of control and treatment cycles is probably due to the fact that a number of ovulations destined to occur late in these irregular cycles have been suppressed. Furthermore, the decrease in the incidence of ovulation indicates that ovulation is not made' to occur prior to therapy. Of the 21 ovulations that occurred in 60 treatment cycles, a third of these were -breakthrough*, occurring during the first 3 or 4 days of the drug treatment period. This again implies that ovulation cannot be forced to occur prior to therapy. Instead, it seems that ovulation will occur with the same degree of variability as before, up to a limited extent. From this data, this limit, beyond which ovulation will not occur with this treatment schedule, is Cycle Day 19 or after 4 days of pills. This is supported by the fact that no breakthrough ovulation occurred beyond Day 19 when therapy was administered from Cycle Days 16 to 25. The evidence gathered from both phases of the study seems to imply that at least 3-4 days of ethynodiol diacetate 1 mg and mestranol 0.1 mg is necessary to suppress ovulation. It would seem reasonable then, to expect a decrease in the number of accidental pregnancies in women on such a regimen if abstinence is practiced up to the 4th day of starting the pills. The onset of abstinence will have to be determined arbitrarily. A reasonable day to commence abstinence, based on the experience of other investigators, is Cycle Day 10. A contraceptive regimen using such pills from Day 16 to Day 25 would necessitate a 10day period of abstinence, from Days 10 to 19, to effect a better protection rate than that often achieved by the rhythm method. A shorter abstinence period could probably be scheduled if treatment was started 2 or 3 days earlier.
