T1  - Suppression of testosterone and androstenedione production rates with dexamethasone in women with idiopathic hirsutism and polycystic ovaries
A1  - Bardin C.W.
A1  - Hembree W.C.
A1  - Lipsett M.B.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - Testosterone and androstenedione plasma levels were measured (isotope dilution) in 7 normal women and 22 hirsute women with either idiopathic hirsutism (IH) or polycystic ovaries (PCO). During dexamethasone administration, plasma testosterone decreased 25% in normal subjects and 40 to 50% in the patients with IH and PCO. Plasma androstenedione levels were suppressed 40 to 55% in the normal and hirsute women. The mean testosterone metabolic clearance rate for 8 hirsute women increased 10% during dexamethasone administration but there was no significant change in the androstenedione metabolic clearance. The decrease in blood androgen levels produced by glucocorticoid was a consequence of decreased androgen production. These studies indicate that a gland which is suppressed by dexamethasone is responsible for a significant fraction of the excess androgen production in women with either IH or PCO.
