T1  - The urinary excretion of the 17 hydroxycorticosteroids and of the 17 ketosteroids in some dynamic functional tests in simple obesity, idiopathic hirsutism, and ovarian polycystosis
A1  - Lodeserto A.
A1  - Reschini E.
A1  - Giustina G.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - In 3 groups of females with simple obesity, idiopathic hirsutism and polycystic ovaries, measurements were performed, on the daily urinary elimination of 17 hydroxycorticoids and 17 ketosteroids, both in baric conditions and following administration of dexamethasone, synthetic estrogens plus dexamethasone, ACTH, and methapyrone with the objective of ascertaining which of the tests is most suitable to distinguish these 3 clinical pictures. The dexamethasone test (2 mg for 2 days and 8 mg for 2 days) was shown to be conclusive. In polycystic ovaries the urinary elimination of 17 KS (and often also of the 17 OHCS) is greater than that observed in simple obesity and in idiopathic hirsutism. A rapid screening test of sufficient reliability was shown to be the measurement of 17 KS elimination prior to and following administration of 2 mg dexamethasone per day for only 2 days. The amount of urinary 17 KS persisting in polycystic ovaries following inhibition with dexamethasone could not be depressed in all cases by the addition of estrogens in the test of adrenal ovarian inhibition, which did not prove significant. Measurements of urinary 17 OHCS and 17 KS following administration of ACTH and methapyrone have less value in distinguishing these pathologic types. As to the possible separation of simple obesity, polycystic ovaries and idiopathic hirsutism from Cushing's disease with bilateral adrenal hyperplasia, the inhibition tests generally proved reliable. In 2 cases, however, the response was equivocal.
