T1  - In vitro researches on the formation of steroid hormones in the corpus luteum, stroma, hilus and follicles of the normal human ovary
T3  - In vitro-versuche zur steroidhormonbildung im corpus luteum, stroma, hllus und in den follikeln des normalen menschlichen ovars
A1  - Lisse K.
A1  - Schurenkamper P.
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - A study was made of the production of steroid hormones after incubation with pregnenolone 4 C<ovid:sup>14</ovid:sup> as the substrate in a pair of ovaries on the 25th day of the cycle and in a single ovary on the 18th day of the cycle. The ovary of the pair that contained corpus luteum was divided into corpus luteum, follicles, stroma and hilus, and the single ovary into corpus luteum, cortex and medullary substance, all of which were incubated separately. Quantitative comparison of the metabolites in the individual components and comparison with the biosynthesis in the complete ovary revealed a tissue specific predilection of the biosynthetic pathways: the corpus luteum produces <ovid:sup>4</ovid:sup> 3 keto metabolites, especially progesterone and 17alpha hydroxyprogesterone. On the other hand, a considerable enrichment of androgens was found in the accessory follicles. It appears that the production of androgens takes place largely via the <ovid:sup>5</ovid:sup> 3beta hydroxy metabolites. The metabolites are produced in approximately the same quantitative proportions in the stroma and in the hilus as in the follicles. A relatively higher estrogen yield and leaser androgen enrichment were found in the whole ovary. Where the steroid hormone production is concerned, the ovary without an active corpus luteum on the 25th day of the cycle behaves like the cortex and the medullary substance, with a particular enrichment of 17alpha hydroxy pregnenolone and DHA (= <ovid:sup>5</ovid:sup> androsten 3beta ol 17 one). This finding constitutes an argument in favor of a preferred metabolic route via the <ovid:sup>5</ovid:sup> 3beta hydroxy metabolites. On the basis of these findings it may be postulated that the enhanced production of androgens in the Stein Leventhal syndrome may be due exclusively to a quantitative increase of the follicular tissue. From a comparative study of the ovarian tissues incubated separately and in association, it can be concluded that the corpus luteum contains sufficient aromatizing enzymes, but only very little enzymes that split off side chains. The accessory follicles, on the other hand, contain sufficient enzymes splitting off lateral chains, but only very few aromatizing enzymes.
