N2  - Neopergonal. A preparation containing mainly FSH, was administered daily to 19 women with amenorrhoea or anovulatory cycles. 24 courses of treatment were given. As soon as the ovary was sufficiently stimulated, ovulation was elicited by injection of 2000 IU of HCG repeated 48 hours later. Four pregnancies were obtained including one twin pregnancy and in 13 cycles of treatment ovulation probably occurred without any serious side-effects being noted. Repeated routine estimations of urinary steroid and plasma oestrogen levels enabled the authors to confirm the variability of the individual response, and a urinary excretion of pregnanediol and oestrogen constantly higher than that noted during normal menstrual cycles. Furthermore, the authors have demonstrated an important though transient rise in plasma oestradiol reaching a maximum 4 to 6 days before ovulation, appearing much earlier than the maximum increase in urinary oestrogen.
