T1  - The dangers of hyperstimulation of the ovaries with clomiphene and gonadotropins to induce ovulation
T3  - Gefahren der ovariellen uberstimulierung bei anwendung von clomiphen und gonadotropinen zur ovulationsauslosung
A1  - Hammerstein J.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - The author reports 13 cases of mild, moderately severe and severe overstimulation of the ovaries in 1/4 of all the cases treated for anovulation with clomiphene, human menopausal gonadotropin/ human chorionic gonadotropin (HMG/HCG) and sheep hypophyseal gonadotropin/HCG (SHG/HCG). Treatment with modern ovulatory drugs is dangerous. After treatment with HMG/HCG. 1 case developed an acute and dangerous Meigs' syndrome, which subsided after abdominal paracentesis. Another patient required laparotomy because of torsion of an ovarian cyst the size of a coconut after therapy with very low doses of clomiphene. Two patients had severe and 4 patients mild abdominal reaction with concomitant development of ovarian cysts between the size of a mandarin orange and a tennis ball. In the remaining 5 cases the ovaries enlarged to between the size of a hen's egg and a mandarin orange without abdominal discomfort. The worst complications developed in early pregnancy shortly after nidation of the ovum. The likely cause is the effect of the trophoblastic HCG on the ovaries primed and sensitized by the ovulatory stimulants. Serial hormonal tests support this idea. During severe hyperstimulation the daily estrogen excretion rose to 1,000-2,800 micrograms and the pregnandiol excretion to 35-38 mg. There are indications that the almost constant concomitant increase in 17-ketosteroid and 17-ketogenic steroid excretion also has an ovarian origin. There is no satisfactory explanation for the frequent discrepancies between the tissue and hormonal reaction in the hyper stimulation syndrome. Retrospective evaluation of the endocrine baseline makes it possible to recognize signs which predispose to hyperstimulation: (1) high basal excretion of 17-ketosteroids increasing after giving metopyrone; (2) a pathological dexamethasone-HCG test; (3) enlarged polycystic ovaries; (4) ovaries of normal size with thickened tunica albuginea and no signs of ovulation. Guidelines to reduce the risk of treatment with ovulatory stimulants are proposed.
