T1  - Thrombosis of the internal carotid artery following a single cycle of oral contraceptives in the third month post partum in a 27-year-old female presenting familial hyperlipemia
T3  - Thrombose de la carotide interne apres un seul cycle de contraceptif oraux au troisieme mois du post partum chez une femme de 27 ans presentant une hyperlipidemie familiale
A1  - De Gennee J.L.
A1  - Maunand B.
A1  - Sacks M.
A1  - Truffert J.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - The present observation, together with the case presented in the preceding abstract in which an equally extensive study of the blood lipids was conducted, appear to be the only 2 cases in which it has been attempted to define the predisposing role of a latent and hereditary anomaly of the circulating lipide in the occurrence of thrombotic and especially cerebrovascular accidents during treatment with anovulatory steroids. As at present the incidence of latent lipid anomalies of genotypic origin is estimated to be 3% of the general population, it is plausible and certainly worth of consideration that in a population selected according to this criterium anovulatory steroids may with statistically significant frequency facilitate the often astonishingly rapid occurrence of such accidents. Furthermore, the rapidity of development of the process so well illustrated by the present and other cases tempt one to ascribe the arterial occlusion to a process of intravascular coagulation where the interference of certain lipid anomalies cannot be ruled out rather than to a process of parietal lipoid infiltration. Confirmation of this concept might be found in certain anatomic data. This novel view of the problem resulting from the present findings has the advantage of not blindly challenging treatment with anovulatory steroids as a whole but of envisaging the possible danger of associating hormonal treatments with a latent predisposition to this kind of accidents, present in the form of a hereditary anomaly of the blood lipide. Every new accident of this type will from now on undoubtedly require analogous studies which are highly advisable prior to the initiation of a treatment with anovulatory steroids.
