T1  - New data on the endocrine function of gonads. New biochemical diagnosis methods by dynamic exploring tests. Pathogeny of polycystic ovaries
T3  - Donnees nouvelles sur les fonctions endocriniennes des gonades. Nouvelles methodes de diagnostic biochimique par les epreuves d'exploration dynamique. Pathogenie des ovaires polykystiques
A1  - Jayle M.F.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - This general review is concerned with different, aspects of the physiopathology, diagnosis and treatment of polycystic ovaries. The role of the hypothalamo-pituitary system and that of biochemical lesions of the ovary shown after incubation in vitro are successively considered. The nature, the production rate of the androgens and their concentration in the ovarian vein and peripheral plasma are investigated. The values of plasmatic and urinary testosterone levels, before and after ACTH and HCG stimulation are determined in polycystic ovary patients and compared with the figures obtained in normal healthy women and men. The diagnosis of the different forms of polycystic ovary is established by using 2 standardized tests, where dexamethasone cortico-adrenal suppression is associated with ovary HCG stimulation. They concern the luteal phase of the menstrual cycle, spaniomenorrhea and anovulatory amenorrhea. The results obtained with sequential treatment HMG (or HPG)-HCG are studied by comparing polycystic and normal ovaries. The different tests of suppression by corticosteroids by estrogens associated or not with synthetic gestagens are discussed. The importance of HCG-dexamethaaone dynamic exploration and estrogen dosage is stressed; they both make a sequential stimulation of sterility possible in order to diminish the accident hazards. Finally, the medical treatment of polycystic ovaries by antiovulatory drugs is discussed.
