T1  - The pathologist and the ovaries of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome
T3  - L'anatomo-pathologiste devant les ovaires du syndrome de Stein-Leventhal
A1  - De Brux J.
A1  - Gerber E.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - If in a number of cases the answer may be precise, more often, because of lack of sufficient material or of complete clinical and biologic notions, it is evasive or limited. Numerous varieties of dystrophic ovaries (so-called stenoid or polycystic ovaries, hyperthecosis) lead to the discussion of the differential diagnosis of the steinian histologic syndrome. Some histologic features, although very typical of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome, are as a rule, not considered as pathognomonic. It is precisely such facts that, in the clinical as well as in the morphologic relations with the neighboring syndromes, allow the Stein-Leventhal to open the way to a better understanding of ovarian dysfunction. On the basis of precise embryologic notions. the Stein-Leventhal syndrome may be compared to a particular ovarian dystrophy that responds to a disorder in the receptivity of the gland. All depends on the stage at which the pituitary stimulus on the ovaries is stopped: to very developed follicles a polycystic ovary responds; if the follicles are stopped at the beginning of their growth, the thecal cells are integrated into the stroma that turns hyperplastic.
