T1  - The Stein-Leventhal disease
T3  - La maladie de Stein-Leventhal
A1  - Netter A.
A1  - Thoret Y.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - This is a clinically original disease easily recognized when typical: extreme and progressive oligomenorrhea independent of any psychologic factor, always primary and constant sterility, luteal insufficiency, hypertrophic, indolent and hard ovaries. On the other hand, the frontiers of the same are ill-defined: on the one hand some gonadal dysgenesis, on the other hand the common sclerocystic ovarian dystrophy. The ovaries have a regular and uniform thickness, are deprived of corpora albicantia and filled up with primordial follicles. Thecal hyperplasia is neither constant nor characteristic. Such ovaries are unable to form a corpus luteum; they may or may not se-crete an excess of male hormone; under the influence of HCG, the androgenic secretion is evident. In the absence of treatment, the syndrome remains stationary and becomes aggravated. The steinian ovary may ovulate under the influence of human gonadotropins and of clomifene; however, there is a danger of monstrous cysts that may rupture. The wedge resection of the ovaries is the elective procedure that has to be limited only to women anxious to have children under the condition of the absence of any other factor of sterility. Multiparity is rare while, sooner or later, there is a relapse of the disease in about half the cases.
