T1  - Study of the effect of experimentally induced endocrine insults upon pregnant and nonpregnant ewes. III. ACTH and propylthiouracil administration and the production of polycystic ovaries
A1  - Nesbitt Jr. R.E.L.
A1  - Abdul-Karim R.W.
A1  - Prior J.T.
A1  - Shelley T.F.
A1  - Rourke J.E.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - It has been demonstrated for the first time in the ewe that a propylthiouracil-induced hypothyroid state results in an ensemble of morphologic changes in the ovaries and in various hormonally responsive tissues, changes strikingly similar to those noted in the Stein-Leventhal syndrome observed in the human. The presence of endometrial hyperplasia, alveolar duct proliferation in the breasts, smooth-muscle hypertrophy in the uterine wall and arterioles, and myometrial condensations resembling focal leiomyomata suggested prolonged, unremitting estrogen stimulation, features often encountered in the human counterpart. Adrenal steroid excretion was not greatly altered, although the daily output of 17-KG steroids was slightly elevated at one stage during propylthiouracil therapy. The adrenal glands were slightly enlarged but no structural changes were observed in response to the antithyroid medication. The PBI was suppressed but serum levels of total cholesterol and total lipids were unaltered. The simultaneous adminis-tration of ACTH to propylthiouracil-treated animals had a modifying effect upon these organ response although, in the ovary, many of the features seen in the animals treated only with propylthiouracil were produced. The distinguishing feature was the numerous atretic and hyalinized follicles observed in the animals subjected to combined treatment.
