T1  - Clomiphene citrate: its effect in some ovulatory defects
A1  - Goidfarb A.F.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - A nonsteroidal estrogen antagonist, clomiphene citrate, has proved to be of great value in the management of various ovulatory defects in the human. Its success is dependent upon the proper selection of the patient for therapy. The patient should have an intact pituitary and good endogenous estrogen production. The mechanism of action of this drug is not completely understood, but it appears primarily to increase pituitary gonadotropin release and sensitize the ovaries to endogenous gonadotropin stimulation. Ovarian cyst formation is the major side effect. Pregnancy associated with clomiphene therapy has a high incidence of multiple pregnancies. The drug is not a panacea for the anovulatory state and failures do occur with therapy. (10, 21).
