T1  - Induction of ovulation with human postmenopausal gonadotropin. iii. effect of varying dosage schedules on estrogen and pregnanediol excretion levels
A1  - Taymor M.L.
A1  - Sturgis S.H.
A1  - Goldstein D.P.
A1  - Lieberman B.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - This study is concerned with the induction of ovulation and subsequent pregnancy in amenorrheic and anovulatory females, human post-menopausal gonadotropin (HiMG) and human chorionic gonadotropin (HCG) being employed sequentially. An attempt was made to determine whether there was a relationship between high estrogen and pregnanediol excretion levels and the development of marked ovarian enlargement following the administration of HMG and HCG. Incidentally the effect of various dosage schedules was also studied and their relationship to the excretion levels of estrogen and pregnanediol. It is felt from observations that it is best to start HMG therapy with less than the maximum dosage. It is suggested that a stepdown pattern that continues 1 or 2 days after the 1st day of 3+ferning might be utilized initially. The amount and administration of HMG can gradually be increased in subsequent cycles; with this approach ovarian over stimulation would be reduced.
