T1  - Histological modifications of the endometrium produced by certain natural and synthetic sex steroids and intrauterine devices used for control of female fertility -
T3  - Modificaciones histologicas del endometrio causadas por algunos esteroides sexuales naturales y sinteticos, y el anillo intrauterino, usados para controlar la fertilidad en la mujer -
A1  - Rosenberg D.
A1  - Zanarzu J.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - The increasing use of synthetic estrogens and progestogens in the therapy of certain endocrine-gynecological conditions in human fertility control, as well as the use of intrauterine devices, necessitates clinicians and pathologists to have adequate knowledge as to the actions of these agents upon the human reproductive system. The effects of synthetic sex steroids and Zipper's intrauterine device on the endometrium, have been studied in 750 young, fertile and healthy women, by means of 1.301 endometrial biopsies performed before, during and after the use of these methods for fertility control or correction of functional endocrine-gynecological pathology. Natural or synthetic estrogens, when given in ovulation-inhibiting doses, prevent the formation of the corpus luteum and secretion of endogenous progesterone. Under these conditions, a proliferative (estrogenic) endometrium is observed throughout the cycle. The continuous use of estrogens produces, within a brief period of time, cystic hyperplasia of the endometrium. Cyclic use of estrogens for ovulation-inhibition also induces cystic hyperplasia after a few months. Progesterone and synthetic progestogens have fertility-inhibiting properties, when used at proper dosage. At such levels, antiestrogenic actions are evident on the vaginal epithelium cornification: secretion and receptibility of cervical mucus to spermatozoa, endometrial growth, etc. Synthetic progestogens are biologically more active. Long-acting injectable progestogens (Depo-medroxy progesterone; Norethysterone enanthate) induce a resting condition of the endometrium, and regression of its glands. These modifications are directly related to dosage.Norethysterone enanthate produces a less marked effect on endometrial regression and inactivity, possibly because it is metabolized as estrogen. Oral, continuous 0.5 mg chlormadinone acetate, does not inhibit ovulation, allowing endogenous ovarian hormone action at the endometrial level. Its fertility inhibiting effect, apparently results, from cervical mucus hostile to spermatozoa. Endometrium histology in this condition, is similar to that of an ovulatory ovarian cycle. In some patients, however, the antiestrogenic effect of the compound is more evident (endometrium glandular regression) at this low dosage. 'Combined1 therapy with estrogens and progestogens, inhibit ovulation and endogenous progesterone secretion. If its use starts on day 5 of the menstrual cycle, precocious progestational changes are seen in the endometrium, as early as day 8 or 9 of the treated cy-'e. Regression of the glands and endometrial inactivity are evident later. At the end of the treated cycle, the glands are small and exhausted. If on the 'combined1 formula, the ftmount of progestogens is reduced, no predecidual reaction is seen, and a more edematoue etroma is observed. 'Sequential' therapy with estrogens and progestogens, usually inhibits ovulation and the production of endogenous progesterone. During the period of time when estrogens alone are given (10-15 days of the treated cycle) proliferative endometrium is obtained. With the addition of a potent progestogen during the remaining 11 to 5 days, until 21 days of therapy are completed, progestational changes develop. However, full progestational maturation of the endometrium is not induced: at the end of the treated cycle, the endometrial pattern resembles that of day 19 to 20 of a nontreated, ovulatory, 28 days cycle. All the endometrial modifications caused by estrogens or progestogens alone or associated with estrogens ('combined1 and 'sequential1 therapy) are reversible. They rapidly disappear, when therapy is discontinued. Reestablishment of normal ovarian function and ovulation is.the rule, without damage to the endometrium. lntrauterine nylon contraceptive devices do not apparently significantly change ovarian morphophysiology, since they do not interfere with gonadal function in women The endometrial histology is similar to what is observed during a normal, ovulatory, nontreated ovarian cycle. However, in 16% of subjects studied a proliferative (estrogenic) endometrium at the premenstrual period was found, as is usually seen in anovulatory cycles. The possibility that the IUD may interfere with ovarian physiology in certain subjects, should be investigated. Inflammatory reaction has been described at the endometrial level in IUD users, without clinical signs., Furthermore, the device causes local edema and pressure on the endometrium with focal or diffuse inflammatory reaction. In 10.5% of subjects, inflammatory reaction without signs of pelvic inflammatory disease was observed. The endometrial histology findings have failed to show permanent damage or pathology to be related to the use of steroids alone or combined, or to Zipper's nylon intrauterine device. Fibrosis, permanent atrophy, polyps or carcinoma were not induced in users of these methods, within the observation period (up to 3 yr).
