T1  - On the significance of an endometrium evaluation in the diagnosis of sterility -
T3  - Uber den Wert der Endometriumbeurteilung in der Sterilita tsdiagnostik -
A1  - Lubke F.
A1  - Staffeldt K.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - In 155 women with primary and secondary sterility, the authors examined 176 specimens of endometria obtained by diagnostic curettage with the object of determining the incidence of pathologic findings which are independent from the cycle. They also investigated, whether deviations in the functional maturation havetobe discussed as causes of sterility. Non-functional pathologic changes in the sense of an unspecific or specific endometritis were found only in 3 women in whom a tubal sterility was present in addition. The findings in the endometrium which depend on the cycle were correlated with the basal body temperature curve, the cervical factors and the karyopyknosis index as in-dicators of hormonal activity. As far as the ripening stage IE concerned, the specimens of endometria obtained in the proliferative phase corresponded to the day of the cylcle. Among to basal body temperature curves with a monophasic courbe, a secretory transformation of the endometrium was found in 4 instances and an anovulatory cycle in 6 instances. Of the 130 specimens of endometria obtained in the corpus luteum phase, 24 showed deviations in the ripening stage. In 12 endometria, the ripening process was found to be retarded and in 2 endometria it proved to be advanced. Kight ondometria revealed a discordant development of glands and stroma and 2 endometria showed histochemical alterations. The pregnancies which occurred in these women later on, in some cases without therapy, led to the conclusion that these changes which are looked upon by ut, a 'functional' deviations do not seem to be of appreciable significance as causes of sterility.
