T1  - Hormonal treatment of female sterility
T3  - Le traitement hormonal de la sterilite feminine
A1  - Stamm O.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - Endocrine dysfunction is a major factor among the causes of sterility. These anomalies can be provoked by 6 different hormonal substances, each of which can be secreted in insufficient or excessive amounts. This leads to a great variety of glandular dysfunctions, each of which may disturb the fragile balance necessary to ensure ovulation. The differential diagnosis of the multiple hormonal dysfunctions is complicated by the fact that of the 6 hormonal factors involved only 2 can be determined quantitatively. Data on the endocrine causes are therefore limited by the great number of the etiologic factors and the insufficiency of diagnostic techniques. Despite this unsatisfactory state of affaire great therapeutic progress has been made in the past 9 yr by the introduction of human pituitary gonadotropins, nonsteroid estrogens and progesteroids and retrosteroids. A new therapeutic era appears to have begun. Great progress may be expected in the treatment of sterility from anovulation and secretory insufficiency.
