T1  - The indications, potentialities and dosage of follotropin (Pergonal) and clomifene in the treatment of the secondary amenorrheas
T3  - Indicaciones, posibilidades y posologia del pergonal y del clomifeno en el tratamiento de las amenorreas secundarias
A1  - Inguiula W.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - From his experience to date the author has gained the impression that follotropin given in a single dose may succeed when fractional treatment has failed. This fact raises the question of the timing of doses. If the recent work on the excretion of FSH confirms the author's findings that there is a rise in this hormone during menstruation, the single-dose method of giving follotropin treatment will require wider application. Normo-gonadotropinuria may mask either a hypothalamic insufficiency, which can be corrected by the use of Clomifene, or an anatomical deficiency of the hypophysis, which expresses its maximal capacity to react by a normal level of gonadotropic secretion. In such cases substitution therapy may be the most logical measure. In the usual gonadotropic amenorrheae there remains still another possibility, namely, a disorder in ovarian biosynthesis with a hold-up of ovulation and the production of metabolites, capable of obstructing the feed-back mechanism. In these cases a single dose of follotropin acting as a massive stimulus, may break down the block and so start ovulation, which does not require any further administration of luteal hormone. Thus, while maintaining the position which he explained elsewhere with regard to the indications for these 2 compounds, the author comes to the following conclusions: (1) Clomifene may be useful in normogonadotropic amenorrheas, in the rare cases of hypogonadotropinuria due to hypothalamic deficiency and, on principle, in all cases of Stein-Leventhal syndrome. (2) Clomifene is ineffective in cases of hyper-gonadotropinuria; (3) There are sound reasons for giving follotropin in a single dose; if this is adopted as the standard posology it will be possible to find the effective dose for each case, while avoiding over-dosage; (4) The efficacy of follotropin is more evident in hypophysial deficit due to anatomical causes, with consequent hypogonadotropinuria, but may also be shown in cases of normo-gonadotropinuria which are the expression of a latent hypophysial deficiency, and also in hyper-gonadotropinurias in which an ovarian response is still possible if only after massive stimulation; (5) In some cases, the action of follotropin may consist in correcting some special enzyme deficiency which is the determining factor of the amenorrhea; (6) In all cases with normo- or hypo-gonadotropinuria in which follotropin fails, the suspicion arises that the dose was insufficient; this also applies to Clomifene, though with this compound there is a toxicological limit which is not found with follotropin.
