T1  - The sclerocystic ovary syndrome
A1  - Pildes R.B.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - Over a monthly period F. S. H. is normal whereas LH excretion is elevated. Delta 5 pregnanetriol in equally elevated. The finding of pregnanetriolone suggests that there is either an abnormality in the adrenal cortex similar to that suggested in adrenal hyperplasia, that the polycystic ovary has a II-hydroxylase, or that abnormal ovarian steroid synthesis secondarily causes disturbances in adrenal cortical synthesis. Stimulation studies with FSH cause marked ovarian enlargement in these patients so that it may be used as a diagnostic test: in addition increases have been found in estrogens, 17 ketosteroids, pregnanetriol, and delta 5 pregnanetriol. Suppression with dexamethasone results in increased total estrogens, total gonadotropin and reduction of 17 ketosteroids. Plasma testosterone follows the same pattern. Several theories are proposed to explain the abnormal biosynthesis in these ovaries. Before treatment by wedge resection is decided upon, therapy with dexamethasone suppression should be tried, at an initial dose of 3 mg per day for 5 days and then a maintenance dose of 0.5 mg per day for 6 to 12 months. Surgery should be reserved for infertile women or for unmarried women in the late thirties. Clomiphene gave interesting results with 17 ovulating patients out of 25, but when large cysts are forming the dosage should be lowered. Hirsutism was not significantly improved. The so called borderline adreno-genital syndrome responds equally well to corticoid treatment.
