AN  - 288089390
T1  - The dynamic exploration of the gonads by the chorionic gonadotropins under inhibitory dexamethazone
T3  - Exploration dynamique des gonades par les gonadotropines chorioniques sous freinage par la dexamethasone
A1  - Jayle M.-F.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - Two tests of stimulation of the ovaries by chorionic gonadotropin (HCG) in the presence of dexamethazone have been suggested by the author. One of these tests, lasting 6 days, commences at the beginning of the luteal phase and stimulates to the maximum the cyclic corpus luteum, which becomes as active as the corpus luteum at the beginning of pregnancy. By comparing, before and after the stimulation test, the urinary hormonal excretions, assayed by rapid chromatography techniques, it is possible to define several forms of ovarian hyperplasia in the luteal phase: a total hyperplasia with increase in the volume of the ovaries and of the secretion of the estrogens, of pregnanetriol and of the androsterone + etiocholanolone fraction. Two rarer forms are also encountered, namely, essential hyperestrogenia and isolated hyperluteinia. Hyperestrogenia and hyperandrogenia are frequently associated. Contrary to the classical opinion, hyperestrogenia is almost never found in the premenstrual syndrome. Glandulo-cystic transformation of the endometrium is produced in the majority of cases by a weak but uninterrupted secretion of estrogens, without the intervention of progesterone. It is therefore the absence of ovulation and of the corpus luteum which is by far the most important cause of this transformation in the endometrium. In the category of the amenorrheas no cases of hyperestrogenia are observed and the majority of the responses are of the hypoestrogenic type. The other stimulation test which lasts 8 days is done outside the luteal phase in order to explore the androgen function of the ovary. An increase of the ovarian androgens by stimulation of HCG is a specific character of ovarian hyperandrogenia. In Stein-Leventhal's disease, the ovaries secrete weak androgens. Aside from this affection, ovular cycles are encountered in which the HCG-dexamethazone test shows a hyperandrogenia which is often associated with a hyperestrogenia. Ovarian hyperandrogenia is not in itself a cause of sterility, nor of repeated abortions; it is only responsible for the fibrous transformation enclosing the ovary in a rigid shell which mechanically resists ovulation. The treatment is surgical. 89% of women presenting a polycystic transformation of the ovaries, which affects the three endocrine functions, suffer from sterility or from repeated abortions. In this form of total hyperplasia of the ovaries, the treatment is not surgical, but medical. It consists in instituting a blockage of the ovaries, preferably of a sequential nature, for a long period until the size of the ovaries and their endocrine activity have returned to normal.
