T1  - A study of the animal ovary. Some comparisons with the human ovary
A1  - Uyttenbroeck F.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - Part I of this monograph (pages 7-104) deals with the normal mammalian ovary. An attempt was made to study at least 1 species from as many orders of this class of animals. Photographic documentation is presented of the cyclic changes in some species for which no extensive material had previously been published. The author describes the findings in the rat, coypu, guineapig, dog, sheep, goat, horse and the primates. The effect of age on ovarian structure, atresia, luteinization, the corpus luteum and the interstitial tissue are described, and comparisons are drawn with the human ovary. Part II deals with 180 spontaneous ovarian tumors in animals studied in the Armed Forces Institute of Pathology. Washington, D.C. Of these tumors, 85 occurred in dogs, 40 in cows, 7 in horses, 1 in a lion, 12 in cats, 11 in rats. 1 in a ferret and 23 in birds. The tumors most commonly seen were granulosa-cell tumors, primary carcinomata, tumors of the covering epithelium, primary or secondary tumors of nonintrinsic connective tissue and a few metastatic tumors. One hilar-cell tumor and 1 Krukenberg tumor are also described. The author compares some of these tumors with human ovarian tumors. Granulosa-cell tumors, especially those with a Sertoli-like pattern, are discussed in particular. It is postulated that Lecene's 'folliculome lipidique' is a luteinized granulosa-cell tumor. As to tumors of the covering epithelium, special emphasis is placed on similarities between animal and human tumors in terms of the histological transition from benign, via low-grade malignant, to distinctly malignant. The histopathogenesis of mesonephromata is discussed on the basis, of a series of tumor in this category. This study disclosed no histological features which might suggest the possibility of a Stein-Cohen-Leventhal syndrome in animals. The limited literature on animal tumors is reviewed. There are 205 illustrations.
