AN  - 288089144
T1  - Management of infertility
A1  - Davis M.E.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - Ten per cent of marriages remain sterile and a further 10% get no further than repeated miscarriages. Half the fertile partners achieve pregnancy within 1 mth, and 75% within 6 mth. For these reasons sterile married partners, of whom the woman is under 30 yr of age, should be examined after 1 yr, if the woman is older, after 6 mth. This examination is best done in the first instance by the general practitioner, who is probably best acquainted with the sexual relationships of the couple. The man and the woman should be examined separately, otherwise there may be no information forthcoming about abortus provocatus or about venereal disease. From the man, who in 40% of cases is the sterile partner, a detailed general and special history should be taken; this applies in equal measure to the examination itself. In this connexion, naturally, the assessment of the sperms is of the greatest importance. When dealing with the woman questioning as to menstruation should be thorough; her examination must be even still more detailed and should include analysis of blood and urine. Of course, this is followed by a scrupulous gynecological examination. If any abnormalities are detected in the man or the woman, they should be sent, resp. to a urologist or a gynecologist. If that is not the case, then there should be a further investigation, especially of the woman. This is done also if abnormalities are discovered that do not point to the cause of the sterility. In the first place, the function of the ovary should be inquired into, in particular, to find out whether she is ovulating. This can be done quite simply by plotting the basal temperature curve. After this a biopsy of the endometrium is performed. Then follows the fern test, estimation of pregnanediol in the urine, and the daily examination of the vaginal smear. If anovulation is diagnosed, the cause must be sought, with a view to treatment. The cervical factor is also of importance, and this can be assessed by examination post coitum of the cervical mucus, or by the Miller-Kurzrock test. The tubes are checked up by insufflation or by hysterosalpingography, the latter, of course, providing the most accurate data; this diagnostic procedure can be carried out during a culdoscopy. The uterine factor can also be appraised by a biopsy of the endometrium, the temperature curve and the hysterosalpingogram. If nothing abnormal is found, so that a psychogenic infertility comes up for consideration, the patient must be sent to a psychiatrist, but not until a culdoscopy has first been done. Socalled idiopathic infertility, which forms a small proportion of the cases, may be based on subclinical endocrine disturbances or on immunity reactions of the female genital apparatus to the sperms of the man. The urologic treatment of the man must be limited to improvement of the general condition and endocrinologic therapy; operation comes into consideration, above all, in congenital abnormalities. Artificial insemination deserves careful thought. The treatment of the woman, apart from combating general complaints, is dependent on the nature of the gynecologic condition. Menstrual difficulties mostly call for endocrinologic therapy, so, too, does endometriosis, although in the latter case, the scalpel may be required; this applies also to anatomical anomalies or tumors. Anovulation can be treated with clomiphene, Pergonal and Humegon. Cervical infections must be cleared up; sometimes surgery (stenosis) or estrogen therapy must be thought of. When the tubes are shut off, repeated insufflations or hydrotubations should be given a trial before proceeding to operation. Finally, with regard to the uterine factor, the administration of progestogens is of especial value in habitual abortion.
