T1  - Treatment with human gonadotropins
T3  - Terapeutica con gonadotropinas humanas
A1  - Gemzell C.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - Treatment with human gonadotropins should only be performed in women with an infertility problem, and the aim of the treatment should be to induce controlled ovulation, i.e. ovulation at a certain time that can be predicted beforehand. Following a single treatment, spontaneous ovulation seldom occurs; and if conception fails to appear after the 1st treatment, a 2nd one has to be given. To make full use of the pituitary material, the selection of women suitable for treatment is important. As a general rule only those women who have normal ovaries but lack urinary gonadotropins should be treated. The 2 main complications that may follow treatment with human gonadotropins are polycystic enlargement of the ovaries, and superovulation leading to multiple births. With low doses of FSH and careful examination of the patients during treatment, the enlargement of the ovaries can usually be avoided. To control the number of ova released from the ovaries, and thus prevent multiple births, seems at present to be the most pressing problem in the treatment of infertility with human gonadotropins. The exact reason for superovulation leading to multiple births is not clear. It is generally felt that exogenous FSH in effective doses inevitably stimulates more than 1 follicle and puts the normal selection of a single follicle at stake. The treatment of male infertility with human pituitary gonadotropins is only indicated in men with hypogonadism due to pituitary failure, and the presence of germinative cells in the testes is essential. It is more likely that a man with aspermia will fulfil the necessary requirements for gonadotropic treatment than a man with oligospermia. For treatment, human pituitary or urinary FSH should be used and given together with chorionic gonadotropin. FSH and HCG act synergistically, both on the germinative cells and the Leydig cells. There is no lasting effect of treatment, and the aim of the treatment should be to obtain a pregnancy.
