T1  - Disorders of ovulation. Etiopathogenic and clinical considerations
T3  - Les troubles de l'ovulation. Considerations etiopathogeniques et cliniques
A1  - Fenasse R.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - The direct consequence of disorders of ovulation results in menstrual disorders and certain cases of sterility. Clinical and paraclinical investigations define the ovulatory character of the cycle and the existence of anomalies of hormonal secretions in relation to dysovulation. There is no certain test of ovulation; those used most frequently are in fact tests of progestative activity and are thus retrospective. Ovulatory disturbances can be intermittent and apparently accidental (syndrome of persistent follicle). More often they are habitual, readily related to polycystic dystrophy of the ovaries. Relatively discrete signs of hyperandrogeny may be present. Prolonged anovulation can manifest itself in several ways. The complete arrest of ovarian function leads often to amenorrhea whose physiopathologic mechanism can be established by careful investigation. The Stein-Leventhal syndrome constitutes an example of prolonged anovulation of probable ovarian origin.
