T1  - Induction of ovulation with clomiphene citrate
A1  - Kempers R.D.
A1  - Decker D.G.
A1  - Lee R.A.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - Clomifene therapy was used in 50 anovulatory patients. Those with good pretreatment levels of urinary estrogens obtained good results. Diminished levels, however, did not necessarily preclude success. All patients with Stein-Leventhal syndrome, all with anovulatory oligomenorrhea, and 3 with hypothalamic amenorrhea had good estrogen levels; pregnancy or apparent ovulation occurred in 33 of these 39 patients (85%). All other patients had low estrogen levels, and only 4 of these 11 (36%) responded. No patient with primary ovarian failure or pituitary failure responded. The overall response rate was 74%. Fifteen pregnancies occurred in 44 infertile patients (34%). Only 1, which terminated in abortion, occurred in the group with low estrogen levels. Conception occurred after the 1st course of therapy in 7 patients, after the 2nd course in 4, after the 3rd in 2. and after the 4th and 5th courses in 1 each. Nine of the 15 have not yet completed their pregnancies; 4 delivered single normal infants at term; 1 gave birth to an infant with congenital anomalies; and 1 aborted. Of the 37 who responded to therapy, all but 4 did so after the 1st course. Some patients responded regularly to clomifene therapy and others responded to some but not all courses. Where there was a response, as many as 7 consecutive courses of therapy were given. Since clomifene may cause luteinization of the unruptured follicle, care should be taken in interpreting the biphasic body temperature curve as evidence of ovulation. One patient showed repeated temperature shifts, yet failed to ovulate as demonstrated by endometrial biopsy.
