T1  - Current concepts in the treatment of anovulation
A1  - Rabau E.
A1  - Serr D.M.
A1  - Mashiach S.
A1  - Insler V.
A1  - Salomy M.
A1  - Lunenfeld H.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - A series of 235 patients with infertility due to disturbances of ovulation were treated with human gonadotropins or with clomifene citrate. The patients were divided into 2 main groups according to the level of urinary gonadotropins to the endogenous estrogen activity. Patients with corpus luteum insufficiency formed a separate group. Group I (low urinary gonadotropins, no evidence of endogenous estrogen activity) comprised 100 patients with primary, secondary, or postpartum amenorrhea. Group II (gonadotropins in normal range, evidence of endogenous estrogen activity) included 89 patients with secondary amenorrhea, oligomenorrhea, or anovulatory cycles. Forty-six patients with corpus luteum insufficiency formed group III. Patients of group I were given sequential HMG-HCG therapy, those of group II received either gonadotropins (34 cases) or clomifene (55 cases) and those of group III were treated with clomifene only. Gonadotropic therapy gave better results in patients of group I than in those of group II (65 and 44.1% of pregnancies resp.). In group II patients gonadotropins and clomifene gave similar results (49 and 44.1% pregnancies resp.). The results in group III were poor (15.2% of pregnancies).
