T1  - Clomifene in the therapy of anovular menstruation
T3  - Il clomifene nella terapia della mestruazione anovulare
A1  - Misurale F.
A1  - Papadia S.
A1  - Storace A.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - After examining the various theories developed as to the mechanism of clomifene action, the authors report the results obtained from 19 patients suffering from anovular menstruation and from 3 patients with secondary amenorrhea, who underwent many cycles of clomifene treatment. In most cases the dosage used was 50 mg daily for 5-6 days, starting the treatment from the 5th day of the cycle: no effect of ovarian hyperstimulation was observed, while side effects due to the drug administration were not very important and limited to 3 cases only (hot flushes, gastralgiae, and in 1 case diplopia); symptomatology, however, disappeared as soon as the treatment was interrupted. From the endocrine standpoint, the authors found that, as to the clomifene administration, the estrogen excretion, determined during and after the treatment, did not show an increase proportional to the drug dosages used. It seems that clomifene does not particularly affect pregnanediol excretion: a hyperpregnanedioluria could be correlated with the maturation of many corpora lutea. The drug action on the 17-ketosteroiduria does not seem to be significant either even if in some cases an increase in values to limits above the basic ones was observed. From the clinical standpoint, the authors believe that clomifene should be mainly used in the treatment of anovular menstruation and luteinic insufficiency, that is forms of sterility characterized by an insufficient LH prehypophyseal incretion connected with alterations of the releasing mechanism. To support this statement the authors report the results obtained in the cases treated: induction of ovulation in 82.2% and of pregnancy in 18.18% of the cases treated. In conclusion they state that clomifene, as well as HMG, is one of the most important therapeutic agents proposed for the induction of ovulation.
