AN  - 288088033
T1  - Female sterility of endocrine origin in the light of the latest therapeutic trends
A1  - Giarola A.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - Out of 3,400 partners of sterile marriages (no children after 3 or more yr of active married life) examined in 2 separate institutions, 446 (13.12 %) were found to suffer from endocrine female sterility. The latest (since 1963) therapeutic approach has been to associate postmenopausal urinary gonadotropins (HMG) and/or chorionic gonadotropins. Treatment was confined to subjects with gonadotropic insufficiency or poor ovarian sensitivity to gonadotropic stimulation, i.e. 71 patients - 13 with primary amenorrhea, 24 with secondary amenorrhea and 34 with anovulatory menstruation. As a whole, ovulation was restored in 72.4% of all cases, and the positive result apparently persisted through the subsequent cycles in 40.9% of the patients so treated. The conclusion is drawn that, although HMG treatment did provide a new potential gonadotropic therapy for endocrine sterility, such statistical data as have been reported lately can only be overoptimistic, particularly when they claim 50% or more of subsequent pregnancies.
