T1  - Ovarian steroid biosynthesis in stein-leventhal syndrome: In vivo and in vitro experiments
A1  - Conti C.
A1  - Sciarra F.
A1  - Concolino G.
A1  - Sorcini G.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - This report deals with experiments carried out to investigate the possible correlations between the androgenic activity of the ovaries determined in vivo by plasma testosterone dosages, and the findings of the in-vitro experiments performed on ovarian homogenates incubated with progesterone-C<ovid:sup>14</ovid:sup> and DELTA<ovid:sup>5</ovid:sup>-pregnenolone-H<ovid:sup>3</ovid:sup>. The investigations carried out on one normal woman and 3 hirsute women with polycystic ovaries gave the following results. When compared with the date of the normal woman, the 2 typical cases of Stein-Leventhal syndrome showed high levels of plasma testosterone which were reduced following Enovid administration, and an increased production of DHA, androstenedione, and testosterone in ovarian homogenates. These results confirm the gonadal origin of the hirsutism in these cases. Taking into consideration the H<ovid:sup>3</ovid:sup>/C<ovid:sup>14</ovid:sup> ratio both of testosterone and androstenedione, it can be observed that testosterone was produced more efficiently via pregnenolone and DELTA<ovid:sup>4</ovid:sup>-androstenedione via progesterone. In another case of hirsutism with polycystic ovaries, testosterone, elevated in basal conditions, was not reduced following norethynodrel-mestranol treatment: the in-vitro experiments revealed an increased production of DHA and a low formation of testosterone and androstenedione. These findings lend support to the hypothesis that the high levels of plasma testosterone, observed in this case, are derived from the peripheral transformation of DHA or from an abnormal adrenal secretion. In all these cases the in-vitro biosynthesis of the estrogens appeared to be low. The in-vitro experiments carried out on ovarian homogenates incubated with chorionic gonadotropin showed no significant modifications of the ovarian steroidogenesis.
