AN  - 288087563
T1  - Female sterility: A statistical study of 520 cases
A1  - Akasu F.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - The incidence of sterility in the clinic was 5.7%; sterility was primary in 442 of 520 patients and secondary in 78. Tubal, ovarian and male factors were found to be most often responsible for sterility. Sterility due to the tubal factor was observed in 36.1% of the cases. In 19.9% of the patients, basal body temperature record showed the monophasic pattern indicative of an anovulatory cycle. In 26.4% of the husbands of the sterile women, azoospermia or motile sperm counts of less than 20 million/ml were found. Sperm counts of 20-30 million/ml were observed in 20.6% of the husbands examined. The importance of the male factor needs to be further recognized by gynecologists. Endometrial tb was present in 22 (4.3%) of all the sterile patients, and a past history of tb was found in 18.9% of all the cases.
