T1  - Gynecological findings in adolescence. A study of 514 patients
A1  - Widholm O.
A1  - Frisk M.
A1  - Tenhunen T.
A1  - Hortling H.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - The mean age of the 514 examined girls was 16.8 and their mean menarche age 13.2 yr. A significant correlation was found between the bone age and the menarche age. Vaginal smear tests in premenstruum showed normal estrogen balance in 65%,hyperestrogenism in 24 and hypoestrogenism in 11%. The incidence of dysmenorrhea among the hyperestrogenous was 53%, of premenstrual tension 40%, and of fluor 30%. All these values were significantly lower for the normal cases. The mean age of the girls with dysmenorrhea was 17.4 yr and their mean menarche age 13.0 yr against 13.2 yr for the total material. In 60% of the cases of dysmenorrhea plus hyperestrogenism, anovulatory menstruations could be shown. A definite correlation to e.g. psychic factors and to overweight could be demonstrated. Otherwise reference is made in dysmenorrhea to an infantile uterus and related factors. Premenstrual tension showed significant correlation to dysmenorrhea, 51%. but correlated also with school performance. Of the girls who stayed in their form for a 2nd yr, 36% had premenstrual tension, while the figure for the whole series was 25%. About 40% of the girls with premenstrual tension had various psychic complaints. Menstrual disorders of varying type occurred in 121 cases (25%). Of these, 11 had had no menarche despite a chronological mean age of 16.0 yr. Menometrorrhagia occurred in 16 cases, while no juvenile metropathies were seen. The remainder of the disorders consisted of irregular menstruation. In 70% of the girls with amenorrhea, the bone age lagged behind the chronological age by 1-4 yr while 55% had hypoestrogenous vaginal smears. Hyperestrogenous vaginal smears occurred mainly in girls with frequent menstruation and menometrorrhagia. A significant difference was demonstrable in Hb values between the hyperestrogenous and the normal patients. Anemia was present in 6.5% (29 cases); only 3 of these girls had profuse menstruation. No pronounced hypo- or hyperthyroidism was diagnosed. Sexual experiences were recorded in 24%, mean age 17 yr. Eight girls, mean age 17 yr. were found to be pregnant. Genital anomalies were few: 2 cases of Turner's syndrome 2 cases of rudimentary uterus, and 32 cases of pronounced uterine hypoplasia. Radiography revealed in 1 case a uterus duplex unicollis, while marked retrouterine endometriosis was diagnosed by palpation. Two ovarian tumors were discovered; one of them was a malignant dysgerminoma and the other a follicular cyst.
