T1  - A study of the animal ovary. Some comparisons with the human ovary
A1  - Uyttenbroeck F.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - Part I of this monograph (page 7-104) deals with the normal mammalian ovary. An attempt was made to study at least one species from as many orders of this class of animals. Photographic documentation is presented of the cyclic changes in some species for which no extensive material had previously been published. The author describe: the findings in the rat, coypu, guinea-pig, dog, sheep, goat, horse and the primates. The effect of age on ovarian structure, atresia, luteinization, the corpus luteum and the interstitial tissue are des-cribed, and comparisons are drawn with the human ovary. Part II deals with 180 spontaneous ovarian tumors in animals studied in the Armed Forces In-stitute of Pathology, Washington, U. C. Of these tu-mors, 85 occurred in dogs, 40 in cows, 7 in horses 1 in a lion, 12 in cats, 11 in rats, 1 in a ferret and 23 in birds. The tumors most commonly seen were granulosa-cell tumors, primary carcinomata, tu-mors of the covering epithelium, primary or secon-dary tumors of non-intrinsic connective tissue and a few metastatic tumors. One hilar-cell tumor and one Krukenberg tumor are also described. The author compares some of these tumors with human ovarian tumors. Granulosa-cell tumors, especially those with a Sertoli-like pattern, are discussed in particular. It is postulated that Lecene's 'follicu-lome lipidique' is a luteinized granulosa-cell tumor As to tumors of the covering epithelium, special emphasis is placed on similarities between animal and human tumors in terms of the histological transition from benign, to low-grade malignant, to distinctly malignant. The histopathogenesis of me-sonephromata is discussed on the basis of a series of tumors in this category. This study disclosed no histological features which might suggest the pos-sibility of a Stein-Cohen-Leventhal syndrome in animals. The limited literature on animal tumors is reviewed. There are 205 illustrations.
