T1  - Endometrial biopsy - interpretation
A1  - Abell M.R.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - A clarification is given in simple words of the microscopic and pathologic criteria differentiating normal from abnormal endometrium. The following are briefly described: anovulatory endometrium (E), irregular shedding E, inadequate secretory E, the various hyperplasias (gestational. cystic, stromal. adenoma tous, focal and atypical glandular, the various metaplasias (squamous, mucous cell and osseous), iatrogenic E changes, endometritis. cancer as well as various fetal tissue implants. It is stressed that the procedure is less formidable than D and C, less accurate and primarily diagnostic; a positive report is significant, a negative one does not rule out disease. When physiologic information is desired, it is mandatory that the pathologist be given the menstrual dates. For accurate interpretation, it is essential that both the clinician and the pathologist be fully acquainted with the normal endometriai cycle. Both terms. 'follicular phase' endometrium and ' proliferative' endometrium are used. To a clinician, many 'prolife native' endometria are not proliferating but merely 'nonsecretory'. In this field a knowledge of normal endometrium will clarify the issue - and the tissue.
