T1  - Is the stein-leventhal syndrome an entity?
T3  - Le syndrome de Stein-Leventhal est-il une entite?
A1  - Greenblatt R.B.
A1  - Mahesh V.B.
A1  - Faucher G.L.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - The clinical symptomatology of this syndrome is sufficiently imprecise as to include a large variety of ovarian and adrenal disorders. Enlarged polycystic ovaries that react to wedge resection constitute the sine qua non condition for the diagnosis of a Stein-Leventhal syndrome. On the base of a typical study of 100 patients in which this syndrome was suspected, the authors answer a number of questions raised by the same. It results that a precise pathogenes is remains unknown; the diagnosis is only advanced a posteriori and that the various concepts related with the physiopathology are yet burdened with a great number of errors. In short, the reduction in the ovarian mass allows to a greater quantity of gonadotropins to become available per unit of ovarian tissue<< a result that may be reached either by reducing surgically the tissue mass itself, or medically by diminishing the inhibitory influence of the steroids produced by the same on the hypothalamic-pituitary axis, by the addition of exogenous gonadotropins or of Clomifene. The institution of cyclic ovulatory periods may be temporary or permanent. There are a number of women suffering from various endocrine diseases who are bearers of enlarged or small polycystic ovaries and the symptomatology exhibited by such individuals is not improved by w edge-resect ion. (10,3*).
