T1  - The polycystic ovary. VII. Intractable uterine bleeding and endometrial hyperplasia possibly related to an extraovarian source of oestrogen
A1  - Goldzieher J.W.
A1  - Fariss B.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - The clinical course of a patient with polycystic ovarian disease was characterized by recurrent endometrial hyperplasia and bleeding which eventually required panhysterectomy. Urinary estrogens did not fall after castration and secretion rate studies showed estrone production (estrone-H<ovid:sup>3</ovid:sup>) averaging 16-18 mug/day on 1 occasion and estradiol production (estradiol-C<ovid:sup>14</ovid:sup>) averaging 72 mug/day during another 4-day interval. There was a marked discrepancy between secretion rate and routine urinary estrogen measurements. Peripheral aromatization of testosterone was 0.6% and of androstenedione less than 1.2%. An estradiol production of 72 mug/day is not likely to have been derived exclusively from peripheral aromatization of these androgens, suggesting that direct adrenal secretion of estrogen may play a role in some cases of polycystic ovarian disease.
