T1  - The nervous control of the ovarian cycle
T3  - Controle nerveux du cycle
A1  - Kordon C.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - The nervous control of gonadotropic functions takes place at several levels. The hypophysis itself does not appear to be very autonomous; it also remains sensitive to variations in the concentrations of circulating steroid hormones. The chief organ of control is the hypothalamus; the hypothalamo hypophysiul system appears to be adequate by itself to ensure the essentials of gonadotropic regulation. However, other nervous circuits may modify the sensitivity of the hypothalamic mechanisms, which explains the effect of numerous external factors on gonadotropic functions. Experimental operations on certain hypothalamic structures have a constant and lasting effect on gonadotropic functions. These structures are not distinct anatomical or functional entities; they form part of complex circuits, of which they are the strategic points, the crossroads where the gradient of neuro endocrine activity is maximal. These circuits are the localization of 2 types of control mechanisms: first order mechanisms which control the basic hormonal conditioning and prepare the ovary for its periodic functions controlled by second order mechanisms. The second order mechanisms cannot become active unless the first order regulations have been achieved; an abnormal basic hormone balance (excess or deficiency of estrogen or progesterone, for example) impairs the liberation of LH and the realization of the ovarian cycle. This dependence of the ovulatory mechanisms on the basic gonadotropic conditioning explains why so many different operations provoke an anovulatory cycle or a permanent estrus; it also seems to explain certain species linked differences in the control of the gonadotropic secretions.
