T1  - Studies on plasma insulin in women. II. Effect of glucose administration in the anovulatory cycle, toxemia of late pregnancy and glycosuria of pregnancy
A1  - Yamamoto K.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - In 4 cases of amenorrhea and 2 cases of Stein Leventhal syndrome, the peak of the blood sugar level after glucose loading was higher than in women with normal menstrual cycles and occurred later, at 60 min after glucose loading. The plasma insulin values reached their peak 120 min after glucose loading, and were higher than normal. In anovulatory menstruation, the blood sugar and plasma insulin values reached peaks 30 min after glucose loading. The peak was higher than in women with normal menstrual cycles. In 15 cases of toxemia of late pregnancy the blood sugar values reached a peak 30 min after glucose loading, and had a similar value to that in the terminal stage of pregnancy, while plasma insulin values were lower. The blood sugar values determined periodically in 2 cases of glycosuria in pregnancy were lower than those in the corresponding stages of normal pregnancy, and the plasma insulin values were also low. In a case of pregnancy complicated by diabetes mellitus, a typical glucose tolerance curve was obtained, whereas the plasma insulin level was low.
