T1  - Coagulation studies in connection with pregnancy and treatment with gestagens
T3  - Koagulationsstudier i samband med graviditet och gestagenbehandling
A1  - Kullander S.
A1  - Nilsson I.M.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Coagulation and fibrinolysis studies, including determinations of thrombocyte adhesiveness, were performed on 27 women in different stages of pregnancy and on 32 women who for 2-24 months had been taking anovulatory preparations in contraceptive or therapeutic doses. In the pregnancy cases there was an increase in the content of P. and P., A.H.F., fibrinogen, plasminogen, antiplasmin and anti-activator. The number of thrombocytes, the thrombocyte adhesiveness, factor V, the hemophilia B factor and the inhibitors of plasminogen activation did not increase. Fibrinolysis activity showed a remarkable decline and during the last trimester no such activity could be demonstrated. In treatment with large doses of gestagens on account of endometritis, an increase in the content of A.H.F., P. and P., fibrinogen and plasminogen was obtained of about the same degree as is seen in the second trimester. Unlike the pregnancy cases, none of these patients showed any reduction of fibrinolysis activity. The fibrinolysis inhibitors declined by 20-40%. Of 25 women who had used Anovlar in the usual contraceptive dose, a slight increase of P. and P. was obtained in 10, of fibrinogen in 4 and of plasminogen in 8. The other coagulation factors, the number of thrombocytes and the thrombocyte adhesiveness were not affected. Fibrinolysis activity and the fibrinolysis inhibitors were normal. From the point of view of coagulation, there are no criteria for maintaining that the changes in the circulating blood which occurred in the gestagen treatment may predispose the patient to thrombosis. Whether gestagenic hormones cause changes in the actual walls of the vessels which may have a thrombogenetic effect is a question which must be left open.
