A1  - Sciarra F.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Having obtained reliable data in favor of the ovarian origin of testosterone which is found in small quantities in the plasma of normal women and sometimes in large quantities in patients with the Stein-Leventhal syndrome, some recent data which would suggest the adrenal genesis of testosterone in other cases of hirsutism and virilism are presented here. Studied were carried out in some cases of congenital adrenogenital syndrome, Cushing's disease, virilizing adrenal adenoma and adenocarcinoma, the diagnosis of which was based on clinical data and hormonal findings and confirmed by laparotomy and histology. In these patients the behavior of plasma testosterone was studied in basal conditions and after stimulation and suppression tests of the adrenals. From the results obtained it appears that in the cases of hirsutism of definite adrenal origin the plasma levels of testosterone are generally increased in basal conditions, are further increased with ACTH stimulation, and significantly decreased by the inhibition test with cortisone-like compounds: these results are unlike those found in normal subjects or in the Stein-Leventhal syndrome. In virilizing adrenal tumors no modification of plasma testosterone is observed after adrenal function tests. On the basis of this observation it can be concluded that in some pathological conditions the adrenal cortex can produce largp quantities of testosterone, which is the main factor in the genesis of hirsutism and virilism of adrenal origin.
