T1  - Oxidative enzymes in luteinization. A histochemical study with special reference to persistent follicular cysts and the stromal theca cell
A1  - Fienberg R.
A1  - Cohen R.B.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Thirty-five whole ovaries and 14 ovarian wedge resertions were studied with the aid of lipid stains and oxidative enzyme reactions. In this material there were 20 corpora lutea from less than 24 hr to 14 days of age. Twenty-four ovaries were available with superficial collagenization and multiple follicular cysts (Stein-Leventhal type). The histochemical pattern, particularly the oxidative enzyme activities were found to be extremely constant in the corpora lutea, thus making this pattern available as a model of luteinization. With the glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase and 3beta-ol dehydrogenase methods, 3 types of follicular cysts were found, 1 of which possessed an oxidative enzyme activity pattern of luteinization. The importance of separating nonluteinized from luteinized follicular cysts in biochemical investigations of the biosynthesis of steroid ovarian hormones is emphasized. The stromal theca cells were found to possess oxidative activity patterns similar to the cells of the theca interna. Correlation between the hematoxylin-eosin criteria of luteinization and the oxidative enzyme activity pattern of luteinization in the follicular cysts was poor. The correlation in the stromal theca cells was inconclusive, but was suggestive of that in the follicular cysts.
