T1  - Steroid hormone formation in the human ovary. iv. ovarian stromal compartment; formation of radioactive steroids from acetate-i-<ovid:sup>14</ovid:sup>c and action of gonadotropins
A1  - Rice B.F.
A1  - Savard K.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Slices of stromal tissue from 8 normal human ovaries, obtained at different stages of the menstrual cycle and pregnancy, were incubated in vitro in the presence of acetate-1-C14. The radioactive steroid formed were identified by reverse isotope dilution and radiochemical purity was established by crystallization to constant specific activity. The biosynthesis of delta4-androstene-3.17-dtane. testosterone. 3beta-hydroxyA9-androsten-17- one. n-hydrosiy-delta4 -pregnene-S, 2O-dione. 3betahydroKy-delta5-pregnen- 20-one. estrone and estradiot-17beta was demonstrated. Little or no radioactive progesterone was found. Radioactive androgens were the major group of steroids found in all incubations. The highest incorporations of acetate-1-C<ovid:sup>14</ovid:sup> into steroids were found with those normal ovarian specimens obtained early in the luteal phase of the menstrual cycle and during pregnancy. Radioactive steroid synthesis could be augmented in certain instances by HCG and by preparations of human pituitary gonadotropins. Ovarian tissues from 2 patients with polycystic ovaries and 1 patient with post-menopausal stromal hyperplasia were also studied by identical technics. The distribution of radioactive steroids found using these pathologic tissues was similar to that observed with normal stromal tissues, the same androgens being the predominant products in both. The formation of androgenic steroids as the principal product of the ovarian stroma suggests that this compartment forms a distinct gland of internal secretion within the human ovary.
