N2  - Detailed clinical and biochemical studies were performed in a 22-yr-old woman with primary amenorrhea. virilization. bilateral sclerocystic ovarian disease and a hilar-cell tumor of 1 ovary. By clinical, radiologie and dynamic functional endocrine tests, the ovarian source of the excessive androgen production was established prior to surgery. In-vivo and in-vitro production of testosterone by the tumor was established as well as its ability to metabolize progesterone-C14 and 4-androstenedione to a variety of compounds. The biochemical characteristics of this tumor strongly resemble testicular tumors, even to the existence of an 110-hydroxylase. Epitestosterone was found in the urine, and the existence of a ITcr-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase was demonstrated in the sclerocystic ovarian tissue. No eetrogen was synthesized by the tumor or the ovarian tissue under the in-vitro conditions.
