T1  - Induction of ovulation with clomiphene. report of a stury including comparison with intravenous estrogen and human chorionic gonadotrophin
A1  - Beck P.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Clomiphene was given to 129 infertile women; 88 (68%) responded to clomiphene at least once, and 65 of these patients ovulated during the 1st trial. The likelihood of inducing ovulation after 2 initial failures with clomiphene is therefore remote. Of 299 drug cycles. ovulation took place in 157 (53%) . It is essential to limit the group of patients to whom clomiphene is administered, rather than indiscriminately offer the drug to any infertile women. The data imply that patients with oligoor anovulation of unknown etiology, or with correctable cndocrinopathies. showed the highest incidence of ovulation following clomiphene therapy; there were 22 pregnancies in this group. Another pregnancy occurred in a patient with Stein-Leventhal's syndrome, after wedge resection. These 23 pregnancies represent a 17% incidence. There were 2 sets of twins. There were no pregnancies in patients with postpubertal adrenogenital syndrome or primary ovarian failure. All the pregnancies occurred following a short course of clomiphene therapy. Therefore. it is recommended that clomiphene be given in doses of 50 mg twice a day for 5 days, beginning on day 10-12 of spontaneous or progesterone-induced cycle.
