AN  - 288079656
T1  - Androgen secretion in the steinleventhal syndrome
A1  - Mahesh V.B.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - The development of newer techniques has enabled several investigators to re evaluate the role of the adrenal and ovary as a source of excessive androgen production. Incubation of ovarian slices with various precursors has yielded a wealth of information on ovarian enzymatic activities. To gain insight into the mechanism cf secretion of various steroids by the normal and polycystic ovary, the fallowing approaches have been made: Using excretion of steroids before and after adrenal suppression and ovarian stimulation; among 45 hirsute women with varying degrees of menstrual failure, 31 showed an increase in one or more of 17-KS fraction, whereas in 14 the levels were normal. Sixteen showed an increase in the 11-oxygenated 17-KS fraction and a similar elevation in the 11-deoxy-17-KS. Since the 11-oxy-17-KS are of adrenal origin, the contribution of the adrenals is evident in these patients. Suppression data with dexamethasone support the above findings. The remaining 15 patients had elevated 11-deoxy-17-KS levels and this indicates the ovarian contribution. Administration of estrogen was adequate to suppress these 11-deoxy-17-KS. Wedge resection of these ovaries results in depression of these steroids. Elevation of these 11-deoxy-17-KS with human pituitary FSH lends support to this concept. Urinary pregnonetrial and DELTA<ovid:sup>5</ovid:sup>-pregnonetrial were within normal limits. Also the levels of urinary estrogen were normal. Plasma 17-KS: elevated levels of dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate and/or andr oster one sulfate were noted which became depressed on wedge resection. Steroid content of ovarian tissue: The major pathway of biosynthesis of estrogen is the conversion of cholesterol into estrogen via DELTA<ovid:sup>5</ovid:sup>-pregnenolone, progesterone 17a-hydroxypregesterone and DELTA<ovid:sup>5</ovid:sup>-endostenedione. The ovaries of patients with the polycystic ovary syndrome contained large quantities of dehydroepiandrosterone via DELTA<ovid:sup>5</ovid:sup>-pregnenolone and 17alpha-hydroxy-DELTA<ovid:sup>5</ovid:sup>-pregnenolone. Steroid content of ovarian venous blood: This indicated a large androgen/estrogen ratio employing blood in steroidogenesis. The conversion of androgen and estrogen peripherally may account for the presence of estrogen in the urine.
