AN  - 288077469
T1  - The Stein-Leventhal syndrome
A1  - Shearman R.P.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Stein and Leventhal first wrote of this syndrome in 1935. They described a group who had infertility, oligomenorrhea or amenorrhea, and enlarged polycyetic ovaries. Frequent findings were hirautism, obesity and enlargement of the clitoris. The perplexing hormonal environment of these patients has recently been reviewed. Studies of cyst fluid and excised ovarian tissue have helped in many ways. A review of the recent literature and various treatments were discussed. With the exception of the unusual patient with endometrial hyperplasia, amenorrhea itself is rarely an indication for treatment. The central problem is to restore ovulation. Human gonadotropins may be used but the choice lies between ovarian wedge resection or clomiphene therapy and corticosteroids. Of 33 patients in this series, 31 have been subjected to bilateral ovarian wedge resection with restoration of ovulatory menstruation in 27. Anovulation has been described but has not yet occurred in those in whom operation was initially successful. Surgery offers permanent cure in more than 80% . Clomiphene can be expected to induce ovulation in 80% of patients with polycystic ovaries, but continued ovulation appears to be dependent on continued treatment. Two cases are presented, 1 without surgery and 1 where surgery failed. Clomiphene caused menstruation in each case as well as ovulation. Therapeutic adrenocortical suppression has a small place in management. Four patients were treated and 2 had regular ovulatory cycles for more than 12 mth. This is not trivial treatment and is not to be undertaken lightly.
