T1  - Turner's syndrome and disease. A report of 16 cases
T3  - Sindrome e malattia di Turner. Presentazione di 16 casi
A1  - Perona G.
A1  - Frezza M.
A1  - Spandri P.
A1  - De Sandre G.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Primary amenorrhea associated with low stature and, with the exception of 2 cases, various other malformations, is described in 16 patients' with a female phenotype. In 7 of these patients, it was impossible from normal gynecologic examination to detect the presence of the gonads; in another 9 patients subjected to exploratory laparotomy. pelvipneumography or autopsy (1 case) there was either absence or dysgenesis of the gonads, varying from streaks, one or more small cysts present on one side or bilaterally, to the presence of 2 enlarged micropolycystic ovaries. None of the patients had a family history of diabetes mellitus nor showed any signs of the disease but 5 had previously suffered from middle ear infections. Studies of the chromosomal patterns demonstrated the mosaicism XO/XX in 8 cases, the anomalous karyotype XO in 6 cases, in 1 a normal female karyotype XX and in another case a karyotype with 47 chromosomes, the additional one being a small metacentric chromosome. On the basis of clinical and chromosomal studies that result from this series of patients and from others quoted in the literature, a distinction is proposed between Turner's disease and Turner's syndrome. The former, defined essentially on an etiologic and pathogenetic basis, should include all those cases with gonadal dysgenesis due to partial or total heterochromosomal monosomy, involving the 'loci' of the short arms. The latter, which comprises the well known symptom complex, should instead include those cases presenting with the characteristic symptomatology irrespective of whether specific chromosomal lesions are present or not.
