Y1  - 1966//
N2  - In 13 women with menstrual disturbances accompanied byhirsutism 17-KS. 17-KGS, pregnanediol, pregnanetrioljdehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA). androsterone. etiocholannlon and eetrogene were deter mined in the urine and conisol (11-OHCS) in the plasma. It was found that determinations of 17-KS. 17-KGS, pregnanetriol. DHEA and particularly cortisol are of diagnostic value in these disturbances. The ACTH stimulation test increases the possibilities of differential diagnosis in women with hirsutism. Owing to this hormonal analysis it was possible to diagnose idiopathic hirsutism in 1 woman, the Stein-Leventhal syndrome in 4. a mild adrenogenital adult-onset syndrome in 4 and a mildandrogenic overactivity of the adrenals in 1 woman. In 3 patients with hirsutism an exact diagnosis was not possible; decreased plasma cortisol level without an increase of its values after the ACTH stimulation test speaks for enzymatic disturbances in the adrenals, especially when pregnanediol and pregnanetriol levels have increased after the ACTH-test. Enzymatic disturbances inhibiting the biogenesis of some adrenal steroids appear not only in a mild form of adrenogenital syndrome. A mild androgenic overactivity of the adrenals as well as idiopathic hirsutism are characterized by normal cortisol ACTH-test, with a simultaneous high increase in 17-KS after ACTH administration.
