T1  - Cunical and patho-anatomic considerations on some cases of 'giant ovary'
T3  - Consider azioni cliniche ed anatomo-patologiche su alcuni cast di 'ovaio gigante'
A1  - Tartaglia P.
A1  - Becca B.
A1  - Uncinimanganelli C.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - The existence of ovaries that were generically defined as 'giant ovaries' has for some time been the subject of discussion. With such an expression there is meant an ovary increased in volume, without pathologic elements. Attention had been attracted by reports of ovaries that were greatly increased in size, with a practically normal histologie structure, accompanied by various clinical symptoms. The clinical picture was dominated by menstrual disorders, with at times absence of any symptoms. The anatornicoclinical entity is not yet defined, so attention is exclusively turned to the histologie aspect, reporting the cases of ovaries which are so-called 'giant* and correlating such data with clinical pictures. From histologie examination it appears that the various constitutional elements of the ovary are in general normal in character, even if of greater dimension. As a whole, there is found a good ovary with constitutional elements dimensionally larger than normal, but without pathologic aspects. From a functional point of view, these ovaries appear hyperfunctional: in fact, in the examined cases there were women with abundant menstruations, both in quantity and in duration, and in 2 cases with metrorrhagias. The following possibilities must be considered : ovaries congenitally bigger than normal, an abnormal gonadotropic stimulation or an abnormal gonadal response to stimulation of the hypophysis, or a prestage of sclerocystic evolution of the ovary. After having reviewed and discussed these different points it is concluded that it is possible to retain 'giant ovary' as a distinct entity, at least under an anatomicopathologic profile, from other cases of physiopathology of the ovary. This matter requires obviously further explanation, especially in the clinical fields, to be able to elucidate the effective functional possibility of such ovaries.
