T1  - OVARIAN STIMULATION by HUBAAN MENOPAUSAL GONADOTROPHIN in PATIENTS with AMENORRHOEA and ANOVULATION -
A1  - Furuhjeim M.
A1  - Lunell N.O.
A1  - Odeblad E.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Three patients with primary amenorrhea, 6 with secondary amenorrhea and 4 with anovulatory cycles have been treated with HMG. In 5 patients injections of HCG followed. The clinical and steroid effects were evaluated by vaginal smears, endometrial biopsies, properties of cervical mucus, inspection of ovaries at laparoscopy and determinations of the 24 -hr urinary excretion of estrogens, pregnanediol. 17ketosteroids and 17 -hydroxycorticosteroids. The ooses of HMG used for the 3 patients with primary amenorrhea varied between 490 and 700 FSH units of HMG. One patient, who also received HCG. ovulated. One showed signs of increased estrogen production, and the 3rd one, with small atrophic ovaries, did not respond. The dosage of HMG used for the 6 patients with secondary amenorrhea was 200-700 FSH units. One patient showed no response. Three patients became pregnant and 1 of them had also received HCG. Four patients with anovulatory cycles were treated with 210-300 FSH units of HMG. The doses given were sufficient to induce urinary excretion of pregnanediol to secretory phase levels, and to cause a rise in the basal temperature. Signs of an increased estrogen production appeared in all patients except 1 with low excretion before treatment. A correlation between estrogen and pregnanediol excretions and the dose of HMG in the amenorrheic groups was not indicated. (X.2c,3,t*).
