T1  - Induction of ovulation with clomlphene. report of a study including comparison with intravenous estrogen and human chorionic gonadotrophln
A1  - Beck P.
A1  - Grayzel E.F.
A1  - Young I.S.
A1  - Kupperman H.S.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Clomiphene was given to 129 infertile women; 08 (68%) responded to clomiphene at least once, and 65 of these patients ovulated during the 1st trial. The likelihood of inducing ovulation after 2 initial failures with clomiphene is therefore remote. Of 299 drug cycles, ovulation took place in 157 (53%). It is essential to limit the group of patients to whom clomiphene is administered, rather than indiscriminately offer the drug to any infertile women. The data imply that patients with oligo- or anovulation of unknown etiology, or with correctable endocrinopathies, showed the highest incidence of ovulation following clomiphene therapy; there were 22 pregnancies in this group. Another pregnancy occurred in a patient with Stein-Leventhal's syndrome, after wedge resection. These 23 pregnancies represent a 17% incidence. There were 2 sets of twins. There were no pregnancies in patients with postpubertal adrenogenital syndrome or primary ovarian failure. All the pregnancies occurred following a short course of clomiphene therapy. Therefore, it is recommended that clomiphene be given in doses of 50 mg. twice a day for 5 days, beginning on day 10-12 of a spor taneous or progesterone-induced cycle.
