N2  - Estrogen production rates were determined before and alter the administration of human menopausal gonadotropin (5 patients) and Clomid (4 patients). Clinically, the subjects described in this paper suffered from menstrual disorders of varying etiology. Pretreatment levels varied from 25223 Mg. /24 hr. Following the administration of HMG. an increase in production rate was seen in all patients. The magnitude of this increase was extremely variable, the highest amount being determined at 4240 Mg. /24 hr. in a patient with polycystic ovaries. Only 1 of the 4 Clomidtreated patients showed a positive response. This was probably due to the timing of the posttreatment measurement. These experiments<< even though conducted in a small series of patients, lend further support to the need of an ovarian stimulation test for better understanding and classification of patients presenting with amenorrhea.
