T1  - In-vivo studies on androgen metabolism after administration of ovulationinhibiting steroids. II. Metabolism of labeled testosterone and dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate in patients treated by lynestrenol, synthetic estrogens and by mixtures of these compounds
T3  - Etudes in vivo sur le metabolisme des androgenes apres administration de steroides inhibiteurs de l'ovulation. II. Metabolisme de la testosterone et du sulfate de dehydroepiandroeterone radioactifs, chez des sujets traites par le lynoestrenol, les oestrogenes de synthese et leur association
A1  - Mauvais-Jarvis P.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Radioactive dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate and testosterone, which are 2 circulating compounds in humans, have been injected into normal men, women and patients with Stein-Leventhal syndrome. These injections were made before and after administration of ethinyl estradiol, lynestrenol and association of lynestrenol and mestranol (Lyndiol). The per cent conversion of injected steroids into 17-ketonic and 17j3-hydroxylated urinary metabolites was calculated. The results observed can be summarized as follows: in all cases, the yields of sulfate metabolites formed from radioactive precursors were more important after treatment with antiovulatory steroids, especially urinary dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate derived from injected dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate; etiocholanolone and and roste r one formed from testosterone. The modifications in the 5s/5o ratio of androstanediols suggest that oral synthetic estrogens and progestins inhibit the 5a- A4 reductase implicated in the ' 17/3-hydroxyl metabolic pathway'of testosterone. A change in 17/3-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase activity is also postulated, because testosterone was more metabolized into androsterone via androstenedione, and less reduced into androstanediol afterantiovulatory steroids.
