T1  - Morphology of acrocentric chromosomes in man
A1  - Lezhava T.A.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Studies were made on the structure of acrocentric chromosomes and the nature of their association; a total of 72 metaphase plates were analyzed from peripheral blood leukocyte cultures of patients with polycystic ovaries. The long arms of acrocentric chromosomes of group D (13-15) showed the presence of secondary constrictions in 2 places. An acrocentric chromosome of group D was identified in which each satellite thread contained 2 satellites: a larger one situated proximally and a smaller one situated distally. Various types of satellites are described and named puff-like, ring-shaped, conjoint and spherical. Chromatid satellites apparently stimulate non-disjunction of chromatids during the second anaphase of meiosis or during mitotic division of the zygote. The observed associations of acrocentric chromosomes can be subdivided into 3 groups: (a) Associations where chromatid satellites of 2 opposite acrocentric chromosomes join each other, (b) associations formed by satellites of 2 opposite chromatids, and (c) associations where the acrocentric chromosomes unite with the short arm of a non-adjoining chromosome.
