T1  - Induction of ovulation
A1  - Shearman R.P.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - It is difficult to prognosticate what the results will be in healthy women, complaining of infertility due to anovulation. It is impossible on purely clinical grounds to select those that will respond to therapy and those who will not. There is also present the possibility of overstimulaton which is a source of danger to the patient. For those patients suffering from ovarian failure this therapy is a waste of time and money. Before treatment is undertaken, there should be a thorough clinical examination and curettage; also the effect of diagnostic gonadotropin stimulation on urinary estrogen excretion should be determined. Those patients with cystic glandular hyperplasia with a sterility problem should be treated with clomifene; for those with Stein-Leventhal syndrome, wedge resection is probably the treatment of choice. Compared with clomifene<< gonadotropins are more difficult to use both for the patient and physician and more dangerous.
