T1  - The indications of the 'two-phase' method in gynecology
T3  - Indikationen fur die 'Zwei-Phaaen-Methode' in der Gynakologie
A1  - Kaiser B.
A1  - Mehring W.I.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - The value of the ao-called 2-phase or sequential method off hormonal therapy in gynecology is discussed. Experimental and clinical results of the treatment of 175 woman with an aggregate number of 548 cycles are reported. Breakthrough ovulations occurred in about 7% of the cases at a daily dosage of 50-90 mug of ethinyieatradiol or 80 mug of ethinyleatradiolmethylether. Signs of a corpus luteum deficiency point towards a reduced fertility even in cycles with breakthrough ovulation. As an oral contraceptive the method appears to be less safe than treatment with combined estrogen-progestin preparations. Sequential therapy is indicated in primary dysmenorrhea with uterine hypoplaaia, in cases with prolonged and too frequent menstrual How. in dysfunctional intermenstrual bleeding, in corpus luteum cysts and acne and also in ovarian hirsutism in young women. A daily dose of 80 Mg of methylether or of 50 vg of ethinylestradiol is sufficient in these cases. Generally, sequential treatment should be reserved for younger women. In cases with anovulatory cycles the sequential therapy facilitates the substitution treatment and the cyclic therapy of amenorrheas with genital hypoplasia. Other indications are the surgical menopause and the premature menopausal syndrome. In younger women, anovulatory dysfunctional bleeding can be successfully regulated by sequential therapy. In women older than 45 y r the combined drugs are more useful. Sequential therapy causes less side effects than combined therapy. The most frequent complication is nausea, usually caused by the oral estrogens.
