AN  - 287072089
T1  - The hypoplastic ovary
T3  - L'ovaio ipoplasico
A1  - Remotti G.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Forty out of 50 cases of ovarian hypoplasia seen during a 6-yr period were submitted to explorative laparatomy with biopsy of the gonads. Twenty-four presented primary amenorrhea, with slight or no development of the secondary sex characteristics, and 16 were suffering from secondary amenorrhea. The hypoplastic ovaries were divided into 3 categories which, in turn, were sub-divided into groups on the basis of their macroscopic and microscopic appearance. The categories aref ovaries presenting abnormalities leading to insufficient overall development or poor development of a component part, ovaries which, besides insufficient development, also show pathological deviations (for instance, poly cystic transformation) and 'senile' hypoplastic ovaries in the partial sense, that is. with definite exhaustion in the component structures. A fair degree of parallelism has been observed between the hormonological and histological characteristics. In fact, high elimination of hypophysial gonadotropins generally predominated in those cases in which the follicular patrimony was very small or even completely missing (primary amenorrhea 8 'extremely early* or 'prepuberaT menopause, secondary amenorrhea - 'early' menopause), while the elimination of same gonadotropins appeared low or normal in those cases where the follicular tissue was present. Confirmation of a constant behavior analogy may give greater weight to the etiological and patoogenetic interpretation of a defect which is at times located within the ovaries and thus primary, and at other times extrinsic and secondary. Barr's chromat in tests were done in all cases of 'hypoplastic ovaries'; the result was constantly positive. Chromosomic analysis, which was performed in the majority of cases of primary amenorrhea. demonstrated the presence of the normal karyotype 44 A + XX in such cases. The importance of systematic bioptic control of the gonads is emphasized, not merely because it is an indispensable supplement to all previous clinical, hormonological and radiological examinations, for diagnostic purposes, but also as a prognostic element in the attempt to obtain functional recovery. The latter is at least temporarily possible with combined HMG + HCG gonadotropic treatment, in high doses, in those patients presenting at least a moderate amount of follicular tissue. (10.5. 9.14,21*).
