T1  - Lh and adrenal androgenesis
A1  - Pauerstein C.J.
A1  - Solomon D.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Three castrated females in the 3rd decade of life were given i. m. HCG. The urinary excretion of etiochoianolone and dehydroepiandr oster one increased significantly in all 3 patients. Total 17-ketosteroid responses were variable while 17-ketogenic steroid levels increased slightly in all patients. This suggests that HCG may have a qualitative as well as quantitative effect on adrenal secretion and subsequent peripheral metabolism. LH (which is immunologically and biologically similar to HCG) apparently stimulates adrenal androgenesis. This biologic activity of LH may be the common denominator in the endocrine mechanisms of such widely divergent phenomena as puberty. Stein-Leventhal's syndrome, and the 17-ketosteroid response to estrogen therapy in gonadal dysgenesis.
