AN  - 287071922
T1  - Clomiphene citrate; experience with 217 patients. variations in response and unusual reactions
A1  - Whitelaw M.J.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Although excessive reactions to Clomiphene have been reported in a dosage of 1,200 mg, these have never been seen below 1.000 mg over a period of 1 mth. Delay in ovulation frequently occurs and the basal body temperature curve shows a prolonged rise up to 24 days. Abnormal thermogenic responses are of 2 types: either a 2-day sharp rise without ovulation, or a 2-day peak followed later on by ovulation and pregnancy or menstruation. With low-dosage Clomiphene, low abdominal pain due to ovarian enlargement was eventually seen but never to a severe extent. In this series of 217 patients 58 pregnancies occurred in 48 patients, of whom 11 aborted and 1 was ectopic, whereas 2 were multiple births. The best candidates for Clomiphene administration are those with dysfunctional bleeding, polycystic ovaries, amenorrhea. and anovulatory cycles with good evidence of estrogenic effect. Patients who have normal or low gonadotropin titers and are refractory to Clomiphene are candidates for HCG therapy. The mode of action of both substances is discussed.
