T1  - Clinical effects of clomiphene in anovulation
A1  - Lamb E.J.
A1  - Guderian A.M.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Thirty-nine patients with idiopathic anovulation were treated with clomiphene citrate. Ovulation occurred in 1 or more treatment cycles in 9 of 17 amenorrheic patients and in all of 15 oligomenorrheic and 1 oligoovulatory patients treated. Thus 31 women (79%) ovulated and 12 (31%) became pregnant. Patients who had had spontaneous uterine bleeding during the preceding G mth or who had withdrawal bleeding after progesterone, those who had an estrogenic vaginal smear, and those with prolifera*!-'a endometrium usually ovulated after clomiphene tre t ment. An elevation of basal body temperature, an incr ise in the degree of cervical-mucus ferning within 2 wk of treatment, or uterine bleeding of normal amount and duration were fairly reliable indicators of ovulation, particularly when studied in parallel. Changes in karyopyknotic or cornification index, the presence of hot flushes, or lue occurrence of pelvic pain were somewhat less reliable indicators of ovulation but were helpful when correlated with other indexes. Clomiphene citrate is an effective ovulatory stimulant in the anovulatory patient who has an intact pituitary-gonadal axis and who does not have low endogenous estrogen levels. Because of the antiestrogenic and probable thermogenic activity of clomiphene, care must be exercised in diagnosing ovulation by the usually accepted clinical criteria when it is employed.
