AN  - 287071864
T1  - Amenorrhoea. a study with particular attention to the problems of ovarian failure
A1  - Ik B.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - A total of 355 patients with amenorrhea are presented. The necessity of dividing the different forms of the picture of this affection into distinct groups is stressed. The material is divided into: (1) primary amenorrhea ( 16.9%). (2) primary oligoamenorrhea (36.6%). (3) secondary amenorrhea (32.7%), and (4) amenorrhea following pregnancy (13.8%). In the 1st group were 20 patients with amenorrhea caused by congenital anomalies of the genitalIa. Forty women had ovarian amenorrhea; 13 of them had abnormal chromosomes. These patients presented small stature, congenital anomalies, absence of development of the breasts, and scarce pubic hair. Only 50% of the women had an increased elimination of gonadotropins in the urine. It is concluded that it is not possible to distinguish between patients with chromosomal abnormalities and badly developed gonads on the one hand, and women with hypoplastic ovaries and a normal karyotype on the other, by means of vaginal smears, endometrial biopsies and hormone assays. Eight patients in the 2nd group presented abnormal cycles, i.e. anovulatory or irregular cycles before the amenorrhea. The majority of the women of this group was of normal height and weight, had no hirsutism, had acrocyanosis and a hypertrophy of the mammary glands. It is assumed in these cases that there is an imbalance of ovarian steroid production. Hormonal assays showed not only a simple failure but also a functional decline of the ovary with low estrogen levels. The excretion of total estrogens. however, was higher in these patients than in patients with secondary amenorrhea. A low urinary excretion of pregnanediol and a high excretion of androeterone was found. In the 3rd group (secondary amenorrhea) a psychogenic disturbance was detected in 49% of the patients; hypometabolism and underweight were also found more frequently. Hypestrogenic vaginal smears and endometrial inactivity in this group was more frequent than in the group of primary oligoamenorrhea. This suggests less active ovaries in the patients belonging to this group. In the 4th group were 27 patients with ovulatory failure from an inability of the pituitary gland to restore the normal function. These patients started to menstruate spontaneously and 6 of them conceived. Twenty-two patients showed evidence of hypothalamic disturbances; none had Sheehan's syndrome. One patient developed signs of necrosis of the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland after an induced abortion. Four women had a Chiari-Frommei syndrome. A grouping as given by the author, is advised, especially for selection of the patients in whom a more detailed investigation is warranted.
