T1  - Human pituitary gonadotropins and their clinical application
T3  - Las gonadotropinas hipofisarias humanas y su aplicacion clinica
A1  - Caballero A.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - This is a short review of treatment with human hypophyses I gonadotropins at the present day. After some considerations on mechanisms of action, forms of administration and units of reference, it establishes the dosage scheme, taking as a base the experience of other investigators, but personally completed; 4,000-16,000 mg. IRP equivalents of HMG; 3,000-6,000 IU HCG. The author gives everv 4 days 600. 400, 200 IU HMG and 100. 500, 1,500 IU HCG. The results obtained are definitely good when the HHG or the HMG are associated with the HCG. But attention is drawn to the great frequency of multiple ovulations, which may give rise to multiple pregnancies. Ovarian cysts may also be produced. The chief indication for this treatment is hypothai am ic-hypophyseal hypo- or disfunction from the g on ad ot r opi c aspect; it is also reasonable to employ it in the Stein-Leventhal syndrome. Administration of gonadotropins are contraindicated in (1) primary ovarian hypofunction, (2) cases of ovarian hyperestrogenicity, (3) psychic hypothalamic-hypophyseal inhibition, hypercorticalism or hypothyroidism. A final indication for HHG or HMG is based on first measures in male sterility. Mateu-Aragones - Barcelona.
