T1  - Induction of ovulation with human gonadotroplvs in gynaecological disorders -
A1  - Shah P.N.
A1  - Mahajan D.K.
A1  - Dave M.J.
A1  - Purandare B.N.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - The observations based on a small series indicate that HPG-HCG treatment have proved to be of great value while treatment with HCG alone is not promising even when the anovulatory menstrual cycles are regular. The work is in progress to show that in the latter group of cases showing varying degree of estrogenic activity, a comparatively small amount of HPG would bring about equally good results. There is no doubt that with the availability of the species-specific gonadotropins, the outlook for the treatment of persistently anovulatory cycles or of ovarian failure due to functional or organic lesions of the hypothalamohypophyseal system would be totally changed. Of the several drawbacks in the wide-scale use of this therapy the most important one is that concerning its availability at present. Commercially available gonadotropins extracted from the menopausal urine are less potent than those from the pituitary and are frightfully expensive (Gemzell, 1963). Therefore, as far as this country is concerned, till the time when gonadotropins can be made synthetically and are cheap, there is no other way but to extract them from the pituitary in one' s own laboratory. Organization of an All India wide collection of human pituitaries at 3-4 centers should not be a difficult problem since autopsies are done routinely on sudden and accidental deaths in most of the teaching Institutions in this country. The other drawbacks like catastrophic overstimuIat ion of the ovaries and occurrence of too many ovulations perhaps could be minimized with the adjustment of the dosage. Fortunately in this small series there were no such mishaps. (10.3*21*).
