T1  - Sequential endometrial alterations during one cycle of treatment with synthetic progestagen-estrogen compounds
A1  - Roland M.
A1  - Clyman M.J.
A1  - Decker A.
A1  - Ober W.B.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Three progestagen-estrogen compounds and 2 estrogen preparations were given cyclically to normally ovulating subjects. Twelve women received 10 mg daily of medroxyprogesterone acetate plus 0.05 mg of ethinyl estradiol (Provest); 5 received 1 mg daily of ethynodiol diacetate plus 0.1 mg of mestranol (Ovulen); 22 received 2.5 mg daily of noresthisterone acetate plus 0.05 mg of ethinyl estradiol (Norlestrin); 3 received 0.1 mg daily of mestranol; and 3 received 0.05 mg daily of ethinyl estradiol. Endometrial biopsies were taken from all patients at 5-day intervals - on days 6, 11 16, and 21. Only in a very few instances was there difficulty in obtaining sufficient material for study, and at no time did inflammatory or reparative phenomena attendant upon earlier biopsy obscure microscopic observations. In general, the pattern of response to the progestagen-estrogen compounds was that previously reported. Of the compounds studied, Provest produced the earliest and most extensive predecidual changes, and glandular secretion tended to persist longer in patients treated with this agent. Dilated venules were noted more frequently in biopsies from women given Norlestrin. Mestranol and ethinyl estradiol administration produced the endometrial pattern of an anovulatory cycle. Mitotic activity appeared reduced in biopsies from subjects given either compound; this possibility needs further study. However, in no instance did either of the 2 estrogens produce the morphologic changes that were seen with the progestagen-estrogen compounds. The method of serial biopsy of the same patient during a given cycle yields a more reliable gauge of the effects of a medication than does a single biopsy, and its recommended. (X.Zc.i*).
