T1  - Significance of dysmenorrhea in infertility. report of a preliminary study of therapy with a sequential estrogen-progestagen regimen
A1  - Roland M.
A1  - Clyman M.
A1  - Decker A.
A1  - Ober W.B.
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - The general impressions derived from this preliminary study are as follows. The sequential program of management appears to be moderately effective in providing relief from pain. Among those patients who did not obtain relief from 2 cycles of treatment, 9 had endometriosis; and 5 responded well after additional cycles of treatment. The sample is too small to permit conclusions as to the effectiveness of the program in correcting the infertility associated with dysmenorrhea in these patients. It is worth noting that more and more, culdoscopy is proving invaluable in the management of gynecologic conditions. Thus, in the present study, the 9 patients with endometriosis could have been diagnosed only by means of culdoscopy or laparotomy. With culdoscopy. it is possible to give the diagnosis of psychogenic dysmenorrhea a more firm foundation, since entities hardly diagnosable except by means of culdoscopy or laparotomy can be excluded. The placebo can be an important adjunct in the diagnosis of psychogenic dysmenorrhea. While, thus far, only 7 of the 44 infertile patiente conceived after treatment, such results compare favorably with those in a comparable number of patients having idiopathic infertility without dysmenorrhea who were treated according to a different plan of manage ment. The findings give no hint as to the mechanism by which induction of anovulation may help to correct the infertility associated with dysmenorrhea in these patients. It maybe speculated, however, that the physiologic rest afforded the hypothalamo-pituitary-gonadal axis by cyclic therapy may in some manner give rise to fertility by 'rebound'. (X, 2c*).
