T1  - Leprechaunism (Donohue's syndrome)
A1  - Kallo A.
A1  - Lakatos I.
A1  - Szijarto L.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - Two cases occurring in sisters are described. A main feature was the premature follicular maturation in the ovaries probably starting in the sixth to seventh intrauterine month with overproduction of estrogens. This resulted in enlargement of the nipples and external genitals, hypertrichosis, increased excretion of 17-ketosteroids, hyperplasia of islets of Langerhans, and large kidneys with calcium deposits in the collecting tubules. There was a suppression of growth hormone, resulting in delay of bone growth. The syndrome may be compared to the Stein-Leventhal syndrome of adults and could be regarded as its analogue occurring in intrauterine life or in infancy. Nothing is known as yet concerning the cause of the intrauterine follicular maturation.
