AN  - 281310105
T1  - The roentgenology of neonatal abdominal masses
A1  - Griscom N.T.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - A review of 117 abdominal masses found in the first 4 wk. of life shows that more than half were renal. Multicystic kidney disease was the most common diagnosis. Hydronephrosis, intestinal duplication, hydrometra or hydrocolpos, neuroblastoma, polycystic kidney disease, and ovarian cyst followed in frequency. Fewer than 15% of the masses were malignant. The clinical data in brief and the details of the roentgenographic findings are given. Use of good roentgenographic technique plus an appreciation of the principle of total body opacification will enable one to select the proper diagnosis from the many possibilities surprisingly often. Surgery permanently cured 60% of these newborns. Only one-fifth of the present series died soon after birth. Even malignant masses often responded well to therapy. In short, this material indicates that a vigorous and hopeful diagnostic and therapeutic approach is fully warranted when an abdominal mass is found in a newborn.
