T1  - Ovulation induction-inhibition test. its appucatlon to study of ethinyl estradiol. chlormadinone and norethindrone
T3  - Le 'test d'induction-inhibition de l'ovulation'. Son application al'etude de l'ethinyl-oestradiol de la chlormadinone et de la norethindrone
A1  - Gueguen J.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - A test is described called the ovulation induction-inhibition test, which was developed in an attempt to elucidate the site of action of the steroids inhibiting ovulation and the nature of the gonadotropin on which these substances act. The inclusion of dexamethasone also means that this test can be used to assess the capacity of the studied steroids to inhibit hyperandrogenism of ovarian origin. The test was carried out in 44 subjects using 3 steroids, ethinyl estradiol, chlormadinone and norethindrone. for which the results are given. In particular, it was found that blocking of ovulation by chlormadinone seems to be due to a peripheral action probably anti-LH and not to a hypothalamopituitary block and that the inhibitory action of ethinyl estradiol on ovarian androgens is superior to that of chlormadinone and norethindrone. An eatrogenic drug and, in particular. a so-called 'sequential' therapeutic drug appears therefore to be more appropriate for the treatment of ovarian hyperandrogenism than therapy by gestogens.
