T1  - Endocrine patterns in polycystic ovarian disease
A1  - Riley G.M.
A1  - Evans T.N.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - This study concerns 13 patients with poly cystic ovarian disease. Ovulatory cycles occurred in 12 patients following ovarian wedge resection, and 9 became pregnant. A prompt increase in gonadotropin excretion was the most constant change after wedge resection. A decrease in estrogen excretion was noted. The 17-ketosteroids determinations varied from higher to lower. Postoperative pregnanediol values were within normal limits characteristic of the follicular phase with 1 exception. All pregnanetriol levels were normal. The preliminary determinations of LH excretion revealed variations in patients with polycystic ovarian disease. It may occur during a normal ovulation cycle. It increases with a rise in urinary total gonadotropin. There is a prompt rise in gonadotropin excretion following wedge resections of the ovaries. Unless normal follicle maturation occurs within a few weeks after operation, the prognosis for restoration of ovulation cycles is poor. Low pregnanetriol levels suggest the absence of adrenal cortical hyperplasia.
