A1  - Smith K.D.
A1  - Steinberger E.
A1  - Perloff W.H.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - A report is given on 301 patients treated with prednisone. These patients suffered from 1 or more of the following symptoms: hirsutism, menstrual irregularity or infertility. 127 patients were diagnosed by peritoneoscopy and laparotomy. The state of the ovaries was described as large ovary with swollen or normal albuginea, and normal ovary with swollen or normal albuginea. The dose of prednisone was 10 mg/day. If improvement was observed, this was reduced to 7.5 mg in the 2nd mth. and to 5 mg in the 3rd mth. and it was kept at this point until regular menstruation appeared and lasted for 6-12 mth. If there was no improvement, or if the hirsutism was very marked, the 10 mg were kept up for 3-6 mth, or raised to 15 mg for 1 -2 mth. The decree of the response was similar in the patients, independently of the state of the ovaries or of its albuginea. It should be noted that the thicker the albuginea the more marked is the hirsutism. The results of the prednisone treatment are comparable with those of wedge excision, for which reason it is recommended to carry on with treatment for 1 yr. before deciding on operation.
