T1  - Treatment of anovulation
T3  - Traitement de aanovulation
A1  - Netter A.
A1  - Salomon-Bernard Y.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - Apart from the Stein-Leventhal syndrome which<< at least temporarily, is curable by wedge resection of the ovary, there was until recently no really efficient therapy for anovulation, particularly if this is due to lack of physiologic stimulation by FSH plus LH. Now the preparation of hormones of human origin with an elevated content of FSH has become possible. Hormones extracted from human pituitaries by Gemzell and Diczfalusy are very active but very rare, so that one has to mainly count on hormone extracted from urine of menopausal women (HMG), provided that it is rich in FSH and poor in LH. To obtain ovulation it is necessary to follow HMG injections by 1 or more injections of chorionic gonadotropin. The dosage is still under study but the results are remarkable. Ovulation may be achieved almost instantly. Women with only reduced urinary estrogens prior to treatment respond to weaker doses. The size of the ovaries must be followed by gynecologic examina t ions every 3rd day, since excessive treatment can produce enormous ovarian cysts which can rupture. The HMG hormones appear to be active in the Stein-Leventhal syndrome, and in Sheehan' s disease. Conversely, pituitary integrity is necessary for the action of Clomiphene. This agent seems to act either on ovarian receptivity or, more probably, through intermediation of the hypothalamus. The dosage, according to the authors , varies from 25 mg to 75 mg and even to 200 mg daily, and treatment duration ranges from 5-10 days up to various weeks. Ovulation can be achieved in 3 out of 4 cases, provided that amenorrhea is neither of menopausai nor of dysgenetic origin. Clomiphene had been suspected of producing fetal malformations but such malformations have occurred only in animals and following administration during pregnancy. The agent should only be used in the absence of ovulation and ovulation occurs only a certain time following the termination of the treatment. On the other hand Clomiphene, like HMG, is able to induce the formation of enormous functioning ovarian cysts which, if they do not rupture, disappear in the long run without treatment.
