N2  - Normal subjects and hirsute women with micropolycystic ovaries were treated with ethinyl-estrenol + 3-methoxy-ethinyl-estradiol (Lyndiol) to study the action of this compound on the production of androgene and on the urinary excretion of their metabolites. In normal men, the production of testosterone and the excretion of androsterone and etiocholanolone are suppressed, whereas the excretion of other 17-ketosteroids and the production of dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate are unchanged. Moreover, the LH activity in plasma is depressed. It seems that the preparation inhibits specifically testicular androgen production, by suppressing the hypothalamohypophyseal control of LH. Testosterone production and urinary 17-ketosteroid excretion are modified in the same way in women with Stein-LeventhaT s syndrome.
