T1  - ARTIFICIAL MENSTRUAL CYCLES INDUCED in OVULATING WOMEN by MONTHLY INJECTION of PROGESTOGEN-ESTROGEN
A1  - Reifensteir Jr. E.C.
A1  - Pratt T.E.
A1  - Hartzell K.A.
A1  - Shafer W.B.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - In 198 treatment cycles, 60 women with regular monthly cycles were given a single injection of 1 ml of a hormone combination, Deladroxate, containing 150 mg of dihydroxyprogesterone acetophenide and 10 mg of estradiol enanthate. The injection was given each month on day 7,8,9, or 10 after the onset of bleeding of the previous menstrual cycle, for up to 6 consecutive cycles. The study was performed by 5 investigators. Thus administered, Deladroxate induced consecutive monthly cycles of desquamation averaging 24.4-27.4 days in length, which were reasonably consistent from patient to patient, and which varied 6 days or less from cycle to cycle in the same individual in 88% of those injected on day 8, and 82% of those injected on day 7,9, or 10. Adequate monthly desquamation with bleeding was induced in consecutive cycles, averaging 6.0 day s in duration (range 4-8 days for 88%) and considered by the patients to be similar to their usual bleeding patterns in quantity (range moderately decreased to moderately increased for 93%). Ovulation was inhibited in the consecutive treatment cycles of all the women, as indicated by their pregnanediol levels. In most of the patients for whom treatment cycles had been discontinued, predominantly anovulatory cycles followed. Spontaneous monthly ovula tory cycles resumed approximately 2-4 mth after the injections were terminated. Deladroxate was well tolerated with a minimum of undesirable hormonal manifestations or unwanted local or systemic reactions to the injections. Only a few cycles with nausea, vertigo, dysmenorrhea, or breast discomfort were reported. None of the women experienced amenorrhea, hemorrhage, change in libido, edema, or any evidence of masculin! zation; none became pregnant while receiving the injections. The characteristics of the artificial cycles induced were indistinguishable from those associated with regular uvulatory cycle>>. The most consistent response was obtained when Deladroxate was injected on day 8 after the onset of bleeding of the previous cycle. On the basis of these findings, Deladroxate is being extensively evaluated as a preparation to provide conception control with a single once-a-month injection. In this evaluation, it is recommended that 1 ml of Deladroxate be administered as a deep i. m. injection on day 8 after the onset of desquamation bleeding, whether or not the flow has stopped. If bleeding failes to appear within 18-20 days, the dose of Deladroxate for the next cycle should be administered exactly 4 wk after the previous injection. When, rarely, day 8 is inconvenient, the dose should be given on day 7 or 9, after which the regimen of a single injection on day 8 should be resumed.
