T1  - Pathogenesis of psychogenic amenorrhea and anovulation
A1  - Igarashi M.
A1  - Tohma K.
A1  - Ozawa M.
A1  - Hosaka H.
A1  - Matsumoto S.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - Sixteen women showing amenorrhea or anovulation following acute psychic trauma, emotional stress, or environmental change were investigated. Urinary FSH was not at the abnormal high or normal high level in any case. It was at the normal medium level in 2 cases, the normal low level in 4. and the abnormal low level in 8. Urinary estrogen level was not elevated in any case. It was at the normal medium level in 3 cases, the normal low level in 9, and the abnormal low level in 4. The progesterone administration test, suggesting endogenous estrogen level, showed uterine bleeding in 10 cases and no bleeding in 6 cases. Urinary 17-KS level was at the abnormal high level in 6 cases, the normal high level in 7, the normal medium level in 1, and the normal low and abnormal low levels in none. Urinary 17-OHCS was at the abnormal high level in 7 cases, the normal high level in 7, the normal medium level in 2, and the normal low and abnormal low levels in none. Moreover. it was clearly demonstrated that low FSH level coincided well with high 17-KS and 17-OHCS levels in psychogenic amenorrhea and anovulation. These results suggest the following mechanism of psychogenic amenorrhea. Psychic trauma or emotional stress induces hypersecre tion of corticotropin releasing factor at the sacrifice of secretion of FSH- and LH-releasing factor at the hypothalamus level, resulting in hypersecretion of ACTH and hyposecretion of FSH and LH at the pituitary level. Psychogenic amenorrhea or anovulation will occur because of the reduction of FSH and LH release from the pituitary. In this investigation, there was no instance of normal FSH and low estrogen levels that could be called ' hypothalamic amenorrhea' as reported by Klinefelter et al. and Reifenstein.
