T1  - THE MORBIDITY of HYSTERECTOMY
A1  - Crisp W.E.
A1  - Sattenspiel E.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - Out of 1,028 cases of hysterectomy, performed for benign reasons in the authors' hospital in 1961, 807 operations were abdominal and 221 vaginal; the proportion, then, was 3.7:1, compared with a proportion of 15.8:1 in 1940. This change of proportions is explained by the authors primarily by the fact that many plastic repairs of vaginal prolapse were superseded by vaginal hysterectomy. They are far from propagating the vaginal approach; the route of access must depend on the nature of the disturbance and the surgeons' standpoint. In comparison with a statistic of Leventhal in 1951, morbidity appears to have but little improved. As far as vaginal operations are concerned, this can be explained by the fact that at present vaginal operations are also frequently performed in adnexal disease, which was formerly inadmissible. The type of anesthesia applied did not appear to be a factor in morbidity. There was a distinct decrease in hospital stay, i. e. from 11 to 8 days for both kinds of operation. The principal causes of morbidity were urologie disturbances: inflammations were prominent in vaginal, and injuries in abdominal operations. This can be explained satisfactorily by the cases in which abdominal operation was imperative, such as postinflammatory adhesions and endometriosis. And this is also the reason why disturbances of the intestinal tract are much more frequently present with abdominal than with vaginal operations; particularly cases of ileus are of frequent occurrence. Of less Import are: hemorrhage, phlebitis, and infection. As for the latter, it is imperative that after a conization of the cervix hysterectomy be performed within the first 48 hr., otherwise it is advisable to wait at least 6 wk.
