T1  - INDUCTION of OVULATION with HUMAN GONADOTROPINS and with CLOMIPHENE
A1  - Jones G.S.
A1  - De Moraes-Ruehsen M.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - All patients considered for therapy with human gonadotropins or clomiphene should have a complete diagnostic study for etiologic factors prior to initiation of treatment. Human gonadotropic therapy is ideal for the patient with hypogonadotropic primary amenorrhea but is also effective in hypogonadotropic axnenorrhea due to peychogenic and neurogenic factors. Patients with normal or elevated urinary gonadotropins should not be selected for this form of therapy. Clomiphene is ideally reserved for patients with anovulation due to disturbances of the hypothalamic nuclei, who have an intact pituitary and competent ovaries. It is believed that patients with the Stein-Leventhal syndrome can justifiably be classified in this group; when such patients are treated, great care must be exerted to avoid overdosage as their ovaries overreact in the same fashion as the adrenals in a patient with Gushing's disease given ACTH. Multiple ovulations with cysts and rupture can occur. For this reason it is also wise to preclude the possibility of pregnancy on the 1st course of therapy. Human pituitary gonadotropins, 40 U (NIH-FSH-Sl) containing as little as 0.04 IU of LH (NIH-LH-Sl)1 will cause immediate estrogen secretion, and 80IU will usually induce ovulation in a hypogonadotropic patient. However, this amount of luteal stimulation is apparently insufficient to induce normal luteal function. A 4-day luteal stimulation with 2,500 IU of chorionicgonadotropin daily is usually sufficient to induce an apparently normal corpus luteum with a 14-day life span. If chorionic gonadotropin stimulation is continued, the luteal function can be prolonged. By using multiple doses, 2 -4 times a day. ovulation can be effected with a smaller amount of human gonadotropin. This method not only conserves the gonadotropin supply but avoids the complications of overdosage, ovarian cyst formation, and multiple pregnancies. Human gonadotropins can be useful as a diagnostic tool for the demonstration of ovarian competence. A stimulation test can establish the diagnosis of premature ovarian failure as well as of pituitary hypogonadotropism. The dosage of clomiphene has not been completely standardized, but usually 50 mg. daily for a 5- or 10-day period is apparently satisfactory. Although the daily vaginal smear and basal body temperature chart are valuable clinical aids in the evaluation of therapeutic response when human pituitary gonadotropins are used, neither of these clinical aids are useful with clomiphene therapy. As clomiphene is apparently an antiestrogenic agent, it blocks the response of the vaginal mucosa; and because it causes the formation of ovarian cysts with release of progesterone or other, thermogenic steroids, it may cause a temperature rise without any other evidence of ovulation. It is therefore necessary to use urinary gonadotropin and/or estrogen assays to assess the initial response. Following cessation of the drug therapy, the vaginal smear and basal body temperature chart again become useful. (X, 2c,3).
