T1  - AMENORRHOEA
A1  - Jeffcoate T.N.A.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - Provided the uterus is present and capable of function, amenorrhea is usually caused by a failure of the ovary to produce estrogen and progesterone cyclically and in adequate amounts. Acquired disease of the ovary only occasionally causes amenorrhea. Amenorrhea due to failure of the gonad to develop or to differentiate to the female side is commonly associated with sex chromosome anomalies. Although an error in the biosynthesis of hormones by the ovary is a feature of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome, this is probably secondary to disturbances in the hypothalamic-pituitary system and the adrenal. It is liable to spontaneous cure, and resection of polycystic ovaries is often not the best treatment. Amenorrhea is rarely caused by organic disease in the hypothalamus and the pituitary, but is often associated with certain general disorders, with dietetic errors resulting in either an increase or a loss of weight, and with psychologic and environmental changes. Treatment of amenorrhea depends on its cause, and the determination of this requires full investigation, which should generally include bacteriologie examination of the endometrium to exclude tb. The prognosis is good in cases of secondary amenorrhea, menstruation returning in 60% of cases irrespective of treatment.
