T1  - EFFECT of ACTH and CHORIONIC GONADOTROPIN upon THE EXCRETION of ESTROGENS in WOMEN at THE ONSET of the MENOPAUSE (Russian)
A1  - Savchenko O.N.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - The effect of small doses of ACTH on the excretion of estrogens in 10 women during the menopause was determined. In order to ascertain whether the ovaries were sensitive to the effect of gonadotropic hormones after the menopause, chorionic gonadotropin was given to 2 women during the menopause. Single doses of 20 and 40 U of ACTH did not increase excretion of estrogens and pregnanediol; administration of the same doses for 2 days caused an increase of the excretion of estrogens and pregnanediol. but this increase was of short duration. Administration of chorionic gonadotropin did not cause any increase of estrogen or pregnanediol excretion. Administration of ACTH followed by chorionic gonadotropin did not influence the excretion of estrogens, which was high; the excretion of pregnanediol was low, and later on it increased slightly. The pattern described is characteristic of the anovulatory cycle; administration of chorionic gonadotropin did not lead to ovulation.
