T1  - INDUCTION of OVULATION with CLOMIPHENE
A1  - Pilldes R.B.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - Clomiphene (MRL-41; chloramphene) is a substance which can successfully be used for the induction of ovulation. Structurally, it is an analogue of the nonsteroidal estrogen chlorotrianisene (Tace). It is also similar to MER-25 and to MER-29 (triparanol). Originally, it was found to have an inhibitory effect on the pituitary gland. Later, it appeared also to be suitable for the induction of ovulation. The purpose of this study was to determine: (1) the ability of the drug to induce ovulation; (2) which conditions were most amenable to treatment; (3) its mechanism of action; (4) the effective dosage; and (5) side effects and toxicity. The author studied 36 patients with amenorrhea of long duration and various origin. All patients had been subjected to an exhaustive endocrinologie examination. Empirically, the optimal dosage was found to be 75 mg/day during 5 days. In responsive patients, the effect appeared within 8 days. Nonresponsive cases were of the Stein -Leventhal or the adrenogenital type. The criteria of responsiveness were a resultant secretory endometrium or pregnancy. Out of the 36 cases. 18 responded; 4 of these became pregnant. The basal temperature curve responded in 70% within 8 days. The author wishes to stress that a typical basal temperature shift is unreliable for evaluating ovulation (ovarian cysts can also cause a thermogenic shift). Hormone assays: Follicle-stimulating hormone: in approximately 50% an increase in FSH excretion was found. Luteinizing hormone: tests seemed to indicate an increased production. 17-Ketosteroids: about one half of the patients exhibited normal values; in the rest, there were increases and decreases. 17-Hydroxycorticoide: the changes paralleled those found with 17-ketoateroid excretion. Estrogens: Clomiphene administered to patients after hysterectomy and oophorectomy gave an increase in estrogen excretion. The author concludes that the adrenals were the source of the increase in estrogens in these rases. Pregnanediol: in general, no changes could be noted aside from an increase with ovulation. Two patients exhibited a marked increase in pregnanediol with therapy despite a failure to ovulate. Histologie findings: the pituitary gland obtained from 1 case treated with Clomiphene could be examined. The gland contained an increased number of S-I cells. The findings in the ovaries were similar to those reported as produced by gonadotropins. The endometrium was hypoplastic. Adrenal and thyroid glands did not reveal any unusual features. Complications: out of 36 patients. 17 developed ovarian cysts which disappeared spontaneously or after administration of androgens. The development of ovarian cysts was definitely related to the total dosage. Side effects: lower abdominal pain (cysts); hot flushes (dependent on dosage); skin rash (pruritic); blurred vision; nervousness; urinary frequency. Toxicity: out of 22 cases, 11 showed a decrease in prothrombin time after therapy, regardless of dosage. No bleeding tendencies have been noted clinically. Liver function tests gave no significant changes. Mechanism of action: Clomiphene exerts its primary action by stimulating estrogen synthesis. Any stimulation of the pituitary or the hypothalamus is secondary. There still remain unsolved problems.
