T1  - Studies on ovarian tissue culture
A1  - Honda A.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - Series 1: When fragments of ovaries of immature mice were cultured, the ova in the follicles present in the fragments continued to survive for about 1 week. The ova in the marginal areas of the fragments entered the medium by means of migration and outgrowth of the cells constituting the ovarian follicles. On the other hand, the ova in the inner areas of the ovarian tissue degenerated within 15 days. The cells of the ovaries except the ova continued to proliferate for longer than 2 months. Series 2: It was investigated whether the morphological structure of isolated ovarian, fragments and the propagation of the strain cells from the ovary of an adult rabbit could be influenced by gonadotrophic hormones in vitro. Isolated ovarian fragments of immature mice could be influenced by the hormones in vitro, i.e. they substantially retained their morphological structure and there was an increase in the rate of cell multiplication of the strain when they were cultured in hormone-enriched medium. Series 3: Adult human ovaries were divided into stroma, cortex, follicles, corpus luteum cells and granulosa cells, and each of them was cultured. The corpus luteum cells could not be cultured in vitro, whereas the other cells could be easily cultured.
