T1  - 'cure' of a hirsute female with diabetes mellitus by means of a synthetic compound (op'ddd) which destroys the adrenals
T3  - 'Gueris on d'un diabete sucre chez une femme a barbe par un antisurrenalien de synthese (op'DDD)
A1  - Klotz H.-P.
A1  - Grunfeld J.P.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - Ortho paraprimary dichlorodiphenyldichlorethane (op'DDD) in high doses destroys the reticular and fascicular layers of the adrenal cortex, moderate doses inhibiting the adrenal cortex in a reversible manner by enzymatic block between DELTA5-pregnenolone and 17-OH-progesterone and by peripheral inactivation. This compound was used to treat a female patient, 43 yr of age, with a diabetic mother and herself presenting long-standing hypertrichosis associated with menstrual disorders. Biological tests showed raised 17-ketosteroids and a prediabetic induced glycemic curve without a tumor image in the retroneumoperitoneum. Cortisone therapy did not improve the hirsutism and castration was performed for sclerocystic ovaritis. The diabetes melltus became overt, necessitating 4 tablets of glucophage daily. Treatment with op'DD was initiated with high doses of 5 and 3 g, and then a maintenance dose of 1 g normalized the glucemia, so allowing glucophage to be stopped. The hypertrichosis regressed, and the general condition improved. The suprarenals remained sensitive in the Thorn test. Digestion and blood tolerance were good. In conclusion, it is proposed that op'DDD or better mp'DDD be used as a possible adjuvant therapy for diabetes mellitus that is difficult to stabilize.
