T1  - A new test of pituitary acth reserve by use of su4885 (adrenocortical 11beta -hydroxylase inhibitor) and routine methods for determination of urinary corticoids in clinical and normal cases (japanese)
A1  - Imoto H.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - In normal subjects, the Su-4885 test caused an increase in urinary excretion of direct 17-KGS to 2-3 times the original value. One patient with prediabetes revealed a normal response to the Su-4885 test and a marked response to the ACTH-Z test. The response to the Su-4885 test was impaired in 2 diabetic patients, but was normal in 5 other diabetic patients. The response to the Su-4885 test was good in a case of myxedema and a case of Stein-Leventhal syndrome, while it was slightly impaired in a case of insnlema and a case of insulome and a case of hyperthyroidiom. Both the responce to the Su-4885 test and that to the ACTH-Z test were impaired in a case of hypophyseal insufficiency. Adrenocortical insufficiency was denied by the Su-4885 test and ACTHZ test in 2 cases in which it was suspected. The Su-4885 test and ACTH-Z test disclosed slightly impaired reactions in a case of obesity with pink striae, but normal reactions in a case of pituitary tumor. The responses to the Su-4885 test and ACTH-Z test were normal in 11 cases of emaciation due to gastric ulcer and gastroptosis, impaired in a case of mucocutaneous syndrome, accelerated in a case of Crouzon's disease, normal in a case of paralytic attacks and normal in a case of juvenile hypertension. The Su-4885 test caused no side effect except for diarrhea and abdominal pain in 2 of 36 cases examined.
