T1  - A case of stein-leventhal syndrome (japanese)
A1  - Itakura H.
A1  - Chiba S.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - A 21-year-old woman complained of obesity, hirsutism and menstrual disturbance. She had striae over her lower abdomen and xanthoma on her right foot. The basal temperature was monophasic and the clitoris was slightly hypertrophie. Blood pressure was 130/72. The serum cholesterol level was 500 mg. %. The plasma total fatty acid, total lipid and triglyc1 ride were slightly elevated, but free fatty acid was normal. Urinary gonadotropin, 17-OHCS, I7-KS, pregnanetriol, estrogen and 1 i-oxy-i 7KGS were normal, but uruiary pregnanediol was lowered to 0. 6 mg. /day and urinary 1 i-deoxy-i7KGS were increased to 4. 3 mg. /day. Cortisol secretion rate was normal (14. 6 mg. /day), while dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA) production rate was increased (39 mg. /day). A normal reaction was obtained to the ACTH test and the dexamethasone suppression test, but no significant elevation of 17-OHCS was seen in the metopirone test. Administration of 2, 000 U. of FSH and LH with 2 mg. of dexamethasone was followed by a rise of urinary pregnanediol to normal and an increase in estrogen and n-deoxy-i7 KGS to about two-fold. SteinLeventhal syndrome was suspected clinically from these findings. Typical polycystic ovary was noted at operation. Analysis by gas-liquid chromatography revealed that estrone, estradiol and testosterone were not present in the ovarian venous blood, cystic fluid and peripheral blood. DHEA and 4-androstene-dione were detected only in the cystic fluid. A significant increase hi the 'Compound X was found in these samples. It is considered that this case had failure of 3(5-01 dehydrogenase and aromatizing enzyme. After wedge resection, a regular cycle was restored and hirsutism decreased. No significant reduction of body weight was seen, but striae disappeared. Ueda - Tokyo.
