T1  - Hormonal excretion and coagulation factors during oral gestagen-oestrogen therapy. Assessment of the risk of thrombophlebitis
T3  - Hormonausscheidungen und blutgerinnungsfaktoren unter oraler gestagen-ostrogen-behandlung (beurteilung des thrombophlebitis risikos)
A1  - Haller J.
A1  - Konig A.
A1  - Poliwoda H.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - Four patients with secondary amenorrhea and proved anovulatory cycles in whom an excretion of hormonal metabolites independent of the menstrual cycle could be assumed were studied. The following tests were carried out prior, during and following the 20 day course of Anovlar: recalcification time (Howell time, citrate plasma), thromboplastin time (Quick value), thrombelastography (Hartert's method). Hirst test, suction cup test (Kuchmeister). The following determinations were done from the 24-hour urine: total estrogen excretion (Ittrich), pregnanediol (Klopper, Michie and Brown), 17-ketogenic steroids (Zimmermann) and 17-ketosteroids (Zimmermann, Anton and Pontius). During the first 8-10 days of hormonal treatment an activation of the clotting mechanism was found. After discontinuation of the treatment a moderate fibrinolysis was shown. However, none of the values was higher than the upper limit of normal. The capillary fragility tests showed no abnormalities. The total estrogen excretion was increased during treatment with norethisterone acetate and ethinol estradiol in 3 out of 4 patients. This was probably due to the administered estrogen and to the estrogenic breakdown products of norethisterone acetate. The pregnanediol excretion did not vary significantly. The 17-ketogenic steroids decreased in 2 patients with high pre-treatment values and increased in 2 patients with moderate or low pre-treatment values. It decreased in all 4 patients after cessation of treatment. In 3 out of 4 patients the 17-ketosteroids rose slightly during treatment, one high initial value decreased during treatment. In 2 patients a high excretion of total estrogens was associated with thrombelastographic signs of increased coagulability. No significant correlation between the hormonal excretions and the investigation of the clotting mechanism was found. Our results support the findings that the oral administration of estrogen-progestin combinations does not significantly increase the risk of thrombophlebitis.
