T1  - Operative treatment of adenocarcinoma of the endometrium in obese women
A1  - Prem K.A.
A1  - Mensheha N.M.
A1  - McKelvey J.L.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - All patients admitted to the service with a final diagnosis of endometrial adenocarcinoma are included provided the admission weight was at least 200 pounds; only those with previous therapy which interfered with the planned routine are excluded. The selected weight was 30-50% over the average of the 40-70 yr age group during this period (1939-1963). All patients were followed to death or to the conclusion of the study in 1963. Altogether 98 patients met the criteria for study out of a total of 486 patients; 72 weighed under 250 pounds and five 300 or more. The age distribution followed that of the total series, although obesity was greater in the 60 to 69-yr group. About 30% were nulliparous. 1 of whom had Stein-Leventhal ovaries. Slightly more than 50% had abnormal glucose tolerance tests. Of these, 88 were treated surgically with 3 postoperative deaths; 2 refused operation and 8 were clinically or technically inoperable. There was a 12% morbidity which included 1 evisceration. 2 thrombophlebitides, 2 patients with atelectasis and 2 with cardiac complications. Operative procedures were: abdominal hysterectomy (77). vaginal hysterectomy (6), Wertheim's operation (1), and exploration only (5). The surgical rate was not influenced by weight, but the mortality under 250 pounds was 1.5%. and over 250 pounds 7.7%. The absolute rate of survival through 1958 was 68% for the lighter ones and 53% for the heavier group; 5- to 20-yr survival rates were equal or better in this group than in the nonobese. but this is nullified after 20 yr because of the decreased life expectancy in the obese. Of those who died, 13 had recurrences and 1 had ovarian cancer; 4 had cardiovascular disease and 2 were operative; the rest were untreated or technically inoperable. It is concluded that obesity alone should not be a deterrent to surgery in the treatment of adenocarcinoma of the endometrium. Standard techniques can be safely applied to this group of patients.
