T1  - Further observations on the effects of clomiphene citrate in anovulatory females
A1  - Kistner R.W.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - The author summarizes the alterations which occurred in the endometrium of 50 women treated with clomiphene citrate, under the following groups: (A) those with atrophie endometrium, (B) those with a proliferative aspect, (C) those with a hyperplastic, anaplastic endometrium ur carcinoma in situ. The action of the preparation is not altogether clear. The dosage was 200 mg daily for 3 days or 100 mg for 5 days. For patients with the Stein-Lev, nthal syndrome a lower dosage is generally recommended. Before the commencement of treatment the following tests are performed: 17-ketosteroids, FSH, PAI, X-ray of the sella turrica, culdoscopy, curettage, vaginal smear. The patient must record a temperature curve. When after institution of the treatment a hemorrhage occurred, a nrucrocurettagt was performed, in the aosence of nemorrhage, signs ot pregnancy were sought for. Group A: In this group were 25 women ranging in age from 18 to 35 yr. One had an atrophie endometrium subsequent to curettage for abortion, 6 had developed the disturbance following usage of mpdroxyprogeeterone. Three patients had more than 20 mg of ketosteroids and had been treated unsuccessfully with hydrocurtisone. In 2 of these ovulatior could be induced with chlomiphene. In 130 cycles treated, 57 ovulations occurred, i.e. in 22 of 25 women teated. Of the 3 failures, 2 showed the picture of hypogonadism. Group B: There were 14 patients. In all of them ovulation was obtained. Group C. In this group there were 11 patients. Two of them had been operated on previously for Stein-Leventhal's syndrome, and in 2 others culdoscopyshowed distinctly enlarged ovaries (Stein-Leventhal). In 45 cycles treated 41 ovulations occurred. With patients in all the groups pregnancies occurred. Strikingly, in 3/4 of the cases this happened after only 1 treatment course. The proper indication for chlomiphene are those women who show signs of follicle maturation but in whom ovulation does not occur. They have normal or somewhat increased values of kctosteroids, a normal thyroid function, normal sella X-rays and normal or somewhat decreased gonadotropin values. There should be sufficient eetronr production (vaginal smear, resp. microcurettage). If decreased estrone values are found, various treatment courses are necessary. Precautions: (1) Close watch must be made for ovarian cysts. The formation of these may be the coriseauence of therapy. No surgical treatment is needed. (2) Liver function tests must be normal. (3) Malignancy must be excluded by curettage. Some women complain of hot flushes or suffer from transient disturbances. Chlomiphene should be considered an efficacious agent in the treatment of patients with the Stein-Leventhal syndrome. Stehouwer The Hatue.
