AN  - 287033463
T1  - Primary amenorrhoea. a study with special reference to the morphology of the genital organs
A1  - Bjoro K.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - The purpose of this study was to clarify the nature of the pathophysiologic process underlying primary amenorrhea in 85 patients. The pathogenesis of the 'streak' gonads and the polycystic ovaries was given particular attention. The patients were classified on the basis of the morphology of the genital organs. Two main groups were established, normally formed vagina and cervix (57 patients) and malformed vagina and cervix (28 patients). Morphologic studies were correlated with observations obtained by other diagnostic aids, including chromosome studies and hormone assays. Maldeveloped ovaries with the naked-eye appearance of 'streak' gonads were found in 20 patients of group A. Thirteen patients presenting features of Turner's syndrome were in this group. 'Streak* gonads were found in 7 apparently normal females. In these patients the sex chromosome complement corresponded to the normal female. Vaginal smears, endometrial biopsies and hormone assays could not differentiate between the 2 types of 'streak' gonads. Polycystic ovaries varying in size, were found in 37 patients of group A. The endocrine studies did not reveal total pituitary failure in any case. Twenty-five patients in group B demonstrated morphologically similar malformations, probably due to irregularities of fusion in the lower portions of the Mullerian ducts. The ovaries showed persistence of corpora lutea. The cytogenetic observations indicated that abnormalities of the sex chromosomes complement do not usually occur in these patients. The syndrome of 'testicular feminization' was diagnosed in 3 patients with blindly ending vagina. The testes were located in inguinal hernias in these cases.
