AN  - 287103139
T1  - Some effects of sex hormones on the fetus amd newborn in relation to later reproductive functions
A1  - Jacobsohn D.
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - The investigations discussed in the paper show that an upset of the equilibrium of sex hormones during embryonic development can lead to persistent disturbances which show most clearly in an inability of females to reproduce when grown up. Most studies were performed on the rat, which implies serious limitations to the validity of general conclusions. Clinical observations such as made by Wilkins on female pseudohermaphrodites agree with those made on rats, however, and it does not seem impossible that one of the variants of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome will be found comparable with the anovulatory ovaries of 'androgenized' rats. The use of the rat was fortunate insofar as it revealed that the development of the reproductive system had during fetal life not advanced sufficiently to withstand influences of sex hormones. The differentiation of the tissues concerned could be influenced even after birth. For technical reasons the condition prevailing in the rat is useful to the experimenter, but with regard to human pathology and pharmacology, other species, notably primates, should be studied. As is apparent from the present report, investigations on further species would benefit from anatomic work filling the gaps in our knowledge of the ontogenesis of the brain regions involved in reproduction. The field of research presented would seem to open new avenues of approach toward a better understanding of abnormalities in sex life both as to physiologic and psychologic factors.
