T1  - Ovarian tumour and pregnancy
T3  - Ovarialtumor und schwangerschaft
A1  - Frank G.
A1  - Buttenberg D.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - A description is given of the diagnosis and treatment in 34 cases. The histological nature of the tumours and the clinical course are presented in tabular form. Fifteen times operation was practised during pregnancy, 7 times during parturition, and 4 times post partum. Four patients with cystic ovaries or retention cysts could be treated by puncture. In 4 other patients with cystic ovaries conservative measures were taken. Favourable therapeutic results are obtained when the tumour is diagnosed at the beginning of pregnancy and is operated on during the first half of gestation. When it is clear that the patient has a cystic ovary, conservative treatment suffices. In the second half of pregnancy it will only rarely be possible to diagnose an ovarian tumour. Intra partum and in the puerperium complications may occur due to the fact that the tumour constitutes an obstacle to delivery, ruptures during delivery, or that a derangement of alimentary functions leads to an acute condition. If an operation has to be performed at the end of pregnancy, then a caesarean section is necessary, at the same time.
