T1  - THE USE of CULDOSCOPY in 1,000 PATIENTS (Japanese)
A1  - Hayashi M.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - Culdoscopy was successful in 944 patients and unsuccessful in 56. The difficulty was due to an ovarian cyst in 1 case and to an adherent retroflexed uterus in another; the remaining 54 all had adhesions of Douglas' pouch. In 813 cases the complaint was sterility (primary sterility in 626 and secondary sterility in 187). Chromoculdoscopy was performed in all 813. Stenosis of the fallopian tube was found in 46.4% and adhesions in 45.4%. In the great majority, tubal stenosis was bilateral. Abnormality of the ovary was noted in 11.2% and of the corpus luteum in 9.5%; tubercles were seen in 8.6%, uterine myomata in 2.7%, hypoplasia of the uterus in 2.7%, endometriosis in 1.1%, and no abnormality in 9.7%. Salpingography and culdoscopy were combined in 210 cases. Of the 67 cases in which both tubes were found to be patent by salpingography, patency was also proved in 60 by culdoscopy. Of 34 cases in which only one uterine tube was found to be patent by salpingography, the same tube was found to be patent in 14 cases by culdoscopy. Of 109 cases in which both tubes were found by salpingography to be obstructed, 97 were noted by culdoscopy to be obstructed. Culdoscopy proved to be more accurate than tubal insufflation. It was also useful in determining the cause of amenorrhea and anovulatory menstruation.
