T1  - EFFECTS of CLOMIPHENE CITRATE on ANOVULATORY OVARIAN FUNCTION
A1  - Riley G.M.
A1  - Evans T.N.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - Clomiphene citrate causes an increase in total gonadotropin either via the hypothalamus or by direct action on the anterior pituitary with an increase in both FSH and LH fractions. This nonsteroid chemical appears to alter the pituitaryovarian relationships so that ovulation may occur in 2 groups of anovulatory women: (1) those in a relatively continuous estrogenic state with normal estrogen levels and (2) those with selective depression of pituitary gonadotropin. Ovarian wedge resections have proved effective in the first but not in the second group. Short, high dose courses, e.g., 150 to 200 mg. orally of clomiphene citrate daily for 3 days<< produce profound pituitary and ovarian activity and minimize side effects incurred by prolonged treatment. Vaginal smears do not serve as a useful criterion of ovulation in the patient takrng clomiphene in view of the pseudopregnancy effects of the drug and a decrease in the pyknotic index at the time of probable ovulation. There was no evidence of adrenal suppression as indicated by little change in 17ketosteroid excretion rates in most patients. Ovulation apparently occurred in 16 of 34 anovulatory women. Five became pregnant, and 1 was delivered of twins. Ovulation occurred in 5 of 12 patients who had transient or no benefit from previous ovarian wedge resections, and 2 of these have conceived. Evidence of clomiphene induction of multiple ovulations and the prompt conception of twins in one patient lead to conjecture about the effect this drug might have on the frequency of multiple pregnancies in both normal and anovulatory women. The remarkable effects of this drug and related experimental data now available, open new avenues for investigation of the mechanism of ovulation and its control.
