A1  - Kase N.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - Various theories have been suggested to account for increased output of androgens in women who have polycystic ovaries. Three cases of the polycystic ovary syndrome are presented. After wedge resection normal periods were restored and two of them completed a normal pregnancy. From a chemical study of the tissue removed the biosynthetic processes were noted to be qualitatively similar to those of the normal ovarian follicle. This study suggests that excess production of the androgens, testosterone, dehydroepiandrosterone, and DELTA<ovid:sup>4</ovid:sup>-androstene-3,17-dione noted in the polycystic tissue may be due to the number of active follicles available for steroidogenesis rather than a reflection of a biosynthetic enzyme 'block'. It is also suggested that when the excess androgen is produced in the polycystic ovary, favorable results may be anticipated from wedge resection.
