N2  - The term of 'common hypertrichosis' was used for these 42 cases of hyperandrogenism from ovarian dystrophy. The clinical diagnosis is based on phenomena of virilization (hypertrichosis, acne, etc.), menstrual disturbances and neurological symptoms. Additional examinations are: hormonal estimations, vaginal or rectal palpation. Coelioscopy or gynaecography were not done as laparotomy is indicated in each case of ovarian hyperandrogenism, confirmed by biological examinations. The differential diagnosis includes congenital hypertrichosis, Cushing syndrome, adrenal virilization and ovarian tumors. A description is given of surgical techniques: exploration of the ovarian hilus, cuneiform resection, sometimes decortication of the ovaries and if necessary a static reconstruction of the genital organs (e.g. rectification of retro-deviation of the uterus). Several micrographs of the morbid-anatomical findings in the surgical specimens illustrate the findings. The results are described; follow-up was impossible for long periods. There were 3 pregnancies, hypertrichosis did not disappear, regularization of the menstrual cycle was seen. Many references are given.
