T1  - The therapeutic effects of human pituitary gonadotrophins
A1  - Edwards R.L.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - This hormone is prepared from a limited number of dried human pituitaries obtained at autopsy, which had previously had the growth hormone removed. Two groups of patients were treated i.e., secondary amenorrhea of long standing, and those exhibiting the Stein-Leventhal syndrome. In the secondary amenorrhea series 11 patients were treated and ovulation and menstruation occurred in every case. Moreover, 9 of those patients subsequently became pregnant. Two patients did not become pregnant, the first gave up treatment on account of severe dysmenorrhea and the second ovulated repeatedly but failed to conceive. In the Stein-Leventhal syndrome group, there were 5 patients treated. All presented the usual features of abnormal menstruation, hirsutism and enlarged micropolycystic ovaries. Full endocrine studies combined with the typical appearance of the ovarian tissue on histological examination clinched the diagnosis. All showed the return of normal ovulatory cycles and in 3 the hirsutism was markedly decreased. The induction of ovulation using human gonadotrophins may open the way to a medical, as opposed to a surgical line of treatment. However, ill-judged doses of these potent therapeutic agents can cause gross damage. At present it is not possible for this very potent material to be made generally available. The dosage is still uncertain, and the author is just beginning to find its place in gynecological and endocrinological therapy.
