T1  - Hormonal investigations in the polycystic ovarian syndrome
A1  - Cassano C.
A1  - Conti C.
A1  - Forchielli E.
A1  - Capone M.
A1  - Sorcini G.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - The investigation was carried out on 14 Stein-Leventhal patients, the diagnosis being based on clinical, radiological, and in some instances surgical observations. The characteristic in all these cases was hirsutism, which only rarely assumed the aspects of true virilism. At the time of hospitalization most of the patients were amenorrheic. Pelvic examination revealed with few exceptions no increase in ovarian volume. The common feature was the pelviographic report which demonstrated enlarged ovaries showing at times polycystic contours. Hormonal investigations revealed the polycystic ovarian syndrome to be characterized in many cases by elevated plasma testosterone levels, normal total and fractionated 17-KS, normal urinary estrogens, normal urinary and plasma 17 -OHCS, and normal response to ACTH and HCG stimulation. Other cases, which from the clinical point of view appeared similar could be distinguished on the basis of a normal or low level of plasma testosterone, a significantly elevated total urinary 17-KS, dehydroepiandrosterone, and 11-oxy-17-KS. In these cases, ACTH stimulation results in a marked increase in the dehydroepiandrosterone fraction and the 11-oxy-17-KS, while HCG stimulation produces an effect which is comparable to that seen in the normal. In a few cases, the same clinical picture can be characterized by normal or subnormal levels of plasma testosterone and urinary 17-KS. In all cases treated surgically there is the clinical improvement after ovarian wedge-resection and, irrespective of the presurgical levels, the 17-KS as well as the plasma testosterone drop significantly. Concluding, the authors think that the syndrome is a functional abnormality affecting both the ovary and the adrenals.
