T1  - Clomiphene citrate in the management of anovulatory uterine bleeding
A1  - Puebla R.A.
A1  - Greenblatt R.B.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - During a woman's reproductive life excessive anovulatory bleeding is frequently encountered, particularly at the postmenarchal and premenopausal periods. The excessive bleeding stems from an endometrium that has been subjected to unopposed or persistent estrogen stimulation without the modifying influences of endogenous progesterone. Nutritional, emotional and metabolic factors contribute to the genesis of the disorder. When estrogen and progesterone are rapidly withdrawn, as in the normal menstrual cycle, shedding of the endometrium is rapid and the flow lasts two to six days. Estrogen breakthrough bleeding or withdrawal bleeding is often prolonged. Clomiphene citrate 1-p(beta-diethylaminoethoxy)phenyl-1,2-diphenyl-2-chloroethylene citrate, because of its ability to induce ovulation, was administered to 26 patients with excessive anovulatory uterine bleeding. Of the 129 menstrual cycles during which the drug was administered, 105 cycles (81.3%) were ovulatory and were followed by normal uterine bleeding. After clomiphene was discontinued, observations made in 52 cycles showed that only 20 (38.4%) were ovulatory.
