T1  - Diagnostic ovarian stimulation with heterologous gonadotrophin
A1  - Shearman R.P.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - Using heterologous serum gonadotrophin, a diagnostic ovarian stimulation test has been developed which has proved of assistance in the differential diagnosis of 'no cause' secondary amenorrhoea. Thirteen patients with hypothalamic/hypogonadotrophic amenorrhoea showed a modest increase in the urinary excretion of oestrone, levels rising from less than 4 mug. to 8-14 mug. /24 hours. In four subjects with polycystic ovaries the excretion of oestrone rose to at least 50 mug. /24 hours. Four of the former group were treated with human follicle-stimulating hormone and human chorionic gonadotrophin. Three showed hormonal evidence of ovulation and two conceived in the first cycle of treatment. Three of the four subjects with polycystic ovaries were subjected to bilateral ovarian wedge resection and each now has regular ovulatory menstruation.
