T1  - Pattern of steroidogenesis of androgens in the normal ovary associated with rhythmic processes of the menstrual cycle
A1  - Duboff G.S.
A1  - Behrman S.J.
A1  - Saraiya H.
A1  - Catchick J.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - In vitro experiments with 20-mu tissue slices of normal human ovaries covering Days 5 to 24 of the menstrual cycle and incubated aerobically with Krebs-Ringer phosphate-glucose buffer provided with 1-C<ovid:sup>14</ovid:sup>-acetate showed that incorporation of C<ovid:sup>14</ovid:sup> during biosynthesis of steroids was greater in the hilum than in the cortical-medullary tissues. By means of comparative paper chromatograms of authentic crystalline steroid compounds and extracts of incubation products the following were also noted: (1) There was a significant variation in the magnitude and distribution of biosynthesis of androstenedione, dehydroisoandrosterone, testosterone, as well as epitestosterone, pregnenolone, 17alpha-hydroxypregnenolone, progesterone, and 17alpha-hydroxyprogesterone, in the tissues associated with the phases of the menstrual cycle. (2) Androstenedione and 17alpha-hydroxyprogesterone production reached a peak at the preovulatory phase, and dehydroisoandrosterone and 17alpha-hydroxypregnenolone formation reached a peak at the midluteal phase. The significance of these findings in relation to normal in-vivo conditions suggests that the normal human ovary is capable of secreting a series of steroids, including androgens. This capability, which had been associated with pathologic conditions of the gland, appears now to be necessary for maintaining the ovary in such a state that it is capable of a smooth and regular activity that is essential if this activity is to be coordinated with ovulation and the secretory activity of the uterus following appropriate and adequate stimulus by anterior pituitary hormones. A new theory is postulated as a possible molecular basis for the formation of the 'Stein-Leventhal' type ovary.
