A1  - MacLeod S.C.
A1  - Morse W.I.
A1  - Hirsch S.
A1  - Tompkins M.G.
A1  - Jacey G.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - The menstrual cycles of 15 oligomenorrheic women were investigated before and during placebo and prednisone administration for 6 months each. Two of the patients had the Stein-Leventhal syndrome the others had no well-defined organic cause for oligomenorrhea. Hirsutism was present in 10 patients and 2 had palpably enlarged ovaries. Ten participants were interviewed by a psychiatrist. Seven of 12 patients showed improvement in menstrual frequency during prednisone therapy; 9 of 15 improved with placebo. Conclusions were: (1) prednisone lacked specific therapeutic value, (2) investigation of the patient and administration of placebo often improved ovarian function and (3) emotions play a role since two thirds of those investigated had psychiatric illness.
