T1  - Ovarian tumor and pregnancy
T3  - Ovarialtumor und schwangerschaft
A1  - Frank G.
A1  - Buttenberg D.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - A description is given of the diagnosis and treatment in 34 patients in whom an ovarian tumor was diagnosed during pregnancy. The histological nature of the tumors and the clinical course are presented in tabular form. Fifteen times operation was practised during pregnancy, 7 times during parturition, and 4 times post partum. Four patients could be treated by a puncture after radioscopy of Douglas' pouch in cystic ovaries or in retention cysts. In 4 other patients conservative measures were taken for cystic ovaries. Favorable therapeutic results are obtained when the tumor is diagnosed at the beginning of pregnancy and is operated on during the first half of gestation. When it is clear that the patient has a cystic ovary, a conservative treatment suffices. In the second half of pregnancy it will only rarely be possible to diagnose an ovarian tumor. The importance of examination at the beginning of pregnancy is emphasized. Intra partum and in the puerperium complications may occur due to the fact that the tumor constitutes an obstacle to delivery, ruptures during delivery, or that a derangement of alimentary functions leads to an acute condition. If an operation has to be performed at the end of pregnancy, then a cesarean section is necessary, at the same time, so that the patient is placed in unfavorable circumstances in view of a following pregnancy and delivery.
