T1  - Use of small doses of estrogen in ovarian dysfunction
A1  - Jefferies W.M.
A1  - Michelakis A.M.
A1  - Weir W.C.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - Smaller doses of estrogen than customary replacement doses have been administered continuously except during menstruation to 12 patients with ovarian dysfunction manifested by irregular menstrual cycles or anovulation. The administration may result not only in clinical improvement but also in an impressive decrease in urinary 17-ketosteroid excretion. No patient had any change in the excretion of cortisol metabolites. The observations are consistent with the hypothesis that these women have defects in the steroid pathway of estrogen synthesis which result in an excessive production of precursors that are excreted as 17-ketosteroids, and that estrogen produces clinical improvement by restoring a normal relationship between the pituitary and the ovaries. Preliminary evidence was also found that some patients may have concomitant defects in steroid pathways in both the adrenals and the ovaries.
