T1  - Induction of ovulation with clomiphene citrate
A1  - Naville A.H.
A1  - Kistner R.W.
A1  - Wheatley R.E.
A1  - Rock H.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - Twenty-one anovulatory patients were treated in 89 cycles with varying dosage schedules of clomiphene citrate, a nonsteroidal, nonhormonal, synthetic drug, in an effort to induce ovulation. Fourteen patients showed signs of ovulation (by basal body temperature graph, endometrial biopsies, urinary pregnanediol, and qualitative and quantitative similarity of the menstrual flow in ovulatory cycles); 3 pregnancies occurred. Fifteen patients with irregular ovulation were treated in 65 cycles; 14 patients indicated ovulation in 49 cycles, with 5 conceptions. The addition of estrogen seemed unnecessary except in patients with estrogen deficiency. There was no change in 17-ketosteroids and no clinical evidence of androgenicity. Total urinary gonadotropins were increased in approximately half the cases. No serious side-effects were observed. The most likely patient to respond to clomiphene citrate is one with secondary amenorrhea and fairly normal endocrine laboratory tests.
