T1  - Multiple pregnancy following wedge resection in the Stein-Leventhal syndrome
A1  - Stein I.F.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - The Stein-Leventhal syndrome, consisting of secondary anovulation, sterility, and bilateral polycystic ovaries, is well recognized. In about 3/4 of the patients one finds a small uterus and atrophic breasts. In approximately 1/2, hirsutism is present; virilism with clitoral or labial hypertrophy or deepening of the voice rarely occurs. The 4 methods of visual diagnosis available to the gynecologist are colpotomy, culdoscopy, gynecography, and laparotomy. The chief differential diagnosis is the adrenogenital syndrome. The most effective method of treating the Stein-Leventhal syndrome is bilateral ovarian wedge resection. It is postulated that by this technique, pituitary function is 'stimulated' . In 106 patients thus operated upon, menstruation became regular in 95%, and of 83 couples followed for sterility, 70% became pregnant. Of a total of 171 pregnancies with 135 live births there were 5 sets of twins. This is 3.5 times the normal rate of expected twins. There is probably a parallelism between the increased number of twins and the increased number of twins which result from the use of pituitary extract of Gemzell to induce ovulation.
