T1  - Reflections on the anovulatory syndromes
T3  - Reflexions sur les syndromes d'anovulation
A1  - Serment H.
A1  - Piana L.
A1  - Felce A.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - After recalling the physiology of ovulation and stressing the role of atresic follicles and that of the cortico-hypothalamo-pituitary control, the clinical picture is outlined: menstrual disorders (absence or scantiness of menstruation or, on the contrary, metrorrhagia), sterility (absolute or relative, primary or secondary), familial history, frequently associated endocrine disorders. These patients can be classed into 3 large groups: Stein-Leventhal's syndrome, cortico-diencephalic functional disorders of psycho-affective origin (Vague's neuro-ovarian syndrome), sclerocystic ovaritis (Netter's ovarian micropolycystosis). Some of these patients retain a strictly feminine appearance; others, without presenting distinct signs of masculinization, exhibit an obesity of the android type and an appearance of minor adrenal hyperandrogenism. When the existence of an ovulatory disorder is confirmed by the clinical signs and the examination (temperature curve, determination of pregnanediol, vaginal smears, endometrial biopsy), one should do an EEG, a determination of the 17-ketosteroids with fractionation, dynamic tests of adrenal inhibition by corticosteroids and ovarian excitation by chorionic gonadotrophic hormones. Patients in whom the hypothalamo-diencephalic or adrenal elements are evident, will benefit from a medical treatment; those in whom the gonadal element seems to predominate, should be submitted to surgical exploration with wedge-shaped resection of the ovaries.
