T1  - Basic clinical and experimental information on the electrical conductivity of the squamous epithelium of the cervix uteri
T3  - Zakladni klinicke experimentalni poznatky o elektricke vodivosti dlazdicoveho epitelu delozniho hrdla
A1  - Stiksa E.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - It was found that the method, which is described in detail, is easily applicable in gynecological research and practice, and that the results are exact and reliable when compared with other methods (colposcopy, cytology, basal body temperature, histology, etc.). The electrical resistance was found to be low after the menstruation, to reach maximal values at midcycle, and to fall again to its original postmenstrual values before the onset of the next menstruation. There was a significant rise in resistance (above 10,000OMEGA) in hyperestrogenic cycles. No influence of progesterone could be demonstrated by this method; there was no difference between ovulatory and anovulatory cycles. In pregnancy there was a slight fall in resistance. In cases with menopausal hemorrhage there was increased resistance if there was evidence of increased estrogenic activity, and it was lowered if there were low estrogen levels. Postmenopausal women had a significantly lowered resistance. The regenerated epithelium after diathermo-coagulation showed higher values than normally. These studies were carried out in out-patients, who were examined twice weekly. The following experimental work was carried out by daily examinations in in-patients, so that the interference of external factors could be eliminated. Under administration of estrogens the resistance increased rapidly, reaching maximal values 2-3 days earlier than the cytological reaction of the vaginal mucosa; after that, however, continued administration produced a fall to medium values. A rise was also achieved by androgens. After pealing off the epithelium layer by layer (with adhesive tape) there was a fall of resistance, which was due to the loss of tissue and also to the reaction of the remaining tissue. Mechanical irritation (by bullet forceps) produced varying results. These investigations show that the method has certain advantages over others (information on the condition of deeper layers while leaving them intact, on the immediate reaction to irritation, on pathological activation of the ovaries in the menopause), and promises to be useful in further research work as well as in everyday practice.
