T1  - Drug therapy in dysmenorrhea
A1  - Black E.F.E.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - A thorough history and physical examination is essential to establish underlying causes before prescribing medication. Any initiating cause as anemia, debility, nervous tension, hypothyroidism or pelvic pathology must be treated as indicated. The patient's co-operation can be enlisted when she is warned that it may take time to find the most effective medication. Analgesics, antispasmodics, sedatives, and tranquillizers, alone or in various combinations, are listed and discussed with warning about possible addiction when they are combined with codeine. Estrogenic hormones and contraceptive pills when used to suppress ovulation also produce painless anovulatory cycles, but straight progestogens are not recommended. Androgenic agents may be useful for endometriosis cases. If a narcotic is required to control the pain, a reassessment including a psychiatric consultation is recommended.
