T1  - Urethral cytology in the diagnosis of secondary amenorrhea
A1  - Castellanos H.
A1  - O'Morchoe P.J.
A1  - Yahia C.
A1  - Sturgis S.H.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - The authors utilized voided urinary cells to aid in the differential diagnosis of secondary amenorrhea. Compared to the vaginal smear, collection of urethra cells is easier, errors in the technic of obtaining vaginal smears are eliminated, and the interference of such artifacts as vaginitis do not occur. Differential counts were found to be reproducible when done independently by 2 laboratory observers. Three aspects of the smear were considered: cornification count, progesterone effect, and non-nucleated cells; characteristic variations were found in the menopause and in anovulatory cycles. Two different patterns were found in the Stein-Leventhal syndrome: low cornification count, higher than normal non-nucleated cell count, and a positive progesterone effect; or, low cornification, high non-nucleated cells, and an absence of progesterone effect.
