AN  - 281123465
T1  - The androgenic ovary, with special reference to the Stein-Leventhal syndrome
A1  - Jeffcoate T.N.A.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - The normal testis produces estrogens as well as androgens, and the normal ovary produces androgens as well as estrogens, as proven by clinical, experimental and biochemical observations. The same is true of the male and female adrenal cortices. The bisexual hormone functions of the gonads and adrenals are in keeping with known bisexual potentials of man and woman, but they appeared paradoxical until many researches showed that progesterone, testosterone, and estradiol are chemically interchangeable. Both the last two can be synthesized from the first. Ovarian function and morphology were discussed, as were the poly cystic ovaries of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome. The question of resection of polycystic ovaries was brought up and various theories offered. The author's own series of 124 consecutive cases were presented and the treatment of 78 with polycystic ovaries discussed. Of these, 46 with symptoms were reported upon. The observations on breast development, together with the reported inconsistencies regarding symptomatology and the results of the treatment, emphasize once more the insecure basis upon which the Stein-Leventhal syndrome rests. There seems little doubt that polycystic ovaries sometimes show one or more clearly defined errors in biosynthesis, but there is an urgent need to show whether all polycystic ovaries have this peculiarity, and how often the same upset is found in ovaries which are not polycystic. Moreover, the evidence to date suggests that overproduction of androgens by an ovary which is not the site of organic disease is merely part of a widespread endocrine dysfunction in which the adrenals and possibly the pituitary and hypothalamus are also affected. The time is fast approaching when the diagnosis of the cause of a defeminization syndrome must rest on biochemical studies and not merely on the visualization or palpation of polycystic ovaries. Polycystic change may be the least significant finding. Even when the ovary is proved to be a source of abnormal androgen production, the cause may be one of several extrinsic agents, the discovery of which demands further exhaustive clinical and endocrine logical studies. It also seems clear that some of these causes are temporary and that the error in ovarian biosynthesis is spontaneously reversible. It has not yet been established that ovarian resection is a specific remedy and, since it gives no better results than other empirical medical or surgical measures, or even than procrastination, it should be reserved for those cases in which everything else has failed. For the future, there is hope that treatment with preparations of human gonadotrophin, or with clomiphene, may help to correct the ovarian dysfunction. Meanwhile, it would seem that conservative measures should form the primary line of treatment of the patient with polycystic ovaries associated with oligomenorrhea, infertility, hirsutism, and obesity without a demonstrable organic cause.
