T1  - Gynecology and obstetrics
A1  - Lock F.R.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - Lock emphasized the benefits to obstetrics and gynecology which have come from discoveries in the field of biochemistry, physiology, and other basic sciences. In relation to general surgery, gynecology has especially advanced. Mentioned were the advantages which have come from metronidazole (Flagyl) for vaginal trichomoniasis, clomiphene for anovulation, and clomiphene and medroxyprogesterone for Chiari-Frommel syndrome. Recent research in endometriosis has tended to support the metaplasia theory in addition to the theory of direct implantation. The improved results which have resulted from population screening with the Papanicolaou smears supports the prediction that carcinoma of the crevix may eventually be eradicated as a primary diagnosis. Improved results in the overall have resulted from standardization of treatment technics for carcinoma of the cervix. Disappointing have been the anticipated better results expected from high voltage radiation sources and the higher incidence of severe complications have made revision to lower dosage necessary. The results expected from overly radical surgical procedures have been justified. A large scale project to evaluate the effects of medroxyprogesterone acetate may bring improved results in the treatment of carcinoma of the uterine fundus. The need for improved methods of making early diagnosis in carcinoma of the ovary was stressed. The treatment of pelvic malignancy by intraarterial perfusion and infusion was viewed as possibly encouraging. The use of cumulative life statistics for evaluation of the results of treatment for pelvic cancer was encouraged as providing more accuracy. Similar improvements were cited for obstetrics. The remarkable reduction in maternal mortality and morbidity was attributed, in part, to better professional-lay education which has resulted in better hospital cooperation in providing improved obstetrical anesthesia, more adequate equipment and facilities. Searching reviews by maternal mortality committees have pointed ways for improvement. The great challenge for the future is in the field of human wastage and neonatal deaths. Basic research is needed in the fields of placental physiology. Improved technics of instrumentation have made possible a better understanding of intra-aminiotic pressures. Fresh probing into the problems of maternal hypovolemia and hypotension has suggested caution in the use of certain vasopressors. Toxemia of pregnancy remains on enigma but the demonstration of pressor substances in the endometrium and in the blood has been substantiated. Uterine oxytocin studies have indicated the subject to be more complex than anticipated. It has been shown that the response of myometrium is species dependent. Hemorrhagic shock has become a leading cause of maternal death. Research has suggested that oxygen therapy may have specific value for the treatment of hemorrhagic shock. A more rational understanding of congenital abnormalities has come about through the use of the principles and technics of genetics to human development. Chromosomal studies have yielded fruitful results for the study of certain human abnormalities. The tetrogenicity of rubella infections and other specific tetrogenic agents have been recognized but the need for more basic research was stressed.
