T1  - Cunical utility of chemical induction of ovulation
A1  - Vorye N.
A1  - Gantt C.L.
A1  - Hamwi G.J.
A1  - Copeland W.E.
A1  - Uilery J.C.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - The capacity of clomiphene ( MRL-41) to induce ovulation in cases of secondary amenorrhea or irregular anovulatory menses of unknown etiology was evaluated in 32 patients. In 18 patients with secondary amenorrhea the compound induced at least 2 successive ovula tory menstrual cycles, as judged by vaginal smears and basai body temperature changes in 9 patients (50%). An additional 3 patients (17%) ovulated irregularly. Four pregnancies occurred in this group. Eleven (79%) of 14 patients with irregular anovulatory menses ovulated regularly while taking this drug. Five pregnancies occurred in this group. Two dosage schedules were evaluated: 100 mg. per day for 20 days each month, and 200 mg. per day for 5 days only each month. In patients with irregular ancvulatory menses there was no difference in the results with the 2 dosage schedules. In the group with secondary amenorrhea. however, the longer dosage schedule gave much better results. The major complication of therapy was the development of ovarian cysts in 19 patients (59%), which regressed with cessation of therapy. The incidence of cysts decreased to 7% with the short dosage schedule. Four patients had hot flushes similar to those seen in menopause. No other significant side effects were noted.
