AN  - 281242366
T1  - Stein-Leventhal's syndrome (masculinity)
A1  - Moiseenko M.D.
A1  - Shakhnovskaya V.F.
A1  - Golubeva I.V.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - Sixty-eight patients in the 20-44 years age group presenting Stein-Leventhal's syndrome were examined. Hirsutism, as a rule, was not too marked. Disturbed menstrual cycles were recorded in all of the patients; out of the total 68 patients, 44 had never had a regular cycle, while in 23 others a regular cycle appeared for the first time at 2.4 years after the menarche. In most cases the first menstruation occurred at the usual age period. In 22 cases hirsutism appeared prior to or at the menarche, and in 41 cases at 2-4 years after the menarche. Apart from hirsutism no other signs of virilism were found. Bilateral wedge resection of the ovaries was performed on 61 patients; this resulted in normalization of the menstrual cycle. Pregnancy supervened in 14 out of 39 patients with primary sterility. Full-term delivery occurred in 11 cases, while 3 patients had spontaneous miscarriages at periods of up to 3 months. The clinical and hormonal findings led to the conclusion that changes in the ovaries are responsible for the Stein-Leventhal syndrome.
