 A1  - Anonymous.
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - The biology of human reproduction is an extremely broad scientific topic, which impinges to some degree on virtually all the basic medical disciplines. In a report of this length, no topic can be treated in other than its most essential and currently important features. The report delineates numerous areas in which information is still seriously lacking, and emphasizes the needs for more knowledge, because the subject of reproduction affects not only the individual, but also the community and the world as a whole. Many of our ideas of the biology of human reproduction are based on information obtained by experiments and observations on a small number of lower animals. This information has very narrow foundations, and these animals cannot be considered as adequate prototypes for the study of human reproduction. Effort should be made to broaden the basis of our knowledge of mammalian reproduction so as to increase the support it can give to the study of human reproduction. Knowledge of geographical and ethnic variations, and of secular trends in human reproductive processes is quite inadequate. Information is required for different people in different parts of the world concerning the age of onset of puberty, the menopause, anovulatory cycles, the length of lactation and its effect on return of menstruation after parturition, and other aspects or reproduction. The biology of the gonads and gametes is discussed and various deficiencies in knowledge recognized. What is the cause of follicular atresia? When does ovulation occur? What is known about the identity of the testicular hormone that activates the hypothalamicpituitary mechanism at puberty? What is the nature of metabolism of the primary spermatogonia ? Answers to these and many other questions need further elucidation. Gestation itself, the biochemistry of the sex steroids, and the pharmacological and immunological aspects of reproduction are critically discussed from the standpoint of what is known and, more important, what is not known. The report ends with a list of recommendations for the organization of surveys, the provision of services, and the promotion of research in relation to the biology of human repro-riuctinn.
