N2  - The authors have determined the urinary excretion of individual 17-ketosteroids in a series of nine normal female subjects and 18 women with different endocrinopathies, mostly hirsutism and virilism, using quantitative paper chromatography of seven fractions: 11-oxygenated ketoeteroids. dehydroe/u'androsterone, epiand r os te rone, androstanedione (+ aetiocholanolone) and artefacts of the HC !-hydrolysis, deriving mostly from dehydroe/wandrosterone. The amounts excreted daily of androstanedione and 'pr'androsterone provide new information, the other normal values were in agreement with those data obtained by other workers. The cases who all had functional insufficiency of the ovaries, were divided into three groups: One group without any sign of masculinization, a second group with different degrees of hi r sut is m and a third group with virilization. The authors do not find any different correlation between the severity of the hirsutism on the one hand and the spectra of the 17-ketosteroids on the other, but there was no correlation either with the manifestation of polycystic ovaries. The authors stress the necessity to determine testosterone and androstenedione, both in urine and blood to obtain a better assessment of androgenic activity in female patients with different degrees of masculinization. An important bibliography is published. Block - Halmstad.
