T1  - BIOCHEMICAL BASIS of VIRILISATION in WOMEN
T3  - Fundamentes bioquimicos de la virilizacion en Ia mujer
A1  - Alloza Berdejo R.J.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - Virilisation is a condition of abnormal appearance of male characters due to a pathological process. Virilism, in contrast, is a constitutional, non- pathological, non- progressive process. Virilisation includes: (1) Idiophatic hirsutism. (2) Adrenal tumors. (3) Congenital adrenal hyperplasia. (4) Ovarian insufficiency. (5) Virilising tumors of the ovary. (6) Stein- Leventhal syndrome. In idiophatic hirsutism there can be an abnormal sensitivity of the hair follicles to normal androgens or, otherwise, a deviation of normal steroid synthesis in the adrenals from the step of delta- 5progesterone and progesterone on, with overproduction of androgens and reduction in cortisol production. Urinary 17- ketosteroids may be normal but the relation androsterone (androgen metabolite) / ethiocolanone (cortisol metabolite) is increased. Adrenal tumors will snow predominantly a virilising syndrome or a Gushing syndrome according to the cellular type predominating. Virilisation depends on a greater synthesis of androgens and the urinary 17- ketosteroids are increased. Congenital adrenal hyperplasia can appear early in pseudo- masculinisation of the newborn or late as in the Apert- Gallais syndrome. In any case there is a reduced activity of 21- hydroxylase with consequent accumulation of 17- hydroxyprogesterone from which is derived androsterone and 11- beta- hydroxyandrostenedione. both androgenic, and subsequent elevation of 17- ketosteroids in the urine. There is also an elevation of pregnanetriol, another 17- hydroxyprogesterone metabolite, from normal 0.3- 0.5 mg. up to 3- 4 mg. Masculinising ovarian tumors include: (a) Hilar cell tumors made up of cells similar to the androgen secreting cells of the Leydig tumors of the testis. (b) Masculinovoblastoma made up of embryonic inclusions of adrenal cells and in all ways similar to the adrenal virilising tumors, (c) Arrhenoblastoma. In this type of tumor it has been shown that the more immature the cells the less capable they are of steroid synthesis from androgen step to the oestrogen one. In ovarian insufficiency insufficient production of oestrogen is by itself a cause of defemimsation. This may be due to a halt at the androgen level of oestrogen synthesis with overproduction of androgenic metabolites. In addition, if the ovarian insufficiency is primary, hypoestrogenism may lead to an overproduction of gonadotrophins and possibly ACTH with subsequent overproduction of androgens on the part of the adrenal. In the Stein- Leventhal syndrome there is deficient aromatisation of the A ring of the androgens with decreased conversion of these into oestrogens. Urinary 17- ketosteroids may be elevated or normal. Among the various components of the urinary 17- ketosteroids, androstenedione is a weak androgen while testosterone, found in that complex in much less quantity, is strongly virilising, and so can be moderately increased with little influence on the total amount of 17ketosteroids yet exerting a strong virilising effect. Oestrogene can be of benefit in some cases of Stein- Leventhal syndrome. Others may improve with corticosteroids as there is a slight adrenal insufficiency of 21- hydroxylases, while still others may be improved with thyroid because there is a thyroid deficiency.
