T1  - CLOMIPHENE CITRATE: NEWER ASPECTS of ITS USE in PREVENTION and TREATMENT of INFERTILITY
A1  - Whitelaw M.J.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - The experimental Introduction of clomiphene citrate has shown that the drug is capable of inducing ovulation in young women suffering from anovulatory endometrial hyperplasia. Also, ovulation may be induced in patients with long-standing secondary amenorrhea and associated atrophie endometrium. Five single girls with proven endometriai hyperplasia were cyclically treated with clomiphene citrate for 2 to 4 days starting on days 4 to G of their cycles, for periods of 4 to 9 mth., with dosages varying between 25 and 150 mg. daily. Basal body temperature curves showed evidence* of ovulation. Hysterograms and endometriai biopsy specimen* confirmed the absence of the original endometriai hyperplasia. Five women with irregular menses varying from 45 to 180 days were also treated with clomiphene citrate. Original biopsy specimens showed cystic hyperplasia or a proliferative endometrium. Two patients who were married became pregnant within 2 mth., both having ovulated the 1st month of therapy. The pregnancies were normal. One patient after 3 trials at 3-week intervals failed to respond. There was no evidence of toxicity noted with this dosage schedule.
