T3  - Androgene polyzystischer Ovarien und Hirsutismus
A1  - Simmer H.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - In an excellent article a survey is given of the literature on the production of androgens in polycystic ovaries. For this purpose the following examinations were made: determination of the total and fractionated elimination of 17- KS in the urine, influence of corticoide in this elimination, isolation of androgens from tissue of polycystic ovaries, demonstration of formation of androgens in this ovarian tissue in vitro, determination of androgens in the blood of the ovarian vein. The author comes to the following conclusion: that production'and secretion of androgens by polycystic ovaries is an established fact. The biosynthesis of steroids is disturbed by blocking of one or more enzyme systems. The participation of the adrenal gland in the production of hirsutism in the case of polycystic ovaries cannot be excluded. It is inexplicable why 50% of the women suffering from this ovarian anomaly do not develop hirsutism. Possibly genetic defects play a role in the genesis of polycystic ovaries, possibly connected with a disturbed biosynthesis. Wedge resection of these ovaries gives an improvement in the hirsutism in only 10% of the patients; corticoid therapy is not satisfactory either. Treatment with oestrogene seems logical, but in that case ovulation is suppressed, so that the sterility, for which most of the patients seek help, persists. Plate - Utrecht (X, 3).
