T1  - The results of the sympathectomy (sympathicectomia hypogastrica subtotalis) in primary algomenorrhea and some other gynaecological diseases. A study on 452 follow-up cases
A1  - Nieminen U.
A1  - Kauraniemi T.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - The history of this operation is outlined. The anatomy and technique of the operation are described in detail. The Pfannenstiel incision was used. There were 738 patients who received the operation. The results are based on 452 answering the subsequent questionnaires. There were 38% with primary dysmenorrhea, 43% with secondary dysmenorrhea and 19% with other indications, including endometriosis, post-inflammatory conditions, polycystic ovaries, uterine myomas, malposition of uterus and sterility. The after-effects usually disappear within 6 mth. Constipation is the most persistent of the after-effects. Operational losses were nil. The results in primary dysmenorrhea after 5-9 yr. were 78.8% successes, 15.4% partial successes and failures in 5.8%. The results in secondary dysmenorrhea were 76.2% successes, 19.1% partial successes and 4.7% failures. Disorders in the menstrual cycle, in the length of duration and in amount of flow appeared to be more normal after the operation. After the operation, 43% of the patients had painless or virtually painless deliveries. In 4 patients regularly recurring toxemia during pregnancy was absent in subsequent postoperative pregnancies. In 4 cases, toxemia appearing during a first pregnancy did not recur in subsequent postoperative pregnancies, or it recurred very slightly.
