T1  - Stein-Leventhal syndrome. Its aetiology, pathogenesis and treatment
T3  - Syndrome de Stein-Leventhal. Etudes sur l'etiologie, la pathogenie et le traitement
A1  - Netter A.
A1  - Musset R.
A1  - Yannotti S.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - The Stein-Leventhal syndrome was first described in 1935 and a detailed study appeared in 1962 (Int. J. of Fertility, 1962, 2, 123). This is a strictly specific, but very rare syndrome not characterized by typical symptoms. As this fact is usually given little attention in the literature and manifold ovarian disturbances (especially simple micropolycystic dystrophy) are confused with the syndrome there is considerable misunderstanding. Of 875 apparent cases observed in the past 9 yr. only 31 belonged to the genuine Stein-Leventhal syndrome. The principal clinical signs are: oligoamenorrhoea; sterility; aluteinism; hard and smooth ovaries on palpation and surgical inspection reveals a surface resembling mother of pearl. The diagnosis is verified only if there are 3 of these 4 features. Another valuable finding is persistent excretion of urinary androgenic metabolites after adrenal inhibition (3 mg. of dexamethasone daily) and ovarian stimulation (5,000 IU per day). None of the anatomical-pathological and biochemical signs is specific for the disease, but their combination is specific and the most characteristic aspect is the clinical entity. Histological diagnosis is impossible. On systematic examination of 7 patients 4 were found to have chromosomal anomalies (mosaics) of various types. Therefore this is a congenital but not hereditary, disease, an enzyme defect preventing synthesis of oestrogens and promoting production of steroid metabolites. Possibly there is a defect of 19-hydroxylase. Treatment is discussed in detail. Deep bilateral cuneiform resection is especially valuable. Its apex should reach the hilus and include some 50-75% of the organ. Good results are obtained, though the mechanism is not clear. In the authors' material 28 pregnancies ensued.
