T1  - Problems of endocrinological diagnosis in practice, with particular reference to amenorrhoea
T3  - Probleme endokrinologischer diagnostik in der praxis mit besonderer berucksichtigung der amenorrhoe
A1  - Zander J.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - Two groups of endocrine changes are distinguished: (1) disorders affecting the patient's phenotype, (2) disorders with an increased, reduced or qualitatively abnormal production of hormones. Of the first group some well-known examples are given and attention is drawn to the localization and quantity of hair and to galactorrhoea. As regards the second group some general remarks on hormonal determinations and loading tests are followed by a discussion on amenorrhoea. Much information can be obtained from a good anamnesis, and some simple tests (vaginal smear, endometrial biopsy, progesterone test). Hormonal determinations can be done in addition, but they are of limited value. If amenorrhoea is accompanied by clinical symptoms of hirsutism more elaborate examination, especially determination of the 17-ketosteroids with and without administration of adrenocortical preparations, is necessary. The Stein-Leventhal syndrome is discussed, as is the value of determination of the sex chromatin.
