T1  - The menstrual cycle in puberty
A1  - Matsumoto S.
A1  - Ozawa M.
A1  - Nogami Y.
A1  - Ohashi H.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - An investigation was performed on the menarche in puberal girls. A new tendency to early menarche was distinctly observed and it was considered to be part of a general improvement of the physique which could probably be attributed to improvement of nutrition in childhood, especially to increased intake of animal protein and fat. Among puberal girls, menstrual disorders were found in high frequency. The authors observed the BBT at menarche in 15 girls, and none of them showed a Diphasic cycle. The authors also requested 1,252 girls (aged 13-19 yr.) of junior and senior high schools to record the BBT, and 2,593 BBT cycles were analysed. Observation of the BBT indicated that high frequency of menstrual disorders in puberal girls would result from an anovulatory cycle, and that the ovarian function attained its maturity not with a leap but by passing through a succession of different stages following the menarche. In association with the development of the ovarian cycle, secondary sexual characters and bodily changes developed in puberty. These 2 factors were intimately connected, and both were found to result from a change in the endocrine milieu.
