AN  - 281276376
T1  - The morphology of the prepubertal ovary: Relationship to the polycystic ovary syndrome
A1  - Merrill J.A.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - Ovaries from 98 children, from newborn to age 15 yr., were reviewed and the microscopic morphology is discussed. The majority of such ovaries contain multiple follicle cysts, athretic follicles, and show luteinization and hyperplasia of the theca. Follicle growth and development proceed throughout childhood. The ovaries of girls aged 10 to 15 are at least the size of adult ovaries and have the additional finding of cortical fibrosis. They thus appear morphologically similar to the ovaries of the polycystic ovary syndrome. Prior case reports are referred to in which ovarian surgery was done in adolescent girls with menstrual irregularities because of abnormal appearing ovaries. These findings suggest that the microscopic morphology of the ovary in the polycystic ovary syndrome is specific only of anovulation. Furthermore the possibility is suggested that the clinical syndrome, at least in some cases, is related to a failure to initiate ovulation or puberty as defined, and possibly to a failure in maturation of enzyme systems related to steroid biosynthesis which may usually accompany regular ovulation.
