T1  - Thecosis. a study of diffuse stromal thecosis of the ovary and superficial collagenization with follicular cysts (stein-leventhal ovary)
A1  - Fienberg R.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - The ovaries of 47 patients, which showed superficial collagenization with multiple follicular cysts (Stein-Leventhal syndrome), thecosis, thecomatosis, hyperthecosis, and diffuse luteinization of the ovarian cortical stroma were studied. They may found to fall into 5 groups histologically according to the presence or absence of superficial collagenization, follicular cysts with prominent theca interna layers, and stromal theca cells. It was suggested that Group I be called interna thecosis. Group 2, combined interna and stromal thecosis, and Group 3, stromal thecosis. No histological connection of the stroma theca with the theca interna could be seen. No definite evidence of progression of one group into another was found, but the type of lesion which occurred probably depended upon the hormonal age of the ovary. Hirsutism and clitorism occurred infrequently, especially in Group 3. The ability of the theca cells to exert androgenic as well as oestrogenic effects was most apparent in the predominantly postmenopausal Group 3. The oestrogenic effect in the latter was indicated by colporrhagia and benign mitotic figures in the endometriurn. A consideration of the newer concepts of oestrogen formation supported the possibility of both androgen and oestrogen formation by the theca cells. The mutability of the superficial cortical layer of the ovary and the unsuitability from the physiological aspect of the terms tunica albuginea or capsule as applied to the ovary are emphasized. It was not possible to separate the theca cells into oestrogen and androgen types by a modified Schultz test recently recommended for this purpose. Hepp - Pittsburgh, Pa. (X, 5).
