T1  - Diagnostic value qf cervical mucus arborization
A1  - Chinoy M.B.
A1  - Jungalwala B.N.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - The diagnostic value of the arborization of cervical mucus was examined in 5 groups. as follows: (1) 50 patients with normal cycle, (2) 43 with primary or secondary sterility, (3* 50 with a period of amenorrhoea and suspected, but dubious, pregnancy, (4) 50 patients with definite early pregnancy, (5) 7 post-menopausal women. The degree of crystallization was classified according to 3 categories. In group (1) therr was a distinct correlation with the cycle; 5 patients had signs of anovulation, as observed from the arborisation test. In group (2) crystallization correlated with the endometrial biopsy findings. In group (3) there were 18% of false-positive tests, in 11 the anatomical substrate (curetting) correlated with the cervical mucus. Ih group (4) 7 patients had a distinct arborization, 2 of these women had signs of imminent abortion, which indeed occurred some time later. In 2 patients with habitual abortion the cause was insufficiency of the ostium uteri. In the 5th group none of the patients showed crystallization. To determine the moment of ovulation a smear was made for 43 women of sterile couples. In 80.4% this was reliable. In determining early pregnancy the test was 80% reliable. It is thought that the arborization test is a reasonably accurate, cheap and rapid method for determining oestrogenic activity, the moment of ovulation, early diagnosis of pregnancy and even in forecasting ciho.
