N2  - Six patients are described who had both pelvic tb and hyperadrenal cortical ism. This association has not been previously recorded in the literature. The pelvic infection was sometimes almost symptomless and the patients presented with the features of viril ism (adrenogenital syndrome) and/or mild Gushing's syndrome. The pelvic infection is considered to precede and to cause the hyperadrenal corticalism. The evidence of hyperadrenal corticalism is based on the characteristic clinical features, the sometimes increased urinary 17-ketosteroids with positive suppression tests and the striking improvement in 2 patients following unilateral adrenalectomy. The relation to the Stein-Leventhal syndrome is discussed and the difference between the 2 syndromes is emphasized.
