T1  - MORPHOLOGY of the GONADS in TURNER'S SYNDROME
T3  - Morfologia gonad w zespole Turnera
A1  - Teter J.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - From a study of 11 cases it was shown that in this syndrome a close interdependence exists between the morphological state of the gonads and external sex organs. In cases of completely vestigial gonads consisting of a strand of fibrous tissue (gonadal aplasia) the external sex organs were infantile without any signs of sexual maturation. The gonadal ducts of these patients undergo female differentiation, regardless of sex chromat in, and structures of the MQllerian duct (uterus and oviduct) develop. JLn cases of dysgenetic gonads containing Leydig cells in the medullary zone hypertrophy of the clitoris and pubic hair were observed. These changes point to androgenic activity of the interstitial Leydig elements. Besides development of MQllerian duct structures development of the Wolffian duct (epididymal tubules) was observed in these cases also. Dux - Warsaw (V, 3, 10) Univ. Med. Cent., Durham, N.C. - J. OBSTET. GYNAEC. BRlT. CWLTH 1963, 70/6 (971-975) This review of almost 30 years'results in an infertility clinic records a pregnancy rate of 37% for the 1,250 copies who had a complete survey. In the first 10 years, interest was chiefly focused on the results of pelvic and cervical operations. There were 36,2% of pregnancies in these 500 couples, It was concluded that most of the operations were unrewarding and gave a low per cent of success. After 10 more years, 39.1% of pregnancies were achieved in 750 couples. These patients were given a poor prognosis if the sperm count was below 20 million, the tubes were blocked, or the post-coital or end omet rial biopsy tests were abnormal. This group had only 18% of pregnancies in contrast to 52% in the good prognosis group. A psychiatric survey had been added, and those \vith an 'inadequate* report showed a correspondingly poorer success rate. In the last decade, no real improvement in pregnancy incidence can be shown. Seventy-nine per cent of the pregnancies in the 'good' group occurred within 6 mth. of completing this survey, compared with only 49% in the poor group. Thirty-six wedge resection operations were done with 16 successes - 2 patients in this group later developed adenocarcinoma. The results from all types of operations for t u bal occlusion consistently produced less than 10% of pregnancies. Further measures that may improve these figures include better education, availability of human gonadotropic principles for anovulation and oligospermia, psychiatric skill, chromosomal and immunological studies and methods to establish precisely the time of ovulation.
