T1  - THE EFFECT of HUMAN FSH and HCG on THE ANOVULATORY OVARY
A1  - Lee Buxton C.
A1  - Kase N.
A1  - Van Orden D.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - Twenty- eight courses of HPG- HCG therapy were given to 11 patients with resultant evidence of progestational activity during every course except one. The patient to whom this course was given subsequently produced progestational activity following a change in dosage. For the most part these cases were individuals who had been amenorrheic or anovulatory for a number of years and who had very low or no urinary gonadotropin excretion. One pregnancy occurred during a course of therapy in a 26- year- old patient who had been amenorrheic for 10 years. Steroid excretion studies on these patients confirmed the clinical finding that some kind of human gonadotropin containing FSH and LH is necessary to trigger oestrogen and progesterone production by the ovary and, presumably, cause ovulation.
