T1  - CONSEQUENCES of UNILATERAL OOPHORECTOMY
T3  - Les consequences de Aova riectomie unilaterale
A1  - Chambraud R.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - After unilateral oophorectomy the remaining ovary grows thicker, muitilobular, tender. It is the cause of menstrual pain, prolonged cycles and squamous leucorrhoea. As for its physio-pathology, the remaining ovary undergoes a compensatory hyperplasia or else becomes dystrophic, especially when resection of more than 50% is performed. Therefore, it is advisable to avoid unilateral oophorectomy whenever possible and to heal tender polycystic ovaries by sedatives, thermal cures, psychotherapy or relaxation therapy. Prolapsed ovaries should be treated surgically by fixation. Infected ovaries require minimal resection. Lamiroy - Bruges.
