A1  - Taymor M.L.
A1  - Clarck B.J.
A1  - Sturgis S.H.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - The history of the work done by Stein and Leventhal in 1935 was discussed and work done since that time was evaluated. Tables of the authors'findings and microscopic photographs of various patients*ovaries were shown. Ovarian size, capsule thickness and thecal cell hyperplasia as well as 17- ketosteroid excretion were discussed. A graph was included that demonstrated the peak luteinizing hormone excretion levels in polycystic ovarian disease. The results of bilateral ovarian wedge resection in 40 patients with polycystic ovarian changes were reviewed. No typical pattern of clinical picture, ovarian size or laboratory findings could be delineated. It was concluded that polycystic ovarian change is a progressive, polyglandular endocrinopathy. the path agenesis of which remain>> obscure.
