T1  - STUDY of the OVARY in CANCER of the ENDOMETRIUM
T3  - Estado del ovario en el cancer del endometrio
A1  - Nogales F.
A1  - Tornero C.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - A histological study was made of the ovaries in 112 cases of endometrial cancer (E.C.) and in the same number of controls. In 85% of the cases the cancer developed in patients between 40 and 60 yr. of age. The ovaries were enlarged, whitish, polycystic, without thickening of the tunica albuginea, but with a specifically hyperpiastic stroma. Twenty per cent of the cases occurred during reproductive life, which controverts the significance of the theory that oestrogene have a carcinogenic effect on the mucosa of the body and that after the menopause they act on a permanent mucosa which does not desquamate. In postmenopausal ovaries the authors found cortical hyperplasia as described by Hertig, with thecal formations in only 22.70% of the cases. However, in 4 out of 31 cases of feminizing tumours of the ovary this association with endometrial carcinoma was coincidental. This is the strongest argument in favour of the carcinogenic role which oestrogene play in E.C. A cytological study was made in 50 cases of E.C. A larger number of oestrogenic smears were found than among the controls. In another group of patients with carcinoma the oestrogene were determined and found to be increased. Even if the ovary is not responsible for this in oestrogene, it exists so that there must be some other source of production. This explains why the excretion of oestrogene continues 8- 10 days after hysterectomy. The kariopyknotic index remains elevated 6- 10 days after bilateral ovariectomy. It is possible that the extra- ovarian source is in the adrenal cortex. Considering that the ovaries of carcinomatous patients have the same morphological appearance as those of the controls, it is concluded that it is difficult to agree that chronic hyperoestrogenism is the causal agent of adenocarcinoma of the uterus. The authors consider that there exists a very close parallelism between E.C. and breast cancer but they do not attach any hormonal significance to either of them.
