N2  - Among 75 women with marked hirsutism, 52 also showed menstrual disturbances. In 19 cases no hormonal changes could be detected, but not all cases had been subjected to all tests. In 5 cases a congenital and in 33 cases a postpubertal adrenogenital syndrome without demonstrable adrenocortical hyperplasia existed. Diagnosis sometimes was most difficult, but the situation could be recognised by estimating 17-ketosteroids and dehydroepiandrosterone before and after ACTH stimulation; the values of both were abnormal. 8 women had polycystic ovaries with so-called mixed ovarian and adrenal types of hormonal secretion. 4 women without enlarged ovaries had ovarian hypersecretion of androgens, as could be demonstrated by the gonadotropin test withHMG and HCG. Four women had Cushing's syndrome, 1 an adrenal, 1 an ovarian and 1 a pituitary tumour. All cases of adrenal origin without tumour were treated with dexamethasone when menstrual disturbances were severe or there was a desire for children. However, in general, the results were unsatisfactory. Hirsutism alone should not be regarded as a sufficient indication for corticoid therapy. In these cases one should restrict treatment to dermatological and cosmetic measures.
