T1  - The menopause and its treatment
T3  - La menopause et son traitement
A1  - Serment H.
A1  - Ayme Y.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - The authors briefly describe the principal clinical manifestations of the menopause and interpret the latest physiological and pathological facts which characterise the two phases of this climacteric period. They insist on the luteal insufficiency with anovulation, on absolute or relative hyperoestrogenesis of the premenopause and on hypergonadostimulinaemia (P.S.H. ) of the established menopause. They underline the importance of diagnosis of cancer of the cervix among the cases of cervical 'met rit is' and of the danger of hyperplasia of the endometrium which constitutes a bed for cancer of the body of the uterus. From the point of view of prophylaxis, they attach much importance to cervical electro-coagulation, and to the treatment of endometrial hyperplasias, necessitating repeated cure t tage when needed. As to the disturbance of hormonal equilibrium, they recommend progesterone and glusynesterone in the premenopause, oestrogen therapy in appropriate doses in the wellestablished menopause; the psychoneurotic troubles are best treated with tranquilisers, and in particular with thioridazine.
