T1  - A HISTOCHEMlCAL STUDY of the OVARIES of WOMEN SUFFERING from THE STEIN-LEVENTHAL SYNDROME
A1  - Dokumov S.I.
A1  - Daehev G.I.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - Tissue removed by wedge resection from the ovaries of 25 women suffering from the Stein-Leventhal syndrome was examined by histological and histochemical me* thods and compared with the ovaries of 10 healthy women killed in accidents. In the Stein-Leventhal group the capsule of the ovary was found to be irregularly thickened with dense connective tissue, rich in collagen fibers and F.A.S. -positive substances., In some areas there was an accumulation of the latter. The number of primordial and primary follicles was greatly reduced. Graafian follicles in different stages of development were found in the test group and these showed increased alkaline and acid phosphatase activity. Mature Graafian follicles were rarely present but many atretic follicles were found beneath the thickened cortex. The theca interna was commonly hypertrophled and hyperplastic, and in many cases showed evidence of F.A.S. -positive substances, increased alkaline and acid phosphatase activity, ascorbic acid granules and. in certain cells, cholesterol and neutral lipids. All these histochemical changes were found principally in the cells producing the steroid hormones. Chalmers - Worcester (X, 5*).
