T1  - TREATMENT of FUNCTIONAL UTERINE BLEEDING
T3  - Tratamiento de las metrorragias funcionales
A1  - Netter A.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - According to the author, during a bleeding episode blood transfusions, ocytocics. ergot derivatives, curettage and hormones may be used but never testosterone. If on endometrial biopsy the uterus is found to be small and the endometrium scarce oestrogene are indicated. If. on the contrary, the uterus is bulky or myomata or adnexal inflammation are present gestagens are preferred. The correct diagnosis must be made between bleeding episodes. Many cases are due to blood coagulation defects. In cases of recent adnexal infections antibiotics and corticoide should be used, and antibiotics and stock vaccines for long-standing infections. In cases with myoma over 45 years of age. bleeding may be treated as pr erne nopa usai functional bleeding. Between 30 and 45 Hypertonie vaginal douches, ergot, hamamelis and hydrastis are sometimes helpful. If not operation should be considered, and if refused, testosterone may be tried (100 mg. a month from day 8 to day 20 of cycle). Noresteroids should never be used as they may induce bleeding in case of my ima ta. Polycystic ovarian dystrophy has a well defined hormone pattern: no inhibition of 17-ketosteroids by dexametasone, no pregnanediol stimulation by G.G. H., estrogen increase after G.C.H. stimulation. Therapy includes psychotherapy, cyclic administration of gestagens. wedge, resection. Uterine bleeding due to hyperoestrogenism calls for curettage followed by cyclic administration of gestagens. In post-pubertal or pre-menopausal bleeding if there are long periods of amenorrhea cyclic administration of gestagens should be used. However if there is metrorrhagia curettage should first be performed to start a new cycle and from then on cyclic administration of gestagens. Gomes - Lisbon.
