T1  - A clinical and anatomo-histological study of 21 cases of hirsutism with menstrual disturbances and ovarian polycystosis. with reference to the problems of the ovarian genesis of hirsutism and of the so-called syndrome of steinleventhal
T3  - Studio clinico e anatomo-istologico su 21 casi di irsutismo con turbe mestruali e policistosi ovarica,, in riferimento ai problemi della genesi ovarica degli irsutismi e della cosiddetta sindrome di Stein-Leventhal
A1  - Zampi G.
A1  - Borghi A.
A1  - Toccafondi R.
A1  - Giusti G.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - In 21 cases of hi r sut ism associated with menstrual disorders and with ovarian polycystosis, histological examination of fragments of the ovaries, obtained by (therapeutic) wedge resection, revealed, as the most singificant finding, pronounced phenomena of 'hyperthecosis' with luteinization. The degree of intensity of these phenomena was fairly well correlated with the degree of hirsutism and with the presence or absence of other signs of virilization. This investigation has once more clearly shown that the so-called Stein-Leventhal syndrome does not possess a sufficiently characteristic and well-defined morphological and clinical substrate, so that it is impossible to distinguish it sharply from other forms of ovarian polycystosis. On the contrary, new evidence has been obtained which supports the conception that in ovarian polycystosis there exists a whole series of intermediary forms between the so-called microcystic degeneration, on the one hand, and the ovary of Geist and Gaines on the other; the Stein -Leventhal ovary constitutes an intermediary form between these 2 conditions. With due reservations concerning the actual nesegraphical autonomy of the 'syndrome of Stein-Leventhal', it may nevertheless be stated that from a purely practical point of view this is still the most suitable classification for the cases of gynecological character, i.e. those characterized essentially by menstrual disorders and by sterility. Those cases in which hirsutism is present in combination with the menstrual disorders and with the ovarian polycystosis, and in which it even often dominatas the picture, should, on the other hand, preferably be classified under the heading of Ovarian hirsutism of non-tumoral nature', in view of the pronounced clinical findings of changes of the piliferous system, and 01 the part played by ovarian factors in its pathogenesis.
