T1  - The gynecological aspects of the adrenogenital syndrome -
A1  - Barclay D.L.
A1  - Dingman J.F.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - The adrenogenital syndrome has been defined, and discussed in regard to 3 age groups due to the clinical manifestations peculiar to each. The clinical characteristics, aetiology, diagnosis and treatment of each group has been outlined. Only the gynaecologic treatment has been stressed. The gynaecologist is concerned with the surgical procedure necessary for correction of the genitalia of female pseudohermaphrodites secondary to adrenal hyp erf unction. The necessity of early diagnosis and treatment of the newborn with ambiguous genitalia has been emphasized. Adrenal hyperfunction in the prepubertal female may first present as primary amenorrhoea or precocious development. Combined androgenic and glucocorticoid hyperfunction of the adrenal cortex must be considered in each patient in this group. A diagnostic approach to the adult female with evidence of virilization and menstrual disturbance is outlined. Adrenal hyperfunction and the 'polycystic ovary syndrome' appear to be distinct entities requiring specific treatment.
