Y1  - 1963//
N2  - Two patiencs with Stein-Leventhal syndrome had chromosome analyses performed on peripheral blood cultures. Both women had had their menarche at the age of 12 and for some time afterwards had had normal menstruation. Then the periods became irregular and were associated with dysmenorrhoea. Both showed hirsutism with masculine distribution of hair. Laboratory investigations for steroid metabolism were normal, as were urinary oestrogenic substances and the gonadotrophins. At laparotomy the ovaries were pale with several microcysts. Buccal smears showed nuclear sex chromatin in 28% and 30% of cells, respectively. Chromosomal analysis revealed an XX chromosome constitution in the first case, and an XX/XXY mosaic in the second. This patient also showed an increase in plasma testosterone. The various constitutions, e.g. XX/XXX, Xx or XX/Xx may explain the rliniral heterogeneity observed Schutt -Edinburgh.
