T1  - Effects of progestins on embryonic mortality of swine
A1  - Morrissette M.C.
A1  - Mcdonald L.E.
A1  - Whatley J.A.
A1  - Morrison R.D.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - Four experiments involving ioo gilts and sows were conducted to test the hypothesis that the daily administration of orally active progestins would reduce embryonic mortality by enhancing intrauterine environment until slaughter at 25 or 40 days post breeding. Within these experiments, significant reduction in embryonic mortality occurred only when the embryonic mortality in the control animals approached the 30 to 35% level reported by previous investigators. There was an unusually low embryonic mortality in some control groups and a high degree of individual variation. Analysis of pooled data wherein 33 pregnant animals given 1 mg. of 17alpha-acetoxyprogesterone (ly-AP) and 0.5 mug. diethylstilboestrol (DES) per pound of body weight daily were compared with 35 pregnant control animals indicated a reduction in embryonic mortality (3.39 vs. 4.89 dead embryos) significant at the probability level of 0.17. There was no reduction of embryonic mortality in the 12 pregnant animals given oa-methyl-iya-acetoxyprogesterone (6-M-17-AP) compared with 14 pregnant control animals. The incidence of cystic ovaries at necropsy was 5 of 17 (29.4%) in the 6-M-17-AP-treated groups, 4 of 45 (8.9%) in the 17-AP-DES-treated groups, and 1 of 38 (2.6%) in the control groups. Significant differences in endometrial alkaline and acid phosphatase activities did not occur between groups except when pregnant and non-pregnant animals were compared.
