T1  - The relative sterility of the years following the menarche
T3  - Uber die relative Sterilitat in den Jahren nach der Menarche
A1  - Doring G.K.I.
Y1  - 1963//
N2  - In a study of the basal temperature records that were kept for a total of 1,471 menstrual cycles by 303 girls and women the author confirmed the hypothesis suggested by v. Mikulicz and Kausch in 1935 that in the years following the menarche the majority of menstrual cycles are abnormal. At first the proportion of anovulatory cycles and cycles with an abnormally short corpus luteum phase to complete and normal cycles is abnormally high. This finding explains why so many women are sterile in the first few years after the menarche. Nevertheless, it is surprising to find for how many years more abnormal than normal cycles occur and how long it takes for 'normal' conditions to be established. The optimum proportion of normal cycles is only achieved with the age group 26-30 yr. With one exception the observations recorded in the literature confirm these findings.
