Y1  - 1963//
N2  - The clinical findings as well as the peripheral blood chromosomal constitution of 2 Stein-Leventhal variants are presented. The first patient revealed an apparently normal chromosomal constitution. The second had, besides XX cells, a significant percentage of XXY cells. Abnormally high levels of testosterone were detected in the plasma of this hirsute patient whose ovary has been shown to produce this androgen. These findings suggest a possible action of the Y chromosome in a female phenotype. The probable influence of the chromosomal constitution on the heterogeneous symptomatology of the syndrome is discussed.
