T1  - Lipexal stimulation of the pituitary-hypothalamic axis in the anovulatory amenorrheic patient
A1  - Giglio F.A.
A1  - Gravlee L.C.
A1  - Jones W.N.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - Seven anovulatory amenorrhoeic patients were studied in regard to plasma elevation and urinary excretion of 17-hydroxycorticosteroide and urinary excretion of 17ketosteroids and follicle-stimulating hormone. Histological correlation of endocrine activity was measured by endometrial biopsy where applicable, and laparotomy where indicated. Results of the investigation are as follows. All 7 patients were found not to be in the range of panhypopltuitary function in regard to the plasma 17-hydroxycorticosteroid secretion following lipexal stimulation. Urinary excretion levels of -hydroxycorticosteroids were elevated in 6 of the 7 patients, the elevation occurring in the 8 hr. immediately following stimulation. The 17ketosteroids were elevated in 5 of the 7 patients, the most common period of elevation being the 8 hr. immediately following stimulation. The urinary excretion of gonadotrophlc hormone (FSH) was elevated in 6 of the 7 patients, most commonly In the 8-hour period 3 p.m. to 11 p.m. Six of the 7 patients had 'menstrual-type* bleeding following stimulation. This is felt to represent endogenous oestrogen withdrawal bleeding as a result of gonadotrophic stimulation of the ovaries in 5 of the 7 whose endometrium persisted in the proliferative phase just prior to the 'menstruation*. Two patients were found to ovulate following stimulation. In one the evidence of this was recorded in a secretory phased endometrium by endometrial biopsy 6 days prior to menstruation. In a second patient, ovulation was detected at laparotomy. where bilateral wedge resection of the ovaries revealed a corpus haemorrhagicum and corpus luteum. Four of the 7 patients, following culdoscopic examination, were diagnosed as Stein-Leventhal syndrome and were treated with bilateral wedge resection of the ovaries, with return of cyclic menstruation in all patients. Two of the 7 patients were found to be 'inUd diabetics'. One patient is maintained on an oral hypoglycaemic, the other on 10 U. of NPH insulin. In neither case were these patients felt to be in poor control. One of these patients ovulated following lipexa.1 stimulation, as reflected in a secretory endometrium prior to menstruation. The other patient exhibited a Stein-Leventhal syndrome and has responded with cyclic menstruation following bilateral wedge resection of the ovaries.
