T1  - Psychogenic factors in anovulatory women. I. hormonal patterns in women with ovarian dysfunctions of psychogenic origin
A1  - Rakoff A.E.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - Endocrine studies were conducted on 38 consecutive young women with longstanding ovarian dysfunctions associated with anovulation and menstrual dysfunction. In 9, the onset occurred promptly after an acute psychiatric disturbance, while in the other 29 there* was a longstanding psychic disturbance. Included in the studies were assays for FSiI oestrogens, pregnanediol, 17-kctosteroids, 17-hydroxycorticoids , vaginal smears., endometrial biopsiest basal temperature records, PBI and other tests of thyroid function. Six hormonal patterns were found: simple hypogonadotropism: hypogonadotropism with hypothyroidism; hypogonadotropism with low B. M. R. (but normal FBI) and low 17-ketosteroids; normal FSH and low oestrogens; normal FSH and persistent normal (orhijfh) oestrogen; nnd nigh FSH nnrl low oestrogens, usually with associated 'menopausal' symptoms. For statistical evaluation, an additional 23 patients with acute psychogenic ovarian dysfunction who had been previously studied were included, making 32 in this category, and a total of 61 patients in whom hormonal assays were done. It was noted that simple hypogonadotropism was the most common pattern in both the acute (44%) and chronic (34%) groups. The next most common pattern in the acute group occurred in patients with a primary ovarian inhibition characterised by high FSH and low oestrogens (22%). In the chronic group, a persistent oestrus pattern was the second most common observation (23%). The patterns of normal FSH or high FSBi and low oestrogens were next in incidence. The low FSH and low 17-ketosteroids occurred in 4 patients with anorexia nervosa. Other patterns discussed with regard to a psychogenic aetiology were persistent corpuslutoum function, especially as seen in the pseudocyesis syndrome, diminished gonadotropins and oestrogens in association with galactorrhoea, and elevated 17-ketosteroids in relation to an acquired adrenogenital syndrome or SteLn-Leventhal syndrome.
