T1  - SECONDARY OLIGO-AMENORRHOEA. a CLINICAL and ENDOCRINOLOGICAL EVALUATION
A1  - BjoriK
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - This is an excellent review worthwhile reading and re-reading. The name is used for any amenorrhoea over 4 months' duration in a woman under 40. The following diagnostic procedures have been found useful and should be employed initially: (1) BLoassay of gonadotrophins in the urine (normal: 4 to 60 MUU./24hr.). (2) vaginal cytology (normal acidophil index -AI-: 22 to 48%; pyknotic index -PI-: 10 to 40%). Agreement with chemical determination of oestrogene in urine extract was found in 94% of cases. (3) Endometrial biopsy. (4) Determination of urinary 17-ketosteroids (17-KS) and its Chromatographie fractionation in androsterone, dehydroepiandrosterone (DHA) and aetiocholanolone. (5) Determination of 17-hydroxicorticosteroids in the urine (17-OHCS). When indicated complementary information was obtained by: (1) Response to corlicotrophin and to chorionic gonadotrophinstimulation. (2) Supressiontestwith 9-alpha-fluorohydrocortisone. (3) Radiology of sella turcica. (4) Urinary pregnanediol determination. (5) Complete study of thyroid function (BMR, serum cholesterol and PBI, thyroid I131 uptake, butanol extractable iodine and in-vitro uptake of I131 labelled L-triiodothyronine by the erythrocytes. Abnormal oestrogen secretion may interfere with the laboratory tests of thyroid function;so additional information can be obtained by the ratio androsterone-aetiocholanolone which is lowered in hypothyroidism and increased in hyperthyroidism. 125 cases were studied and classified according to the total gonadotrophic activity of the urine. This classification has at least a prognostic value since no spontaneous reestablishment of menses was seen in both hypo- and hype r gonadotrophic cases. Ih both these groups hypooestrogenism was the rule. Hypogonadotrophism (under 4 MUU.) was disclosed in 10 cases, 5 of which with panhypopituitarism and 5 with dissociated pituitary failure (normal thyroid and adrenocortical function). Stimulation with chorionic gonadotrophin induced vaginal bleeding in the last group but was of no effect in the first one. There was no case of Sheehan's syndrome. Seven cases were in the hyper gonadotrophic group (over 60 MUU.) and were considered as primary ovarian failures (premature menopause). Ages were from 23 to 32. None had signs of increased production of ACTH or TSH. 84.4% of the cases fell in the normogonadotrophic group and were subsequently divided according to the oestrogenic state: In 4 cases the endocrine pattern was one of normogonadotrophic activity with hyperoestrogenism. After uterine curretage regular menses were reestablished spontaneously in 2 cases and after progesterone therapy in the other 2. Hypooestrogenie normogonadotrophic oligoamenorrhoea was diagnosed in 55. In 39 of these no other endocrine disturbance or organic lesion was found and a subdivision was made of these 39 according to the gonadotrophins being between 14 and 35 MUU. (27 cases) or 35 and 60 MUU. (12 cases). In the first group 21 had spontaneous re establishment of menses and 2 became pregnant. The patients of the second group were believed to be identical to the premature menopause ones. All were given cyclic therapy but none became pregnant. Ih the remaining 16 cases the following conditions were found: tumours of the pituitary (2), Chiari-Fromme 1 syndrome (3), hyperthyroidism (1) and adrenal androgenic hyperf unction (10). This last group was characterised by marked increase in 17-KS and DHA4 both rising still (20 to 45%) after ACTH stimulation and decreasing after suppression with fluorohydrocortisone. Finally 49 cases were included in the normogonadotrophic normooestrogen group, so distributed: Normal endocrine pattern: 10 cases, 9 spontaneous recoveries, 3 pregnancies. Isolated failure of progesterone production: 18 cases with 5 spontaneous recoveries. 13 bleeding regularly after cyclic progesterone therapy, 4 becoming pregnant. Nonreacting endometrium: 3 cases (1 Ashermann syndrome, 2 uterine insensibilities). Hypothyroidism: 3 cases (1 secondary to hypothalamic - pituitary dysfunction had also adrenocortical failure and was cured with triiodothyronine followed by thyroxine plus prednisolone, 2 of primary hypothyroidism treated the same way except for omission of prednisolone, with re-establishment of menses but no pregnancy). Ovarian androgenic hyperf unction: 15 cases. All had only slight increase in 17-KS. and a more definite increase in androsterone. After ACTH stimulation there was only slight or no increase in 17-KS (O to 25% increase) and there was no alteration after the suppression test. Ih this group were found: 1 case of ovarian tumour (adenoma testicularis of Pick), 3 cases of Stein-Leventhal and 4 of thin-walled polycystic ovaries. Comes - Lisbon.
