T1  - THE ANATOMO-PATHOLOGICAL and BIOLOGICAL ASPECTS QF THE SYNDROME of STEIN-LEVENTHAL
T3  - Sur lea aspects ana t omo-pathologiques et biologiques du syndrome de Stein-Leventhal
A1  - Piotti L.A.
A1  - Mazzi C.
A1  - Ferrari E.
A1  - Savi C.
A1  - Ghiringhelli F.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - A study on 10 cases of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome revealed an increase in the urinary excretion of 3<r-ll-desoxyketosteroids, metabolites of testosterone and androstenedione. The hypothesis that the ovary is responsible for the genesis of the hormonal disturbance can be based on the following findings; ( 1 ) The histological and histochemical data which show the presence of lipoidophilic tissue in the ovarian interfollicular, and especially the juxtahilar interstitium. (2) The inhibition of the adrenal cortex by dexamethasone. (3) The increase in the urinary metabolites after the administration of chorionic gonadotrophin with inhibition of the hypophysoadrenal system. The results of the AC T H test appear t iindicate that the adrenal s are involved in the hyperandrogenism, however. The hypothesis of a congenital disturbance of the steroidogenesis in the ovaries permits assumption of a pathological chain as follows: primary hypoluteinism, luteotrophin anterior hypophyseal reaction, stimulation of the interstitial androgen-producing cells of the ovary and adrenal cortex. (X. 5).
