T1  - HYPERTENSIVE FORM of CONGENITAL ADRENOCORTICAL HYPERPLASIA. ANALYSIS of a CASE with COEXISTING POLYCYSTIC OVARIES
A1  - Bergman P.
A1  - Sjogren B.
A1  - Haansson B.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - A case of the hypertensive type of congenital adrenocortical hyperplasia (EberleinBongiovanni's syndrome) is described, The patient was followed up for 12 yr. The urinary steroid pattern was characterized by the presence of tetrahydro11desoxyhydrocortisone and tetrahydrolldesoxycorticosterone. The urinary excretion of pregnanetriol was only moderately increased. Adequate cortisone treatment was started 11 yr. after hypertension was demonstrated. Treatment had no effect on the blood pressure but the excretion of steroids became normal. The patient was 14 yr. old when first seen by the authors. She then showed virilism. Menstruation occurred for the first time after 10 days of cortisone treatment. Laparotomy revealed polycystic ovarian changes of the type seen in theSteinLeventhalsyndrome. Wedge resection of the ovaries was followed by normal menstruations, without any cortisone treatment. The relationship between abnormal secretion of steroids by the ovaries or the adrenal cortex and polycystic changes of the ovaries is discussed. (III, 10).
