T1  - THE EFFECT of ORAL MONOBENZYL ETHER of STILBESTPOL on OVULATION. UTERINE BLEEDING. ANDINFERTILJTY
A1  - Laberge J.L.
A1  - Rock J.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - An analysis of the effects of Monozol therapy on ovulation, uterine bleeding and infertility in 116 patients was presented. The group studied included 56 patients with ovulatory disorders and 60 complaining of impaired fertility. Of 68 patients with ovarian dysfunction 25 (36.7%) demonstrated some stimulation of ovulation as a result of Mor.ozol therapy. In 4 this function continued after the cessation of therapy, and in one the effect may have been permanent. In the group of patients with ovulatory disorders, 7 (4 with secondary amenorrhoea and 3 with interspersed anovuloand oligomenorrhoea) showed a peculiar elevation of temperature of short duration (5-6 days). The rise always occurred 3 or 4 days following a 21-day span of Monozol administration. This suggests stimulation of luteal activity similar to that noted in 2 other cases (with anovulomenorrhoea) with prolonged high temperature for 3540 days, which in one terminated with the expulsion of a decidual cast without chorionic vilfr. Among the 48 more classic ovulators, delayed ovulation was recorded in 7, while in 7 others ovulation appeared to be inhibited. In another patient of this group, Monozol probably corrected permanently persistent premenstrual staining. Of the entire series of 116 patients. 14 (12%) presented only withdrawal bleeding and/or staining. Most of these had received the larger dosages (4.5-13.5 mg. daily). Various undesirable side effects, totalling 25 instances, were reported in 20 patients (17.2% of the series). In the entire group of 116 patients. 10 (8.6%) pregnancies occurred either during Monozol therapy or within 2 months following its cessation. Of these 10 conceptions, one resulted in abortion in the first trimester, and 9 terminated in normal, term deliveries. Seven of these 10 patients were among the 25 who showed some stimulation of ovulation from Monozol treatment. In several of the patients, other/ factors which would limit fertility of these women were implicated, i.e. tubal occlusion. Stein - Leventhal ovaries, conditions leading to poor postcoital tests, oligospermia of the husband, etc. The effect of Monozol on the physiology of ovulation is unpredictable in any given case.
