T1  - CONTROVERSIAL ASPECTS of the STEW-LEVENTHAL SYNDROME
A1  - Stein I.F.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - One of the controversial aspects of the Steln-Leventhal syndrome is the duration of benefit from bilateral wedge resection. Some physicians have reported that it is only temporary. In the author's series of 103 patients, over a period of 30 yr., there have been no recurrences. In 2 cases, one 12 yr. and the other 28 yr. after ovarian resection, there was no evidence of recurrence of the polycystic change in the ovaries. The author believes that many unsatisfactory results occurred because of faulty or incomplete diagnosis and through individual variations in surgical technique. A visual method of diagnosis is urged in all cases to establish a definite diagnosis. There has been some question as to whether a syndrome actually exists, the criterion depending upon the pathologist's report of resected tissue. The author believes that the syndrome is a clinical entity and that the pathological report is of secondary importance<< inasmuch as poly cystic ovaries which are quite similar occur in a number of disorders other than Stein-Leventhal syndrome. Hirsutism. which occurs in slightly more than half of the patients with this syndrome, is believed by some authors to be ovarian in origin and adrenal by others. Why it occurs at all has not been satisfactorily explained. Some interesting investigative work is in progress on this phase of the syndrome. The author has reported to date 103 patients; 76 couples were followed for sterility, in which 67 of the women became pregnant one or more times (88.1%); 161 pregnancies and 136 live births, including 5 sets of twins, were reported.
