T1  - INADEQUATE SECRETORY ENDOMETRIUM
A1  - Malkani P.K.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - A total of 4,483 endometrial biopsy specimens were taken from 2,556 infertile women. The morphology of the endometrium was studied>> and the specimens were dated histologically in relation to the day of the cycle. The patients were divided into 3 categories with respect to the type of infertility. Group I. Primary Sterility: Those who had never conceived: 1,725 patients. Group II. Secondary Sterility: Those who had given birth to premature or full term babies: 747 patients. Group IU. Aborte re: Those whose pregnancies had ended in abortions: 84 patients. Endometrial tb was diagnosed in 241 of the 2,556 patients (9.4%). The percentage of patients showing proliferative phase endometrium (average 29%). adequate secretory phase (average 52%), and inadequate secretory endometrium (average 18%) was practically the same in all the groups. Inadequate secretory endometrium was found more often (19.8%) in Group I than in Groups II (17.3%) and IU(17.1%). The percentage of patients with inadequate secretory endometrium is lowest in the age group 26 to 30 yr. (23.0%). whereas the frequency rises as the age advances (27.2% to 34.3%) and is also higher in the younger age group (26.0% to 32.1%). The frequency of inadequate secretory endometrium is maximal (43%) in patients with, menstrual cycle lengths of 42 to 60 days. Anovulatory cycles, inadequate secretory endometrium. and tuberculous endometritis cause sterility in 52.7% of infertile women. The frequency of these unfavourable factors increases as the menstrual cycle length increases.
