T1  - CRITICAL CONSIDERATIONS about CRYSTALLIZATION in THE CERVICAL MUCUS and THEIR PRACTICAL APPLICATION. with PARTICULAR REFERENCE to THE PROBLEM of STERILITY -
T3  - Kritische Bemerkungen uber Kristallisation im Cervixachleim und ihre Nutzanwendung, besonders auf daa Sterilitats-Problem
A1  - Rodecurt M.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - A. large series of experimental studies led to a number of new findings in connection *ith the significance of the crystallization of the cervical mucus. From the quantity jf the mucus, its pattern and its drawing-out properties, estimations of the term rf ovulation are possible. These macroscopical alterations of the mucus are frequent.y absent during ovulation. A distinction is also made between 'fresh-green* and dry* arborization. Pure fern patterns have remarkably often been found in the second phase of the cycle<< and an amorphous image in the first phase. The interrupion of the fern phenomenon (positive-negative-positive) parallel the cyclic curve of Ae follicle-hormone level* Before, during and shortly after the menstruation fern >henomena can also be observed. The quantity, drawing strength and arborization of he cervical mucus are only manifestations of variations of the ratio between the .'olliculin and the progesterone level; the quantity is further also influenced by psychical milieu and local-pathological factor>>. A sudden increase of the quantity of mucus, with good drawing strength and fern phenomenon often characterize ovulation; good drawing strength has also been observed with the amorphous image in 11.5% of the cases. Discrepancies between the fern phenomenon and macroscopical mucosal findings can be explained from the biological variations of the follicuUn-iprogesterone level. With a normal 28-day cycle none of these phenomena constitute differential-diagnostic elements in regard to the ovulation term and the second peak of the folliculin level<< A persistent fern phenomenon does not necessarily mean an anovuIatory cycle. With interruption of the phenomenon an anovulatory cycle is a possibility, but it does not have to persist until haemorrhage occurs. The phase of the cycle cannot be determined on the basis of the fern phenomenon; a brief occurrence of the phenomenon in ovarian insufficiency apparently means a marked deficiency of folliculin and progesterone. Tt is important that the penetration rather than the invasion test be carried out, and that large dry smears are prepared* Important elements in connection with sterility are: artificial suppression of excessive mucus secretion; studies of arborization in cervical fluor; testing of dry smears of 23-32 days, and testing with pure NaCl solution. In all. the author examined 5422 smears from 1600 cases. Heiss - Graz.
