T1  - HYPERANDROGENS of OVARIAN ORIGIN
T3  - Les hyperandrogenes d'origine ovarienne
A1  - Paget M.
A1  - Gaudefroy M.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - After an introduction and some historical notes concerning hyperandrogenism of ovarian origin, mention is made of the principal anatomo-pathological lesions which may bring about these endocrinological conditions. These lesions can be schematically subdivided into: (a) arrhenoblastomata; (b) dystrophic ovaries of Stein; (c) hilar hyperplasia of Berger. The first group can be subdivided in its turn into intermediary arrhenoblastomata which have little virilizing effect and are not very malignant, and the atypical arrhenoblastomata which have a high virilizing potency and are strongly malignant. The clinical signs are a male-type hairgrowth, which is the first sign of an abnormal androgenic state, the menstrual alterations, which develop very quickly and which in the more severe cases may end in amenorrhoea, and general alterations of psychic nature, etc. The diagnostic criteria and the examination methods are particularly interesting. The androgenic steroids are excreted with the urine in the form of and roste r one and of ethiocholanolone which are likewise metabolites of the androgens of adrenal origin, and this mixed origin renders the biochemical diagnosis difficult. This problem can best be solved by quantitative determination of certain urinary steroids under the following conditions: (1) before and after stimulation of the adrenal cortex; (2) before and after block of the adrenal cortex; ( 3) before and after stimulation of the ovaries with the adrenal cortex blocked; (4) before and after simultaneous block of the adrenal cortex and the ovaries. The principal diagnostic methods are briefly described. Special attention is drawn to the differential diagnosis; it is pointed out that cases of hyperandrogenism of non-ovarian origin are more frequent and furthermore, that the diagnosis is often to be made by elimination. This article is very accurate particularly where the diagnosis is concerned, and gives some brief notes on prognosis and treatment.
