T1  - SECRETION of ANDROGENS by THE POLYCYSTIC OVARY and ITS SIGNIFICANCE
A1  - Mahesh V.B.
A1  - Greenblatt R.B.
A1  - Aydar C.A.
A1  - Roy S.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - The authors have studied the role of the ovary in the secretion of excessive androgens in the poly cystic- ovary syndrome. They found 2 types of polycystic ovaries. One of these contained large quantities ofA- androstenedione and 17ar- hydroxyprogesterone while the other contained dehydroepiandrosterone. The levels of urinary dehydroepiandrosterone, androsterone and etiocholanolone remained elevated even after adrenal suppression. Furthermore, when the ovaries were stimulated with exogenous human- pituitary FSH while the adrenals were kept suppressed, there was a marked rise in the above- mentioned steroids in the urine of patients with the Stein- Leventhal syndrome. These observations indicate the secretion of large amounts of androgens by the polycystic ovary. Dehydroepiandrosterone or A4androstenedione was detected in the ovarian venous blood of patients with the SteinLeventhal syndrome. The question has been raised whether the secretion of weak androgens such as A4- androstenedione and dehydroepiandrosterone can account for the hirsutism in the polycystic- ovary syndrome. The authors have demonstrated in- vivo conversion of these steroids to testosterone in normal women and postulate that the androgenic activity of these weak androgens is mediated by their conversion to testosterone.
