T1  - TREATMENT of the SYMPTOMATIC COMPLEXES and COLLATERAL SYNDROMES of the MENSTRUAL CYCLE (DYSMENORRHOEA, MIDPAINS and PREMENSTRUAL TENSION) - Trata ment o dos complexes sintomaticos e efndromas eclaterais do ciclo menstrual. (Dismenorreia, dor intermenstrual e tensao pre-menstrual)
A1  - De Albuquerque E.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - As fundamental causes of secondary dysmenorrhoea the following are mentioned: pelvic congestion, endometriosie, adenomyosis and membranous dysmenor rhoea. As regarde pelvic congestion the following are among the releasing factors: use of contraceptive drugs or methods, sexual maladjustment, fear of pregnancy, conjugal conflictss etc. The psychiatrist can help in establishing the right treatment. The author recommends daily rest for 2 hr. in the horizontal position in order to diminish the venous pressure in the pelvis and to stimulate the return circulation. The daily practice of cold baths during the intermenstrual period has given satisfactory results to some authors. With reference to endometriosis. conservative treatment is recommended, except in cases with invasion of intestines, bladder or ureters, which alters their function. If the patient has not had children, in the conservative treatment periodical suppression of menstruation is recommended for 4-6 mth. by administration of stilboestrol, methyltestosterone or nortestosterone. If surgery is necessary before the age of 35 yr., it should be conservative. In patients over 35 yr. the treatment should be exclusively surgical, with preservation of ovarian function if possible. With reference to adenomyosis, hysterectomy is recommended if the condition is diffuse and local surgical treatment in localized forms. In membranous dysmenorrnoea the author recommends suppression of ovulation or use of testosterone. The results vary from one case to another. In extreme cases, the presacral nerve can be resected. With reference to primary dysmenorrhoea, the au\thor advisee: (1) preventive treatment: favourable familial environment, no increase in affectivity and care during menstruation, maintenance of ordinary activity, healthy, adequate diet and healthy life in free air complete these preventive measures. (2) Spasmolytic treatment, which should be started 24-48 hr. before the probable date of menstruation and be repeated during 4-6 cycles. Commercial spasmolytics, papaverine and association of codeine-phenacetin or acetylsalicylic acid give good results. (3) Hormonal treatment, which is based on suppressing ovulation. In this way the large contractile waves of small frequency of the secretory phase are replaced by waves of small amplitude and large frequency, which are typical of anovulatory cycles. Oestrogene should be given from the 5th to the 25th day of the cycle. Stilboestrol suppresses ovulation in 50% in a dose of 1 mg. daily, and in 80% in a dose of 3 mg. daily. The effective dose of ethinyloestradiol varies between 0.05 and 1 mg. daily. (4) Surgical treatment. The most effective is resection of the presacral nerve or the superior hypogastric plexus. Poor results are believed to be due solely to a faulty technique. (5) Cure by pregnancy. In many young patients with dysmenorrhoea the onset of pregnancy often means definitive cure of this disease, owing to the great alterations which pregnancy involves. The author also deals with intermenstrual pains, for the treatment of which it is necessary to know in the first place if there exists some infective lesion, dystopia of the genital organs or a circulatory disturbance. Once these processes have been ruled out, suppression of ovulation by androgens before and during the possible ovulation solves the problem. Finally, premenstrual tension is dealt with. The removal of salt from the diet and administration of diuretics, the latter 10-14 days before the menstrual cycle. Recently, 8-bromotheophyllinate has been employed, which although not being a diuretic properly speaking, behaves as such, since it mobilizes the water of the oedema and helps in its elimination. It gives better results when associated with mepyratnine maleate or, in order to neutralize its depressive action, with amphetamine sulphate. Garzon - Burgos.
