T1  - Relation of central ncrvona system, pituitary gonadotrophins, and ovarian hormone accretion
A1  - Rothghild I.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - The present concepts of the relationship between the central nervous system and pituitary gonadotrophin and ovarian hormone secretion allow to divide the gonadotrophins into two main groups on the basis of function and regulation. The folliculotrophins, FSH and LH, constitute one grouping, these having their primary site of action on the follicular portion of the ovary. The other group consists of a single hormone, luteotrophin, which has its primary site of action on the corpus luteum. These two groups of hormones are controlled by the GNS by two entirely separate and oppositely acting systems. The fplliculotrophins are entirely dependent on the CNS for their secretion and on tne influence of nervous stimuli and ovarian hormones with respect to the acute release of ovulating hormone. Luteotrophin, on the other hand, is inhibited by the brain; it is secreted as an intrinsic property of the pituitary, and under physiological and pathological circumstances, is secreted only when the tonic inhibition by the brain is itself suppressed or removed. The possibility that the luteotrophin-progesterone system is one of positive feedback - that is, that progesterone may be one of the factors that can suppress the inhibition over LTH secretion - is a tantalizing one, and offers a possible clue to the reason why the corpus luteum is so typically shortlived. Finally, folliculotrophin secretion may also be subject to inhibition by the GNS, this inhibition presumably acting upon either the portion of the CNS that tonically stimulates foHiculotrophin secretion or the one controlling acute release of ovulating hormone, or on both. This concept offers a possible explanation for the way in which oestrogens reduce the rate of foHiculotrophin secretion, for the absence of foHiculotrophin secretion during the prepubertal period, for the occurrence of cyclic anoestrus in seasonal breeders, and for the influence of psychic factors in human anovulation.
