AN  - 281176183
T1  - PSYCHOSOMATIC INFERTILITY
A1  - Rothman D.
A1  - Kaplan A.H.
A1  - Nettles E.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - Six cases of psychosomatic infertility treated successfully by psychotherapy are reported. The therapy was offered generally on a weekly basis but frequently less often. The technique of therapy emphasized the development of a warm accepting relationship between the patient and the physician with history taking, ventilation, confession, encouragement, and emotional support. Nearly all of the patients exhibited the common features of an infantile dependent individual., unable to express anger to her parents for fear of being rejected, starved, or destroyed. In general, they were overprotected and felt uneasy as they developed a feminine identification because of a marked dependency to a hostile rejecting mother. In earlier years the women feared separation and desertion. Conscious acceptance of the culturally valued goal of pregnancy produced serious conflict in these women. Becoming pregnant meant accepting sexual feelings, being comfortable in competing witn a stronger maternal figure, giving up the fantasy of remaining a child, and not having to compete with the unborn child. Since the meeting of any of these demands was frightening, infertility was the symptom of choice. The fear of becoming a mother revived in them their own unmet dependent relationship to their parents, especially the mother, and unconsciously they developed a defence against conception. Their continued inability to become pregnant was to these women clear indication of their lack of femininity and a punishment for their unconscious attitudes. Just how these factors operate to produce infertility is not always clear. There is some evidence to indicate that psychological factors might interfere with conception by producing anovulatory menstrual cycles, tubal spasm, hostile cervical secretions, vaginismus, and the avoidance of coitus during fertile periods.
