T1  - The treatment of anovulation (japanese)
A1  - Watanabe H.
A1  - Maeda K.
A1  - Kusuda M.
A1  - Otsuji Y.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - Patients with anovulation were treated with gonadotropin, synthetic adrenocorticosteroid or dieneephalo-hypophyseal X-irradiation, and results were compared. Thirty-four patients who complained of sterility and had phases of secondary amenorrhoea or oligomenorrhoea were treated with 1,000 to 8,000 I.U. gonadotropin (PMS) daily for 5 days, followed by treatment with 1,000 I.U. gonadotropin (HCG) daily for 5 days, and in half of them ovulation was induced. Whereas 17 out of 23 cases of 1st grade amenorrhoea were induced to ovulate, none of 11 cases of 2nd grade amenorrhoea could be induced to ovulate by this treatment. Nine patients with anovulation who showed no response to the gonadotropin therapy were treated with 5 nag. of prednisolone or 0.5 mg. of dexamethasone by oral administration daily for a month, and 4 of them were induced to ovulate. Ten patients with anovulation were treated by diencephalohypophyseal, low-dosage irradiation of X-rays 3 to 5 times at 1-week intervale. Though only 2 out of these 10 cases were induced to ovulate by this treatment, it should be noted that the success rate depends upon the cause and the grade of anovulation. It is suggested that the dieneephalohypophyseal X-irradiation therapy should be tried before gonadotropin or other therapy.
