T1  - Gynandroblastoma. Report of a case with hormonal studies
A1  - McBride R.A.
A1  - Sturgis S.H.
A1  - Crigler Jr. J.F.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - A case of gynandroblastoma is presented in detail with pre- and postoperative hormonal studies, and microscopic findings. This leads to a discussion of any classification of these tumours on the basis of either hormonal or morphological characteristics. The authors' patient presented hirsutism, clitoral enlargement, and deepening of the voice, with amenorrhoea, but also showed a maintenance of well developed female secondary sex characteristics and a high cornification of the urinary sediment. Preoperatiye and postoperative AGTH tests were interpreted as compatible with the conclusion that the tumour produced androgcns as precursors for the 17-ketosteroids in the urine. In considering the histogenesis of these tumours, the authors note that zones of intimate intermingling of arrhenoblastoma and granulosa-cell tumour might be considered indirect evidence of origin of both tumours from the same cell type. The contralateral ovary in this case was found to show typical features associated with the Stein-Levcnthal syndrome. It is suggested that the virilizing ovarian tumour in one ovary might represent one aetiological pathway for the development of some of the ovarian features of Stein-Leventhal in the other.
