AN  - 281291434
T1  - STATISTICAL SURVEY of STERILITY (Japanese)
A1  - Maeyama M.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - Statistical studies were carried out on 116 patients with sterility seen from 1959 to 1962. They were classified according to the classification list of Schultze, Tsherne and Engerhalt. It was shown that sterility was most common among ages ranging from 25 to 29 years and that the percentage of this age group was 52.6% of the total number of gynaecological cases. A considerable number of patients with sterility gave a history of appendicitis (35.0%) and tuberculosis (35%). Hypoplasia uteri was considered to be the most important primary causal factor, confirmed by hysterosalpingography. It might be of interest that a small number of patients had an anovulatory cycle revealed by continuous observation of the basal body temperature. Successful pregnancy resulted in 2 cases treated by surgical reconstruction of occluded fallopian tubes and by an ovarian wedge, resection for polycystic ovarian disease in a case in which ovulation could not be induced by conventional hormonal treatment. Aspermia or oligospermia were found among male sterility factors in 4.3% of the total number of sterility patients.
