AN  - 281486930
T1  - The effect of oral monobenzyl ether of stilbestrol on ovulation, uterine bleeding, and infertility
A1  - Laberge J.-L.
A1  - Rock J.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - An analysis of the effects of 'monozol' therapy on ovulation, uterine bleeding, ana infertility in 116 patients was presented. The group studied included 56 patients with ovuiatory disorders aau 60 complaimag of unpaired fertility. Among 44 anovulatory patients, evulation was induced during or after treatment is 13 (29.5%). One of these apparently became a regular ovulator and continued to be such after cessation of therapy. Ovulation was also temporarily induced in 12 (50%) of 24 irregular ovulators. Thus, of 68 patients with ovarian dysfunction 25 (36.7%) demonstrated some stimulation of ovulation as a result of 'monozor therapy. In 4, this function continued after the cessation of therapy, and in one, the effect may have been permanent. In the group of patients with ovuiatory disorders, 7 (4 with secondary amenorrhoea and 3 with interspersed anovulo- and oligomenorrhoea), showed a peculiar elevation of temperature of short duration (5-6 days). The rise always occurred 3 or 4 days following a 21-day span of 'monozol' administration. This suggests stimulation of luteal activity similar to that noted in 2 other cases (with anovulomenorrhoea) with prolonged high temperature for 35-40 days, which in one terminated with the expulsion of a decidual cast without chorionic villi. Among the 48 more classic ovulators, delayed ovulation was recorded in 7, while in 7 others ovulation appeared to be inhibited. In another patient of this group, 'monozol' probably corrected permanently persistent premenstrual staining. Of the entire series of 116 patients, 14 112%) presented only withdrawal bleeding and/or staining. Most of these had received the larger dosages (4.5-13.5 mg. daily). Various undesirable side effects, totalling 25 instances, were reported in 20 patients (17.2% of the series). In the entire group of 116 patients, 10 (8.6%) pregnancies occurred either during 'monozol' therapy or within 2 months following its cessation. Of these 10 conceptions, one resulted in abortion in the first trimester, and 9 terminated in normal, term deliveries. Seven of these 10 patients were among the 25 who showed some stimulation of ovulation from 'monozol' treatment In several of the patients, other factors which would limit fertility of these women were implicated, i.e., tubal occlusion, Stein-Lcventhal ovaries, conditions leading to poor postcoital tests, oligospermia of the husbands, etc. The effect of 'monozoP on the physiology of ovulation is unpredictable in any given case.
