T1  - The application of urinary ertragen measurements to problems in gynecology
A1  - Brown J.B.
A1  - Matthew G.D.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - This survey is based on personal experiences. To obtain an insight in the aetiology of disturbances and a rational basis for therapy and for determining the effect of treatment on the ovarian function the urinary oestrogen excretion was' assayed in healthy women and patients with various gynaecological disorders. Oestrone, oestradiol and oestriol were determined with Brown's method and the reliability of the method was tested with OMabelled oestriol. Women with normal menstrual cycles and women in the post-menopause were used as controls. In women with normal menstrual cycles a low excretion is observed in the first week after menstruation. Thereafter the excretion rises slowly to reach a peak on the i5th day of the cycle, then falls abruptly and slowly rises to a peak lower than the first and occurring approximately on the 4th day before menstruation. This is followed by a decrease and menstruation sets in. Women in the post-menopause naturally have a low excretion which stays below io mg. per 24 hr. Patients with gynaecological disorders were divided into 3 large groups: (I) amenorrhoea, (2) abnormal uterine bleeding and (3) functional ovarian tumours. The group of amenorrhoea was divided into primary amenorrhoea (6 cases) due to congenital and other changes in the uterus, ovaries or hypothalamus, and secondary amenorrhoea (40 cases) caused by ovarian hypofunction and pplycystic ovaries, in some cases accompanied by hirsutism. The group of patients with dysfunctional bleeding contained women with a constant oestrogen excretion and other patients with fluctuating levels. This group consisted of patients with anovulatory cycles (17 cases), polycvstic ovaries (2 patients), and patients with functioning ovarian tumours (3 patients). The endometrial image correlates with the amount of oestrogens in the urine, except in cases of polycvstic degeneration of the ovaries with hirsutism. A fluctuating oestrogen excretion, as seen in women with normal cycles, is observed in some cases of anovulatory bleeding and in cystic glandular hyperplasia. The resulte of studies on patients who had been treated by irradiation of the ovaries permitted the conclusion that the dose used (721 r.) suffices to prevent development of new follicles but has no effect on a follicle which has already started its cycle. The influence of progestational agents on the ovaries was also studied. The effect of these drugs depends on the dosage and the phase of the cycle at administration.
