T1  - Functional and morphologic studies of the ovaries and suprarenal glands in the Stein-Leventhal syndrome
A1  - Leventhal M.L.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - Two hirsute patients with the syndrome were studied, one was 31 yr. of age, the other 20 yr. The adrenal glands showed no histological evidence of hyperfunction. Microscopic study of ovarian tissue showed that the hilus was normal. The important findings in study of ovarian tissue was unusual hyperplasia of the theca cells. Anatomically, in these 2 cases, the author infers that the polycystic ovary is the site of pathological change and that the adrenal gland does not play a role in the syndrome. Steroid studies before and after laparotomy and in-vitro studies of ovarian steroid biogenesis lend further credence to the notion that the changes in the ovary account for the symptom complex.
