AN  - 281487295
T1  - Induction of ovulation in the human. Older and newer approaches
A1  - Swyer G.I.M.
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - In patients with disturbances of ovulation without definite endocrine cause cyclical oral administration of oestrogens is still used. On account of the possible genetic repercussions irradiation of the hypophysis and ovaries with X-rays has gone out of practice. This form of treatment was only effective if the patients did not have amenorrhoea. So far the following substances have been used, (i) Human chorion gonadotropin. According to some authors this is ineffective and might even lead to ovarian atresia. Other authors are of the opinion that this hormone can indeed provoke ovulation. (2) Serum gonadotropin. This has been seen to provoke ovulation, but not constantly so. (3) A combination of HCG and serum gonadotropin. This led to promising results, but the number of patients treated is still too small to permit conclusions. Ovulation has been also reported after treatment with 'synapoidin', a combination of HGG and an extract of animal anterior hypophyseal lobe. (4) Anterior pituitary gonadotropins. The results obtained led to the use of: (5) Human anterior pituitary extract. This was given by Gemzell at a dosage of 10 mg. for periods of 10 days. Polycystic enlargement of the ovaries was seen in 27 of 40 women treated. The oestrogens increased in 14, pregnanediol in 4 patients. In 2 7 women an atrophie endometnum was found; 16 reacted by proliferation, none with secretion, possibly due to incapability of the hypophysis to release luteinizing hormone. Ten patients with proliferation were treated and 7 were found to have secretion. IfHGG was added later the excretion of pregnanediol and 17-hydroxyketosteroids increased considerably. In 5 women with amenorrhoea ovulation was repeatedly induced, 2 became pregnant. Buxton and Herrmann also induced ovulation with this substance. (6) Human menopausal gonadotropin (HMG]. The results are encouraging, but conclusions cannot yet be drawn. (7) Finally ovulation can be induced by chemical means. 'MER-25' and clomiphene have been used. 'MER-25' at low dosage caused ovulation in several patients with Stein-Leventhal syndrome, at higher dosage it has an anti-oestrogenic effect. Clomiphene was given from the ioth to the soth day of the cycle, 50 mg. daily. Temperature became biphasic, endometrial biopsies revealed hyperplasia or early secretion, oestrogen excretion increased and: the pregnanediol increased in a few cases. Therefore this substance possibly does not have a gonadotrophin-stimulating function, but stimulates the adrenocortical functions.
