T1  - DEFECTIVE BIOSYNTHESIS of OVARIAN STEROIDS in THE STEINLEVENTHAL SYNDROME
A1  - Short R.V.
A1  - London D.R.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - An analysis of the steroids present in cyst fluid from the ovaries of five patients with the Stein-Leventhal syndrome revealed a very high concentration of androstenedione, and no detectable amounts of oestradiol-17-beta oroestrone. In seven control patients, on the other hand, in whom normal or cystic follicles were an incidental finding at laparotomy, the concentrations of androstenedione were significantly lower, and oestradiol-17-beta was detected in every instance. On the basis of this evidence it is postulated that in the Stein-Leventhal syndrome there is a defect in the biosynthesis of oestrogens within the cystic follicles, as androstenedione is, normally, an intermediate in the biosynthesis of oestradiol-17-beta from progesterone, and the defect in the biosynthesis leads to its accumulation. This could possibly account for the virilism seen in some patients. A tentative explanation is also offered for the success of the wide variety of non-specific surgical procedures in curing the condition: their common factor is trauma to the ovary, which, like artificial rupture of follicles in some animals, brings about luteinization. Rohan - Valasske Mezirici.
