T1  - CLINICAL TRIALS of ORAL CONTRACEPTIVES
A1  - Mears E.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - Over 200 new steroids have already been tested for contraceptive action but norethindrone and norethynodrel (enavid) are most used. Side effects occur but seem to diminish later. The dosage of 10 mg. was diminished to 5 and later to 2. 5 mg. norethynodrel with apparently the same results. Trials were organised by the Family Planning Association in London. Preliminary trials were made on postponement of menstruation (giving 5-mg. tablets from day 20 for 20 days), inhibition of ovulation (with 5-mg.tablets from day 5 till day 25), the secretory change of the endometrium in amenorrhoeic women (giving progesterone from day 10 till day 20 after premedication with oestrogens). In large scale trials the method of administration was the same as in the Birmingham trial. The tablets contained 2.5 m g. norethynodrel with changing percentages of E O- 3- ME. i.e. 0.035, 0.1 and 0.15. With 0.1 and 0.15 mg. there was no breakthrough bleeding though apparently there was anovulation, which was not effectuated with 0.035 EO-3-ME per tablet. Nausea as side effect was present most often in the first cycle but diminished rapidly. Most patients claim to have more libido. The efficiency of the tablets depends to a great deal on the contents of oestrogen. 0.035 per tablet is not enough to prevent ovulation, but 0.1 and 0.15 is sufficient. Of 89 women only one conceived (in 589 worn en-months). In general the method is well accepted though a few patients stopped because of side effects. Breakthrough bleeding occurred in 22% in patients using the 2.5-mg. tablet with 0.15 EO-3-ME.
