AN  - 280886986
T1  - Estrogens and endometrial carcinoma
A1  - Andrews W.C.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - Although the incidence rates vary from paper to paper with different interpretations of pathological material, the majority of evidence would seem to indicate an increased incidence of endometrial hyperplasia both prior to and in association with carcinoma of the endometrium. Hyperplasia of the endometrium is known to be produced by unphyBiological oestrogen activity. There is an increased incidence of endometrial carcinoma in postmenopausal women with functioning ovarian tumours. The incidence is higher with the comas than with granulos a cell tumours. The majority of evidence supports a conclusion of increased incidence of cortical stromM hyperplasia of the ovary in women with carcinoma of the endometrium. Cytological evidence indicates continued oestrogen production postmenopausally in a significant number of patients, particularly those with endometrial carcinoma. This at times may be extra-ovarian. Studies of the myometrium and the majority of the studies of the end omet Hum give further indication of this continued function. The lack of supporting evidence in studies of tube and cervix suggests the possitility of variation in threshold of response to oestrogen in these structures. The production of endometrial carcinoma in rabbits by oestrogen administration is a significant link in the chain of evidence. The above evidence, while not conclusive, is strongly suggestive of a causal relationship between prolonged unphysiological oestrogen activity and the production of endometrial carcinoma. No conclusions can be reached about the role of exogenous oestrogen, age of menopause, hepatic insufficiency, or the incidence of myoma s. although some suggestive evidence is found, particularly in regard to myomas. The increased incidence of obesity, infertility, anovulation, hypertension and diabetes seems to indicate a general endocrine aberration in patients with endometrial carcinoma. There is also evidence of increased pituitary activity in these patients. It seems reasonable to hypothesize a general endocrine imbalance, particularly involving the gonadotrophins and oestrogen, as aetiological factors in the development of endo me trial carcinoma. The genetic substrate is probably of great importance in determining which patients react to this imbalance by reaching the end point of endometrial carcinoma.
