T1  - SYNTHETIC PROGESTINS in THIS MANAGEMENT of ANOVULATORY DYSFUNCTIONAL UTERINE BLEEDING
A1  - Taymor M.L.
A1  - Sturgis S.H.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - Two synthetic progestins, 17a-ethinyl-19-nortestosterone (norlutin) and 17alpha-ethinyl-5(10)-oestrenolone (enovid), have been used in treatment of dysfunctional bleeding. In 13 of 14 patients with anovulatory bleeding, haemorrhage ceased within 72 hours, after therapy with 10 mg. three-hourly of either drug had begun. In order to prevent the build-up of endometrium in an anovulatory cycle, withdrawal bleedings were induced with either 17alpha-methyl-19-nortestosterone (methalutin) or norlutin in doses of 1.25 to 3 ing. daily for 4 days. This resulted in a withdrawal bleeding and prevented the excessive and prolonged bleeding of the anovulatory cycle. It is pointed out that this is symptomatic control only and that the underlying trouble in these cases should be sought. In some instances the patient can be tided over until menstrual function ceases altogether and hysterectomy may often be avoided. Chalmers - Worcester.
