T1  - PREDNISONE in THE INDUCTIONOF OVULATION
A1  - Hochstaedt B.
A1  - Langer G.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - The most frequent cause of anovulatory cycles, causing nearly half of functional sterility, appears to be hyperfunction of the adrenal cortex (hyperandrogenaemia). Forty-eight such cases were investigated and ovulation occurred in all but 5 patients with prednisone dosage of 5 mg daily or this same dosage plus 1 mg. of diethylstilboestrol daily. Anovulation was corrected in 4 patients with marked hirsutism but normal 17-ketosteroids, pregnancy occurring in one of them. Prednisone therapy caused 17-ketosteroid depression as early as the 4th day, while cortisone required 10 to 14 days. Ovulation usually occurred during the first cycle treated. Intrinsic oestrogen seemed essential for successful therapy. Prednisone and oestrogen seem to have a synergistic action in regulating the all important ratio of FSH and LH necessary for ovulation. So-called 'idiopathic hirsutism'was thought to be due to androgemc substances not detectable by the Zimmerman reaction.
