T1  - PREDNISONE in THE REGULATION of MENSTRUAL DYSFUNCTION
A1  - Perloff W.H.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - Fourteen normal control women and 119 patients with irregular menstruation and/ or infertility were treated with 10 mg. of prednisone each day for 28 days and 5 mg of prednisone for up to one year. The major groups of patients included the following diagnoses: follicular cysts of the ovaries, elevated urinary 17-ketosteroids with and without hirsutism, and hirsutism without elevated 17-ketosteroids. There were also women with Stein-Leventhal ovaries, ovulatory defects, and smaller groups of miscellaneous disorders, and 18 patients in whom no definitive diagnosis was made. Prednisone administration resulted in no appreciable change in the menses of normals. Sixty-five of 94 women witn irregular menses, varying from irregi lar to grossly irregular to amenorrhoea, showed improvement in their menstrual status after prednisone therapy, and 30-45 women whose primary complaint was infertility conceived at least once. On the basis of the results described, it is suggested that a close relationship exists between ovarian and adrenal dysfunction, and that the corticoids are an effective therapeutic agent.
