T1  - Induction of ovulation in the human with human gonadotropins. preliminary report
A1  - Buxton C.L.
A1  - Herrman W.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - Eight amenorrhoeic women were given 1 to 3 courses of human pituitary extract (HPG) combined in most cases with chorionic gonadotrophm (HCG). All patients had either primary amenorrhoea or had failed to menstruate for from 3-6 years. One patient was given HCG alone and resumed menstruation and all signs of ovulation and has continued to menstruate arid apparently ovulate in a normal fashion ever since. She was not included in the series. Of the 7 remaining patients, two failed to respond to treatment. One of these was a case of congenital adrenal hyperplasia and the second of Stein-Leventhal syndrome. Both of these patients had previously failed to respond to wedge resection of the ovaries. The remaining five patients responded to treatment by uterine bleeding from a secretory endometrium and had basal body temperature charts indicating ovulation. The ovulation which occurs is apparently multiple as was shown by 1 patient in whom culdoscopy was done. A patient coming to operation for endometriosis was given a course of therapy before surgery and the ovaries were found to be enlarged about three times average size with several fresh corpora lute a present. None of the patients in this series became pregnant and none continued to menstruate or ovulate after treatment was discontinued.
