T1  - Menarche and pregnancy Menarche und Schwangerschaft
A1  - Follmer W.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - In 1935 Von Mikulicz-Radecki and Kausch reached the conclusion, on the basis of a study on 1,440 cases of girls of 14-19 yr. of age observed in the Gynaecological Hospital of Berlin University, that the menarcne, which on the average was at the age of 14, does not imply complete sexual maturity. At this moment the internal female genital organs have not yet fully developed and pregnancy was therefore usually considered impossible before the age of IQ. In 70.4% of these cases the first sexual intercourse had taken place between the ages of 13 and 17. Only 22% of these cases became pregnant, mainly girls of 17. Therefore it was thought that during the first years of the so-called sexual maturity European women are physiologically sterile. Thus far no contradictory articles had appeared; therefore the aforementioned theory was constantly Quoted in handbooks and other publications as an established (act. Publications from India, Cochin-China and other countries agreed. Negro girls have an early menarche, have early intercourse but frequently become pregnant at an older age. The present author, who has lived in Libya tor a considerable period, thinks it doubtful that such a physiological sterility does exist. He examined too non-selected, normally fertile Arabian women of the middle and lower social levels. The enquiry was carried out by himself, with the aid of a Libyan nurse. Therefore problems of language and misunderstanding were excluded. As in most underdeveloped countries menstruation, intercourse, pregnancy and delivery absolutely dominate the life of the women. The exact data are difficult to establish, however: the women cannot give their age, births do not have to be registered and therefore there are no records, so that one can only estimate. The studies, which are presented in tabular form, showed that 33% of the women had married prior to the menarche. Though it is frequently believed that these marriages are only formal, the contrary is true, as is shown by the early pregnancies. Some 50% of the women examined married in the first year after the menarche; 78.6% became pregnant within the first year, 71.4% of them within the first 6 months. For many women the first menstruation is also the last. One woman even became pregnant without having had a single menstruation. The author concludes that in Arabian women, who are no sooner sexually mature in any respect than European women, there is no physiological sterility, and suggests that this holds also true for European women. It could not be determined whether the menstrual cycle in these young women was anovulatory. Consequently it is impossible to say whether pregnancy at this age was due to ovulation caused by the intercourse. The question as to whether these pregnancies may be completed, in view of the relatively small internal genital organs, is refuted since 89% of pregnancies during the first 2 yr. after the menarche reached term.
