N2  - Prednisone appears to be an almost infallible means of inducing ovulation in cases of hyperandrogenaemia following adrenocortical dysfunction. In comparison with cortisone, prednisone is evidently more effective in the treatment of the anovulatory cycle, as it acts more quickly and efficiently, frequently in the first cycle treated. A syncrgctic effect of prednisone and oestrogen was observed. The increase of the ly-kctosteroid excretion is not an absolute criterion in the choice of the prednisone treatment, i he existence of androgenic substances, at the time being unidentified) is supposed. In patients with subnormal oestrogen excretion and an index of karyopyknosis in the vaginal epithelium never exceeding 20% prednisone failed to induce ovulation.
