T1  - Adrenal androgenic hyperftutcdon and infertility
A1  - Zener F.B.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - Adrenal androgenic hyperfunction is defined as a disturbance of adrenal cortical function resulting in an excess of adrenal androgens, as evidenced by an elevation of 17-KS excretion of over 10.0 mg. in 24 hr., or, in the presence of a normal excretion rate (below 11.0 mg./24 hr.), a shift in the components of the 17-KS group as shown by paper chromatography. The characteristic features of this syndrome are: infertility associated with (1) hirsutism, acne, and other evidences of virilism; (2) ovarian dysfunction resulting in (a) menstrual anovulation, irregularity, or amenorrhoea, and (b) hypoplasia of female sex-linked organs; (3) general metabolic (anabolic) changes. Treatment of infertility resulting from this syndrome yielded good results. Of 26 women treated with 'cortril', 19 became pregnant, producing 12 normal term pregnancies, with 10 non-viable pregnancies. Treatment with 'delalutin' yielded slightly better results: 29 of 36 women became pregnant, producing 27 normal term pregnancies with 10 non-viable pregnancies. 'Kenacort' yielded the best results: 26 of 31 women became pregnant, producing 22 normal term pregnancies with 6 non-viable pregnancies. Treatment of the cnaracteristic features of hirsutism, acne, ovarian dysfunction, and general metabolic changes in a group of 222 women who did not desire pregnancy was very satisfactory. Hirsutism and acne were relieved in all but 3 instances, while ovarian dysfunction, as evidenced by menstrual abnormalities, was corrected in all but 2 instances, both in amenorrhoeic women. There were 21 women whose chief complaint related to the metabolic disturbances associated with this syndrome, and improvement was obtained in each instance. The data advanced m this report indicate that the condition is due to a disturbance in the adrenal cortical synthesis of hydrocortisone from 17-alpha-hydroxyprogesterone, resulting in the formation of excess androgens, as evidenced by an increased urinary excretion of 17-KS. It is suggested that the prevalent upper limit of normal 17-KS excretion is too high, and that it should be not more than 11.0 nur. in 24 hr.
