T1  - Development of the human ovary. A study using histochemical technics
A1  - Pinkerton J.H.M.
A1  - McKay D.G.
A1  - Adams E.C.
A1  - Hertig A.T.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - A report of histochemical findings (MacManus, PAS, RNA, alkaline and acid phosphatase, 5-nucleotidase) in 6 embryonal gonads and 29 ovaries of foetuses and children. The germ cells, characterized by a high alkaline phosphatase activity and glycogen content, migrate into the mesenchyme of the medial slope of the mesonephric ridge before the 8th week (ovulation age). After a period of intense mitotic proliferation (8-20 weeks), the oogonia enlarge, lose cytoplasmic RNA, glycogen and alkaline phosphatase activity (ovocyte I), acquiring in the meantime a ring of follicle cells, derived from the mesenchyme. During childhood atresia decreases the number of ovocytes. The coelomic mesoblast, 'germinal epithelium', is never a source of oogonia but contributes mesenchymal cells to the underlying gonad until the 15th week, when a well-marked basement membrane is established. The follicle theca cells stem from the ovarian stroma, which arises from connective tissue, accompanying ingrowing blood vessels. 5-Nucleotidase activity is conspicuous in a normal adult tunica albuginea, but is lacking during childhood and in the Stein-Leventhal type of ovary.
