AN  - 281216603
T1  - Oral contraception by norethynodrel. a 3 year field study
A1  - Cook H.H.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - Progesterone prevents ovulation via an inhibition of the gonadotrophins. On oral administration the daily dosage is more than 3 mg. The cost of such oral contraception is prohibitive. Pincus et al. synthesized 3 steroids that have the same effect but at a lower dosage, also on oral administration. These drugs are 'norlutin' (norethisterone), 'enavid' (contains norethynodrel and 3-methylethinyloestradiol) and 'nilevar' (norethandrolone). The second was the most suitable as regards reliability, freedom from toxicity and reversibility of the gonadal functions. As bject for the study two population groups from Puerto Rico were chosen, especially on account of the high birth rate, the low death rate and great density of the population. These factors have made birth control imperative. The first group (R; consisted of 150 women who had at least 2 children, were 40 yr. old or less and had a normal married life. They were visited by a social worker, instructed and handed the tablets. The second group (P) consisted of 400 women who consulted a centre for family planning after a parturition. All patients were given a gynaecological and internistic examination. Method : from the 5th day after the onset of menstruation 1 pill was used daily (during the evening meal). This was continued for 20 days. In the cases with post-partem amenorrhoea treatment was. started immediately. If 10 days after cessation of the pills menstruation did not occur another series of administration was begun. In cases of 'break-through' the dose was doubled. The tablets contained 5 mg. norethynodrel and 0. 075 mg. cthiny Iocs trad iol. The results were as follows. The women from groups P and R were equivalent to 518 woman-years (i. e., the number of women who might have become pregnant during one year). During the trial 11 women became pregnant: 4 had already been pregnant prior to the trial and 7 had not followed the instructions. None of the women who had conscientiously followed the instructions became pregnant. The main side effects were: disorders of the digestive tract, premenstrual syndrome and signs resembling those in the beginning of pregnancy. Alter discontinuance of the tablets menstruation is at first anovulatory, but this steps after a short period. Usually mentruation occurs 2 days after the tablets have been discontinued. In 75% of the women the above-mentioned side effects occurred, necessitating discontinuance of the trial in one fifth of them. Four months after the cessation of norethynodrel 79% of the women became pregnant. The conclusion is drawn that the drug is a reliable and safe contraceptive.
