T1  - Unilateral hypoventilation in man during temporary occlueion of one pulmonary artery
A1  - Swenson E.W.
A1  - Finley T.N.
A1  - Guzbian S.V.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - In eight patients with chronic lune disease, studied during and after temporary unilateral pulmonary arterial occlusion (TUPAO) in order to determine the ventilatory response to one-sided obstruction of the flow of mixed venous blood: (a) On the average, the total ventilation was unchanged, (b) At the same time, the mean arterial Pco, did not rise, indicating that alveolar hypoventilation had not occurred, (c) The physiological dead space increased less than might have been expected considering that 45% of the total ventilation and oxygen uptake was originally performed by the lung whose pulmonary artery was later blocked. (d) In several cases the 'alveolar plateau' of CO2 became irregular during the occlusion and sloped downward; this was interpreted as delayed emptying of the lung whose COx output was curtailed from lack of perfusion. In Q patients, studied by bronchospirometry and unilateral pulmonary arterial occlusion : (a) After obstructing the flow of blood to one lung the tidal volume of that lung decreased so that its contribution to the total ventilation diminished from a mean of 45 to 29% during the occlusion, (b) During unilateral pulmonary arterial occlusion the anatomical dead space in that lung (below the carina) decreased from a mean of 31 ml. before, to 19 ml. during occlusion, (c) Although the total ventilation increased by a mean of 22%, under these circumstances the shift in the distribution of ventilation allowed the contralateral lung to increase its ventilation by a mean value of 63% (5.73 1. per min. before, 9.32 during occlusion); the normal arterial Pcos figures (mean of 38 before, 40 mm. Hg during) attest to the magnitude of this shut, (d) Allowing the 'unperfused' lung to breathe 6% CO2 m 2 cases resulted in a return to the preocclusion values for distribution of inspired gas to the right and left lungs. It is suggested that the immediate reduction of ventilation in one lunc following the occlusion of its pulmonary artery is due to bronchoconstriction which occurs in response to local airway hypocapnia and leads to regional atelectasis. (XVIII, 15*).
