T1  - Discussion on infertility
A1  - Buxton C.L.
A1  - Sharman A.
A1  - Boyd G.
A1  - Mills W.
A1  - Stallworthy J.
A1  - Green-Armytage V.B.
A1  - Loeser A.A.
A1  - Nixon W.C.W.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - The paper is concerned with pituitary failure as a causative factor in anovulation and amenorrhoea. The first evidence of decrease in gonadotrophin excretion is a decrease in FSH. When FSH and LH are no longer excreted ovulation stops and LTH is excreted unopposed. Frequently colostrum or milk can be obtained on nipple pressure,in cases of amenorrhoea and anovulation caused by hypothalamic disease or psychogenic failure to stimulate pituitary action. The treatment with chorionic gonadotrophin, pregnant marc serurn, pituitary extracts from sheep, cattle, hogs and various synergistic combinations was disappointing. The results of extracts of human pituitary obtained from autopsy material are described by the author: 8 amenorrhoeic patients were treated, 2 with primary amenorrhoea and one being a case of adrenal cortical hyperplasia. The others suffered from secondary amenorrhoea. The patients were first treated with human pituitary extract, 25 mg. per day for 4 days. This was followed by anovulatory bleeding on 6 occasions in 4 patients arid ovulatory bleeding in two. The dosage schedule was changed: to human pituitary gonadotrophin 25 mg. for 8 days during the last four days 1600 U.human chorionic gonadotrophin was added. Ovulation occurred in each of 7 cycles produced in 4 patients. By culdoscopy several recently ruptured follicles were observed. In one case iaparotomy was carried out. The ovaries were four times the normal size and contained several corpora lutea.
