T1  - Influence of ovarian function on the fibrinolytic enzyme system. ii. influence of exogenous steroids
A1  - Phillips L.L.
A1  - Turksoy R.N.
A1  - Southam A.L.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - The influence of exogenous steroids on the fibrinoiytic system was investigated. The subjects included 2 women with normal ovulatory menstrual cycles, and 6 anovulatory patients, 2 with bleeding and 4 with oligomenorrhoea. In addition, intravenous conjugated equine oestrogene were administered to 2 patients. One patient was found to have a low fibrinogen level following dilatation and curettage; the other patient had an intrauterine foetal death of 6 weeks' duration. The results indicate that the oestrogene and the 19-norsteroid compounds used do exert an influence on the fibrinoiytic enzyme system. The results of individual patients, before and after administration of these hormonef, and the averages of groups of patients, before and after, showed significant increases in profibrinolysin levels and somewhat less marked elevations in the antifibrinolysin as measured by methods previously described. Fibrinogen levels showed a variable pattern. In addition, active fibrinolysin was observed following intravenous conjugated equine oestrogene as well as following prolonged oral administration of norethynodrel, EE3ME, and norethindrone. This usually occurred after the profibrinolysin levels had become abnormally elevated. The author s indicated that the mechanism for the changes in the fibrinoiytic enzyme system could not be postulated from these experiments.
