T1  - Influence of ovarian function on the fibrinolytic enzyme system. I. ovulatory and anovulatory cycles
A1  - Turksoy R.N.
A1  - Phillips L.L.
A1  - Southam A.L.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - Ten normally menstruating women, 11 anovulatory women with dysfunctional bleeding, 2 female castrates and 2 normal young men were assayed for fibrinogen (Ratnoff and Menzie technique), free fibrinolysin (casein hydrolysis), total fibrinolysin and inhibitors (difference between total and free). Each of these factors was measured 96 times in the ovulatory group, 94 times in the anovulatory group, 4 times on each of the female castrates. 4 times and 3 times respectively on the 2 men. Males and surgical castrates apparently show constant levels of all factors. Ovulating women have a double peak in their cycle, each peak occurring several days after the corresponding oestrogen excretion peak in the normal 28-32 uay cycle. Anovulatory females presented greater fluctuation of all factors, and higher levels of fibrinogen without cyclic patterns. These higher levels are presumed to be related to higher oestrogen excretion levels in the dysfunctional bleeding group. The oestrogen levels of these patients are not given.
