T1  - Studies on the endocrine anomalies encountered in the course of stein-leventhal's syndrome
A1  - Mauvais-Jarvis P.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - Stein-Leventhal's syndrome is conceived by the author, as by Netter, in its restrictive form according to strict clinical and anatomical criteria. Seven cases were submitted to stimulation by chorionic gonadotrophin with inhibition of the adrenal cortex by dcxan.cthascnc. In 3, this was done before and after wedge resection of the ovaries. The basic 17-ketosteroid concentration was moderately increased. The chromatographical fractionation did not indicate the origin of the androgens; neither did the stimulation test by ACTH. Chorionic gonadotrophin. with inhibition by dexa methasone, provokes a significant increase in 17-ketosteroids, as well as in pregnanetriol, which tends to show that these substances are produced by the ovaries. These reactions are irregularly attenuated under the influence of wedge resection. These facts speak in favour of the ovarian origin of the increased androgen concentration in Stein-Leventhal's syndrome.
