T1  - EFFECTS of ORAL ADMINISTRATION of ESTROGENS on THE 17KETOSTEROID EXCRETION of VIRILIZED WOMEN
A1  - Mellinger R.C.
A1  - Smith Jr. R.W.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - Synthetic oestrogens were given orally to virilized women with hirsutisnm and menstrual disorders, in amounts sufficient to suppress gonadotrophin excretion to immeasurable levels. In most subjects a significant and sustained reduction in urina-ry 17-ketosteroid excretion was observed both in patients with sclerocystic ovaries and in those with acquired adrenal virilism. In 2 patients receiving prolonged cyclic therapy, previously enlarged ovaries became impalpable, and in one case the reduced 17-ketosteroid excretion was maintained after therapy. Oestrogen therapy significantly decreased urinary 17-ketosteroid excretion in an oophorectornized woman, but this effect was minimal in virilized subjects treated with prednisone. Accordingly, a functioning adrenal cortex seems necessary for the oestrogen effect. A functioning ovary is not essential, but inhibition of its androgen secretion may result from oestrogen therapy. Alteration in the secretion, plasma binding or metabolism of adrenal steroids is a more probable explanation for the reported observations.
