T1  - A critique of the stein-leventhal syndrome
A1  - Blewett E.K.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - The author discusses the typical picture of this condition of obscure aetiology and stresses the point that the ovaries need not always be enlarged when other symptoms are present. Emphasis is placed on the performance of culdoscopy to make or exclude the diagnosis of sclerocystic ovaries and thus avoid unwarranted operation. Surgical treatment is best postponed until after marriage and proven infertility as the improvement of ovarian function and the correction of the infertility is most likely in the first few months following wedge resection. The author has encountered 10 (1.6%) cases among 611 women with a primary com plaint of infertility. While the sclerocystic ovary is the keystone in diagnosis he found the ovaries to be normal in size in 6 of the 10, in 2 unilateral enlargement was present and in 2 bilateral enlargement was present. All patients such as he reports should undergo the standard investigation for an infertile marriage before operation is performed.
