T1  - Diagnosis and results of therapy of ovarian tunica fibrosa withcystic changes
A1  - Epstein J.A.
A1  - Kupperman H.S.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - Report on 20 women on whom the above diagnosis was made solely on the basis of persistent failure to ovu la te in response to at least three trials of intravenous administration of 20 mg. of 'premarin'. None of the 20 presented the classical picture of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome including enlargement of the ovaries. Appropriate tests were employed to determine normal thyroid and adrenal function and the presence of proliferative endometrium. In addition these patients were all married and presented the problem, of infertility. Other possible causes for the latter condition were excluded prior to operation. 19 of the 20 women with normal sized ovaries underwent laporotomy and in all but one the anticipated pathological changes were encountered: a thickened fibrous ovarian capsule with subcapsular follicular cysts, with or without evidence of hyperthecosis. 14 of the 19 are know to have ovulated following the wedge resection. 8 of the 14 have become pregnant, 11 pregnancies among them. Two patients had been operated but recently and their ovulatory status remains in doubt. Two of the 19 patients were found to have small hy poplas tic uteri in contrast to the remainder whose uteri, fallopian tubes and ovaries were of normal size. The authors suggest that there may be a significant number of patients who fall into the category under discussion but who do not receive appropriate treatment as they do not present the classical picture of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome. Four cases are presented in detail.
