T1  - TREATMENT and PREVENTION of DIENCEPHALOPITUITARY DISORDERS in GYNAECOLOGY (Czech)
A1  - Malek J.
A1  - Trnka V.
A1  - Cepelak J.
A1  - Dykova H.
A1  - Hontela S.
A1  - Presl J.
A1  - Sterba R.I.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - The present-day possibilities of treating and preventing dieneephalo-pituitary disorders are reviewed. For substitutional treatment, gonadotrophic hormones are used. It is necessary, however, first to ascertain whether the endometrium and ovaries are not refractory to stimulation. In pituitary hypogonadism and in anovulatory cycles, FSH and chorionic gonadotrophin are used in combination; where sufficient follicular stimulation is present (some an ovulatory cycles, Lu teal insufficiency, juvenile bleeding, glandular cystic hyperplasia), chorion -gonadotrophin alone is sufficient. Substitution is ineffective in the Sheehan and the Chiari-Frommel syndrome; in these cases, stimulation rather should be used. The dangers of this form of treatment are: formation of ovarian cysts (necessitates constant gynaecological control during treatment, use of the smallest effective dose), allergy (due to impurities, or to the potentiating effect of the se rum-globulins on c horion-gonadodotrophin), and antihormones (necessity of intervals during treatment, change of preparation). As to stimulation or inhibition of the pituitary by hormones, not much positive knowledge is available on the mechanism. Small doses of oestrogens stimulate, large or prolonged doses inhibit. Progesterone mainly stimulates: so do the corticoids. Hormonally inactive steroids with a sedative (hydroxydione) or diuretic effect (spirolactones) are mentioned, as well as norsteroids with a central anti-ovulation effect, which are used for contraception. Non-hormonal stimulation can be achieved by X-ray or short-wave diathermy of the diencephalon. by cervical dilatation, procaine-infiltration of the cervical ganglia, physical therapy applied to the genitals, and protein therapy. Chlorpromazine stimulates LTH-production and is successfully used in anovulatory cycles and luteal insufficiency. In animals, stimulation is brought about by yohimbin. certain sulphonamides, and vitamin B1. Oxytocin may act as a 'gonadotrophin releasing factor'. Hormone production may be influenced indirectly via the other pituitary hormones (regulating general metabolism) and by psychotherapy. As to prevention, attention must be focused on infections (streptococcal angina leading to endocraniosis). allergy, nutrition (viz. the problem of overeating, strumigenic factors etc.), mental stress, alcohol, nicotin, fear and neurotization, post-par turn hypopituitarism, and the influence of ionising radiation in medicine, industry, or from nuclear tests.
