T1  - FSH LEVELS in THE STEIN-LEVENTHAL SYNDROME and SMALL-CYST DEGENERATION of the OVARIES (Czech)
A1  - Zenisek L.
A1  - Talas M.
A1  - Stehlikova J.
A1  - Balon O.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - The diagnosis of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome, especially its differential diagnosis from small-cystic degeneration of the ovaries in patients with oligo- or amenorrhoea. sterility, and hirsutism. is often very difficult, sometimes impossible, without hi s to logical examination of the ovaries. Many of the diagnostic methods used are unreliable. Therefore FSH-levels were determined in 9 patients with established Stein-Leventhal syndrome (8 cases confirmed histologie ally. 1 by 17-ketosteroid chromatography), in 7 patients with a clinical picture of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome, which was not confirmed by histology, in 4 women with an adrenogenital syndrome, and in 5 healthy women. The FSH-levels were determined biochemically by the method of Crook and Butt. In the Stein-Leventhal syndrome, the values were normal or slightly less (136-401 gamma, average 268), in small-cystic degeneration they were lower (83-234 gamma, average 163). and the lowest values were found in the cases with the adrenogenital syndrome (40-163 gamma, average 86). Thus, very low values exclude a Stein-Leventhal syndrome, whereas normal values tend to confirm it. Further diagnostic possibilities are mentioned: fractional 17-ketosteroid chromatography (too exacting a method to be used extensively) and adrenocortical function tests (there is not sufficient experience available as yet for the assessment of their value). Rohan - Valasske Mezirici.
