N2  - A report of histochemical findings (MacManus, PAS, RNA. alkaline and acid phosphatase, 5-nucleotidase) in 6 embryonal gonads and 29 ovaries of foetuses and children. The germ ceils, characterized by a high alkaline phosphatase activity and glycogen content, migrate into the mesenchyme of the medial slope ofthezcesonephiic ridge before the 8th week (ovulation age). After a period of intense mit otic proliferation (8-20 weeks), the oogonia enlarge, lose cytoplasmic RNA, glycogen and alkaline phosphatase activity (ovocyte I), acquiring in the meantime a ring of follicle ceils, derived from the mesenchyme. During childhood atresia decreases the number of ovocytes. The coelomic me s ob last, 'germinal epithelium', is never a source of oogonia but contributes mesenchymal cells to the underlying gonad until the 15th week, when a well-marked basement membrane is established. The follicle theca cells stem from the ovarian atroma, which arises from connective tissue, accompanying ingrowing blood vessels. 5-Nucleotidase activity is conspicuous in a normal adult tunica albuginea. but is lacking during childhood and in the Stein- Leventhal type of ovary. (1. 10I.
