T1  - Carcinoma if the endometrium. a case study illustrating the evolution of the disease in a 24-year-old woman
A1  - Reicher N.B.
A1  - Phillips R.S.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - The patient had an unremarkable childhood and began menses at age 12. One year later because of an injury of the left breast she received daily X-ray treatments over a period of weeks, with the eventual atrophy of this breast. Subsequently, her menses alternated between amenorrhoea and haemorrhage, requiring a curettage at age 15. Biopsy reports demonstrated simple hyperplastic pattern. Two years later she had a laparotomy for abdominal pain, at which time a normal appendix and hydatid cyst of Morgagni were removed. At age 17 she was obese and had to be transfused and curetted for menorrhagia. Pathology report was endometrial hyperplasia. No haematological defect was found at age 18 to account for the menorrhagia. From age 18 to 22 the patient was controlled with cyclic hormone therapy with oestrogen and progesterone, but after therapy was discontinued at ace 22 she had 3 regular cycles following a period of amenorrhoea. Following this she had a severe interim of haemorrhage and pathological report from a curettage revealed 'somewhat atypical adenomatous polypoid hyperplasia'. She then became amcnorrhoeic for 9 months. At age 23 a curettage plus bilateral ovarian wedge resections revealed atypical glandular hyperplasia of the endometrium and simple physiological ovarian cyst. Endometrial biopsies 5 months later revealed endpmetrial carcinoma in situ. This was confirmed by later biopsies. During this time menses were grossly irregular. At age 24 curettage revealed endometrial carcinoma, and an abdominal hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy were done. Pathology report revealed no invasion. In no ovarian section was there a corpora lutea demonstrated. There appears a similarity in this case and in the Stein-Leventhal syndrome in that in both there is hyperoestrogenism and failure of ovulation and there is no progesterone activity. The lack of primordial follicles in the ovary in this case is perhaps caused by the radiation therapy and its Scattered doses', Tn the pubescent girl the ovaries are close to the breast. The thought was entertained that in the young girl with endometrial hyperplasia patent progesterone agents should be used to prevent endometrial carcinoma. Hodgkinson - Detroit, Mich.
