N2  - A'-Pregnene-3s: i7<x:2oa-triol(5-PT) was found in all urines analysed, indicating that its presumptive adrenal precursor 3s: i7a-dihydroxy-A*-pregnen-2O-one is regularly formed. After separation from other metabolites, 5-PT was quantitatively determined by oxidation to dehydraesiandrpsterone (DHA), using periodic acid and then the Zimmermann reaction. The titres varied from 4 mg. to 53 mg. per day in 5 patients with adrenal carcinoma, and from about i. emg. to 0.4 mg. in io subjects without endocrine disorders. Elevated titres were not found in 2 patients with Cushing's syndrome, nor in 2 with the Stein-Leventhal syndrome. Titres of 5-FT tended to vary inversely with those of DHA, suggesting the possibility that an inefficient conversion of gs: i7a-dihydroxy-A'-pregnen-2O-one to DHA may cause increased formation of 5-PT. Both 5-PT and DHA were sharply reduced when amphenone was given to a patient with adrenal carcinoma, whereas other Ci,Oft steroids showed little change. Thus, saturated ly-ketpsteroids (e.g. aetiocholanolone) may arise from precursors other than DHA in adrenal cancer. A*-Pregnen-3p : 2Oa-diol was detected for the first time in the urine of all subjects without endocrine disorders. It was present and elevated in the urine of 4 of the 5 adrenal cancer patients. In adrenal carcinoma, A'-androstenediol excretion was about one-tenth that of the DHA. This steroid was also found in the urine of 3 other subjects.
