N2  - The karyotypes of 4 patients were determined by means of tissue culture. Three had Stein syndrome (strictly defined as including intense spaniomenorrhoea, absence of corpora lutea, and a distinctive type of ovarian hypertrophy). All 3 had mosaic karyotypes: (1) normal cells and triple X in about equal numbers; (2) normal cells and cells with deletion of one X chromosome in about equal numbers; (3) cells tentatively typed as XX, XO and XY. The 4th case, a transitional type of gonadal dysgenesis, was of a single deletion caryotype, one of the X chromosomes lacking part of the longer arm. In the first 2 patients cuneiform resection produced normal menstrual and luteal cycles.
