T1  - The functional state of the thyroid gland in women at the climacterium
A1  - Vikhlyaeva E.M.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - Investigations were carried out on 103 patients with varying clinical courses of the climacterium; thyroid gland function was increased in 41%, reduced in 26%, and within the normal ranges in the remaining cases. Women with anovulatory haemorrhage showed a tendency to increase function of the gland while in women in whom the menopause took a more or less normal course the functioning of the thyroid gland was normal or only slightly reduced. The development of the climacteric syndrome is considered to be unconnected with the increased glandular function, and to result rather from neurohumoral changes occurring at this period. There is a certain correlation between the function of the thyroid gland and the ovarian function. Some features of the functional state of the thyroid gland introduce certain peculiarities in the course of the climacterium, particularly in women with pathological symptoms (climacteric syndrome, recurring anovulatory haemorrhage).
