N2  - DELTA<ovid:sup>5</ovid:sup>-Pregnene-3beta:17alpha:20alpha-triol (5-PT) was found in all urines analysed, indicating that its presumptive adrenal precursor 3beta:17alpha-dihydroxy-DELTA<ovid:sup>5</ovid:sup>-pregnen-20-one is regularly formed. After separation from other metabolites, 5-PT was quantitatively determined by oxidation to dehydroepiandrosterone (DHA), using periodic acid and then the Zimmermann reaction. The titres varied from 4 mg. to 53 mg. per day in 5 patients with adrenal carcinoma, and from about 0.1 mg. to 0.4 mg. in 10 subjects without endocrine disorders. Elevated titres were not found in 2 patients with Cushing's syndrome, nor in 2 with the Stein-Leventhal syndrome. Titres of 5-PT tended to vary inversely with those of DHA, suggesting the possibility that an inefficient conversion of 3beta:17alpha-dihydroxy-DELTA<ovid:sup>5</ovid:sup> -pregnen-20-one to DHA may cause increased formation of 5-PT. Both 5-PT and DHA were sharply reduced when amphenone was given to a patient with adrenal carcinoma, whereas other C<ovid:inf>19</ovid:inf> O<ovid:inf>2</ovid:inf> steroids showed little change. Thus, saturated 17-ketosteroids (e.g. aetiocholanolone) may arise from precursors other than DHA in adrenal cancer. DELTA<ovid:sup>5</ovid:sup>-Pregnen3beta:20alpha-diol was detected for the first time in the urine of all subjects without endocrine disorders. It was present and elevated in the urine of 4 of the 5 adrenal cancer patients. In adrenal carcinoma, DELTA<ovid:sup>5</ovid:sup>-androstenediol excretion was about onetenth that of the DHA. This steroid was also found in the urine of 3 other subjects.
