T1  - The karyotype in Stein-Leventhal disease
T3  - Etude du caryotype dans la maladie de Stein-Leventhal
A1  - Netter A.
A1  - Bloch-Michel H.
A1  - Salomon Y.
A1  - Thervet F.
A1  - De Grouchy J.
A1  - Lamy M.
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - After having redefined and restricted Stein-Leventhal's syndrome, the authors describe four cases, three of which fulfill all the requirements of this entity, the fourth case being somewhat disputable (gonadal dysgenesia?). Sex chromatin was found in resting nuclei. Karyotypes (Lejeune's method): case I. Nine normal cells (XX) and eight in which Xx was found, x being a partial deletion of the long arm of X; case 2. Eleven normal cells (XX) and nine cells with 47 chromosomes (XXX); case 3. Probably a mosaic XO, XY and XX; case 4. Forty-six chromosomes comprising Xx (partial deletion). These cases also reveal that different chromosomal constitutions may produce the same phenotype. The XX-Xx mosaic points to the possibility that chromosomal deletions may occur after fertilization in the zygote. It is quite possible that normal karyotypes will also be found in the presence of this disease (gene defect; cryptomosaic). From the developmental point of view, the absence of corpus luteum formation remains a problem.
