A1  - Mattingly D.
A1  - Mills I.H.
A1  - Prunty F.T.G.
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - In cases of simple hirsutism (no adrenal lesion) and Stein-Leventhal syndromes a low-dosage prednisone therapy was attempted; in the same period 0.05-0.3 mg. ethinyl oestradiol daily for 3 weeks in every 4 was added. The women presenting the Stein-Leventhal syndrome were so treated only after the usual ovarian wedge resection had been made. It is concluded that while the steroid therapy may be nefit the occasional patient when a reasonably low dosage level is used, this is not the general rule and it is not yet possible to predict whether any particular individual will respond to the treatment. The ovarian wedge resection resulted in 4 pregnancies out of 6 patients who attempted to become pregnant.
