T1  - Acromegaloid syndrome with polycystic ovaries
A1  - Epps D.R.
A1  - Imperia Gomes C.S.
A1  - Lima M.L.M.T.
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - Two female acromegaloid young patients are described. In one, congenital hirsutism was present. Theca lutein cysts, ovulatory cycles, high pregnanediol, theca lutein cysts with theca hyperplasia were present. In another case, follicle cysts, inactive and fibrotic stroma, anovulatory cycles were recorded. In this case, pregnanediol rose on the first day of luteotrophic administration, together with 17-ketosteroids in the urine. It is possible that progesterone or progesterone-like substances, produced under excessive LH stimulation, contribute to the hirsutism of acromegaly. That progesterone is potentially androgenic has been reported recently in medical literature. Adrenals were hyperreactive, in both patients, after ACTH stimulation, but the 17-ketosteroids decreased after ovary wedge resection in both cases, which seems to indicate that the ovary is an important factor in the development of hirsutism in acromegaly.
