T1  - Some relationships between short range and long range risks of unwanted pregnancy
A1  - Potter Jr. R.G.
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - The introductory part of the article points out that most American women marry near the age of 20 and have their desired 2, 3, or 4 children by 30. This leaves a 'risk period* of eior more years, during which the problem of preventing undesired pregnancy becomes urgent. There are only few couples who end the uncertainty by sterilization. A discussion is presented on 'natural immunity' in pregnancy, lactation and subsequent anovulatory cycles. The fecundability, i.e., the chance of conception in the absence of contraceptive measures is stated to remain constant during the entire 'risk period'. Theoretical considerations and a mathematic probability calculation on the incidence of pregnancies follow. It is supposed that contraceptive measures should be very effective to keep the monthly risk of pregnancy lower than 2-3%. Calculations showed that such a measure incorporates a real danger of more than 3 accidental pregnancies in a risk period of 10 yr. The monthly risks of accidental pregnancy yielding 95% assurance of not exceeding i, eor 2 pregnancies during a risk period of 10-15 yr. are presented in a table. For 2 accidental pregnancies in a risk period of 10 yr. the monthly risk of contraceptive failure should be kept below 0.01.
