T1  - Clinical and biological syndrome of common hirsutism
T3  - Le syndrome clinique et biologique de l'hypertrichose commune d'apres 720 observations
A1  - Vague J.
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - After a study comprising 720 cases the authors consider the syndrome of common hirsutism to consist of: (a) psychic disturbances of greater or lesser degree; (b) generalized hirsutism, ranging from a mild exaggeration of normal body hair to more severe virilization; (c) disturbances of the menstrual cycle, from scarcity of menses to sterility; (d) normal or slightly elevated 17-ketosteroids; (e) polycystic ovaries with thecal hypertrophy and thickening of the albuginea. The lesser degree of ovarian disturbances would apparently distinguish this syndrome from that described by Stein and Leventhal, and from simple or idiopathic hirsutism where no ovarian abnormality is demonstrable. The authors believe the syndrome to arise from congenital anomalies paired with a possible excess of androgen of probably ovarian origin.
