T3  - Auslosung und Unterdruckung einer Ovulation mit Steroidhormonen
A1  - Pots P.
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - The opinion that in the presence of an anovulatory cycle ovulation can be induced by postmenstrual administration of oestrogens for a short time, similar to the Hohlweg effect, was tested but could not be confirmed. A rebound effect, analogous to androgen administration in male sterility, could not be substantiated. Induction of ovulation with progesterone or with moderate doses of ethinyl-nortestosterone could not be produced. It is concluded that in an anovulatory cycle ovulation cannot be induced by steroid hormones. On the other hand, it is possible, in the presence of an ovulatory cycle, to suppress the ovulation with progestational compounds. This requires a daily oral dose of 20 mg. ethinyl-nortestosterone or 4 mg. of its acetate. The absence of ovulation was demonstrable by the absence of pregnanediol excretion. This method is suitable for anticonceptional treatment if it is applied only intermittently. However, it entails the risk of inhibiting not only the gonadotrophic but also the other trophic functions of the anterior pituitary.
