T1  - Evaluation of electrovaginal potential recordings as a therapeutic guide in gynecological problems
A1  - Parsons L.
A1  - Whittaker J.O.
A1  - Lemon H.M.
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - The authors record and interpret over 4000 observations of the vaginal-abdominal electropotential pattern of 450 women during the menstrual cycle. Concomitantly 563 vaginal smears were studied as were the cyclic 24-hour oestrogen excretion levels in 38 subjects. The acuity of the method is excellent because results were reproducible. A highly sensitive vacuum tube recording millipotentiometer of 5 megaohms resistance was used, measuring the potential difference between a saline-filled glass vaginal electrode and a similar reference electrode on the anterior abdominal wall. The vaginal smear was not as sensitive a recorder as the potentiometer, the greatest divergence being at the time of peak oestrogen levels. Electrovaginograms were recorded during a 15- to 20-minute span with the patient lying quietly in bed. Recordings were electropositive when urinary oestrogen excretion was below 10 ng./24 hr.,and electronegative with excretions above 21 ug./24 hr. Intermediate groups varied. X2 results were significant at P - 0.05<O.01. Typical curves were low and flat at menstruation and premenstrual recordings, flat and positive at ovulation, low-negative to high-positive with a sharp rise in both pre- and postovulatory times, rising from -20 to as high as +30 mv. in 10-15 min. Clinically 62 subjects with breast cancer and 20 without were studied. Premenopausal patients had initial negative readings>> postmenopausal averaged on the positive side. Untreated postmenopausal patients develop a very low reading when a low dose oestrone is given, but have positive recordings after prednisone. Favourable oestrogen suppression by prednisone produced this typical change in potential recording, and high potentials were present in 90% of those with favourable response<< Conversely failures did not show this response. Remission continued while the positive response persisted. Patients with polycystic ovaries had responses in the negative range, and this helps to differentiate those with ovarian aplasia. The authors determine an average progestational time of approx. 20 days in the cycle<< and assume that ovulation occurs at the onset of this time. Their figures agree only with the electrovaginal recordings. They admit that all other tests show great variation. <ovid:br/>Conclusion(s): these potential readings reflect ovarian activity, and cyclic variations are present during the menstrual cycle, disappearing in the menopause. These recordings reflect antioestrogen therapy in cancer patients. The discontinuity of activity in the recordings appears to coincide with the disappearance of pregnanediol excretion in the 24-hour urines. Eichner - Cleveland, O.(X,2*).
