N2  - Jones, Greenblatt, Perloff and Channick, Jefferies and others have treated patients with amenorrhoea and anovulatory haemorrhages with prednisone: some of these patients showed hirsutism and/or increased 17-ketosteroid excretion due to a possible adrenocortical dysfunction; the results were sometimes good. The authors treated 14 patients with amenorrhoea and 11 patients with anovulatory haemorrhages with prednisone (3x5 mg. d. d., after some months 1x5 mg. d. d.). Ten patients showed hirsutism and/or increased 17-ketosteroid excretion. Six of the 25 patients developed ovulatory cycles (4 patients with amenorrhoea and 2 patients with anovulatory bleeding). There was no difference in results between the patients with and those without any sign of a possible disturbance in the adrenocortical function. The authors concluded that prednisone has a therapeutic importance in conditions related to congenital adrenocortical hyperplasia, virtually regular anovulatory cycles and normo-oestrogenic amenorrhoea. Ovarian wedge resection was primarily performed in the successfully treated 4 patients with amenorrhoea. So the question arises as to whether the results should not be attributed to the combination of bilateral wedge resection of the ovaries and prednisone treatment. This question is at present under investigation in the Utrecht university clinic.
