T1  - The endometrium in functional uterine haemorrhage
T3  - Elendometrio en las hemorragias uterinas funcionales
A1  - Gonzalez Merlo J.
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - A general review is made of the histochemistry of the endometrium. In the normal cycle there exists a small proportion of acid mucopolysaccharides in the first half of the cycle; the alcian blue-p. a. S. staining shows violet granules. In the second half of the cycle there are large quantities of acid mucopolysaccharides in the glandular lumen which present a homogeneous violet colour after alcian blue-p. a. S. staining. The neutral mucopolysaccharides have 2 maxima, toward the 10th-18th days, and toward the 24th-26th days. In the strom a of the endometrium the neutral mucopolysaccharides appear on the 8th day of the cycle, reach their maximum between the 17th and 21st days to decrease after wards. The neutral mucopolysaccharides exist in abundance in the first half of the cycle, decrease toward the 16th-21st days, and increase again from the 21st day onward. They are localized around the spiral arteries. In cases of cystic glandular hyperplasia glycogen is found in the glandular epithelia at the basal pole. There exists also a large quantity of acid mucopolysaccharides in the glandular lumina. In the anovulatory cycle, acid mucopolysaccharides are found in the stroma, but not in the lumina. There is no glycogen either. In cases of irregular desquamation, glycogen is found in the epithelium and mucopolysaccharides in the lumina. In cases of irregular maturation there are some zones with glycogen in the epithelia and neutral mucopolysaccharides in the stroma; other zones present hardly any glycogen and an abundance of acid mucopolysaccharides in the glandular lumina and around the spiral arteries of the stroma; again other zones are in a stage of proliferation and have a small quantity of acid mucopolysaccharides in the glandular epithelia and a large quantity of this substance in the stroma. In cases of deciduiform transformation, the decidual cells are rich in glycogen. With reference to the enzymes, the findings are as follows: Glandular hyperplasia: abundant alkaline phosphatase in the glandular epithelium. In the anovulatory cycle alkaline phosphatase is present throughout the cycle. It does not diminish in the second half, as was to be expected. In cases of irregular maturation of the endometrium, there is abundant phosphatase in the second half of the cycle. In cases of deciduiform transformation of the endometrium, the glandular epithelium and the lumina do not contain any phosphatase activity; the picture is similar to the advanced secretory phase. With reference to the nucleic acids: In cases of cystic glandular hyperplasia, the DNA content is very high. In the anovulatory cycle, the DNA content does not diminish in the second half of the cycle as occurs in the normal cycle. In cases of glandular maturation of the endometrium, in addition to the glands which contain hardly any DNA in the nucleus, there exist others which contain a large quantity of DNA in the premenstrual phase. Feulgen's reaction is specific. In the pathological endometrium DNA is distributed in the following manner: In cases of glandular hyperplasia there is almost complete absence of DNA in the glandular epithelia. In the anovulatory cycle there exists a large quantity of DNA, which is localized at the basal pole, in the second half of the cycle. In cases of irregular maturation of the endometrium. there exist glands with complete absence of DNA; others contain a large quantity of this substance, which is usually situated at the basal pole of the cell. The plasma cells contain a large quantity of DNA, so that this method proves very useful for the diagnosis of endometritis. This reaction is specific for DNA if it is digested with ribonuclease.
