T1  - The use of estrogens and gestogens to induce human ovulation
A1  - Garcia C.R.
A1  - Harrigan J.T.
A1  - Mulligan W.J.
A1  - Rock J.
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - Reported are observations on the ovulation-inductive efficacy of various hormonal agents given orally or parente rally. Oral oestrogene (diethylstilboestrol,monozol, estinyl, 3-methyl ether of ethynyl oestradiol, and 'SC-6924', manvene) did not produce results sufficiently encouraging to warrant their continued use. Intravenous conjugated oestrogens (premarin) were given in 20 mg. doses 14 days after withdrawal bleeding was obtained by intra-muscular progesterone administration. Of 12 anovulators given 30 intravenous injections of premarin, only 1 ovulated. Of 16 oligo-ovulators who received a total of 66 injections, 6 had 10 ovulations. Combinations of one of several oral oestrogens with one of three 19-norstroids (norlutin, enovid and nilvar) were tried in 17 anovulators and 14 oligo-ovulators. Ovulation occurred in 1 anovulator and 1 oligo-ovulator, both in the first post-trsatment cycle. The 19 nor-steroids alone were given to 10 anovulators and 8 oligo-ovulators from days 5 through 25 of 3 to 6 cycles. No instance of ovulation was observed during the first month after administration of the 19-nor steroids. Gonadophysin (FSH) was given intramuscularly to 13 anovulators for 5 daily doses of 100 to 1500 R. U. This regime was followed by progesterone 20 mg. intravenously. The therapy failed to evoke ovulation. Intramuscular progesterone was given to 13 anovulators and 8 oligo-ovulators in doses of 25 to 100 mg. from 1 to 6 times at intervals of 10 to 15 days. No ovulations were noted in the anovulatory group, and only 3 ovulations occurred among the oligo-ovulator s. A single intra-muscular injection of 25 to 100 mg. of progesterone given near or on the 24th day of repeated cycles produced 2 ovulations among 15 anovulators. Nineteen oligo-ovulators ovulated in 7 instances. Results suggest the lack of specificity of these agents.
