T1  - An investigation of ovarian tissue and urinary 17-ketosteroids in patients with bilateral polycystic ovaries
A1  - Trace R.J.
A1  - Keaty E.C.
A1  - McCall M.L.
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - The Stein-Leventhal syndrome was diagnosed in 19 patients, the polycystic ovaries being confirmed by gynaecography. The study group averaged 8.2 mg. of total neutral urinary 17-ketosteroids more than the control group (5 patients) per 24 hr. which is not statistically significant. Six weeks post - operatively, all patients in the study group showed an average decreased excretion of 11.4 mg. per 24 hr., which is statistically significant. There was no correlation between ovarian size, amount of tissue resected, ovarian tissue steroid content, microscopic pathology and the pre and post-operative urinary steroid excretion. Eighteen patients established normal menses post-operatively, and one remained amenorrhoeic. The authors concluded that the ovary is not responsible for the increased neutral 17-ketosteroids excreted in the urine of these patients. The ineffectiveness of ACTH on this disease gives considerable doubt to the adrenal cortex theory.
