T1  - Ovarian surgery and stein-leventhal syndrome
T3  - Ovarialkirurgi och stein-leventhals syndrom
A1  - Bergman P.
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - Surgical intervention on the ovaries may be injurious just as it may be beneficial. Resection of the ovaries may lead to the formation of adhesions and to late sterility. Even relatively small ovarian cysts can occasionally be manifestly or potentially malignant. The choice of treatment, i. e. surgical or conservative, is difficult if ovarian enlargement is only slight and the patient young. Polycystic ovarian changes in the Stein-Leventhal syndrome should always be treated surgically without reservation. The author describes a series of 17 cases of Stein-Leventhal syndrome, 8 with amenorrhoea and 9 with refractory anovulatory bleeding. Wedge resection of the ovaries regularly resulted in the return to normal ovarian function. Three of the patients subsequently became pregnant. Three had recurrences of the syndrome. Two of these were re-explored. The second operation revealed marked adhesions in the pelvis. Repeated wedge-resection was performed in one case. In the other the operation was limited to dividing the adhesions. In both of them the second operation was followed by the permanent return of normal ovarian function. It appears reasonable to assume that, as with a thickened cortex, a mantle of adhesions around the ovaries can impair ovarian function. At the time of operation there were no mature follicles. After operation and the return to normal intra-ovarian pressure, follicular activity re-appeared. This required a certain time. Ovulation occurred about 2 weeks after wedge resection and menstruation 2 weeks later. In most cases of Stein-Leventhal syndrome - in 14 of the present 17 - ovarian function was insufficient from the menarche on, i. e. (oligomenorrhoea or oligomenorrhoea followed by amenorrhoea). The author inclines to the view that in most cases of Stein-Leventhal syndrome there is an embryological anomaly of the ovaries. But the aetiology of Stein-Leventhal syndrome is probably not one and the same in all cases.
