T1  - The relationship of adrenal androgenic hyperfunction to ovarian function and infertility. A preliminary report
A1  - Zener F.B.
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - The author suggests the term 'adrenal androgenic hyperfunction' for the clinical syndrome of infertility, anovulation, menstrual irregularity, acne, hirsutism and anabolic changes induced by hypersecretion of androgens by the adrenal cortex. From the adrenogenital syndrome it is to be distinguished by the lack of obesity, the only occasional occurrence of oligomenorrhoea, the rarity of amenorrhoea, and the common anovulatory cycles, only moderate hypoplasia of the internal genitals, the slight clitoral enlargement, moderate muscular development and strength, increased fatigability, increased glucose tolerance and the moderate elevation of 17-ketosteroid excretion (in some cases only an increase of the active androgen group being found by partition chromatography). 235 patients with this syndrome are reported, and methods for diagnosis and treatment are given. The treatment of 38 women with glucocorticoids (hydrocortisone or triamcinolone) resulted in 28 pregrtancies, treatment with 17alpha-hydroxyprogesterone caproate of 44 women led to conception in 32 The possible mechanisms involved are discussed.
