N2  - Two oral compounds, norethynodrel (enovid) and norethindrone (norlution), have been investigated in various categories of infertility. In cases with ovulatory cycles ovulation can be suppressed when the drug is given early in the cycle and continued for 20 days. In a group with anovulatory cycles ovulation was noted in 16 out of 39 patients within two to four months following cessation of norethynodrel therapy. Four of the patients became pregnant. Best results were produced in a group of 24 patients with inadequate secretory phase. The endometrium after treatment revealed an excellent secretory response and 8 successful pregnancies resulted. In dysfunctional uterine bleeding therapy was continued for 3-4 months and patients remained amenorrhoeic for 3-5 months after cessation of bleeding. In a surgical castrate of 21 years norethynodrel produced a deciduoid stroma, increase in glandular size with evidence of secretion. The urinarv FSH was depressed from less than 105.6 m.u./24 hr. to 13 m.u./24 hr.
