T1  - Hirsutism in adolescent girls. Possible Stein-Leventhal syndrome
A1  - Hayles A.B.
A1  - Cowger M.L.
A1  - Salassa R.M.
A1  - Pratt J.H.
A1  - Dockerty M.B.
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - The authors report on a syndrome of hirsutism, obesity, and menstrual disturbance (Stein-Leventhal syndrome) in 3 girls 13, 13, and 14 years of age. Blood and urine steroids were normal. Exploratory surgery revealed polycystic ovaries consistent with the diagnosis. Removal of wedge-shaped pieces of cortex of the ovary containing the cysts plus cortisone therapy did not alter the menstrual irregularity. In adult women we find also small breasts, amenorrhoea, oligomenorrhoea, ormenometrorrhagia and infertility. Untreated cases excrete increased amounts of 17-ketosteroids and pregnanetriol in the urine, and the administration of cortisone or similar steroids causes regression of virilization and decrease of the abnormal steroids in the urine. The general type of treatment: wedge-shaped surgical removal of the ovary polycystic areas followed by 5 mg. prednisone (meticorten), given every 8 hr. Menstruation occurred in 1 case 26 days, and in another case 28 days after surgery. In one case the woman became fertile.
