T1  - Biosynthesis of two steroid glycols from 17alpha-Hydroxyprogesterone by surviving human ovarian slices
A1  - Sandor T.
A1  - Lanthier A.
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - Surviving human ovarian slices were incubated with 17alpha-hydroxyprogesterone in a Krebs-Ringer phosphate medium (pH 7. 4), at 37degreeC. under an oxygen atmosphere. The substrate was partially transformed to 2 steroid glycols, designated as X<ovid:inf>1</ovid:inf> and X<ovid:inf>2</ovid:inf>. Chromatographic mobility studies, derivation, and spectra in 95% ethanol and in concentrated sulphuric acid suggested that XI might be identical with DELTA<ovid:sup>4</ovid:sup>-pregnene-17alpha:20alpha-diol-3-one, and X<ovid:inf>2</ovid:inf> with DELTA<ovid:sup>4</ovid:sup>-pregnene-17alpha:20beta-diol-3-one. Synthetic DELTA<ovid:sup>4</ovid:sup>-pregnene-17alpha:20beta-diol-3-one was prepared from 17alpha-hydroxyprogesterone. It was found identical with X<ovid:inf>2</ovid:inf> by the above-mentioned criteria. In addition to normal human ovarian tissue, slices of human Stein-Leventhal type ovaries were also incubated with the precursor and the transformation rates to X<ovid:inf>1</ovid:inf> and X<ovid:inf>2</ovid:inf> calculated for both types of tissues. Experiments were performed using as substrate DELTA<ovid:sup>5</ovid:sup>-pregnene-3beta-ol-20-one and progesterone in order to study the reaction with biosynthetic 3 7er-hydroxyprogesterone. The transformation to X<ovid:inf>1</ovid:inf> and X<ovid:inf>2</ovid:inf> seemed to follow the same course as with synthetic 17alpha-hydroxyprogesterone.
