AN  - 280886758
T1  - PATTERNS of STEROID EXCRETION in THREE TYPES of POST-PUBERTALHIRSUTISM -
A1  - Brooks R.V.
A1  - Prunty F.T.G.
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - The steroid excretion was studied both before and during the administration of ACTH. The types of hirsutism distinguished were post-pubertal adrenal virilism (3 cases), idiopathic hirsutism (5 cases) and the Stein-Leventhal syndrome (7 cases). The patients in the adrenal virilism group were found to have a pattern of steroid excretion of the type seen in congenital adrenal hyperplasia. Thus they excreted relatively small amounts of hydrocortisone metabolites in the urine, but the excretions of pregnanetriol, 17-hydroxypregnanolone, 11-ketopregnanetriol and 11-hydroxyandrosterone were high. The patients with idiopathic hirsutism showed a tendency to excrete relatively more of those 17-ketosteroids derived from Ci9 precursors compared with those derived from hydrocortisone. The evidence suggests, however, that this disproportion is due not to an impairment of hydrocortisone synthesis but to a potentiation of the production of adrenal androgens. A similar abnormality in the patterns of steroid excretion was also found in some of the patients with the Stein-Leventhal syndrome. Since this abnormality includes the excretion of increased amounts of those 17-ketosteroids thought to be exclusively of adrenal origin, viz. de hydro r/wandr oster one and 11-hydroxyandrosterone, this would suggest adrenal involvement in at least some of the cases. (III, 10).
