T1  - A functional test for the stein-leventhal syndrome (French text)
A1  - Netter A.
A1  - Jayle M.F.
A1  - Musset R.
A1  - Lambert A.
A1  - Mauvais
A1  - Jarvis P.-
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - Urinary hormones were studied in 3 selected cases of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome following treatment with dexamethasone (3 mg. per day for 12 days) and chorionic gonadotrophin (10,000 U. on days 5 and 6 of the treatment with dexamethasone). In the normal female dexamethasone depressed both the urinary 17-ketosteroids and the 17-hydroxycorticoids, and chorionic gonadotrophin failed to modify the effect of dexamethasone on the urinary 17-ketosteroids. In the 3 Stein-Leventhal cases, dexamethasone caused a drop in the urinary 17-ketosteroids but only of the order of 50 to 60%. The remaining 17-ketosteroid fraction consisted primarily of androsterone and aetiocholanolone. Chorionic gonadotrophin caused an increased output of androsterone with little effect on the aetiocholanolone, resulting in an ratio greater than 2 as compared with 0.5 for normal women. In addition, gonadotrophin treatment was also followed by an increased output of urinary oestriol as compared with oestrone and oestradiol. It is concluded that the ovary in the iJtein-Leventhal syndrome produces considerable amounts of androgen and also shows a deranged oestrogen metabolism.
