T1  - 'In vitro' production of androgenic steroid by human normal and 'Stein-Leventhal type' ovarian slices
A1  - Lanthier A.
A1  - Sandor T.H.
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - The Stein-Leventhal syndrome is characterized by menstrual irregularities, sterility, hirsutism and micropolycystic ovaries with hyperthecosis. Slices of normal and 'Stein-Leventhal type' human ovaries were incubated with and without the addition of human chorionic gonadotrophin, DELTA5-pregnene-3beta-ol-20- one or 17alpha-hydroxyprogesterone, and the resultant steroids chromatographed. Under stimulation with the gonadotrophin, normal ovarian slices produced detectable amounts of progesterone and lya-hydroxyprogesterone but no A4-androstene-3: ly-dione (AD); whereas, under the same conditions, slices from 'Stein-Leventhal type' ovaries secreted at 0.4 mug./g. tissue/hr., but no progesterone or 17alpha-hydroxyprogesterone. Thirty-five mug. of AD were isolated from the incubation medium and partially identified by paper chromatography mobilities, ultra-violet absorption spectrum in concentrated sulphuric acid and micro-Zimmerman reaction. It is postulated that the Stein-Leventhal syndrome may be caused, at least partially, by exaggerated formation of AD or possibly by decreased dramatization of this androgenic steroid.
