T1  - The syndrome of polycystic ovaries and hyperthecosis. a clinical evaluation
A1  - Lanthler A.
A1  - Lauze S.
A1  - Crignon C.E.
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - An evaluation has been made of 18 patients with polycystic ovaries and hyperthecosis diagnosis as such within 2 yr. in a general hospital. Ten of the young women were below the mean age of 25 yr. Only half of the patients were definitely overweight. Hirsutism, although difficult to evaluate, was present in all cases but certainly only of very minor degree in 3 of them. The most constant menstrual irregularities were oligohypomenorrhoea and periods of amenorrhoea dating back to the menarche in two-thirds of the patients. Two women presented with a history of menometrorrhagia. Twelve of 13 married women had been sterile. The ovaries were greatly enlarged in only 8 cases. In all the other patients, the ovarian size was around the upper limit of normal. The major histological findings were: thickened tunica albuginea, microcysts, hyperthecosis and stroma hyperplasia in some cases. All patients, except one, responded to bilateral, ovarian wedge resection with normal menstrual periods. Three pregnancies have occurred during the 21 months' follow-up period. Absolutely no change in the hirsutism has been noted in any of the patients following operation. The only hormonal finding that may be of some significance is a mean urinary 17-ketosteroid value 4.2 mg. higher than the mean for normal women. Chromatographie separation of the urinary 17-ketosteroids was done in 8 patients. Three were found to have an increased excretion of androsterone and etiocholanolone, one an increased level of dehydroc/v androsterone and the 4 others had a completely normal pattern. It seems that, at least in some patients with polycystic ovaries and hyperthecosis, there may be an increased secretion of an androgenic steroid either from the adrenal cortex or the ovary.
