AN  - 280840248
T1  - Symptoms and etiology of the stein-leventhal syndrome
A1  - Personen S.
A1  - Timaonen S.
A1  - Mikkonen R.
Y1  - 1959//
N2  - This report covers 8 typical cases of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome, -which are analysed according to the clinical symptoms, ovarian histology, vaginal smear, and hormone analysis. The hormone analysis included the determination of urinary oestrogenic and gonadotrophic hormones, pregnanediol and 17-ketosteroid fractions (Dingemanse). Before surgical operation the hormones were also determined after chorionic gonadotrophin and ACTH tolerance tests. Controls were 2 apparently healthy women and 2 castrated women, on whom the same tolerance tests were performed. On the basis of the clinical and histological features 2 main types of cases were distinguished. The first group (typel) was characterized by ovarian activity and the second group (type 2) by absence of signs of ovarian function. In both types, however, greatly enlarged, fibrotic, small-cystic ovaries w ere encountered. The 2 types differed in the hormone analyses in the respect that in type 1 theandrosterone/aetiocholanolone ratio(A:E)> 1, especially in the chorionic gonadotrophin tolerance test, while in type 2 it was < 1. The interpretation given to the findings is that in type 1 the masculinizing factor originates in the ovaries, possibly in the stroma, in which lipid staining showed a positive reaction. In type 2, on the other hand, because of the inactivation of the ovaries, the hypophyseal gonadotrophin exerts its effect on some other gland, most probably the 'sexual zone' of the adrenal cortex, which may be the source of the masculinizing factor in these cases.
