T1  - Anovulation as functional disturbance of the ovary
T3  - Falta de ovulacion como trastorno funcional del ovario: Consideraciones sobre su tratamiento
A1  - Zanartu J.
A1  - Hamblen E.C.
Y1  - 1959//
N2  - The authors present a group of 65 otherwise normal young women (mean age 27 yr.) complaining of sterility or menstrual disturbances. In 33 cases the menstrual disturbance dated from the menarche and in 32 from some time after. Of the 57 married patients, 47 had never been pregnant; the remaining 10 had had a previous pregnancy and 8 of these had ended in spontaneous abortions. In 40 cases the cycles were regularly monophasic (basal temperature) and 20 occasionally presented one or two ovulatory cycles. In the colpocytogram an abundance of cornified cells were present. At the beginning of menstruation, endometrial biopsy showed in 48 cases a proliferative, in 8 a 'mixed', and in 2 a secretory endometnum. The thyroid function was normal in 38 cases and insufficient in 27. The excretion of total neutral 17-ketosteroids was normal in all the cases. In 5 patients with more regular cycles a diminished excretion of pregnanediol was observed. The urinary gonadotrophin excretion was normal in 23 cases, low in 3 and high in 6. The sex chromatin in the epithelium of the buccal mucosa was always 'positive'. For treatment, use was made of several schedules which can be associated with each other: (1) Diet hygiene, especially taking into account protein and vitamin supply (B,C, D). (2) Thyroid extract in hypothyroidsim. (3) Cyclical oestrogens. (4) Oestrogens and progesterone according to Hambien's scheme. (5) Cyclical oestrogens and progesterone. (6) Gonadotrophins according to Hamblen's method. (7) Irradiation of the hypophysis and ovary. (8) Prednisone or prednisolone (5-10 mg. by the oral route). Appearance of biphasic cycles, their persistence after the treatment and the occurrence of pregnancy were considered as signs of 'improvement'. Persistence of anovulatory cycles or oestrogen ic endometrium were considered signs of failure. In total 52% improved, 22% had incomplete results and 25% were failures.
