T1  - The treatment of congenital ovarian malformations - die therapie der konnatalen ovariellen fehlbildungen
A1  - Stange H.-H.
Y1  - 1959//
N2  - These malformations are subdivided into 6 groups. For rational treatment exploratory laparotomy is obligatory. In agonadism - a rare occurrence - protracted oestrogen treatment is indicated. In hypogonadism a substitutive treatment with oestrogenic substances is of advantage for the development of the secondary female sex characteristics. In order to prevent continuous haemorrhages, however, the non-functional internal genital apparatus which fails to respond to all attempts at stimulation with go nado trophic hormone should be removed. Hypergonadism requires no therapeutic measures. In pseudo-hypergonadism (Stein-Leventhal syndrome) the numerous methods of treatment proposed indicate the insufficiency of any individual form of therapy; in the gynaecological clinic of Kiel, surgical treatment is preferred (bilateral wedge resection with puncture of the remaining cystic follicles and where necessary removal of the thickened tunica albuginea). The treatment of dysgonadism (syndrome of Klinefelter) consists, in view of the primary testicular insufficiency, in substitution with depot testosterone. In the last group of ovarian malformation? that of ambigonadism. which includes true hermaphrpditism, it is not the somatic and morphological condition which should determine the therapy, but rather the psyche, sexual inclination and preference of the patient. Surgical corrections are often unavoidable. The article is completed with clear, didactically well-chosen illustrations.
