T1  - The use of gonadotrophins in gynaecological clinical practice
T3  - L'utilisation des gonadotrophines en clinique gynecologique
A1  - Leclercq E.
Y1  - 1959//
N2  - After a brief survey of the development and action of the One-two cyclic gonadotrophin treatment' introduced by Hamblenfor the treatment of ovarian sterility, the author discusses Hamblen's present conception after 13 yr. of experience gained in the service of Ham bien himself. On the basis of the gonadotrophin concentration in the urine, the cases of amenorrhoea are divided into 3 groups: hypogonadotropuric, eu gonadotropuricand hypergonadotropuric amenorrhoea. Hypergonadotropuricamenorrhoea does not respond to gonadotrophin therapy, because the gonadotrophin concentration is already increased (menopause, amenorrhoea following castration, amenorrhoea due to ovarian agenesis). In hypogonadotropuric amenorrhoea (amenorrhoea after the age of 16, amenorrhoea with organic lesions of the pituitary or the hypothalamus), a gonadotrophic therapy will occasionally produce effect, but only after preparation, sometimes for a very long time, with oestrogenes and even with progesterone. Eugonadotropuric amenorrhoea includes psychical amenorrhoea, amenorrhoea in obesity, amenorrhoea with endocrine disturbances such as hypothyroidism, adrenogenital syndrome, etc. Only after aetiological treatment will a gonadotrophic treatment produce beneficial results in cases with good oestrogenization. The technique and dosage of the gonadotrophin treatment in sterility of ovarian origin are subsequently discussed. In Stein-Leventhal syndrome, a gonadotrophic treatment (FSH type) is not effective, except that a further increase in the already enlarged volume of the ovaries is obtained, so that the use of this treatment may be considered in the diagnosis of a suspected Stein-Leventhal syndrome. It is concluded that treatment by gonadotrophins has very specific indications and should be used only after treatment with oestrogens and progesterone. Huyghebaert - Malines.
