N2  - Four patients in whom a diagnosis of endometrial hyperplasia had been made by biopsy or curettage, and 2 patients whose endometrium revealed carcinoma in situ were treated with varying doses of 17a-ethinyl-17-hydroxy-5(10)-oestren-3-cne and ethinyloestradiol-3-methyl ether ('enovid') for from 24 to 80 days prior to curettage or hysterectomy. There was 1 more patient in whom Hertig had made the diagnosis of invasive carcinoma but who was thought to have 'atypical hyperplasia with foci of secretory activity'; this patient received 1 Tor-hydroxyprogesterone caproate ('delalutin') and 'enovid'. The protocols of the 7 cases are reported in detail. The general impression was that both cystic and adenomatous hyperplastic glands may undergo regression, and that actively growing stroma may be converted into decidua by the action of potent progestins. These changes were noted even in the usually stable basal layer of the endometrium and were more marked after prolonged therapy. It is not known whether areas of 'carcinoma in situ' were converted into secretory glands or whether these foci had been removed by curettage. Although the changes described in this report were produced in imenopausal and postroenopausal women, they should not be interpreted as cures, for in all probability as soon as progestin therapy is discontinued the original hyperplasia will return. Thus this approach is not suggested as definitive therapy for patients in this age group. However, in the younger patient who does not ovulate consistently and in whom pregnancy does not occur, the cyclic use of these preparations to secure secretory change and pseudomenstruation seems indicated after all other efforts to produce ovulation, e.g., wedge resection in Stein-Leventhal syndrome, have been explored and have been found wanting. (XVI, 3, 5, 10).
