T1  - The treatment of congenital ovarian malformations
T3  - Die therapie der kotinatalen ivarie lie n fehlbildungen
A1  - Stange H.H.
Y1  - 1959//
N2  - These malformations are subdivided into 6 groups. For rational treatment exploratory laparotomy is obligatory. In agonadisxn - a rare occurrence - protracted oestrogen treatment is indicated. In hypogonadism a substitutive treatment with oestrogen!c substances is of advantage for the development of the secondary female sex characteristics. Hype r g ona dis m requires no therapeutic measures. In pseudo-hypergonadisin (Stein-Leventhal syndrome) the numerous methods of treatment proposed indicate the insufficiency of any individual form of therapy; in the gynaecological clinic of Kiel, surgical treatment is preferred (bilateral wedge resection with puncture of the remaining cystic follicles and where necessary removal of the thickened tunica albuginea). The treatment of dysgonadism (syndrome of Klinefelter) consists, in view of the primary testicular insufficiency, in substitution with depot testosterone. In the last group of ovarian malformations, that of ambigonadism, which includes true hermaphroditism, it is not the somatic and morphological condition which should determine the therapy, but rather the psyche, sexual inclination and preference of the patient. Surgical corrections are often unavoidable. The article is completed with clear, didactically well-chosen illustrations. Reiffenstuhl - Graz (X, 3).
