T1  - Ovakian changes concerned with gonadotrophic dysfunction and associated with amenorrhoea and infertiuty. treatment by ovarian wedge resection and eversion with giluam suspension
A1  - Bailey K.V.
Y1  - 1959//
N2  - The aetiology of this syndrome and the ovarian changes associated with it remain in doubt. Pathologically 3 main types of ovarian changes are recognized in conjunction with the clinical aspects of this syndrome: (I) The polycystic ovaries, which constitute about 80% of the cases; () the cirrhotico-cystic and diffuse cirrhotic ovaries; and (E) cystic and cirrhotic atrophy of the ovaries. These may result from gonadotrophic dysfunction initiated de novo, or possibly may result by slow retrogressive change from the former type. The rationale of ovarian eve r s ion combined with Gilliam suspension is again described. All forme of medical and hormonal treatment must first be tried. It is, however, unwise to unduly prolong medical treatment where there is evidence of no success and where examination discloses the presence of the uterine, endometrial and ovarian changes described. Approx. 80% of the cases conform clinically and pathologically to the Stein-Le venthal syndrome. Nevertheless, these may be regarded as forming the major part of a large clinical hormonal syndrome caused and initiated by the same type of gonadotrophic dysfunction, and manifested only by the degree to which this dysfunction is operative in the particular individual. (X, 3).
