N2  - Changes in the normal average of reticulocytes in the blood occur in healthy women with age and with the stage of the menstrual cycle. Previous research indicated that gonadotrophin, thyroid hormone, vit. E and folic acid did not alter the reticulocyte count in persons with normal blood values. Exogenous oestradiol in some dosages seemed to stimulate erythropoiesis. The reticulocyte counts in women treated with gonadotrophic hormone for ovarian dysfunction were studied. In patients with hypoplastic or polycystic ovaries the reticulocyte counts varied with the secretion of oestrogen. Patients with hypoplastic ovaries had low reticulocyte counts before treatment. It is suggested that under some conditions the reticulocyte count is a useful and practical method of oestrogen analysis.
