T1  - The treatment of dysfunctional uterine haemorrhage with ethinyl-nor-testosterone acetate
T3  - Die behandlung funktioneller uterusblutungen mit athinyl-nor- testosteron-acetat - Nevinny
A1  - Stickel J.
Y1  - 1959//
N2  - Many new compounds with progestational activity have been investigated.,, among them the methyl-, the ethyl- and the ethinyl-nor-testosterone. Esterification with acetic acid enhanced their activity considerably without increase of side effects. The author treated 67 patients, suffering from dysfunctional bleeding, with daily dosages of 3 or 4 mg. of 17-alpha-ethinyl- 19-nor-testosterone-acetate. In 51 cases a curettage before hormonal treatment showed endometrial tissue without progestational effects (in proliferative phase or with hyperplasia). The age of the patients was 42 times between 40 and 51 years, 7 patients were between 14 and 24 yr. Medication was given during 8 days; 30 women were simultaneously treated with ethinyl-oestradiol. In 49 cases the bleeding was arrested within 48 hr., in 57 cases within 72 hr. It made no difference whether oestrogens were given or not, and the results did not depend upon the morphological appearance of the endometrium before treatment. Three to four days after discontinuing medication a menstruation-like bleeding occurred. Though the steroid may be used to control dysfunctional bleeding, a curettage will always be necessary in order to exclude organic (malignant) causes, unless the haemorrhage is of the juvenile type, or a recurrence and curettage has been performed the first time. A basal temperature record may be helpful in diagnosing an anovulatory cycle before bleeding occurs, and in those cases the steroid may be given prophylactically. Side effects were not observed.
