T1  - Amenorrhea. a review of etiology and treatment in 350 patients
A1  - Jones G.E.S.
A1  - Nalley W.B.
Y1  - 1959//
N2  - 350 patients with amenorrhoea have been studied in an effort to determine the aetiological factors. These factors fell into 8 groups: (1) lesions of the nervous system, (2) congenital anomalies. (3) endocrine disturbances, (4) nutritional deficiencies, (5) constitutional disease, (6) physiological states, (7) artificial conditions, and (8) psychogenic disturbances. There were 25 patients who were unclassifiable. Certain groups have a much better prognosis than others. The most favourable was the post par turn lactation amenorrhoea. Next, correctable endocrine logical dysfunction, i.e., the Stein-Leventhal syndrome, adrenal dysfunction, and hypothyroidism. On the other hand, the psychogenic group was remarkably resistant to therapeutic measures such as psychiatric care, cyclic steroid hormonal therapy and, occasionally, pituitary gonadotrophic ther-apy.
