T1  - The endometrium before and after wedge resection of the ovaries in the stein-leventhal syndrome
A1  - Kaufman R.H.
A1  - Abbott J.P.
A1  - Wall J.A.
Y1  - 1959//
N2  - Seventeen cases of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome have been followed with p re operative endometrial biopsies, bilateral wedge resection of the ovaries, and postoperative endometrial biopsies to determine: (1) what type of endometrial abnormalities, if any. are present, (2) the effect of surgery on any endometrial changes which may have occurred, and (3) the possible relationship between the Stein-Leventhal syndrome and endometrial carcinoma. The results presented indicate that varying degrees of endometrial change may be seen in association with the SteinLeventhal syndrome. The changes characterized by hyperplasia may be an individual response of the patient to prolonged oestrogen stimulation. Six of the 10 patients who demonstrated endometrial hyperplasia preoperatively revealed no evidence of this lesion following ovarian resection. In two of 3 women with atypical hyperplasia the atypism disappeared following operation. It is concluded that wedge resection of the ovaries in most instances will bring about a reversion of the endometrium to a normal pattern. Development of endometrial carcinoma can probably be prevented by early resection. A diagnostic curettage should be done in all cases with the clinical characteristics of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome before treatment.
