T1  - Medullary resection of the ovaries in the Stein-Leventhal syndrome
A1  - Alien W.M.
A1  - Woolf R.B.
Y1  - 1959//
N2  - A new aetiological theory is proposed, ft is based on the premise that the ovary produces just enough extra androgen to partially inhibit the pituitary. This occurs in the medullary portion of the ovary. Twenty-two patients with the syndrome were subjected to medullary resection of the ovary. All showed varying degrees of stromal cell hyperplaela. Luteinization of the cells was also apparent, leeding occurred 30.1 days, on the average, following operation. The ensuing cycles appeared normal with no dysfunctional bleeding. Correction of infertility was fairly good. The results are indicative of some steroid which exerts an inhibitory effect on the function of the ovarian cortex. The chemical nature is obscure, but an androgen is quite likely.
