N2  - Seven of 45 women with hirsutism had surgically verified Stein-Leventhal syndrome. In 22 the latter was associated with irregular menstruation. In 16 patients the hirsutism coexisted with irregular menstruation. Prednisone, in daily doses of 7.5-15 mg., for 19-219 days, reduced the total neutral 17-ketosteroid excretion to normal and gave from fair to good improvement of hirsutism in all patients. Also amenorrhoea and menometrorrhagia improved following the administration of prednisone. It is suggested that in hirsutism of this type the ovarian changes are secondary to primary changes in the adrenals.
