T1  - A comparative study of the effect of the progestational agents in human menstrual abnormalities
A1  - Southam A.L.
Y1  - 1958//
N2  - The drugs used were : i. m., buccal, and vaginal progesterone; oral progesterone combined with oestrogens; i.m. 17alpha-hydroxyprogesterone caproate; and 2 of the 19-norsteroid group: 17alpha-ethinyl-17-hydroxy-5(10)- oestren-3-one and 17alpha-ethinyl-19-nortestosterone. The two 19-norsteroids were contaminated with varying amounts of 3-methyl ether of ethinyl oestradiol. The agents were evaluated (1) as tests for endogenous oestrogen production in amenorrhoeic women, (2) for possible therapeutic value in amenorrhoea, (3) for possible benefit in the treatment of infertile women with inadequate secretory endometria, and (4) as therapeutic agents in the management of anovulatory bleeding. The patients treated were seen for infertility, amenorrhoea or anovulatory bleeding. Progesterone given by any route and 125 mg. of 17alpha-hydroxyprogesterone caproate produced withdrawal bleeding in amenorrhoeic women only if the endometrium showed some degree of active proliferation, and are therefore useful in evaluating endogenous oestrogen effect. The 19-norsteroids produced withdrawal bleeding from atrophic endometria and are useful in the evaluation of the ability of the endometrium to respond to stimulation, but are not useful as indicators of endogenous oestrogen production. The clinical response obtained with the 19-norsteroids indicated that these drugs or their metabolites had oestrogenic as well as progestational properties. A significant therapeutic effect could not be demonstrated for any of the progestational drugs used in the treatment of amenorrhoea or infertility associated with an inadequate secretory endometrium. The 19-norsteroids used were effective in promptly decreasing or arresting anovulatory uterine bleeding. Continued therapy delayed the onset of withdrawal bleeding until the medication was stopped. 17alpha-Hydroxyprogesterone caproate caused a temporary definite decrease or arrest of blood loss before the onset of withdrawal bleeding occurred. Recurrent haemorrhage associated with prolonged anovulatory cycles could be prevented by the production of cyclic withdrawal bleeding with any of the progestational drugs used. As to the time required for onset or the duration of withdrawal bleeding, no drug was superior to the single i.m. injection of progesterone. Unless oestrogen was also given, only the 19-norsteroids were effective in preventing frequent anovulatory bleeding.
