N2  - The histochemical effect of 17-ethinyloestrenolone on sites of glycogen, lipid, and alkaline phosphatase is reported in the endometria of 13 anovulatory women. The dose used was from 5 to 10 rag. daily for 7 to 21 days. A comparison was made with normally ovulating women in the secretory phase. AU the p re-treatment specimens of endometria showed histochemical reactions to these 3 compounds consistent with the proliferative phase. Post treatment, both typical and atypical secretory responses were encountered. In general, use of this steroid under the conditions of the experiment produced relatively normal secretory type endometria w ith sites of glycogen, lipid, and alkaline phosphatase similar to those found in secretory endometria of normally ovulating women.
