T1  - Comparison of the endometrial activities in man of anhydrohydroxyprogesterone and 17-acetoxyprogesterone, a new oral progestational compound
A1  - Goldzieher J.W.
A1  - Eterson W.F.
A1  - Gilbert R.A.
Y1  - 1958//
N2  - To 16 patients under 35 yr. of age, showing primary anovulatory ovarian failure, recent panhypogonadism, Sheehan's syndrome of recent origin, or post part urn amenorrhoea of at least 4.5 months' duration, 1 mg. stilboestrol t.i.d. was administered for 20 consecutive days. From the llth day of therapy on, progestational compounds were given in 3 different tests: consecutive cycles of 17-acetoxyprogesterone (I), consecutive cycles of I followed by one or more cycles of ethisterone (II) at the same dose level, and consecutive cycles of II followed by I. The efficacy of the therapy was evaluated by means of repeated endom et rial biopsies, and on clinical grounds. Clinically, the time interval between cessation of therapy and the onset of withdrawal bleeding was studied. Histologically, the appearance of glycogen in endometrial gland cells, glandular enlargement and cystic dilatation, the appearance of corkscrewing and deoidual change s in the stroma were interpreted as progestational effects. As the responsive ness of the endometrium increases in the course of cyclic therapy, the results of treatment during initial cycles must be separated from those obtained during subsequent cycles. The progestational effect of I is equal or superior to the effect of II, but neither substance is able to reproduce the histological characteristics of the menstrual endometrium in their entirety. In fact, it is still impossible to give a definition of a progestational compound, as all of the new steroids with 'progestational' potency may reproduce only some of the characteristics produced by the corpus lute urn hormone. Comparing those steroids to progesterone requires the assumption that progesterone is itself the ideal, the ultimate progestin - which is nothing more than an assumption!
