T1  - Induction of ovulation in the human: therapeutic and diagnostic importance
A1  - Kupperman H.S.
A1  - Epstein J.A.
A1  - Blatt M.H.G.
A1  - Stone A.
Y1  - 1958//
N2  - Forty patients were examined for normal adrenal, thyroid and ovarian oestrogenic function. Tests used were 17-ketosteroid excretion, 5-hour glucose tolerance test, FBI and serum cholesterol levels and successful'withdrawal' bleeding following 100 mg. of progesterone i.m. in oil. These same patients were then given 20 mg. of conjugated equine oestrogens i.v. as a single injection. Ovulation was determined by: (1) Basal body temperature rise of significant degree within one to 3 days after the injection and lasting at least 12 days. (2) Increased pregnanediul excretion 7 to 10 days after the injection. (3) Endometrial biopsy revelation of secretory endometrium on the 1st day of the ensuing menses. (4) Conception. Ovulation was induced in 17 infertile patients, pregnancy occurring in 9. Failure to induce ovulation occurred in 16 patients, 8 of whom eventually submitted to wedge resection of the ovaries with the diagnosis of poly cystic ovaries being returned by the pathologist. Of these latter 8 patients 3 became pregnant and the rest resumed normal menses. Ovulation in the remaining patients was not restored. Early diagnosis of polycystic ovaries, induction of ovulation in ovarian failure and controlled induction to correlate with timing of artificial insemination are emphasized.
