T1  - Conservative treatment of endometriosis
A1  - Kietner R.W.
Y1  - 1958//
N2  - Endometriosis is a benign disease with certain malignant characteristics. It may result in ovarian destruction, deformity of the oviduct, bladder dysfunction and large bowel obstruction. Absolute infertility is present in about 30% of cases. Definite treatment has too often been surgical, in the form of complete hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy. Endometriosis seems to occur after prolonged periods of ovulation (5yr. or more). Periods of anovulation, as brought about by pregnancy, seem to prevent the development of the disease and to provide palliation from symptoms. Repeated pregnancies may provide a prophylactic method of therapy. Palliative therapy includes observation and analgesia, hormonally induced anovulation and conservative surgical procedures. Anovulation for periods of 5 to 9 months may be brought about by oestrogens or progestins, or combinations of each. This pseudopregnancy results in amelioration of symptoms and regression of the endometriosis as long as the treatment is continued. Androgens should be utilized with care but they seem to be effective without producing anovulation. Conservative surgical procedures consist of excision of areas of endometriosis, resection of ovarian cysts, presacral and uterosacral denervation, uterine suspension. Preoperative anovulation with norethynodrel seems to simplify the operation. A bilateral oophorectomy should always be performed with a complete hysterectomy for endometriosis. Exogenous oestrogens may be given to prevent symptoms of and metabolic derangements associated with 'hypo-oestrinism'.
