T1  - The pathologic anatomy of the stein-leventhal syndrome
A1  - Plate W.P.
Y1  - 1958//
N2  - The Stein-Leventhal syndrome may be characterized clinically by hirsutism, obesity, sterility and menstrual disturbances. The ovaries show many follicle cysts and 'hyperthecosis' (hypertrophy and luteinization of the theca interna). In addition there is often a marked fibros is of the ovarian strom a and in a few cases luteinization of the theca externa as well as the theca interna. It is postulated that the amenorrhoea which occurs can be explained by lack of ovulation as can metrorrhagia and sterility, and that hirsutism results from production of androgen by the interstitial cells of the cystic ovary, from an imbalance between oestrogen and androgen or from hyperfunction of the adrenal cortex. With wedge resection of the ovaries 57% of 65 anovulatory patients whose ovaries showed hyperthecosis developed an ovulatory cycle, but 29% of 14 patients whose ovaries showed no such change also became ovulatory after wedge resection.
