N2  - 17-Ketosteroid excretion was studied in four cases of hirsutism in the age of puberty by fraction chromatography according to the method of Pond (simplified method of Dingemanse). In these four cases, in which once an enlarged adrenal was found by retroperitoneal aerogram and once an enlarged ovary by gynaecography, high 17-ketosteroid levels were observed chiefly of fractions IV and V, sometimes of fractions II and III, rarely of fractions VI and VII. Doses of 20,000 U. chorionic gonadotrophin administered to these patients always caused (except in one case) an increase in the 17-ketosteroid output concerning principally the fractions IV and V. It occurred in adrenal hyperplasia as well as in the polycystic ovarian syndrome. Doses of 300-600 mg. prednisone produced a quick decrease of 17-ketosteroids elimination and especially of fractions II, III, IV and V, as long as treatment was applied. It was most noticed in adrenal hyperplasia.
