N2  - The urinary 17-ketosteroids in women, with the exception of the insignificant catabolic products of ovarian steroids, are practically all metabolites of adrenocortical steroids. The normal value for women in the reproductive age groups varies between 7 and 17.5 mg. per 24 hr. In case of abnormal values, Chromatographie fractionation is often very valuable. Normally ACTH stimulates the production of adrenocortal steroids only up to the compound. with the 5:3-hydroxy-grouping (pregnenolone and dehydroepiandrosterone), whUe the biosynthetic reactions of the C-21 .teroid eerie. to cortisone, hydrocortiaone and corticoeterone take place independently. The biosynthesis of the C-19 eerie. to 4-androetene-3:17-dione and 4-androtene-110-01-3:17-dtone aleo appear. to be independent of ACTH. Hydrocortieone in particular appear. to have a counter-regulating effect on the ACTH secretion of the pituitary. The adrenocortlcosteroids are broken down to pregnane derivative. and 17-ketoeteroid.. The 17-ketoeteroide are subdivided into 4 related group., A, B, C and D with, so far, 48 separate fraction.. A. the consequence of hyperfunction of the adrenal cortex eeveral syndromes may occur, with the disturbances originating in the anterior lobe of the hypophysis or in the adrenal cortex. The Gushing syndrome is characterised by increased production of adrenocortical steroids, in the first place of cortisone and hydrocortisone. The 17-ketosteroids, especially the values of the C and O groups, are often increased. In the adrenogenital syndrome the synthesis of certain C-21 steroids, which are responsible for the regulation of the ACTH secretion of the hypophysis, appear. to be inhibited, with unlimited secretion of ACTH as the result. This leads to stimulation of the adrenal cortex and considerable Increase of the 17-ketoeteroids. In the adrenogenital syndrome with congenital hyperplasia of the adrenal cortex the percentage of increase i. the same for all four group.. The adrenogenltal syndrome with adenoma of the adrenal cortex is associated with an enormous increase of the 17ketosteroids, of which the increase of the B fraction (dehydroe/wandrosterone and epfandrosterone) constitutes a large part (up to 54% of the total secretion of neutral ketosteroids, a. compared with a normal percentage of 7-20). In condition. of stress, the noxious influence causes, via the intermediary of the hypophysis, hyperfunction of the adrenal cortex with increased secretion of corticosteroids. The chromatogram in these cases show. that the secretion of all 17-ketostero id fractions i. increased, but that of the D group most. Hypofunctional conditions of the adrenal cortex can be subdivided into primary forms, in which the adrenal cortex itself is damaged, and secondary forms, in which the hypophyseal stimulation is Insufficient. A distinction can further be made between absolute and relative insufficiency of the adrenal cortex. In absolute insufficiency the capacity is too email to meet even the ordinary requirement. of life, whereas in relative insufficiency there is not enough capacity for special circumstances. In these conditions the neutral 17-ketosteroids are always somewhat decreased, but not enough to be significant. The ACTH test, on the other hand, is highly significant. Virilizing tumours of the ovaries produce an abundance of androgena, the cycle becomes irregular and amenorrhoea appears. This group include. the arrhenoblastomas, the hilus or Leydig cell tumour., and the Stein-Leventhal syndrome. The 17-ketosteroids are increased (19-29 mg.per 24 hr. particularly the C fraction (androsterone and aetiocholanolone). Testicular femininization is an accurately defined form of male pseudo-hermaphroditism. The patients are chromosomal male and possess testicles, but the external genitals and mental outlook are female. There is primary amenorrhoea. The chromatogram .how. a slightly increased secretion of the total 17-ketoeteroid. with a normal distribution of the fraction group. It i. concluded that Chromatographie fractionation i. a valuable diagnostic aid.
