T1  - The clinical treatment of anovulation
A1  - Bergman P.
Y1  - 1958//
N2  - Ovulation does not necessarily mean corpus luteum formation and progesterone production; both phenomena can occur separately. Anovulation can manifest itself as regular anovulatory cycles, glandular cystic hyperplasia or amenorrhoea. It can be due to insufficient gonadotrophin stimulation of the ovaries, or to disturbances of ovarian function. It does not seem to play an important role in the aetiology of sterility, as in a series of 438 sterility cases there was evidence of anovulation only in 4%, and of these, 63% became pregnant later. That infers anovulation is only seldom permanent and refractory to treatment; sometimes anovulation rectifies itself spontaneously. Some cases will be cured by curettage. In those refractory to curettage, chorionic gonadotrophin (1500 I.U. on 3 subsequent days for 6-12 months) is, as a rule, successful. In those failing to respond to this treatment, there may be a Stein-Leventhal syndrome (treated by wedge resection of the ovaries), a granulosa-cell tumour (operation), or hypothyroidism (responding to thyroid treatment). The same applies to cases of glandular cystic hyperplasia, 35% of which will be cured by curettage.
