T1  - The borderline adrenogenital syndrome: An intermediate entity
A1  - Gold J.J.
A1  - Frank R.
Y1  - 1958//
N2  - Six representative case studies are presented of patients who exhibit varying degrees of hirsutism, menstrual abnormalities, and in some instances bilateral polycystic ovaries. They demonstrate normal to high-normal urinary 17-ketosteroids, and an elevated 'pregnane complex' in the absence of evidence of ovulatory cycles. This elevation in 'pregnane complex' falls with adequate prednisone therapy, indicating its probable adrenal origin. Normal cyclic ovulatory menses may occur on such therapy and pregnancy may follow. These patients do not appear to fit into the category of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome or the overt adrenogenital syndrome but appear more as an intermediate entity.
