T1  - The results of endometrial biopsy in 2,000 sterile women
T3  - Les resultats du microcuretage chez 2000 femmes steriles
A1  - Bottella Llusia J.
Y1  - 1958//
N2  - Endometrial biopsy is an obligatory part of the standard investigations in every sterile woman. It should be done between the 23rd and the 26th day of the cycle, since endometrial biopsies taken at the beginning of menstruation are much more difficult to interpret correctly. To obtain the best information the slide should be stained also by the Gomori and the Best or Hotchkiss-MacManus techniques for the study of alkaline glycerophosphatase and glycogen. Only 45% of the cases showed a normal secretory endometrium. The most important changes were absence of secretion (anovulatory cycles) in 27.1% and endometrial tb in 10%. If some investigations have shown a lesser frequency of endometrial tb, this could be due partly to the difficulty of correctly diagnosing tuberculous nodules. It is believed that endometrial tb is never per se a cause of sterility, which is produced by the accompanying tuberculous obstruction of the tubes. In 1.8% biopsy revealed abortion remnants so that in some cases the sterility is only apparent and the result of a precocious abortion. Only in one patient was uterine cancer found.
