N2  - A group of 49 young women developing post-pubertal hirsutism was studied. A high incidence of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome within this group was noted, characterized by menstrual irregularities including anovulatory cycles and sterility. These patients could be shown radiologically to have some, if only minimal, ovarian enlargement. They differed from others with hirsutism by reason of their normal mental attitude. Detailed examination of the 17-ketosteroids in the urine indicated a tendency for the ratio ll-hydroxyandrosterone: ll~hydroxyaetiocholanolone to be raised in the Stein-Leventhal syndrome. Other hirsute patients were characterized as a group by a high ratio of 17-ketosteroid/17-ketogenic steroid in the urine after adrenal stimulation with ACTH. The importance of estimating pregnanetriol in the urine was shown by the finding of one patient with true adrenal virilism characterized by relative failure of hydrocortisone synthesis with excess androgen production, who developed symptoms and signs of the condition only after reaching puberty.
