T1  - The stein-leventhal ovary. A manifestation of hyper-adrenocorticism
A1  - Perloff W.H.
A1  - Channick B.J.
A1  - Hadd H.E.
A1  - Nodine J.H.
Y1  - 1958//
N2  - Seven patients are reported all of whom showed signe of increased adrenocortical function and 6 of whom showed sclerocystic ovaries typical of Stein-Leventhal syndrome. The two syndromes may be the result of the same metabolic disturbance with the adrenocortical hyperfunction preceding the ovarian changes. Wedge resection of the ovaries improves menstrual function primarily, but treatment with prednisone not only accomplishes this but also improves adrenocortical function. The way in which the pathology of this condition develops is not known. An interesting supposition is that a primary metabolic defect of the adrenal cortex leads to low serum corticoid production. This in turn causes an increase in ACTH with a resulting increase in androgen from the adrenal. The increased androgen produces ovarian follicle cysts. Oestrogen from these cysts by its action through the pituitary gland causes further hypertrophy of the adrenal cortex and this tends to perpetuate the condition. It is suggested that the wedge resection acts by removing oestrogen producing tissue and the use of prednisone by lessening the effect of the primary adrenal metabolic defect. Brans comb - Birmingham. Ala. (X, 3).
