AN  - 280840228
T1  - Polycystic ovarian disease (Stein-leventhal syndrome). Etiology and rationale for surgical treatment
A1  - Evans T.N.
A1  - Riley G.M.
Y1  - 1958//
N2  - Wedge resections of the ovaries were performed in 25 patients diagnosed as having Stein-Leventhal syndrome. Ovulatory cycles developed in 19 and 16 became pregnant following the procedure. Little therapeutic response was obtained in 6. All those in whom good results were achieved had normal oestrogen and FSH levels postoperatively. The following theory is suggested to account for the development of the syndrome and its correction by wedge resection: A series of anovulatory cycles results in an accumulation of atretic follicles which secrete oestrogen at a uniform level/thereby failing to incite pituitary release of LH. Menstruation fails because of the constant oestrogen level. With ovarian resection the oestrogen level suddenly falls, gonadotrophin production increases, and uterine bleeding occurs.
