AN  - 280839925
T1  - TITRATION of URINARY ADRENAL STEROIDS after INFUSION of ACTH. I. DIAGNOSIS of ADRENAL HYPOCORTICISM. II.DIAGNOSIS of CUSHING'S SYNDROME. III. DIAGNOSIS of ADRENAL and OVARIAN HIRSUTISM in WOMEN
T3  - Titrace korovjch steroidu v modi po infusi ACTH. I. Diagnosa insuficience nadledvinkove kury. II. Diagnosa C us hing o va syndromu. E. Diagnosa nadledvinkove ho a vajeinikoveho hirsutismu u fen
A1  - Charvat J.
A1  - Kandra M.S.
Y1  - 1958//
N2  - I. Mean values of 17-OH-corticoids, determined by the Porter-Silber method,were about 8 mg./24 hr. Mean values of 17-ketosteroids (Zimmermann reaction) were about 15 mg./24 hr. in normal males and about 10 nag. /24 hr. in normal females. After infusion of ACTH (25 I. U. in 500 ml. 5% glucose solution administered over 8 hr. ) the level of 17-OH-CS in normal people rose to 3-4 times above the basal excretion. In 17-KS the rise rarely exceeded 100%. In the diagnosis of adrenal hypocorticism only the 17-OH-CS are decisive. In Addis on's disease the basal values are very low and do not rise after ACTH. In central hypocorticism basal excretion is also very low but it rises after ACTH to normal values. The response to the second ACTH infusion may be delayed. Analysis of clinical data of one case of Addison's disease, 2 of central hypocorticism and 6 of skin pigmentations of various origin are given. The ACTH test is very valuable in distinguishing skin pigmentation of various origin from the true Addison's disease. II. The diagnostic value of ACTH infusions in hypercorticism is based on the assumption that there exist 2 forms of Cushing's syndrome: one central (hypothalamicpituitary) and the other peripheral, caused by hormonally active cortical tumours. In the central form the urinary elimination of corticoids is increased, but it increases further after ACTH because the adrenals have not lost their dependence on the pituitary. In the peripheral form, however, no further increase of corticoids after ACTH occurs, the tumour being already independent of pituitary stimulation. Analysis of clinical data of 4 cases of central hypercorticism, 2 of peripheral hypercorticism and 5 of suspected Cushing's syndrome, in which the ACTH test was decisive, are given. Low basal elimination of corticoids and/or sluggish response to ACTH exclude the diagnosis of Cushing's syndrome. III. The ACTH test (25 I. U. of ACTH in 500 ml. 5% glucose solution over 8 hr. with estimation of the rise of 17-OH-CS and 17-KS) can be used for the differentiation of adrenal and ovarian hirsutism in certain cases only. In congenital or acquired disturbance in the production of the 17-OH-CS, basal 17-OH-CS values are low and do not rise after ACTH. By contrast, 17-KS values are high and increase still further after the administration of ACTH. In some cases where the primary cause is in the hypothalamus or pituitary the rise of 17-OH-CS after ACTH is normal and the reaction of 17-KS exceeds the levels found in normal subjects. The raised values of 17-KS in cases of Stein-Leventhal syndrome do not increase after ACTH or only slightly. The ACTH test is not by itself sufficient for a diagnosis of hirsutism due to a malignant tumour of the adrenal or ovary. Analysis of clinical data and results of ACTH tests in 9 cases of hirsutism of various origin are given. In general, the ACTH test is a less reliable diagnostic guide in hirsutism than in hypo- and hypercorticism.
