AN  - 280839721
T1  - THE REACTION of POLYCYSTIC OVARIES (STEIN-LEVENTHAL SYNDROME) to GONADOTROPHIC HORMONES
T3  - Die Reaktion polyzystischer Ovarien (Stein-Leventhal-Syndrom) auf Verabfolgung gonadotroper Hormone
A1  - Stange H.H.
A1  - Schaumkell K.W.
Y1  - 1958//
N2  - Seventeen patients with the Stein-Leventhal syndrome were treated with serum and chorionic gonadotrophins in the dosage of Staemmler; a wedge-resection of the ovari es was performed immediately afterwards in 15 cases, and after a second period of treatment in 2 cases. In the first 15 cases, the ovaries were found to be swollen, oedematous, and covered with dilated arteries; the cut surfaces showed many haemorrhagic follicles, with broad, yellow lut ein-walls, and also many haemorrhagic corpora lutea. On microscopic examination, fields of decidual cells were found in the surface-stroma, as well as a thickened tunica albuginea with oedema, atresia of the primary and primordial follicles, and extremely distended blood vessels, with haemorrhages in follicles, corpora lutea, and in the parenchyma; further, there were large fields of granulosa-lutein cells, either around the follicles and the more or less completely developed corpora lutea, or in the parenchyma only. The rete- and hilus cells also showed proliferation. As late results of the gonadotrophin therapy, the 2 other cases showed, on the contrary, a general fibrosis of the ovaries, with sclerotic blood vessels and only sporadic follicles, embedded in cicatricial tissue. It is assumed that Stein-Leventhal ovaries result from a too high titre of gonadotrophins in the second half of intrauterine life, and that these ovaries show a hypersensitivity after the menarche, to the renewed production of gonadotrophins, which results in the well-known changes in ovaries and menstrual cycle.
