AN  - 280661322
T1  - Progressive muscular dystrophy in the dog
A1  - Whitney J.C.
Y1  - 1958//
N2  - Three cases of myopathy in dogs are described: (1) A 12-year-old Sable Pekinese dog with congestive heart failure and no other known clinical details. At post-mortem examination the semimembranosis and semitendinosis muscles of both hind limbs were pale and slightly atrophic. In addition chronic valvular endocarditis was found. (2) A 10-year-old very fat Labrador bitch with slight weakness of the hind limbs and excessive thirst 1 month before death presented signs of pyometra and cardiac incompetence. At post-mortem examination the semimembranosis and semitendinosis muscles of both hind limbs were not atrophic but pale and showed faint grey streaking. In addition cystic ovaries with hormonal pyometra cystic nodular hyperplasia of the adrenal cortex and chronic valvular endocarditis were present. (3) A 10-year-old Alsatian bitch with a 2 weeks' history of weakness of the muscles of the hind limbs. The vastus medialis, vastus lateralis and rectus femoris were atrophic and hypotonic, especially on the right side. A diagnosis of right femoral paralysis was made and the bitch was killed. At post-mortem examination the extensors of the hind limbs were pale and atrophic, the flexor muscles being normal. In addition an adenoma of the thyroid gland, a small heart tumour, cystic hyperplasia of the endometrium and cystic follicles of both ovaries were found. No histological abnormalities were present in the spinal cord and femoral nerves. The histopathology of the involved muscles in all 3 cases was identical; atrophic muscle fibres of varying size, marked increase of fat cells and no increase of connective tissue. There was some proliferation of sarcolemmal nuclei and slight perivascular lymphocytic infiltration in 1 case. Although the photographs of the muscle pathology in these 3 cases are not very convincing, it is the opinion of the author that these cases of myopathy in the dog are similar to muscular dystrophy of the limb-girdle type in man.
