AN  - 280909744
T1  - Malignant Brenner tumor of the ovary. With the report of one case
A1  - Reel P.J.
Y1  - 1958//
N2  - Brenner tumours of the ovary may be considered not to be malignant and not to produce hormones for all practical purposes. Also, these tumours (even the benign class) are among the rarest neoplasms occurring in the ovary. Ten cases of malignant Brenner tumour have been previously reported. The 11th case is that of an 84-year-old multipara from whom an 18 by 12 cm. left cystic ovary was removed. The diagnosis was malignant Brenner tumour of the ovary presenting in addition pseudomucinous admixture. The histogenesis of these tumours is not well defined. Robert Meyer designated the tumour as arising from islands of indifferent cells first described by Walthard in 1903. Schiller theorized in 1940 a non-ovarian source of origin from tissue misplaced into the ovary in foetal life. Subsequent studies by the author have left the problem again on the doorstep of speculation.
