A1  - Mattingly D.
Y1  - 1958//
N2  - The authors review 49 cases of post-pubescent hirsutism in females in an attempt to assign the cause by examining the nature of the steroids in the urine before and after stimulation with corticotrophin. Nine cases of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome (group I) (sterility, menstrual irregularity) were observed and subjected to laparotomy. Each was found to have slightly to greatly enlarged ovaries, portions of which showed histologically persistent follicles, a tendency to cyst formation as well as proliferation and luteinization of the theca interna. Seven other subjects (group II) had the clinical manifestations of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome but were not explored. Thirty-two patients (group III) were called 'hirsutism' out were not considered examples of the Stein-Leventnal syndrome because ovulation was present. However, even this group was apparently heterogenous since 6 had ovarian enlargement. One example of the adrenogenital syndrome was observed. The excretion of 17-KS in the urine was significantly higher in group I than in group II or III. The ketogenic steroid excretion was equal in groups land III but lower in group II. Steroid excretion after corticotrophin injection for 4 days was determined and compared with measurements in normals. For 17-KS: group III>group I>group II> controls. For ketogenic steroids: controls were approximately equal to all study groups. The ratio of ketogenic steroids/17-KS was significantly higher in group III than in controls. When measured in 11 cases, representing all groups, the ratio of androsterone to aetiocholanolone was normal. Induction of excretion of pregnanetriol by corticotrophin indicated, in the 13 patients in whom it was measured, some interference with synthesis of ketogenic steroids though of a much lower order than seen in the adrenogenital syndrome. The output of gonadotrophin in selected cases of each group was normal. The authors conclude that post-pubertal hirsutism in the female is surprisingly frequently due to the Stein-Leventhal syndrome. There was no good evidence to indicate excess secretion of androgens by the ovaries. Rather there appeared to be some abnormality in adrenal steroidogenesis. No evidence was found of excess luteinizing hormone.
