T1  - Polyembryonic embryoma of the ovary of parthenogenetic origin
A1  - Simard L.C.
Y1  - 1957//
N2  - In a 38-year-old woman laparotomy revealed a tumour filling almost the entire abdominal cavity and infiltrating both parametria. There were metastases on the peritoneum, on the mesentery and on the liver. The removal of the tumour was difficult; at the same time a subtotal hysterectomy was performed. The patient's condition deteriorated gradually and she died 2 months after the operation. The greyish-white tumour, measuring 34 18 16 cm., contained numerous cysts. The greater part was a mixture of almost all tissues of the human body. The diagnosis established was the classical polycystic embryoma (teratoma) of the ovaries. In addition, there were structures which must be considered early stages of human embryos. In the stroma more than 20 of these young embryos were observed. Reference is made to the blastomeric theory and to the parthenogenetic theory to explain the origin of teratomas in the ovaries. The first theory is based on speculations. The possibility that the tumours come from parthenogenesis appears from the study of the spontaneous and experimental parthenogenetic phenomena in mammals and birds, and from the study of human teratomas. The tumour described here also corroborates this theory.
