T1  - Hypertrichoses. (With special reference to polycystic ovaries). Treatment with glycocorticoids and other methods
T3  - Hipertricosis (Con especial referencia al ovario poliquistico). Su tratamiento con glicocorticoides y otros metodos
A1  - Gerosa H.N.
Y1  - 1957//
N2  - By hirsutism is meant the existence of hair excessive in number, thickness or length, at the sites normal to the sex. It is distinguished from hypertrichosis when this hair growth passes beyond the limits of the usual zones. Apart from certain generalized and localized forms of hypertrichosis, whether acquired or otherwise, a form is distinguished in cases of polycystic ovaries, where it is associated with alterations in the menstrual cycle and impaired fertility. The laboratory findings are not constant, except for the 17-ketosteroid excretion which is higher than normal. In the pathogenesis, the hypothalamus plays a role; it induces the hypophysis to secrete corticotrophin which causes the adrenal cortex to produce and liberate glycocorticoids. Conversely, the glycocorticoids alter the production of corticotrophin. If the hypophysis is not inhibited by it, FSH and LH, which are also produced by the hypophysis, provoke the production of oestrogene, progesterone and androgens, which also are able to inhibit the hypophyseal secretion of corticotrophin. When the metabolizing function of the liver is increased, the inhibiting potentiality of the glycocorticoids is again lost. There are authors who believe that it is the adrenal cortex which, on losing the capacity to hydroxylate the steroids with C-21 into 17-hydrocorticosterone, is responsible for this disturbance. The last-mentioned substance is considered to be the one with a truly inhibiting capacity and in similar abnormal situations intermediary bodies are produced such as 17-hydroxyprogesterone which possess androgenic properties, do not inhibit corticotrophin, but do block the production of gonadotrophin. Thus, whereas the FSH is inhibited, the LH is intensified and then the ovary each time requires more LH. The LH causes atresia of the primordial follicles, or degeneration of its granular layer, death of the ovulum and concentric proliferation of the theca. When the follicle has almost reached maturity, disintegration of the stratum granulosum and the ovulum are produced with ensuing cystic atresia of the follicle. Moreover, there is cutaneous sensitivity of the hair follicle. There are different methods of treatment: (1) Glycocorticoids which act (a) on the trophic hormones of the hypophysis, (b) directly on the hair follicle, and (c) as a local factor on the ovary. The treatment lasts 270 days, i.e. 3 cycles of 90 days according to the drugs employed and according to their metabolization by the liver. The 'cutaneous sensitivity test' by means of the intradermal application of hydrocortisone serves as a guide for establishing the doses. (2) Wedge resection of the ovary. (3) Combination of the 2 afore-mentioned methods. (4) In cases of failure of these methods, deep radiotherapy of the renal region, in 4 fields, 2 anterior and 2 posterior, the dose being 200 r. per field, and the total dose necessary for reaching the adrenal glands being 4000 r. The final treatment consists in depilating radiotherapy, which is carried out when the clinical improvement is complete.
