T1  - Genital circulatory alterations in gynaecological symptomatology
T3  - Alterazioni circolatorie pelvigenitali nella sintomatologia ginecologica
A1  - Revoltella G.
Y1  - 1957//
N2  - The symptoms of congestion of the pelvic organs may be due to 4 principal factors: inflammatory, biochemical (and principally oestrogenic), mechanical and nervous factors. The last 2 factors are considered. The most important mechanical factors are abnormal positions of the uterus, which by causing an obstruction of the blood flow also create the conditions for the development of a pelvic varicocele. The circulatory disturbance has its repercussion on the ovary (disordinate and accelerated maturation of the follicles; anovulatory menstruation; menstrual disturbances, etc.) and on the uterus (sclerosis due to chronic stasis). Other predisposing conditions are special working conditions which force the patient to remain in the erect position (charwomen, shop-girls, etc.) or, on the contrary, to remain seated for a long period of time (dress-makers, etc.). Also the continuous use of bicycles and athletics may be very harmful. The subjective and objective symptoms are described and treatment should be directed to correcting the malposition of the uterus, and need not necessarily be surgical. In some cases, good results may be obtained with pessaries. In cases where the pelvic congestion is not caused by malposition of the uterus (pelvic varicocele, improperly called primary), cure is difficult and surgical treatment often ineffective. A study is made of the importance of the relationship between psychical trauma and pelvic circulation. It is concluded that pure cases of pelvic congestion can undoubtedly be verified, also on a psychical basis alone.
