T1  - Ovarian anomalies in primary amenorrhoea. (A clinical contribution to diagnosis and treatment)
T3  - Uber keimdrusenanomalien bei primarer amenorrhoe. (Ein klinischer beitrag zur diagnostik und therapie)
A1  - Staemmler H.-J.
A1  - Stange H.-H.
A1  - Rumphorst K.
Y1  - 1957//
N2  - A case is reported in which the ovaries were absent; a string of connective tissue replaced the left tube and there was a short stump left of the right one, histologically recognizable as such. The uterus was the size of a pigeon's egg. The patient was genetically a woman; the FSH and 17-ketosteroid excretions were normal. The abnormality is regarded as a defect due to early degeneration from an exogenous cause (parotitis?). The second case reported is one of Turner-Albright syndrome. This patient was also genetically female. Laparotomy revealed, both left and right in the peritoneum, in the vicinity of the linea innominata, a thickening 12 x 2 mm. in size. Histological examination revealed no follicular tissue. The stroma contained hyperplastic hilar cells. The third was a case of prepuberal menopause with marked hypoplastic ovaries, containing atretic follicles with a well-vascularized theca wall and small accumulations of typical hilar cells. The patient, who was genetically female, was reported to suffer from flushes now and then. The fourth was a case of secondary amenorrhoea with polycystic ovaries (Stein-Leventhal syndrome). The ovaries were very large and had grown considerably after administration of large doses of gonadotrophin. In the resected part of the ovary, many cystic atretic follicles with marked thecal hyperplasia were found. The last case was one of adrenogenital syndrome with pronounced virilization. The left adrenal was hyperplastic. The patient was genetically a female. The proposed treatment was amputation of the clitoris and partial resection of the left adrenal cortex with administration of cortisone.
