A1  - Marsalek J.
Y1  - 1957//
N2  - This article is based on a detailed analysis of 5 cases and a review of the literature. Three main problems remain unsolved: laboratory tests for diagnosis, pathogenesis, and the inconstant appearance of hirsutism. The importance of determination of the individual fractions of 17-ketosteroids is stressed; fractions II and III are decreased, IV and V increased (whereas in adrenal hirsutism fractions III and IV are increased), and after operation the values return to normal. Special staining methods for acid mucopolysaccharides (Hale, alcian blue), and muco- and glyco-proteins (Rinehart-Abul-Haj) showed an accumulation of these mainly in the adventitia of the blood vessels, especially arteries, along the blood vessels, and in the theca; in these sites, as well as between the germinal epithelium and the deeper ovarian layers, the collagen tissues are thickened, and its fibres coarsened. From these findings the author concludes that the essential moment in the pathogenesis of this syndrome is an alteration of the metabolism of the ovarian mesenchymal tissue. Whether this is caused by androgens or oxysteroids, remains to be settled.
