T1  - Chorionic gonadotropin. Its place in the treatment of infertility
A1  - Palmer A.
Y1  - 1957//
N2  - Eighty-four of 500 infertile women were presumed to be infertile because of significantly shortened progestational ('biphase') cycle in their basal body temperature (BBT) charts. Male and other female factors for infertility were apparently ruled out. 1000 I. U. chorionic gonadotropin (CG) was given i. m. every other day for 5 injections starting on the 5th or 6th day of biphase. Biphase was prolonged to 14 or more days in all treated patients (198 cycles ). Fifty-three patients became pregnant in treated or 1st post-treatment cycle. Following philosophic discussion the author concludes 'CG deserves no place in the treatment of infertility in the anovulatory human female nor in the infertile ovulatory human female during the preovulatory phase'. The hormone was harmless in the amounts used, and no detectable ovarian disorders ensued. CG is preferred to ovarian steroids for treatment of the short luteal phase. CG can prolong this phase in the human for at least 14 days. The occurrence of pregnancy may have been coincidental. The early hormonal diagnosis of pregnancy may be false as the injected hormone may be detected in the patient's urine.
