N2  - An anatomo-clinical study was made of 5 cases of encephalitis which were characterized by a two-stage development: a stage of excitation with manifestations of manic-depressive or depressive-paranoid agitation, and a stage with confused agitation of hyperkinetic type, leading to death within 8-16 days. The morbidanatomical findings indicated the influenzal aetiology of the process. In the brain, the principal lesions were localized in the hypothalamus, they consisted of congestion and oedema, perivascular infiltrates and degenerative changes in the nervous cells. The female patients (4 cases) showed, in addition to the CNS changes, a dysendrocrine condition with a diffuse micro-alveolar goitre, micro-polycystic ovaries and hyperplasia of the uterine mucosa (simple or glandular-cystic). It is thought probable that there existed a relationship between the psychotic syndrome and the observed dysendocrine state.
