T3  - Vergleichende morphologische Untersuchungen uber die sog. kleincystische Degeneration des Ovars und das polycystische Ovar (Hyperthecosis ovarii)
A1  - Gy G.
A1  - Laszio J.
A1  - Feher L.
Y1  - 1957//
N2  - Material: ovarian wedge resections from 20 cases of hyperthecosis ovarii; 25 ovaries, removed for other reasons, from patients without endocrinological symptoms; cystic ovaries found accidentally at autopsies. Examination of native preparations, frozen sections, and pa raff in-bloc k preparations. <ovid:br/>Finding(s): (1) Microcystic degeneration; usually unilateral; small ovary, grey lumpy surface; thin capsule, with little collagen; the stroma contains densely packed foci of cicatrization; no theca activity; corpora lutea and albicantia present; cysts caused by retention; no clinical symptoms. (2) Polycystic ovary: usually buateral; enlarged ovary; white smooth surface; thick capsule, with deeply penetrating collagen; loose oedematous stroma, with paralutein cells; marked theca activity, atretic follicles; cysts caused by hypersecretion; clinically: hirsutism, obesity, meno- and metrorrhagias, sterility, headaches (Stein-Leventhal's syndrome). An old infection is most likely the basis for microcystic degeneration, while the polycystic ovary is caused by hormonal disturbances, and, in its turn, gives rise to other hormonal disturbances (endometrium). The microcystic ovary does not have to be operated on; in the case of Stein-Leventhal's syndrome, resection of the ovary should be performed. Oettgen - Cologne (V, 10).
