T1  - A discussion of the report concerning provoked and spontaneous forms of hyperaniirxjvinism. personal experience
T3  - Discussion du rapport apropos des hyperandrogenie s provoquees et spontanees. Notre experience
A1  - Appni A.
A1  - Flenin N.
A1  - Codaggioni T.L.
Y1  - 1957//
N2  - All the patients studied, with the exception of 1 case of virilLzing tumor of the ovary which had been referred by the Department of Endocrinology, had applied for an CjRL consultation because they were alarmed by theirs dysphonia. Il is interesting to note that none of them had previously become aware because of the other signs of hyperandrogemsm such as changes of the ovarian cycle or hypertrichosis. After the interviews, which brought to light some signs of virilization, the authors asked the advice of an endocrinologie specialist. Also, with the exception of the case of ovarian tumor and 4 cases of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome, all lhe patients with dysphonia presented a minimal form of the common syndrome of hypertrichosis. This discrepancy between the dysphonia and the signs of hormonal equilibrium gives rise to 2 hypotheses: (I) the hypothesis of a different sensitivity of the receptors to androgens: the larynx in these particular cases was the most receptive organ, probably also because of the nonhormonal predisposing factor (20 cases out of 30). (2) The hypothesis that the dysplionia of the syndrome of common hypertrichosis is to be considered not from liie hormonal but from the neurologic point of view. Classically, the neuropsychic disorders are described as the principal part of the syndrome. As is known, 1hey range from very slight neurotic manifestations to psychoses, via a clinically manifest or latent epilepsy, with intermittent depression being the commonest form. The sign of Chvostek was encountered in 42o of these patients, in the course of an examination carried out in the endocrinologie clinic of Marseilles; in the majority of the cases, it constitutes the expression of a neurogenous spasmophilie and reflects a neuromuscular hyperexcitability. l:i view of these findings, the question is raised whether the dyspVionia of the syndrome of common hypert ricljosis might not have a neuropsychiatrie as well as a hormonal mechanism. (.3 ).
