AN  - 280926354
T1  - Anovulatory cycles in women
A1  - De Allende T.L.C.
Y1  - 1956//
N2  - During the period of sexual activity anovulatory cycles are comparatively frequent but quite unpredictable. They constitute the predominant type at puberty and climacterium. Anovulatory cycles can occur with the most varied degrees of ovarian follicular activity. The vaginal smears, by revealing the degree of cellular differentiation produced by oestrogens, very well portray the intensity of their effect. This can be visualized in the shape of the curve drawn with the daily percentages of caryopyknotic cornified cells along the whole cycle. The anovulatory cycles can be classified according to the type of the curve: (1) Hypotrophic, acyclic cornification curve (hypo-oestrogenism without fluctuations). (2) Hypotrophic, cyclic cornification curve (hypo-oestrogenism with fluctuations). (3) Eutrophic anovulatory cornification curve (normal oestrinism). (4) Elevated cornification curve (sustained hyperoestrogenism). In type 1 and 2, the women may show metabolic, somatic or psychic disturbances due to the ovarian insufficiency. In type 3, the anovulatory cycle is ignored, since it causes no objective or subjective disturbances. It becomes important as a cause of infertility. In type 4, somatic or psychic disturbances may appear and the condition may lead to the verge of a haemorrhagic metropathy. Wistar Institute (I, 3, 10).
