T1  - Oestrogen shock in the treatment of anovulatory cycles
T3  - El choque de estrogenos en el tratamiento de los ciclos anovulatorios
A1  - Foix A.
Y1  - 1956//
N2  - It is assumed that a single large dose of oestrogens causes the sudden liberation of gonadotrophins in young animals, with the consequent discharge of an ovum and production of corpora lutea, whereas the uniform and prolonged administration of these substances exercises an inhibitory action upon the hypophysis. A study was made of 2 groups of patients. The first group, comprising 38 patients who were sterile due to anovulatory cycles, were given an injection of 10 mg. oestradiol benzoate on the 10th or 12th day of the cycle. The basal temperature was not changed by this treatment. Two patients became pregnant. The second group comprised 14 patients with bilateral tubal occlusion, to whom 3 mg. of the oestrogen were administered for 20 days, treatment being started after the cessation of menstruation. In 5, the basal temperature graph did not change. In 7 a monophasic curve was produced and in 2 ovulation was inhibited during one month, but took place in the following. On the basis of these results it is believed that the inhibitory action of oestrogens in high doses is not constant. It is stated that the fact that a single dose gives good results in rare cases only may be due to a disturbance in the endocrine balance (ovary, hypophysis, thyroid or adrenal glands and, in other cases, an organic disease). High doses administered for a long period may inhibit the production of FSH. However, this is only a theoretical answer and not until accurate methods have become available for the determination of the 3 gonadotrophic hormones, will it be possible to give an exact answer.
