T1  - Ovulation in hypomenorrhoea
T3  - La ovulacion en la hipomenorrea
A1  - Galbis M.
Y1  - 1956//
N2  - The existence of hypomenorrhoea does not signify a special disturbance of the ovarian function, but may be observed also in cases of cyclic ovulation. Hypomenorrhoea may accompany any type of endometrium at any stage of ovarian function. To determine whether or not there is ovulation 3 methods are employed: Serial colpocytology, basal temperature and biopsy of the menstrual endometrium. A study was made of 38 cases. In 19, endometrial biopsy revealed a menstrual mucosa of normal characteristics and the colpocytology and basal temperature also showed the characteristics proper to the ovular cycles. In 7 cases, the 3 methods revealed absence of ovulation and signs of over-all ovarian hypofunction. In 3 cases, biopsy of the endometrium revealed a tb endometritis, in one of these cases the colpocytology was of ovulatory character and in another of anovulatory character. In 2 cases there existed a typical anovulatory cycle, with proliferative endometrium of the oestrogenic type. Attention is drawn to 7 cases which showed peculiarities: either an irregular endometrium with slightly hypoplastic characteristics, with an evident secretory reaction; or normal glandular development; or not very marked secretory disturbances; or an endometrium which had become evidently atrophied. The colpocytological characteristics were also different in these 7 cases. The basal temperature in all the cases was biphasic.
