T1  - Clinical contribution to the study of hypogastric sympathectomy
T3  - Contributo clinico allo studio della simpatectomia ipogastrica
A1  - De Marzo V.
A1  - Vivori C.
A1  - Zanutta E.
Y1  - 1956//
N2  - Although presacral neurectomy is the commonest operation for the treatment of dysmenorrhoea, it is not the only one, because in a considerable percentage of the cases the dysmenorrhoea may be due rather to an affection of the ovary and its plexus. If no clinical differentiation has been possible before operation, the finding of a sclerocystic ovary may indicate that the operation be completed with pelvic sympathectomy by the technique of Ruggi-Browne. Interruption of the ovarian nerves and vessels does not abolish the function of this organ, which is still sufficiently vascularized and, under hormonal stimulation, continues its regular cycles of follicular maturation, so that the patient remains fertile, as has been demonstrated clinically. Resection of the ovarian plexus, the fibres of which are directly damaged, may render it unnecessary to perform partial resection or removal of the organ in case its alterations are not very severe, because the possibility exists that resection of the affected nerve fibres may lead to regression of the degenerative condition.
