T1  - The ovarian theca cell. Part IV. The hyperthecosis syndrome
A1  - Shippel S.
Y1  - 1955//
N2  - The hyperthecosis syndrome is characterized as a condition which from an insidious beginning runs a protracted course of 10, 15 or more yr. before it reaches its climax and in so doing completes its transformation of the human female into a masculinized, hirsute, sterile, often frigid individual with temporal hair recession, atrophied uterus and endometrium, and occasionally enlargement of the clitoris and atrophy of the breasts. During its course it passes through phases of irregular menses, menorrhagia and amenorrhoea. The endometrial picture varies according to the stage of the disease: crowding of the endometrial glands and pseudostratification of their cells, glandular intussusception, cystic glandular hyperplasia and endometrial atrophy. Despite the occasionally marked masculinization the 17-ketosteroid values are usually low and at most slightly elevated, which suggests that the theca cell androgen is usually not broken down to a 17-ketosteroid. The material, which consists of 37 cases (6 with a fully developed picture of Stein-Leventhal's syndrome) is accounted for in detail with clinical data and microscopic examination of ovarian and endometrial tissue. The material was divided into 6 groups according to the degree of deviation from the normal and to the thecal-granulosal ratios, which groups exemplify various stages of the disease. The commonest cause of the syndrome is a persistent anovulation during the first few years after menarche or after the age of 40, Other aetiological factors are pregnancy, conditions which tend to stimulate the reticulo-endothelial system and local pelvic irritative conditions. Contrary to the generally accepted concept, the primary cause is believed not to be abnormal or excessive pituitary stimulation, but rather factors inherent in, or locally irritative to, the ovaries.
