T1  - The hypercorticism syndrome during salicylate therapy
T3  - Contributo alla conoscenza della sindrome di 'ipercorticismo' in corso di terapia salicilica
A1  - Gregoris L.
A1  - Drudi C.
Y1  - 1955//
N2  - Two women suffering from acute rheumatism were treated with salicylates and cortisone. Although the doses of the latter have been very small (1 g. and 0.375 g. respectively) both patients displayed metabolic disorders such as: puffy face, streaks in the skin, impaired carbohydrate, salt and water metabolism, brief spells of arterial hypertension. This is considered to be a support of the hypothesis of a hormonopoietic role of the salicylates. The absence of androgenic elements and the inconstancy of the other peculiar symptoms of this syndrome are taken to justify the denomination of 'dissociated functional therapeutic hypercorticism'.
