T1  - Differential diagnosis of virilism
A1  - Segaloff A.
A1  - Gordon D.
A1  - Horwitt B.N.
A1  - Weed J.C.
Y1  - 1955//
N2  - Six patients are described. Of primary importance is the definition of virilism, especially as compared with simple hirsutism. Virilism is an abnormal endocrine condition with characteristics of excessive androgen production. Hirsutism is only abnormal hairgrowth with normal feminine characteristics and normal androgen production. These conditions may be recognized clinically and biochemically. A patient may develop virilism by exogenous administration of testosterone (case I) and by endogenous abnormal androgen production. The organs which may produce abnormal quantities of androgens are: (a) the adrenal cortex (cases V and VI); (b) the ovary (case III). Abnormal androgen production by the adrenal cortex with very high urinary 17-ketosteroid excretion may be due to bilateral hyperplasia or a tumour. These 2 possibilities are differentiated by i. v. administration of compound F. If the administration of cortisone is followed by a sharp drop of the 17-ketosteroid elimination, there is adrenal hyperplasia. If there is no decrease, a tumour is present (cases V and VI). Tumours of the ovary may give rise to virilism, but in these cases the 17-ketosteroid level is mostly only slightly increased. Marked virilization with a slightly elevated 17-ketosteroid excretion, not decreasing after administration of cortisone, is a strong indication of an ovarian tumour (case III). Case II is an example of simple hirsutism. Case IV is an example of Stein-Leventhal's syndrome. The diagnosis of these conditions is very important with regard to the application of the correct therapy. In familial non-endocrine hirsutism, treatment is not necessary.
