T1  - Luteal insufficiency and hyperexcretion of 17-ketosteroids
T3  - Insuffisance luteale et hyperexcretion 17-cetosteroidique urinaire
A1  - Netter M.A.
A1  - Lambert A.
A1  - Salomon Y.
Y1  - 1955//
N2  - In a previous publication the authors described a peculiar syndrome of amenorrhoea accompanied by hyperandrogenism and polycystic degeneration of the ovaries. The hyperandrogenism was assumed not to be of adrenal, but of ovarian origin. Cortisone had a favourable effect. Since then, increased urinary excretion of 17-ketosteroids was often observed by the authors, even in patients with a normal menstrual cycle. Among them were women with symptoms of insufficiency of the corpus luteum and it was precisely in these that cortisone had an immediate therapeutic result: the anovulatory sterility and all cases of luteal insufficiency were cured. Three instructive cases are reported. If pregnancy follows, the administration of cortisone is discontinued. The mechanism of action of cortisone is unknown. ACTH was presumed to reduce the secretion of androgenic substances, but it is also active in those cases where no androgenaemia was present. It is liable to some doubt whether ACTH activates the gonadotrophic activity of the hypophysis. Further investigations will follow.
