T1  - The total and fractionated determination of the urinary excretion of 17-ketosteroids in women, in connection with age, normal or pathologic gonadal function and presence or absence of hirsutism
T3  - De totale en gedifferentieerde bepaling van-de 17-ketosteroiden-uitscheiding van de vrouw in verband met de leeftijd, de al dan niet gestoorde gonade-functie en de aan- of afwezigheid van hirsutisme
A1  - Stolte L.A.M.
A1  - Bakker J.H.J.
A1  - Verboom E.
Y1  - 1955//
N2  - Description of a technique for continuous fractionation, to be preferred to the discontinuous method of Dingemanse et al. because the displacement of certain fractions from one peak into another (caused by abrupt transience from lower to higher percentages of alcohol during elution) is avoided. It is pointed out that, though lowering or absence of certain peaks in the diagram means decrease or absence of one of the steroids normally present in this peak, elevation of a peak does not necessarily mean increased excretion of a certain steroid. Stimulation of the adrenal by ACTH leads to elevation of most peaks, whereas administration of cortitisone does not result in elevation of the so-called gonadal peaks. The difference between 'adrenal' and 'gonadal' peaks must therefore be considered as insufficiently founded. The newborn has an extremely low urinary 17-KS-excretion, which - in girls - increases till the menarche. Pseudohermaphroditism (one case) shows a high 17-KS-excretion, while pubertas praecox may give a normal or an elevated excretion (3 cases, 3/4, 3 and 8 yr. old). From the diagrams of patients with primary amenorrhoea and of patients with secondary amenorrhoea with ovulatory and anovulatory cycles it appears, that no clear differences in 17-KS-excretion can be found, depending upon absent, hypoplastic or qualitatively normal ovaries; in ovarian agenesis the percentages IVth and Vth peak were significantly lowered, though the peaks never were absent. After castration or in the menopause the 17-KS-excretion is lowered; also here the IVth and Vth peak are never missing. Determinations in cases of hirautism showed that the 17-KS-excretion is elevated while with increasing age the factor, causing both high excretion and hirautism, is weakened. A correlation between ovulation and 17-KS-excretion could not be found with this technique. An elevated IIIrd peak was found in three cases of adrenal tumours, and - remarkably - in two cases of hyperthecosis ovarii. In cases of the Stein-Leventhal-syndrome the hirsutism, the nature of the menstrual cycle and the microscopic changes in the ovaries showed no clear relationship to high IVth and Vth peaks, and even an eleyated IIIrd peak may be found in patients with this syndrome. Together with the clinical findings these data render the Stein-Leventhal-syndrome as a clinical entity rather unlikely, though there must exist a close connection with the condition of the ovary, as appears from the success of the wedge-shaped resection. The authors draw attention to the fact, that the diagram according to Dinge man se in a single patient may show a different pattern after some time; elevated IVth and Vth peaks may therefore not be considered as strictly pathognomonic.
