T1  - Application of radio-active iodine (I<ovid:sup>131</ovid:sup>) for the evaluation of the thyroid function in gynaecological affections
T3  - La methode de l'iode radio-actif (I<ovid:sup>131</ovid:sup>) dans l'appreciation de la fonction thyroidienne dans certaines affections gynecologiques
A1  - Schockaert J.A.
A1  - De Muylder E.
Y1  - 1955//
N2  - 143 patients with a history of habitual abortion, female sterility, foetal polymortality, amenorrhoea and oligomenorrhoea, and 20 cases of menorrhagia, metrorrhagia and anovulatory cycle were studied. In a considerable percentage of the cases, there was no clinical evidence indicating abnormal function of the thyroid, which could be demonstrated with radioactive iodine. In habitual abortion, hyperthyroidism was encountered more often than hypothyroidism (31.5% against 18.5%); in cases with repeated foetal mortality these figures were 50% against 12.5%, in amenorrhoea and oligomenorrhoea 33.3% against 12%. In sterile patients, the difference was less evident (21.2% against 17.3%). In 9 pregnant women thyroid function was found to be normal in only one. There was hyperthyroidism in 7 and hypothyroidism in 1. Once more it was demonstrated that determination of the basal metabolism is not sufficiently reliable for assessing thyroid activity.
