AN  - 280953433
T1  - Treatment of 'gestoses' with oestrogens
T3  - Tratamentul gestozelor cu estrogeni
A1  - Badarau L.
Y1  - 1955//
N2  - The author uses oestrogens in the treatment of all forms of 'gestoses', a term which includes all disturbances of pregnancy caused by an excess of progesterone. In pregnancy there is always either an insufficiency, or a great 'relative' deficiency of oestrogens, due to an alteration in the quantity of oestrogens present in the organism and the quantity of progesterone with contrary functions. This predominance of progesterone during pregnancy shows trimestrial fluctuations which may be detected clinically as well as by vaginal smears. Contrary to the theory of Smith, treatment with oestrogens - either synthetic or natural - corrects in the opinion of the author this deficiency by inhibition of the excess of progesterone. The examination of 4,500 vaginal smears during pregnancy has shown cytologically a deficiency of different types which represents the pathogenic aetiology common to all forms of gestoses. Thus, strictly from the cytomorphological point of view, the vaginal smears could be of the superficial intermediate, the deep intermediate, or the atrophied type. Each represents a more or less differentiated type of proliferation of the vaginal epithelium which, in the absence of the superficial layer, could reach a height of 450-500 mu. by the disproportionate development of the intermediate or basal layer because of the influence of other proliferating factors. From the point of view of function one can distinguish: (1) An inflammatory type with insufficient intracellular glycogenic metabolism with a flora specific to an alkaline reaction, trichomonas, monilias and leucocytes. (2) A type of cytolytic smear with increased glycogen metabolism, with a flora specific to an acid milieu. The author has treated 300 cases of disturbed pregnancy with good results. The method of administration has been exclusively vaginal (into the posterior fornix). The therapeutic doses of 5-20 mg. per day have been 10-30 times less than those given by other methods of administration.
