N2  - 143 patients with a history of habitual abortion, female sterility, foetal polymortality, amenorrhoea and oligomenorrhoea, and 20 cases of menorrhagia, metrerrhagia and anovulatory cycle were studied. In a considerable percentage of the cases, there was no clinical evidence indicating abnormal function of the thyroid. In habitual abortion, hyperthyroidism was encountered more often than hypothyroidism (31.5% against 18.5%); in cases with repeated foetal mortality these figures were 50% against 12.5%; in amenorrhoea and oligomenorrhoea 33.3% against 12%. In sterile patients, the difference was less evident (21.2% against 17.3%). In 9 pregnant women thyroid function was found to be normal in only one. There was hyperthyroidism in 7 and hypothyroidism in 1. Once more it was demonstrated that determination of the BMR is not sufficiently reliable for assessing thyroid activity.
