T1  - A new conception of ovulation
T3  - Ovulasie - 'n nuwe be grip
A1  - Du Toit D.A.H.
Y1  - 1954//
N2  - Three types of cells are of importance in the process of ovulation, viz. granulosa cells, theca cells and stroma cells. Theca cells are stroma cells which have changed in form and function. In ovulation, therefore, there is never an active invasion of theca cells in between the stroma cells. Examination of hundreds of serial sections of polycystic ovaries showed that the cysts are nearly always localized in a loosely meshed tissue, i.e. are always surrounded by interstitial tissue spaces resulting from fusion of increasingly vacuolized luteinized theca cells. Wherever a follicle (normal or abnormal) develops, the surrounding stroma cells are subject to hyperplastic transformation into lutein theca cells; vacuolization is most marked in the theca cells surrounding the follicle on the side of the ovarian surface, i.e. at the base of the so-called Strassmann cone. (It is regarded as likely that the transiently vacuolizing theca cells produce androgen which, according to Gaarenstroom and De Jongh, is required in the normal development of the follicle.) Due to degeneration of the vacuolized cells, the developing follicle finds space available mostly in the direction of the ovarian surface. At the same time, new theca cells are being formed at the apex of the cone; as a result, the cone apparently moves in the direction of the ovarian surface. The only cells which are destroyed are not the stroma cells between the cone and the ovarian surface, but the theca cells at the base of the cone (by self-disintegration). When the described wedging between follicle and ovarian surface lacks, a follicular cyst occurs and ovulation does not occur. The fact that the cone is invariably formed between the follicle and the ovarian surface is explained by the contention that the embryonic Gruenwald formations have predetermined the site where later the cone will develop.
