N2  - Three cases are reported in which obesity of female type, hirsutism sometimes with virilism, and menstrual disturbances were associated with sterility and bilateral polycystic ovarian dystrophy. Similar cases have already been recorded by Stein and Leventhal (1935) and by Geist and Gaines (1942, syndrome of diffuse luteinization). The 17-ketosteroids are usually normal or slightly increased, oestrogens and FSH normal and pregnanediol sometimes increased; the temperature curves are monophasic. The information afforded by vaginal smears and by endometrial biopsy is contradictory. The ovarian and the endocrine theories of explanation are discussed. Medical treatment and ovarian or hypophyseal treatment give variable results. Bilateral partial ovariectomy would appear to offer the best results. A separate place should be accorded to ACTH and cortisone, which constitute the modern treatment of this type of syndrome.
