T1  - Is unilateral ovariectomy reasonable?
T3  - L'ovariectomie unilaterale est-elle logique?
A1  - Pye A.
Y1  - 1954//
N2  - After a study of 24 unilateral ovariectomies it is concluded that (1) in 8 cases the pain, on account of which the operation was carried out, persisted or was aggravated; (2) in 10 cases hormonal disturbances developed, mostly of a hypo-oestrogenic type, with manifestations of early menopause. Several causes are mentioned: (1) Hypophyseal: the ovaries are submitted to increased gonadotrophic stimulation on account of hypophyseal hyperactivity, as only part of the ovarian parenchyma is able to respond to the hypophyseal stimulus. (2) Ovarian: insufficient or hyperactive ovaries. (3) Vascular: sclerosis as a result of insufficient vascularization of the parenchyma. It is insufficiently recognized that removal of an ovary may activate one of these causes, because it aggravates the hypophyseal-ovarian disequilibrium. Finally, the treatment of sclerocystic ovariitis should be as conservative as possible. In prophylaxis, arbitrary injections of oestrogen or gonadotrophic hormones should be avoided in every young woman. Therapy should be by hypophyseal inhibitors, especially testosterone, and by diathermy.
