T1  - Amenorrhea due to polycystic ovaries (Stein-Leventhal syndrome)
A1  - Klinefelter Jr. H.F.
A1  - Jones G.E.S.
Y1  - 1954//
N2  - 'Teaching Clinic' report. Two complete case reports are given. Diagnosis requires presence of bilaterally enlarged ovaries, menstrual irregularities and hirsutism. Sterility, enlarged clitoris and underdeveloped breasts may be associated. 17-Ketosteroids (17-KS) are usually within normal limits. Culdoscopy and/or gynaecography are preferred to exploratory laparotomy. If 17-KS are high, attempt further adrenal evaluation, excluding perirenal air because of inherent danger. Treatment is operative (bilateral wedge resection of ovaries) or medical (25 mg. cortisone twice daily to normal ovulation and suppression of elevated 17-KS). Thyroid, oestrogen and chorionic gonadotrophin are of little use. <ovid:br/>Discussion(s): cause unknown; only ovary involved, bilaterally; thickened, fibrotic capsule without evidence of inflammation: follicular cysts of all sizes, with abundant theca and scanty granulosa; minimal evidence of ovulation. Pregnanediol excretion high, but high progesterone level not proven. Pituitary and adrenal implication not proven. Wedge resection results in normal menstruation in 90% of patients, with fertility in 2/3 of sterile patients, with no results in hirsutism, obesity or clitoral involvement. Disease appears to be primarily ovarian.
