A1  - Kresnik Vl.
Y1  - 1954//
N2  - A rare cardiovascular anomaly was associated with other anomalies (micrognathia, horseshoe kidney, common mesentery, cystic ovaries, syndactylism, pes valgus and arthrogryposis) in a female, prematurely born child who died 3 days after birth. Autopsy revealed the following cardiovascular changes: (1) atrial hypoplasia (particularly of the left atrium); (2) constriction of the left atrioventricular ostium (almost pinpoint size); (3) aplasia of the mitral valves; (4) hypoplasia of the left ventricle; (5) relatively narrow aorta overriding an interventricular septum defect; the aorta devided into the brachiocephalic trunk, the left common carotid artery and the left subclavicular artery; (6) aplasia of the aortic arch; (7) a descending aorta inserted by a wide ductus arteriosus into the distended pulmonary artery; (8) abnormal atrial septum with a defect which was regarded as a secondary foramen ovale. The stenosis of the atrioventricular ostium is regarded as the primary anomaly causing the other cardiovascular anomalies. The atrial septal wall clearly showed 2 closely adherent septa; the right is the primary and the left the secondary septum. A table shows the gradual increase in the frequency of developmental anomalies in infants within the first year of life and over the period 1941-1951. and the predominance of cardiac anomalies.
