T1  - Wedge resection for polycystic ovaries. A critical analysis of 40 operations
A1  - Buxton C.L.
A1  - Van De Wiele R.
Y1  - 1954//
N2  - In reviewing 40 cases in which polycystic ovaries were found at laparotomy, and who were treated by wedge resection of the ovaries, the authors have attempted to determine whether polycystic ovaries occurred with all sorts of menstrual disturbances as well as amenorrhoea, and whether they constituted a coincidental finding in cases of extragenital endocrine disturbances such as adrenogenital syndrome. Of the 40 patients, 14 had amenorrhoea, 16 oligomenorrhoea, 7 menometrorrhagia, and 3 had regular cycle: 27 patients had hirsutism, and 14 were sterile. Of 28 patients who had menstrual abnormalities before operation, 20 were cured, 4 improved and 4 unaffected: of the 27 patients with hirsutism, 1 reverted to normal pattern, 4 became worse, and the remainder were unchanged. Four patients conceived after operation, but it is not stated whether they were previously sterile. Estimation of 17-ketosteroids in 26 cases showed normal levels in 23, and repeatedly high levels in 3 Administration of cortisone in 3 cases produced no change and it was assumed that the symptoms were not due to adrenal pathology. In all 3 cases normal ovulatory menses occurred after operation. Normal levels of FSH were found in the 8 cases investigated.
