AN  - 281415309
T1  - Premenstrual tension: A critical study of the syndrome
A1  - Mukherjee C.
Y1  - 1954//
N2  - In 74 cases of premenstrual tension the symptoms most commonly met with were headache, a feeling of tension, mastalgia and heaviness and stiffness of feet and hands, The syndrome was present in all age groups during reproductive life and seemed commoner in women in the higher social class, With the exception of endometriosis, organic gynaecological lesions were not more frequently present than in a control series, Eosinophilia was present in one-third of all cases, an increase in the eosinophil count occurring when the symptoms of tension developed. A low fasting blood sugar and an increased tolerance to carbohydrates was a frequent feature, The most significant metabolic change was abnormal water retention accompanied by a gain in weight in the premenstrual week, Premenstrual oliguria was followed by postmenstrual diuresis, When water retention was produced in normal subjects some of the symptoms of premenstrual tension developed in two-thirds of the patients, From a study of basal temperatures and the examination of vaginal smears it was deduced that absence or deficiency of progesterone was present in about two-thirds of all cases, Striking confirmation for this was provided by the detection of anovulatory menstruation in 51% and endometrial hyperplasia in a further 11,8% of the total, Salt deprivation alone resulted in improvement in two-thirds of cases where abnormal water retention was a prominent feature, Benefit was obtained by 3/4 of the patients treated by progesterone alone, Androgen therapy, however, produced disappointing results and water retention symptoms were actually aggravated in some instances, Most of the resistant cases were improved by the combined use of salt deprivation, injections of progesterone and antihistamine preparations.
