T1  - The benign syndrome of pain in the pelvic bones, muscles and joints during pregnancy (false surgical syndrome during pregnancy)
T3  - Le syndrome douloureux osteo-musculo articulaire abdomino-pelvien benin des femmes enceintes. (Quelques faux syndromes chirurgicaux au cours de la grossesse)
A1  - Lacomme M.
Y1  - 1954//
N2  - This syndrome - briefly referred to as 'painful pelvic syndrome' - is frequently seen in pregnant women, When marked, it may suggest serious affections such as appendicitis, ileus, torsion of a cyst, adnexitis, pyelitis, abortion and extra-uterine pregnancy, Milder forms, however, are seen in numerous pregnant women, who accept it as part of a normal pregnancy and often regard it as ischialgia. The pain is localized mainly in the lower abdomen and the lumbar region, Objective findings include typical pressure pain of the following localizations: (1) the posterior aspect of the pubic bone, lateral to the symphysis, (2) the ovarian region, , against the acctabulum and (3) the muscle mass of the levator ani muscle, Since these are the only symptoms, it is not difficult to differentiate the condition from the above-mentioned affections, which always involve other symptoms as well, The pathogenesis is still obscure; hypocalcaemia, it is pointed out, was seen in 60% of patients, Injections of a KCl solution (5-6 intravenous injections daily of 10 ml, of a 10% solution) were sometimes successful, as was oral administration, Local injections of procaine are rejected in view of the pain involved.
