T1  - Amenorrhoea due to vascular causes
T3  - Amenorreas de causa vascular
A1  - Vanrell-Cruells J.
Y1  - 1953//
N2  - The blood supply to the uterus and ovary may be disturbed by various pathological conditions causing amenorrhoea. The following causes are cited as factors which may alter the circulation: (1) general causes; heart disease, renal disease; (2) pathological conditions of the pelvis; parametritis, phlebitis (the spastic factor is of great importance in these cases), reflex vasospasm (due to emotional shock). These conditions cause ischaemia of the ovary, which, when it persists, alters the function of the ovary. A certain significance is attributed to the vascular factor in the pathogenesis of amenorrhoea with polycystic ovaries and Stein-Leventhal syndrome; (3) local changes, destruction of the endometrium by curettage, specific infections, functional vascular disturbances of the endometrium. Treatment is briefly reviewed. This paper is a review, including personal theories but no case reports.
