T1  - Variations of the coloured test for vitamin C during the menstrual cycle and at ovulation time
T3  - Variazioni della reazione colorata per l'acido ascorbico durante il ciclo mestruale e tempo di ovulazione
A1  - Manfredi P.
Y1  - 1953//
N2  - The test to determine the time of ovulation is based on the fact that vit C in excess of the requirements of the body is promptly excreted in the urine; an existing deficiency in the system must be corrected by administering vit. C. One tablet of dichlor-phenol-indo-phenol (Roche) is dissolved in 50 ml. of water; 5 ml. of the solution are pipetted into a beaker. Freshly voided urine is titrated quickly into this solution, and the quantity required to decolorize immediately the blue of this solution gives the quantity of vit. C present in the sample of urine. (Vit. C reduces dichlor-phenol-indo-phenol to its colourless leuco-derivative). The quantity of vit. C will be lowest on the day of ovulation, i.e., the quantity of urine required to decolorize the dye solution will be largest, and a marked increase will be noticed on the day. In anovulatory cycles, there is no marked increase, nor is this the case with male urine and that of climacteric women or during pregnancy, while in the multiovular cycles, there will be more than one rise.
