T1  - Cytochemical study of alkaline phosphatase in the endometrium
T3  - Estudio citoquimico de la fosfatasa alcalina en el endometrio
A1  - Galbis Pascual M.
Y1  - 1953//
N2  - The author studied 62 endometria: 42 normal ones in different periods of the cycle and the others belonging to anovulatory cycles. Alkaline phosphatase is found in the glandular and surface epithelium, and in the vessels, but never in the connective tissue. In the early proliferative phase it progressively increases in the glandular epithelium, attaining a maximum in the late proliferative, in the premenstrual and in the menstrual phases. In phosphatase located in the vessels, no cyclic modification can be detected. If the endometrium of anovulatory cycles is obtained during the period of amenorrhoea, a great quantity of the enzyme is observed in the glands; in the period of metrorrhagia it is absent from the glands, it remains in the vessel s without any substantial modification, although it may be irregularly distributed in some 50% of the cases, independently of the phase of the cycle. Evidently glandular phosphatase follows the same rising curve as the production of oestrogens during the cycle, inhibiting progesterone from coming into play. Phosphatase in the vessels does not possess any specific significance but shows the same picture as in all the vessels of the organism. The intervention of endometrial phosphatase in the synthesis of glycogen is a debatable point; the endometrial distribution of the latter follows an opposed course: absent in the proliferative phase, it is deposited at the height of the progesterone phase. The function of phosphatase is said to be to intervene in the endometrial proliferation stimulated by the oestrogens, by its catalytic action on anaerobic glucolysis proper to a tissue in proliferation; by its action on the lipid metabolism, which facilitates the liberation of choline and acetylcholine, and because in catalysing the degradation of the phospholipids it supplies the amount of phosphorus necessary for nucleic synthesis.
