T1  - Secondary dysmenorrhea
A1  - Falls F.H.
Y1  - 1953//
N2  - A dull ache generalized through the abdomen which persists throughout the entire menses and gradually disappears after the flow has ceased is characteristic of secondary dysmenorrhoea. Among the abnormal physiological states contributing to painful menstruation the author mentions pelvic vascular congestion, chronic pelvic inflammation, polycystic disease of the ovaries, endometriosis, adenomyosis, fibroids of the uterus, chronic cervicitis associated with uterosacral lymphangitis, and dorsal nerve route neuritis. Secondary dysmenorrhoea may be associated with lesions in the urinary tract. Chronic cystitis and abnormalities of the ureter are mentioned. Tuberculosis involving the pelvic organs may first manifest itself in the form of acquired dysmenorrhoea. Uterine displacement is a contributing factor in some cases. Severe dysmenorrhoea is seen in patients with rudimentary uteri and various congenital anomalies of the genital tract. In the discussion of this paper much emphasis is laid upon the psychosomatic factors contributing to painful menstruation. The usual array of clinical statistics is presented to support this concept.
