T1  - Transabdominal pneumoperitoneum as an aid in the diagnosis of sex-endocrine disturbances
A1  - Kunstadter R.H.
A1  - Guterman H.S.
A1  - Tulsky A.S.
Y1  - 1953//
N2  - The technique of this valuable aid to diagnosis is described. Usually 300 to 700 ml. carbon dioxide is introduced into the patient's peritoneal cavity. The patient is then X-rayed in such a position that the pelvic viscera can be outlined in the X-ray film. Sixteen cases between the ages of 1 and 23 were subjected to this investigation. Of these 7 had ovarian agenesis, 2 sexual precocity, 2 hypo-ovarianism, 1 cystic ovary, 1 hypopituitarism and 3 pseudohermaphroditism. The results were helpful in making a diagnosis in these cases. No untoward reaction to the treatment was noted. Such treatment, however, is undesirable if there is any likelihood of the patient having an intraperitoneal inflammation, bowel adhesions fixed to the parietal peritoneum at the site of abdominal puncture, cardiac or respiratory disability, or a systemic disturbance.
