AN  - 280948814
T1  - Use of the steroids and gonadotrophins in gynecology
A1  - Taylor Jr. H.C.
Y1  - 1953//
N2  - A summary and evaluation of specific indications for the use of steroids and gonadotrophins in gynaecology are presented. At least 3 kinds of error would invalidate the assumption that a sound rationale underlies a method of gynaecologic endocrine therapy: (1) The incorrect evaluation of the physiological mechanism of the disorder. (2) The assumption that response in women will be identical with that observed in experimental animals. (3) Failure of the clinician to grasp the real objective of his therapy. Two confusing factors make the evaluation of a therapeutic measure difficult: (1) Almost all gynaecological functional disorders are variable and subject to spontaneous remissions or relatively permanent cures. (2) Confusion of 'curative' with 'substitutional' therapy. Practical principles of therapy discussed included: decision on the physiologically indicated hormone; selection of the proper preparation and route of administration; determination of dosage and duration of therapy; timing in the menstrual cycle and in pregnancy; synergistic action of hormones and avoidance of complications. Indications for oestrogen therapy considered acceptable were menopausal symptoms and atrophic vaginitis. Probable occasional indications were functional metrorrhagia, amenorrhoea, oligomenorrhoea, anovulation with sterility and postpartum breast engorgement. Doubtful indications were dysmenorrhoea, abortion, pregnancy and diabetes, pregnancy and toxaemia, endometriosis, pruritus vulvae, adolescent acne, migraine, involutional melancholia and urinary incontinence. Indications for progesterone therapy considered acceptable were surgical excision of corpus luteum in early pregnancy. Probable occasional indications were metrorrhagia, amenorrhoea and 'inadequate' secretory phase. Doubtful indications were dysmenorrhoea, premenstrual tension, abortion, pregnancy and diabetes or toxaemia, breast adenosis, myoma uteri and cancer of cervix. No acceptable indications for androgens were noted. Probable indications were menopause with oestrogens contraindicated, metrorrhagia and menorrhagia, premenstrual breast pain, suppression of lactation and recurrent breast cancer. Doubtful indications were dysmenorrhoea, mid-cycle pain, endometriosis, frigidity, premenstrual tension and migraine. For gonadotrophin therapy no generally acceptable or probable occasional indications were noted. Doubtful indications were sterility due to anovulation (pituitary, equine, synergistic), inadequate secretory phase (chorionic), menorrhagia (chorionic, luteotropin), abortion (chorionic).
