T1  - The syndrome of hyperoestrogenism
T3  - Le syndrome d'hyperfolliculinie. Conceptions actuelles
A1  - Flamand Ch.
Y1  - 1953//
N2  - A parallel is drawn between this syndrome as described in France and the Stein-Leventhal syndrome and the opinion is expressed that the 2 are, in fact, one and the same condition. In a description of the classical features attention is drawn to 2 elements which are often overlooked - a moderate degree of goitre and virilism. These 2 phenomena suggest a pluriglandular rather than a specifically ovarian affection; they are evidence of thyroid participation and suprarenal hypercorticism (with a 17-ketosteroid figure just a little above normal). The morphology of women so affected is indicated and attention is drawn to the importance of endometrial biopsy, the examination of vaginal smears, study of the basal temperature curve and examination of vaginal mucus. In a discussion of the pathogenesis the points in favour of a true hyperoestrogenism are given as: (1) the experimental production of a syndrome in all respects similar to that seen in certain castrates following the administration of excessive doses of oestrogens or implantation; (2) the demonstrable correction of the HGK of the endometrium by administration of antagonists of oestrogen; and (3) comparison with the vaginal smears and biological assays. Against this, however, is the fact that estimation of phenolsteroids gives contradictory results. Aetiologically, an ovarian origin is certain only in the case of certain feminizing tumours. The most common causal condition would appear to be a hypophyseo-ovarian imbalance or possibly even a thalamo-pituitary dysharmony, and the effect on other endocrines is another point in support of this view. After various trials, the best treatment would appear to be a combination of androgens, chorionic gonadotrophins and synthetic steroids, androstanolone benzoate and methyl androstenediol dipropionate; androstenediol propionate appears to be less reliable.
