AN  - 280948492
T1  - Significance of correlations between sclerocystic oophoritis and the puerperium
T3  - Importance des relations entre ovarite sclerokystique et puerperalite
A1  - Pollosson M.
A1  - Notter A.
Y1  - 1953//
N2  - It would be preferable to avoid the word 'oophoritis' in this connection and to speak of sclerocystic ovaries, as the former term presupposes an inflammation, which is not always found. In practice the name covers 2 types of ovary: (1) slightly sclerotic but highly cystic; and (2) highly sclerotic but not cystic ovaries surrounded by a thick, grey tunica albuginea which gives them a porcelain-like appearance. The diagnosis sclerocystic ovaries has been made (and verified by operation) 30 times in 5 yr. in this clinic; 18 of these 30 women had had a confinement or abortion and in 8 the puerperium had been disturbed. The ages ranged from 23 to 35 yr. In 10 cases the sclerocystic ovaries were discovered by chance on the occasion of an operation for retroflexion of the uterus (7 cases), adnexitis (2) or myoma (1). In practically all cases conservative treatment was used, consisting of puncture of the cysts or thermocauterization. Only in 1 case was castration performed (on account of marked lesions of the uterus) and in 2 cases unilateral ovariectomy. The following conclusions are drawn: (1) True sclerocystic oophoritis has become rare since the victory over puerperal infections; (2) sclerocystic ovaries without inflammation are relatively frequent and occur both in cases of sterility and after childbirth. Large, congested ovaries often accompany retroflexion of the uterus. (3) The operative verification of sclerocystic ovaries confirms the clinical impression of enlarged ovaries in multiparae in the interval between pregnancies. Except for the rare condition of sclerocystic 'porcelain' ovary (Stein), which is generally accompanied by sterility, a pregnancy can occur and develop normally in cases of sclerocystic ovary after medical, hormonal, physical or surgical treatment of the ovaries themselves, their vascularization or the relations of the pelvic organs.
