T1  - Biology of the endometrium
T3  - Biologie van her baarmoederslijmvlies
A1  - Joossf L.A.
Y1  - 1953//
N2  - An attempt is made to interpret the changes occurring in the endometrium under the influence of the sex hormones in the light of modern data on cell biology. It is suggested that oestrone and progesterone can attach themselves in a characteristic manner to the surface of the cell. The grouping of these molecules determines the state of the cell at a given moment and the manner in which the enzymatic processes within it will run. A hypothesis is developed which resembles in some ways the hypotheses used since the time of Ehrlich to elucidate immunological reactions. As oesctrone and progesterone are very similar in their chemical structure, the author represents the molecule of oestrone as a cone with a concave base and that of progesterone as a cone of the same size but with a convex base. The cell is represented as a sphere. Oestrone is the true cell hormone: with their concave bases the oestrogen molecules fit nicely on the surface of the cell. Oestrone and progesterone do not combine with each other; they are present in the circulation as separate molecules and as such come into contact with the cells. Progesterone cannot attach itself to the surface of the cell; the only chance for the progesterone cones is to insert themselves, with the apex towards the cell, into the openings between the oestrone cones which cover the cell surface completely or partiaiiy; in the former case the sides of the progesterone cones will adhere to the sides of the oestrone cones, and in the latter case only a very imperfect adhesion will result, progesterone itself has no specific action on the cell, but if it forms part of a chain with oestrone molecules it can modify the metabolism of the cell and act, for instance, as a catalyst for processes set up in the cell by the action of oestrone. It is also pointed out that the metabolism in the functional layer of the endometrium is stimulated by progesterone, with anoxia of the tissues as a result. The marked tortuosity of the coiled arteries and dilatation of the venules are consequences of this anoxia. This favours local haemorrhages, e. g. under the influence of a drop of the hormone level. The fact that the menstrual haemorrhage is relatively small and of short duration, whereas the anovulatory bleeding is usually prolonged, is believed to be due to the presence in the endometrium in the 2nd stage of metabolic products which favour desquamation. It is suggested that the stroma cells during their development into decidual cells will demand a continually increasing amount of hormone. With a persistent corpus luteum, bleeding will finally occur. Only the chorionic villi of the developing ovum can keep up with this increasing demand for hormones. With the aid of this theory the author succeeds in offering an acceptable explanation of all kinds of endometrial changes such as decidua formation, delayed irregular shedding, 'medical curettage', menstruation, endome trial hyperplasia, dysmenorrhoea membranacea, etc.
