T1  - Fern figures in the cervical mucus
T3  - Las figuras de helecho en el moco cervical
A1  - Yanez A.
A1  - Crisosto C.
A1  - Saavedra R.
Y1  - 1953//
N2  - The intensity of crystallization is directly proportional to the oestrogenic activity. The crystals may disappear as a result of the action of progesterone or a more or less rapid decrease of oestrogen activity. The variations in crystallization of the mucus during the menstrual cycle coincide with the variations in basal temperature, vaginal smears and endometrial biopsy; the information obtained from the cervical mucus is even regarded as more conclusive than that furnished by the basal temperature and vaginal smears, enabling rational interpretation of the actions of oestrogens and progesterone. When, the menstrual cycle is normal, crystallization usually appears on the 7th-8th day and shows an increase in intensity, attaining its maximum during the period of ovulation and subsequently decreasing and disappearing during the 17th-22nd day of the cycle. Crystallization persists until the appearance of the menstrual flow or just about this time in anovulatory cycles. Obvious crystallization in cases of amenorrhoea excludes pregnancy, as it is evidence of a sufficient oestrogenic action. No fern figures are observed during the first 3 months of pregnancy, which fact may be used in establishing an early diagnosis. Even a slight crystallization is evidence of an insufficient progesterone activity and therefore of the possible danger of a spontaneous abortion.
