T1  - Use of steroids and gonadotrophins in gynaecology
T3  - Uso de los esteroides y gonadotropinas en ginecologia
A1  - Taylor Jr. H.C.
Y1  - 1953//
N2  - The indications for treatment with sex hormones are divided into acceptable or hardly questionable, occasional and presumptive and doubtful. According to this classification the menopause and atrophic vaginitis are acceptable indications for treatment with oestrogens, while functional metrorrhagia, amenorrhoea and oligomenorrhoea, anovulation and post-partum mammary congestion are occasional presumptive indications. The other indications are doubtful. The clinical condition following surgical excision of the corpus luteum in pregnancy is regarded as an acceptable indication for treatment with progesterone, while anovulatory metrorrhagia, amenorrhoea and the stage of 'inadequate' secretory phase are occasional presumptive indications. The other conditions are doubtful indications, There are no completely acceptable indications for treatment with androgens; presumptive indications are the menopause in which treatment with oestrogens: contraindicated, menorrhagia and metrorrhagia, premenstrual pain in the breast, suppression of lactation and treatment of recurrent carcinoma of the breast. The other indications are doubtful. For the time being there are no acceptable indications for treatment with gonadotrophins; nor are there occasional presumptive indications, though there are some doubtful ones, such as sterility due to anovulation, inadequate secretory phase, menorrhagia and the prevention of abortion.
