T1  - Cortisone in treatment of the hirsute woman
A1  - Greenblatt R.B.
Y1  - 1953//
N2  - Distinction is made between pituitary, adrenal and ovarian hirsutism; it is emphasized that several organs may be the primary localization of a given clinical picture, e.g. Cushing's syndrome (pituitary and the adrenals) and the Stein-Leventhal syndrome (pituitary gland - excess of LSH; the adrenals - postnatal adrenogenitalism; the ovaries - hyperthecosis). Cortisone was used in the treatment of 27 hirsute women (oral administration, as a rule of a daily dose of 50 mg.). Treatment was instituted in some cases by intramuscular administration of 100 mg. cortisone and in other cases by implantation of 6 pellets of 100 mg. each. The patients received a high-protein, low-fat and low-carbohydrate diet. The NaCl intake was reduced, instead of which 325 mg. potassium chloride was given thrice daily; 30 mg. thyroid extract daily was given in addition. Distinction is made between 4 groups of patients, viz.: 15 with amenorrhoea, 6 with irregular menstruation. 4 with regular menstruation and 2 hysterectomized women. Treatment had an unmistakably favourable effect on the cyclic ovarian function. Treatment was but brief in 2 of the 15 cases of amenorrhoea; 2 showed no improvement; 8 showed a larger number of ovulations and 3 an increase in the number of anovulatory haemorrhages. Only 4 showed some improvement of hirsutism. Of the 6 cases of irregular menstruation, 2 remained uninfluenced and 4 showed an increased frequency of ovulations; only 1 showed some improvement of hirsutism. Hirsutism was slightly improved in 1 of the 4 women with regular menstruation. Both the hysterectomized women showed some improvement in hirsutism. It is contended that there is as yet no completely satisfactory explanation of the ability of cortisone to cause ovulations in some hirsute amenorrhoeic patients. Cortisone decreases the 17-ketosteroid excretion and probably not only inhibits the production of ACTH. but also alters the activity of the pituitary in such a manner that a considerable quantity of gonadotrophic hormone is liberated. It is contended that excessive androgen production may be attributable to ovarian hyperthecosis (excessive luteinization), to the adrenal cortex or to both sources. The effectivity of cortisone, ovariectomy or a combination of both then depends on the source of the androgens. In one case of marked hirsutism in a woman of 28 showing alternation of amenorrhoea and menorrhagia, cortisone treatment led to a decrease in 17-ketosteroid excretion from 25 to 15 mg. per 24 hr. The patient had an adeno-acanthoma. Panhysterectomy was performed. The ovaries were large, white and smooth, as seen in the Stein-Leventhal syndrome. The 17-ketosteroid excretion subsequently decreased to 5 mg./24 hr., and increased to about 10 mg./24 hr. after discontinuation of cortisone treatment. This would seem to suggest that the ovaries were responsible for the increased excretion of 17-ketosteroids in this case. This is probably true for many cases of hirsutism.
