T1  - Carcinoma in the period of sexual activity
T3  - Corpuscarcinom in der geschlechtsreife fundus
A1  - Husslein H.
A1  - Schuller E.
Y1  - 1952//
N2  - The authors start from the hypothesis that without oestrogenic hormone i.e. without proliferation of the endometrium, there can be no fundus carcinoma. The follicular hormone itself is not carcinogenic, it is simply an indispensable prerequisite for this carcinoma. It is therefore surprising that fundus carcinoma is incomparably more frequent in the menopause, with its normally lower hormonal levels, than in the period of sexual activity. The fact that the figures given in the literature vary from 0.56% to 13% testifies to the difficulties of diagnosis. Not infrequently an incorrect diagnosis of fundus carcinoma is made instead of the condition - which has only recently become known - of 'atypical hyperplasia'. This the authors demonstrate in part directly and in part from deductions by analogy based on personal investigations. They deal with a total of 501 cases of fundus carcinoma over 1925-46. Only 11 (2.2%) occurred during the period of sexual maturity; on critical reconsideration, however, it appeared that 8 of these cases had to be regarded as cervix carcinoma or atypical hyperplasia, leaving only 3 cases (0.59%) of true fundus carcinoma at the age of sexual activity. The histories (in all 3 cases there was a history of months or years of characteristic disturbances of the cycle of anovulatory or hyperplastic type) lend support to the idea that fundus carcinoma in the period of sexual maturity can only occur if the oestrogenic hormone can act for a long time on the mucosa without the interrupting effect of progesterone, i.e., if a condition exists which corresponds to that normally present only in the dimacterium. The extreme difficulty of histological distinction between fundus carcinoma and atypical hyperplasia is discussed In doubtful cases one should not operate too hastily but should consider the diagnostic and therapeutic possibilities of testosterone treatment in high dosage. It is known from experience that this causes regression of atypical hyperplasia, whereas no influence on a carcinoma can be expected, in operation on a carcinoma, the ovaries must also be removed, not so much as bearers of metastases as on account of their hormone-forming properties.
