T3  - Die bedeutung des histologischn glylcoeennachweises im endomecrium fur die beurteilung des cyclischen geschehens im
A1  - Augustin E.
Y1  - 1952//
N2  - The endomecrium was examined with glycogen staining in 76 cases, after operations in which the ovaries could be reliably examined (by inspection or histologically) for the presence of corpora lutea. Glycogen formation is a sign of a diphasic process in the ovary, it probably does not occur before a follicle is ready to rupture. In one rase in which a well-formed corpus luteum, as in a normal cycle, was present, some glands were found to be secreting well while others were entirely without secretion. In many cases corpora lutea undergoing vasculari zation were observed, while the endometrium showed only traces of glycogen and the other signs of pregravid transformation were also incomplete. These findings suggest that the functional sluggishness or inferiority lies in the endometrium. Examination of fragments of mucosa may, under some conditions, lead to an incorrect conclusion that an anovulatorv cvcle is present.
