T1  - Fundus carcinoma in the period of sexual activity
T3  - Corpuscarcinom in der geschlechtsreife
A1  - Husslein H.
A1  - Schuller E.
Y1  - 1952//
N2  - This is a series of 501 cases of fundus carcinoma over 1925-46. Only 11 (2.2%) occureed during the period of sexual maturity; on critical reconsideration, however, it appeared that 8 of these cases had to be regarded as cervix carcinoma or 'atypical hyperplasia', leaving only 3 cases (0.59%) of true fundus carcinoma at the age of sexual activity. The histories (in all 3 cases there was a history of months or years of characteristic disturbances of the cycle of anovulatory or hyperplastic type) lend support to the idea that fundus carcinoma in the period of sexual maturity can only occur if the oestrogenic hormone can act for a long time on the mucosa without the interrupting effect of progesterone, i.e. if a condition exists which corresponds to that normally present only in the climacterium. The extreme difficulty of histological distinction between fundus carcinoma and atypical hyperplasia is discussed. In doubtful cases one should not operate to hastily but should consider the diagnostic and therapeutic possibilities of testosterone treatment in high dosage. It is known from experience that this causes regression of atypical hyperplasia, whereas no influence on a carcinoma can be expected. In operation on a carcinoma, the ovaries must also be removed, not so much as bearers of metastases as on account of their hormone-forming properties.
