AN  - 280894583
T1  - Senile endometrial byperplasia and its origin
T3  - U ber die senile Hyperplasie des Endometriums und ihre Genese
A1  - Dhom G.
Y1  - 1952//
N2  - Among 23 cases of uterine haemorrhage in women aged 60-75, there were 23 of senile hyperplasia not associated with ovarian tumours. In all cases, cystic glands were found, white the endometrial stroma was involved in the hyperplasia. Ovarian tumours were found in 5 cases. In 4 of these, granulosa-cell tumour or theca-cell tumour was excluded with certainty. In the 5th case, the nature of the tumour was not determined as the patient died of an intercurrent disease (no autopsy). In 4 cases hyperplasia was only visible at the glands, which, however, showed no cystic distension as yet. The characteristic stromal changes were not found. It is contended that in these cases the causative agent had not yet exerted its influence long enough. In 2 cases the ovarian hilus showed foci with a diameter of some 1 mm., with wide, thin-walled capillaries. These foci consisted of fairly large cells with foam-like protoplasm, which absorbed little dyestuft and showed round nuclei of a dark colour. In both cases the ovaries were polycystic. These foci of hilar cells (closely resembling the cellular foci described in ovarian thecosis) probably secrete a substance activating the ovarian parenchyma (cyst formation). The hormone produced by the ovarian parenchyma probably causes endometrial hyperplasia. An adrenocortical influence is not excluded. Strikingly, cure was in nearly all cases obtained by simple curettage. Uterine carcinoma was found in 2 cases. These growths probably developed on the basis of senile endometrial hyperplasia.
