T1  - Clinical delimitation and pathogenesis of hyperfolliculinism
T3  - Essai de delimitation clinique et pathogenique de l'hyperfoiliculinie
A1  - Flamand C.
A1  - Simon J.
Y1  - 1952//
N2  - The authors discuss in an exhaustive study the so-called hyperfolliculinic syndrome (syn: hypophyso-ovarian dysharmony - hyper-oestrogenism - Stein-Leventhal syndrome - premenstrual tension etc.) Clinical signs are: abdominal and sacral pains -menstrual troubles - sexual disturbances - pain in the breast - hyperplasia of the thyroid and hirsutism. Endometrial biopsy shows the preponderance of oestrogens. Three phenotypes can be described: Cbesity coexisting with hyperfolliculinism. Hyperfolliculinism without obesity. Epheboid hyperfolliculinism. Cervical mucus is very abundant at ovulation time. Vaginal simears are of value but must be taken during the whole menstrual cycle. A basal temperature curve is of value for diagnosis of ovulation. From 102 cases studied the authors believe that hyperfolliculinism is a pluriglandular syndrome (hyperactivity of the ovaries, the thyroid and the suprarenal glands). The main feature of the pluriglandular dysfunction seems to be a diencephalo-pituitary instability.
