T1  - The events of the primate ovarian cycle
A1  - Corner G.W.
Y1  - 1952//
N2  - Delivered as the 21st Huxley Lecture, this article is a summary review of the currently known patterns of the two basic events in the cycle of every mammalian female, namely, maturation and discharge of the ovarian follicle, by which the corpus luteum is formed and the progestational phase of the reproductive cycle initiated, and retrogression of the corpus luteum bringing that phase to an end. A strange difference exists in the outward expression of these two events of the cycle between the human species and other mammals. In the latter, ovulation makes itself evident by the excitement of oestrus, allowing accurate detection of that critical event. In the human female, ovulation is not marked by any reliable observable sign but the conclusion of the corpus luteum phase is denoted by the conspicuous event of menstruation. The latter phenomenon, occurring only in higher primates, is also notable in slightly altered form in two other mammals, the platyrrhine monkeys and the elephant shrew. Sexual activity in lower mammals is closely bound to the ovarian cycle, the female accepting the male during oestrus only. This is not so apparent in female monkeys and apes who may, and often do, accept the male at all times of the cycle. In the human female it is difficult to assess sexual rhythmicity because it is so largely controlled by psychological factors. In studies of the human sexual cycle, most investigators agree that any tendency to maximal responsiveness is related to menstruation, rather than ovulation, an inefficient biological arrangement, one contrary to that observed in animals. Such observations suggest that in women sex arousal is not under endocrine control but is probably subordinate to neuropsychological factors. The rate of follicle maturation is rapid in the commonly observed laboratory animals, including the rhesus monkey. By certain indirect evidences, vaginal smears and gonadotrophin assays, it appears to be a matter of a few days from follicle enlargement to ovulation. There is as yet no certain, simple, convenient test for human ovulation available. Moreover, there is an unpredictability of whole ovarian cycle which makes the standard 28-day cycle length merely a statistical mode. There are not only variations in the rate of follicle growth and maturation, but there are significant variations in the rate of retrogression of the corpus luteum. Viewing all of these and considering the additional puzzle of anovulatory cycles, it is apparent that the ovarian cycle is a biological activity of extremely complex nature. How much of this should be attributed to the domination of nervous and mental processes is problematical.
