T1  - Anovulatory cycles
T3  - Anovulatoriska cyklar
A1  - Bergman P.
Y1  - 1952//
N2  - In a series of 188 cases submitted to diagnostic curettage on the 1st to the 3rd menstrual day, anovulation was noted in 4.3%. Anovulatory cycles were commonest in the beginning and at the end of reproductive life. About half of the women with anovulatory cycles presented the clinical picture of hypo-oligo-menorrhoea. In 28.8% of the entire series the women showed one and the same clinical picture. The series included 137 women who sought help for sterility. Only 4 of them showed evidence of anovulation. In cases with anovulatory cycles the following types of therapy were tried: chorionic gonadotrophin (Pregnyl), thyroid extract, and surgical intervention with wedge resection of the ovaries. Most of the cases with anovulatory cycles responded to chorionic gonadotrophin therapy, but in some instances it was not until they had been treated with thyroid extract. In the absence of a favourable response to hormone therapy, wedge resection of the ovaries seems to be indicated, because in some refractory cases this operation was followed by normal ovulatory cycles, and in 1 case the woman became pregnant.
