T1  - Significance of histological detection of glycogen in the endometrium for the judgement of cyclic events in the ovary
T3  - Die bedeutung des histologischen glykogennachweises im endometrium fur die beurteilung des cyclischen geschehens im ovar
A1  - Augustin E.
Y1  - 1952//
N2  - The endometrium was examined with glycogen staining in 76 cases, after operations in which the ovaries could be reliably examined (by inspection or histologically) for the presence of corpora lutea. Glycogen formation is a sign of a diphasic process in the ovary, it probably does not occur before a follicle is ready to rupture. In one case in which a well-formed corpus luteum, as in a normal cycle, was present, some glands were found to be secreting well while others were entirely without secretion. In many cases corpora lutea undergoing vascularization were observed, while the endometrium showed only traces of glycogen and the other signs of pregravid transformation were also incomplete. These findings suggest that the functional sluggishness or inferiority lies in the endometrium. Examination of fragments of mucosa may, under some conditions, lead to an incorrect conclusion that an anovulatory cycle is present.
