T1  - A simple test for the determination of ovulation, estrogen activity, and early pregnancy using the cervical mucus secretion. A preliminary report
A1  - Roland M.
Y1  - 1952//
N2  - Papanicolaou demonstrated that when the cervical mucus is spread on a glass slide and allowed to dry, a certain form of crystallization with arborization takes place, this most abundant at about the time of ovulation. The absence of this 'fernlike' phenomenon at the time of ovulation is said to indicate mucus with poor sperm penetration qualities as reported by Compos du Paz in 1950. The author found the 'fernlike phenomenon' from the 5th to 22nd day of the cycle in 20 normal females. After the 20th day and before the fifth a cellular type of pattern prevailed. In 30 infertile patients with known anovulatory cycles the cervical smear showed persistent 'fernlike structure' up to the onset of menstrual bleeding. In women from 45 to 65 years of age, all with menopausal symptoms, no sign of this 'fernlike structure' was found until after high dosages of oestrogens were given. In a group of 300 pregnant women all those pregnant less than three months showed no typical fern pattern, but only cellular elements closely grouped together.
