A1  - McCutchen G.T.
A1  - Kinder E.C.
Y1  - 1951//
N2  - Eighteen proved cases and one suspected case of bilateral polycystic ovaries, collected during the past 4 years, are reported. Bilateral wedge resection of the ovaries, in which approximately one-half of the ovarian tissue is removed, apparently tends to disrupt a vicious circle. The theory of Weed and Collins, based on experiments with rabbits, according to which the follicular atresia is due to changes in the blood supply resulting from ovarian prolapse, is adhered to. After operation only 3 of 9 women who had complained of sterility became pregnant. Since some women were operated on only a short time previously, more favourable results may perhaps still be obtained. In 2 cases the operation did not produce permanent improvement. Six women were affected with severe and 2 with mild headaches, usually showing a frontal localization. These headaches, which are already severe on wakening and which invariably are more severe at the time the patient should normally menstruate, are considered a symptom to be included in the clinical picture. Only three women were obese and none of the patients showed hypoplasia of the breasts.
