T1  - Hirsutism and hypertrichosis in women with cyclical bleeding
A1  - Holmer A.J.M.
Y1  - 1951//
N2  - In women exhibiting abnormal hairgrowth cyclical bleeding can be either ovulatory or anovulatory. The latter cases can be considered as belonging to the Stein-Leventhal syndrome. After wedge-resection of the ovaries the patients showed biphasic cycles, and some became pregnant. The hypertrichosis remained unchanged. The author thinks that an overproduction of FSH results in the development of several follicles, and that an excess of prolactine provokes luteinization before ovulation can take place. The luteinized tissues produce testosterone instead of progesterone. When there is a sufficient amount of oestrogenic hormone to counteract the testosterone, no hirsutism develops, but the prolactine inhibits the formation of FSH, and the oestrogen-levels drop. This explains the involution of the endometrial and mammary tissues. When the levels drop to a very low grade, amenorrhoea and hirsutism can develop.
