T1  - Sclero-cystic oophoritis
T3  - Ovarite sclero-kystique
A1  - Malinas
A1  - Bory R.
Y1  - 1951//
N2  - The prevailing aetiological explanation for sclerocystic ovaries is hypersecretion of gonadotrophins giving rise to hypersecretion of oestrogens, and causing cystic hyperplasia of the endometrium. (amenorrhoea followed by menorrhagia), blocking of ovulation (sterility), and hyperexcitability of the uterine muscle (dysmenorrhoea). This theory is based on the fact that administration of gonadotrophins gives rise to massive development of follicles (though not to cystic atresia), and increased excretion of gonadotrophins in the presence of the disease. Sclero-cystic ovaries are physiological at puberty and in the menopause; persisting follicles have not always a pathological effect; the only admissible pathology is the arrest of cyclical function. Clinically, primary amenorrhoea is seldom permanent; though medical treatment is disappointing, ovariectomy should never be contemplated. Menorrhagia accompanying cystic ovaries should be treated medically, unless their size warrants surgery, which should be as conservative as possible. Surgery is certainly not indicated in cases where ovulation is partially or totally blocked, and ovariectomy should not be performed in the course of presacral neurectomy for relief of dysmenorrhoea.
