N2  - This affection is believed to be due to anatomical, mechanical, dystrophic and consbtutional factors, combining to produce a clinical picture which is chiefly subjective and functional and does not correspond to the objective findings. A study of the pathology of 100 cases (out of a total of 293) showed special characteristics which give the syndrome an anatomical unity. Treatment was based on 3 methods: subperitoneal resection of the lumbo-ovarian vasculo-nervous trunk, cuneiform resection of the ovary and hysteropexy. In the majority of cases this was combined with obliteration of Douglas' pouch, and sometimes elimination of the plica vesico-uterina. In cases where 'hypogastric plexalgia' was suspected, presacral resection was done. There were 11 failures and 16 partial improvements out of 293 cases. Pregnancy occurred 36 times in 25 patients after operation.
