T1  - Clinical considerations of benign ovarian cystomas
A1  - Randall C.L.
A1  - Hall D.W.
Y1  - 1951//
N2  - Preservation of ovarian tissue by resection is more desirable than oophorectomy, and prophylactic oophorectomy is unwarranted when neoplasms are benign. Whether this is unwise was studied of 1,112 women operated on for ovarian tumours from 1931 to 1947. Haemorrhagic follicular or luteal 'cystic ovaries' were excluded. Also excluded were 180 malignant ovarian tumours and 49 tumours classified as potentially malignant. The latter group included teratomas, granulosa cell tumours and dysgerminomata. The ovarian tumour most frequently encountered was the chocolate cyst associated with endometriosis (294 cases). Unilocular simple cystomas multilocular cyscadenomas, and dermoids totalled 526 cases. There were 50 fibromes, 8 fibroadenomyomas and 5 Brenner tumours. In 176 patients observed for 5 or more years, there was a 2.3% incidence of pathological change in the remaining ovary. Four required re-operation for benign tumours in the preserved 'other' ovaries. The incidence of bilateral benign ovarian cystomas or the ultimate incidence of ovarian malignancy does not warrant the removal of an contralateral normal-appearing ovary merely as a prophylactic measure. Careful inspection, palpation and bisection of the opposite ovary is, however, often necessary before it can be regarded as normal and uninvolved. There were 80 cystadenomas exhibiting grossly papillary linings, 16 with a pseudomucinous and 64 with a serous content. Three of the serous cystomas, all 3 multilocular, papillary and occurring bilaterally, recurred as malignant tumours. The clinical course was benign in the other 77. Resection of the ovary should be considered more often and oophorectomy employed less as a routine in the management of benign ovarian cystomas. There has been no evidence in this study to suggest the recurrence of an ovarian neoplasm in the ovarian tissue remaining after resection of a benign cystoma. When ovarian tumours are discovered in women over 50 yr. of age, 40% prove to be benign. Preoperative irradiation administered merely because of the presence of an ovarian tumour is not advisable.
