T1  - Menstruation and other forms of functional bleeding
T3  - Over menstruatie en andere functionele bloedingen
A1  - Joose L.A.
Y1  - 1951//
N2  - An attempt is made to elucidate the mechanism of menstruation and other forms of functional bleeding by means of endometrial biopsy. In anovulatory bleeding, various types of mucosa are found - usually hypertrophic, as a sign of increased proliferation, but sometimes atrophic. In menstrual bleeding the action of progesterone on the glands (secretion) and on the stroma (decidual changes) predominates. Further, however, there is a very fine fragmentation of the tissue (dissociation) and a diffuse infiltiation with leucocytes (leucodiapedesis). In anovulatory bleeding the 2 last-mentioned features are absent as a rule. After the conclusion of a treatment with chorionic gonadotrophin ('pregnyl') or with progesterone for a short period, however, a mucosal type appeared in which, despite the absence of secretion and decidual changes, there were both dissociation and leucodiapedesis, i.e. characteristics of a menstrual bleeding. Since bleeding is a vascular phenomenon, it must be concluded that the small blood vessels react even to a very slight progesterone influence of short duration, while the stroma and the glands do not yet react. It also appears that the highly tortuous course of the coiled arteries, as normally seen during the secretion phase of an ovulatory cycle, is not necessary for the occurrence of menstrual bleeding.
