T1  - The constitutional factor in cancer of the corpus uteri and its clinical utilization
T3  - O fator constitucional no cancer do corpo uterino e sua utilizacao na clinica
A1  - De Souza Rudge W.
Y1  - 1951//
N2  - In this connection a study has been made of (1) heredity; (2) co-existence of characters suggestive of a tendency to cancer and (3) changes and (4) environmental factors which may lead to cancer. Gray pointed out that women with cancer of the corpus uteri are generally fatter and heavier than those with cancer of the cervix. An increased proportion of cases of cancer of the corpus occurs in patients with a disturbed climacterium with copious haemorrhage, indicating a relationship between this form of cancer and substances stimulating genital growth, especially oestrogens. An increased incidence of glandular hyperplasia of the endometrium is often noted, although retarded menopause, increased incidence of sterility, anovulation etc. are also factors of endocrine imbalance. A difficult clinical problem is the treatment of cases in which endometrial biopsy shows atypical hyperplasia. Novak is of the opinion that such hyperplasias are divisible into 2 groups, one not justifying radical treatment and the other calling for active measures to avoid possible transformation into a true cancer. It is therefore considered that an atypical hyperplasia in a patient with the above-mentioned morphological and clinical characteristics constitutes an authorization for prophylactic hysterectomy.
