T1  - Bilateral poly cystic ovaries, the Stein syndrome
A1  - Leventhal M.L.
A1  - Cohen M.R.
Y1  - 1951//
N2  - The syndrome of Stein, bilateral polycystic ovaries, is reviewed completely, including theories of its pathogenesis, methods of diagnosis, and pathology. Hyperplasia of the theca interna, frequently associated with the polycystic state, may be an explanation for the symptoms of amenorrhoea and hirsutism. The thecal cells are the source of steroid hormones which, in this syndrome, may be produced in abnormal quantitative variations. During a 4-year period, 1945-48, 10 patients with bilateral polycystic ovaries were operated upon by members of the gynaecological staff of the Michael Reese Hospital. The small number of such cases is emphasized wih the viewpoint of stressing the need for careful selection of the patients for the recommended wedge-shaped resection.
