AN  - 281607023
T1  - The syndrome of large, pale ovaries and its differentiation from adrenogenital syndrome and Cushing's disease
A1  - Greenblatt R.B.
Y1  - 1951//
N2  - Ten patients with the Stein-Leventhal syndrome showed feminine characteristics, both mentally and physically. All had hirsutism, some to a very marked degree, but no other signs of masculinization were present. All had amenorrhoea or menorrhagia after periods of amenorrhoea. The endometrium showed signs of hyperplasia in most cases; only once was a secretory phase observed. All patients had large, pale ovaries, showed abiotrophy on histological examination. Only one recent corpus luteum was found. 17-Ketosteroids were normal in 7 and slightly high in 3. 11-Hydroxycorticosteroids were normal or low in the 7 cases in which they were determined. Urinary gonadotrophins were high (4 cases) or normal (3). LH was found in 2 cases but not in a 3rd. Wedge-resection of the ovary is the best treatment for this condition, but it does not favourably influence the hirsutism. Differential diagnosis is required from the adrenogenital syndrome, by which the author understands only the true masculinization resulting from hyperactivity of the corticosexual group of adrenal hormones. He believes that this syndrome can also be stimulated by masculinizing ovarian tumours. This syndrome is often the antithesis of that of Cushing. Proteins are preserved by the corticosteroids, instead of being converted into carbohydrates. The carbohydrate metabolism is not disturbed as a rule. The 'infant Hercules' is not seen. If the disease develops in an adult woman, hirsutism, lowering of pitch of the voice and/or enlargement of the clitoris are seen. The muscular power is increased. 17-Ketosteroids amount to 40-150 mg., sometimes even 1,000 mg. or higher. 11-Hydroxycorticosteroids are normal as a rule. In cases of adrenal cortex tumour the s-ketosteroids are generally increased, but not in adrenal hyperplasia. The pyelogram shows distorsion of the calyces and displacement and rotation of the kidney. The treatment is adrenalectomy. The adrenogenital syndrome is primarily a disturbance in the sexual sphere. Cushing's disease is a metabolic disease in which the chief physiological disturbance is hypergluconeogenesis. The affection of the adrenal cortex is secondary, although important. Other features are negative nitrogen balance and pronounced accumulation of fat, with marked loss of protein owing to its conversion to sugar (due to excess of 17-hydroxycorticosterone). Hirsutism is found in Cushing's disease, but no clitoris hypertrophy or changes of voice. The 17-ketosteroids are normal or slightly high; 11-hydroxycorticosteroids high. The fasting eosinophil count is generally below 100 (Thorn test). Treatment is surgical if an enlarged adrenal or an adenoma is found. As regards endocrine therapy, oestrogens are not very successful. Androgens have more effect, although this seems paradoxical for a woman with hirsutism.
