AN  - 280604136
T1  - Ovulation after pregnancy
A1  - Sharman A.
Y1  - 1951//
N2  - The study supports the impression that 2 factors are involved in the postpartum resumption of ovulation, namely, one concerned with the process of ovulation itself and the other with the coordination of ovulation with menstruation. In regard to the first factor, the author's evidence indicates that ovulation does not occur during the first 6 weeks post partum and that the first ovulation occurs in connection with either a 5th or a 7th menstruation. In regard to the coordination between ovulation and menstruation, it was noted that the first menstruation was of the anovulatory type with much greater frequency than the succeeding menstruations. In addition, the author uncovered 3 ovulations which were not associated with menstruation. The material also indicates that the general effect of lactation appears to be to retard the postpartum resumption of ovulation. The study concludes with a comparison of postpartum ovulations with ovulation occurring after spontaneous abortions and ectopic pregnancy. In each of the latter 2, ovulation seems to occur earlier than it does following term pregnancy.
