T1  - The elderly primigravida. A thirtheen year review
A1  - Hawkins R.J.
A1  - Foley Jr. W.E.
A1  - Tierney T.M.
Y1  - 1951//
N2  - The elderly primigravida has been arbitrarily defined as the one who attains the age of 35 years and subsequently delivers her first term pregnancy. The capacity for becoming pregnant diminishes rapidly after the age of 35. Anovulatory cycles become more frequent and other evidence of ovarian failure is apparent in many women. A series of 383 elderly primigravidas is presented. In those cases in whom the pregnancies came to term without severe complications there was little difficulty with vaginal delivery. The number of toxaemias was significantly increased as a result of the process of aging and prolonged labours were common, while the number of operative deliveries and the incidence of postpartum haemorrhage increased. 66% of the patients were delivered through the birth canal either spontaneously or with minima] surgical aid. There is a tendency to increase the number of caesarean sections done in the upper age brackets though the operation carries a very definite mortality, 2 deaths in these series being so caused. The incidence of medical complications such as cardiac disease, tb, and diabetes did not differ greatly from that encountered among younger women. Foetal mortality was 2.6% which is only slightly higher than the general hospital average of 2.2%. The elderly primigravida does not present the formidable obstetrical risk that is su often feared.
