AN  - 280467066
T1  - The effect of adoption on fertility and other reproductive functions
A1  - Hanson F.M.
A1  - Rock J.
Y1  - 1950//
N2  - Physicians and laymen have long thought that it is quite common for couples who have previously been childless to have a child of their own following adoption. That psychogenic disturbances play an important role in reproductive physiology and may influence conception is an interesting theory. A study of 202 couples who adopted children between 1938 and 1948 is reported. Eighty-five of these 202 couples were studied as to the aetiology of their own infertility. Pregnancies had occurred in 15 of the 202 couples. Eleven of these 15 couples were studied as to the cause of the presumed infertility and how it was relieved. Of the 85 couples, 74 adopted because of childlessness, 2 because of a limited number of natural children already in the home, 4 because of neonatal deaths, 3 because of constitutional disease in the wife and one because of psychological disturbance. Thirty-five of the 85 couples reported pregnancies prior to adoption that failed to reach term. Forty-five of the 85 had submitted to operations in the treatment of their infertility or existing pathology. Occupation had no effect on fertility in any instance. In 15 the wife had been sterilized or the husband was azoospermic. Following adoption 19 of the 85 couples reported loss of premenstrual and menstrual discomfort, lengthening of the cycle or improved regularity in menstruation. Twenty-two couples reported improved sexuality. Two reported less interest in intercourse. Since only 15, or 8%, of the 202 adoptive parents achieved a subsequent pregnancy, the authors conclude that adoption is not followed by normal pregnancy to any remarkable degree. From statistical surveys 10% of spontaneous cures is to be expected. Eleven of the fifteen pregnancies fall within the 85 couples on whom detailed studies were made. Of these eleven, 5 couples had uncompleted pregnancies prior to adoption. In 2 of these 5 there was oligospermia, and also presumably in the other 3 cases. Spontaneous cures in habitual abortion and oligospermia without adoption are not uncommon. It is concluded that in these 5 cases, adoption is not the curative factor. One case of infertility was due to a juvenile uterus and anovulation. Adoption may have resulted in more regular ovulation, but there is no proof of this. Four couples with pregnancy occurring soon after adoption and in whom there was possibly a psychogenic factor, attributed their normal pregnancy to adoption, which acted, as they described it, by relief from mental strain connected with childlessness. There seem to be no significant physiological factors on which changes in menstruation and sexuality following adoption could be explained. The causal relationship is problematical.
