AN  - 280532709
T1  - Anovulatory menstruation in women
A1  - Wong A.S.H.
A1  - Engle E.T.
A1  - Buxton C.L.
Y1  - 1950//
N2  - This subject is discussed with material obtained from 36 women of child-bearing age whose complaint was sterility. By endometrial biopsies, anovulatory cycles were found in 47 instances. Twenty-eight of the 36 women were nulliparas; the majority were in the 20 to 30 age groups; the duration of sterility ranged from one to 5 years. Of the nulliparous women over 21% had from one to 3 abortions. Only one-third had normal menstrual histories. The predominant change in the menstrual cycle of the remaining patients was one ranging from oligomenorrhoea to periodic amenorrhoea. Nineteen of the 36 women were anovulatory throughout the investigation period. The remaining 17 were periodically so. The anovulatory cycles ranged from 1 to 5 during the period of investigation. The endometrium is classified as actively proliferative, or not actively profiferative depending on whether it shows oestrogen effect or not. The distinction is based on the character of the glands and epithelium and the abundance or poverty of coiled arteries in lower layers of endometrium as well as the presence or absence of mitotic figures. The time incidence of anovulatory cycles is higher than generally suspected. The average range found by other investigators appears to be between 4% and 10%. Temperature charts are a valuable adjunct to investigations of patients, but endometrial biopsies are more reliable.
