AN  - 280532462
T1  - Significance of post-partum haemorrhages from the endocrine point of view. Combined study of vaginal smears and endometrial biopsies
T3  - Que signifient les hemorragies du retour de couches au point de vue endocrinien? Etude des frottis vaginaux combines aux biopsies endometrials
A1  - Van Meensel Fr.
Y1  - 1950//
N2  - In the immediate post-partum period (with or without breast-feeding of the infant) 2 kinds of cells are found: of vaginal and uterine origin. These show both absence of oestrogenic stimulation and elimination of residual placental elements. In the later post-partum period, from the 10th day, distinction must be made between smears from nursing and non-nursing mothers. (1) In nursing mothers the first bleeding occurs in the 5th to 6th week after parturition and is preceded by either (a) a normal cycle with oestrogenic phase, ovulation and luteinic phase; (b) a possibly ovulatory cycle but remaining under the influence of strong oestrogenic stimulation; (c) an anovulatory cycle with oestrogenic hyperstimulation and absence of luteinic reaction or (d) an anovulatory cycle with distinct hypo-oestrogenism. (2) In women lactating for a short time (3-4 weeks), the smears show absence of oestrogenic stimulation. When lactation ceases the smears resume their usual appearance. (3) In women who have been lactating for a long time (more than 3 months) an anovulatory cycle with hypoestrogenism is observed when the first bleeding occurs during lactation and an appearance of 'lactation type' without signs of oestrogenic stimulation when the first bleeding does not appear until after weaning of the infant. The first bleeding, therefore, does not possess a uniform physiological significance. It may be identical with normal menstruation. In the majority of cases it represents an unbalanced hormonal action: either deficient (hypoestrogenic) or exaggerated (hyperoestrogenic). It may fail to occur if the ovaries are inhibited by a sufficient amount of prolactin.
