AN  - 280532304
T1  - Ovarian resection for the relief of sterility
A1  - Meaker S.R.
Y1  - 1950//
N2  - The author reports 65 patients in whom the pre-operative diagnosis of multiple retention cysts was confirmed at operation. The diagnosis of clinically important retention cysts is suggested by sterility in the absence of other major causes and by subnormal menstrual behaviour of long duration, and is confirmed by bi-manual palpation. There was some degree of uterine hyperplasia in about one-fourth of the patients. The basal temperature charts usually showed no evidence of ovulation. In a group of 16 sterile women with regular menstruation, the endometrium of 12 showed anovulatory cycles. In the 65 patients reported the metabolic rates ranged from plus 9 to minus 24, with 49 being on the minus side. The author performs a wedge resection as advocated by Stein. All cysts are painstakingly eliminated by exsection, puncture or electro-coagulation. In addition to simple retention cysts, 18 other pathological structures were found in the 130 ovaries examined. 38 of the 39 amenorrhoea patients were followed up for one or more years. In 26 there was regular and normal menstrual function. Of 50 patients complaining of sterility, 35 became pregnant with an average interval of 5 months between the operation and the first conception. To date there have been 48 pregnancies in this group with 42 normal deliveries. Of 4 patients with menometrorrhagia, 2 were entirely relieved, one improved, and one received no benefit from operation. Seven patients showed improved development of the uterus. In 80% of the patients who failed to conceive and in unmarried girls with menstrual disorders, endometrial biopsies or basal temperature charts showed ovulatory cycles. In the early stage of the formation of polycystic ovaries the aetiology is probably endocrine. In the late stage the chief impediment to their function would appear to be a degree of intra-ovarian tension, which paralyses the follicular apparatus.
