T1  - Hormonal changes following low dosage irradiation of pituitary and ovaries in anovulatory women
A1  - Rakoff A.E.
Y1  - 1950//
N2  - In a group of 12 sterility patients selected because of anovulatory cycles and failure to respond to the usual methods of treatment, low dosage irradiation to the pituitary and the ovaries was administered according to the technique of Kaplan. Eight of this group had gonadotrophic deficiencies, 3 had primary ovarian deficiencies and 1 had an adrenogenital syndrome. Two of the patients became pregnant. Of 4 with long-standing secondary amenorrhoea, 2 continued amenorrhoeic. There was improvement in the menstrual cycles of 6 patients who previously had irregularities. In 8 patients with gonadotrophic deficiencies there was improvement in the hormone pattern of 5 as evidenced by a more marked and sustained level of oestrogen excretion over that of the excretion of pituitary gonadotrophins. From changes in the hormone assays, vaginal smears and basal temperature charts, the effects of irradiation appeared to be rapid in responsive patients but in 6 months the benificial effects had waned in all improved cases but one.
