AN  - 280533014
T1  - Classification of disturbances in the menstrual cycle, menstruation and the bleeding mechanism
A1  - Shushanija P.G.
Y1  - 1950//
N2  - According to Russian authors, the role of oestrogens in these conditions is more important than that of progesterone: oestrogens stimulate the growth of the endometrium, uterine blood vessels and myometrium in the normal cycle and in pregnancy. After their elimination the uterus becomes sensitized and contracts. The following classification of menstrual disorders is proposed: (1) Biphasic shortened menstrual cycle (polymenorrhoea), due to premature destruction of the ovum owing to pelvic congestion with consecutive tissue hypoxaemia, increased CO<ovid:inf>2</ovid:inf> concentration, and production of toxic agents. The disorder is not to be confused with 'normal' three-weekly menstrual cycles. (2) Biphasic prolonged menstrual cycle (oligomenorrhoea). The proliferative phase is prolonged to 26 days or more, because the ovum dies on the 14-16th day, the follicle atrophies and the development of the corpus luteum phase is arrested. In the meantime a new follicle producing a sufficient amount of oestrogens develops and comes to ripening; ovulation occurs followed by a normal secretory phase. (3) One-stage concealed menstrual cycle (amenorrhoea, 1st grade). The ovum does not develop and the end of the first stage goes over to the first stage of the following cycle. The absence of stratum granulosum is significant. The endometrium persists in the follicular stage and no bleeding occurs. (4) Absence of menstrual cycle and menstruation (amenorrhoea 2nd grade). The development of both phases is arrested, and the vegetative and generative ovarian functions are suppressed. The sex organs atrophy and microcystic degeneration is seen in the ovaries. (5) One stage pathologically prolonged menstrual cycle (metropathia haemorrhagica). The proliferative phase is pathologically prolonged. During the amenorrhoeic stage the oestrogens are retained in the body, causing endometrial proliferation. When excreted, the uterus contracts and provokes nutritional disturbances, necroses and bleeding. (6) One stage menstrual cycle-anovulatory 'menses'. Frequent monthly bleedings of usual duration. The endometrium is in the proliferative stage. This type can be found from the menarche to the preclimacteric.
