T1  - Bilateral polycystic ovaries, Stein-Leventhal syndrome
A1  - Ingersoll F.M.
A1  - McDermott Jr. W.V.
Y1  - 1950//
N2  - The Stein-Leventhal syndrome is characterized primarily by amenorrhoea and sterility. Grossly, the ovaries are large, pale and polycystic. Microscopically, they show a thickened tunica albuginea, with an absence of corpora lutea and corpora albicantia. The aetiological factor in this disorder is primarily a hormonal imbalance with over-activity of the pituitary, resulting in persistent failure of ovulation. The authors have accumulated 21 cases in 12 years. They have found hormonal therapy unsuccessful; resection of the ovary was successful in 68% of their cases.
