T1  - Discussion on the use of oestrogen therapy in gynaecology. Oestrogen therapy in primary dysmenorrhoea
A1  - Macgregor T.N.
Y1  - 1950//
N2  - Thirty-eight cases of primary dysmenorrhoea were studied. In 33 (87%) the cycle was ovulatory, as shown by basal temperature and endometrial biopsy. Oestrogen (ethinyl oestradiol 0.05-1 mg. or dienoestrol 1-10 mg.) was administered during the first 20 days of the cycle to 30 of the patients who were known to be ovulating. The dysmenorrhoea was relieved in all the cases in which the dosage of oestrogen was adequate to suppress ovulation, but pain recurred with the next ovulatory cycle. When oestrogens were administered during the pre-menstrual or post-ovulatory phase, 55% of the cases were cured or relieved, but 24% relapsed. Oestrogen-induced anovulatory bleeding is painless: post-ovulatory bleeding is frequently painful. It is considered that the intervention of the luteal hormone, progesterone, determines whether menstruation will be painful or not. Since the majority of menstruating women ovulate but do not have dysmenorrhoea, it is inferred that menstruation is painless when oestrogen and progestogen are in equilibrium and synergistic, but painful when this balance is disturbed. It is suggested that oestrogenic substances may be parasympathetic stimulants, and that progesterone has the opposite effect.
