AN  - 280821625
T1  - Newer aspects of infertility
A1  - Guerriero W.F.
Y1  - 1950//
N2  - The author reviews the recent theories regarding the problems of infertility with special reference to the views concerning imprisonment of ova with failure of luteinization. The phenomenon of the development of a mature graafian follicle without rupture yet with an apparently normal corpus luteum function may account for many cases of relative infertility. Deficient luteum function from this cause should be suspected when the thermal shift of the basal body temperature record occurs late, so shortening the 'secretory' phase, which normally should last 12-14 days. Biopsy in such a case may reveal only the early secretory phase of the endometrium. It is possible, however, for the endometrium to be refractory to progesterone and to show a proliferative phase on biopsy simulating an anovular cycle, when ovulation has actually taken place. It is not wise to declare any patient infertile because of anovulation since at any time ovulation may occur. When the ovum is imprisoned, the administration of gonadotropin may be of value in precipitating its extrusion. When ovulation has occurred in the absence of adequate luteal function, the use of chorionic gonadotropin or progesterone daily from the day of ovulation is of definite value in preparing the endometrium for implantation and nidation of the ovum, but one should be aware of the possibility that pseudo-pregnancy may occur.
